<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChryslerContract 1stLd-Writethru a0898 05-12 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler Contract, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0898,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Workers Narrowly Approve Two-Year Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with contract approved. No pickup. Version
also moving on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers on Wednesday ratified a
contract giving 66,000 Chrysler Corp. employees in 15 states
greater job protection, the union said.
   The two-year contract was approved by about 54 percent of those
voting, according to union officials who spoke on condition they
not be identified.
   Two former American Motors Corp. locals in Wisconsin also voted
Wednesday, approving separate pacts reached during the national
contract talks at Chrysler's Highland Park headquarters. Chrysler
bought AMC in August.
   The UAW and the No. 3 automaker reached the agreement May 4
after 2{ weeks of early negotiations aimed at mending a series of
conflicts. Talks normally would have begun in July or August.
   The contract, which replaces a three-year agreement that would
have have expired Sept. 14, mirrors that signed last fall at Ford
Motor Co. and General Motors Corp.
   The Big Three contract prevents layoffs except when production
is cut because of slow sales, forbids plant closings not announced
before talks began and makes it harder for companies to transfer
work to outside companies or foreign countries.
   The Chrysler contract also provides 3 percent lump-sum bonuses
in 1989 and 1990, a $1,000 signing bonus and, for the first time,
profit-sharing according to the formula that has generated
thousands of dollars for Ford workers.
   But the Chrysler pact also prevents the company from paying cash
or stock bonuses to executives in years when a profit-sharing
formula included in the contract generates no payout for workers.
   The UAW was angered in the past two years when GM workers
received no profit-sharing while executives were awarded generous
bonuses.
   Union leaders, including Vice President Marc Stepp, have said
they expected the pact, approved last week by local union leaders
on the UAW's 140-member Chrysler bargaining council, to be ratified
by a comfortable margin.
   However, the contract was rejected at several large locals,
including Detroit's Jefferson Avenue assembly plant and Mound Road
engine plant and a stamping plant in Sterling Heights, union
officials said.
   Chrysler's 3,500-worker Warren Truck plant approved the contract
with 65 percent in favor, said Local 140 President Gil Wojcik.
   ``I'm surprised. I'm flabbergasted. I thought it would pass by a
wider margin,'' said Wojcik, chairman of the elected 10-member
bargaining committee.
   Unlike the GM and Ford pacts, the Chrysler contract also
protects 2,200 workers at four closing Acustar Inc. parts plants
from layoff. When any of the plants are closed, workers will be
paid their regular wages and placed in a job bank.
   If any of the four plants _ one in Van Wert, Ohio, and three in
the Detroit area _ are sold instead, workers can choose whether to
go into the job bank and wait for a Chrysler opening or go with the
new employer.
</TEXT>
