<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Berlin 1stLd-Writethru a0847 05-12 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Berlin, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0847,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fans Put on the Ritz for Berlin's 100th Birthday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Carnegie Hall concert,
picking up 3rd graf `At midday ...' Changes byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY201</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From Frank Sinatra to Isaac Stern, show business
put on the Ritz for Irving Berlin and raised a classy, schmaltzy
salute to the songwriter Wednesday on his 100th birthday.
   The creator of thousands of tunes was not in Carnegie Hall for
the three-hour concert, but family members filled a row.
   The event started big and ended bigger, with the Army Chorus and
soldiers from Ft. Dix, N.J., filling the stage in front of a
30-piece orchestra, Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts standing in the
aisles and Marilyn Horne's mezzo-soprano voice soaring above them
in Berlin's ``God Bless America.''
   Then the evening's performers filed in the audience stood, and
everybody sang a lusty ``There's No Business Like Show Business,''
still another Berlin classic.
   The artists included Ray Charles and Leonard Bernstein on piano.
It was Bernstein's Carnegie Hall singing debut with Berlin's
``Russian Lullaby.''
   Director-choreographer Tommy Tune tapdanced to ``Puttin' on the
Ritz,'' and Willie Nelson, in formal black with a black cowboy hat,
brought his band for ``Blue Skies.''
   ``We wouldn't think of doing a show without including it,''
Nelson said.
   Sinatra sang ``Always'' and ``When I Lost You,'' Nell Carter did
``Alexander's Ragtime Band,'' Jerry Orbach and Maureen McGovern
``Easter Parade,'' and Rosemary Clooney ``Count Your Blessings
Instead of Sheep'' and ``White Christmas.''
   Isaac Stern narrated a film of highlights of Berlin's life. The
evening, a benefit for the American Society of Composers, Authors
and Publishers Foundation and Carnegie Hall Society, was taped by
CBS for broadcast May 27.
   ``Irving Berlin took common American talk and made it into
poetry. He gave it back to us as beautiful treasures of how we
feel, not fancy, not too highbrow, simple and graceful,'' said
Garrison Keillor, formerly of the musical radio program ``A Prairie
Home Companion.''
   At midday, 14 cast members of the Broadway show, ``A Chorus
Line,'' warmed up the festivities with an enthusiastic songfest at
the Central Park Arsenal, a 140-year-old landmark.
   ``There's no business like show business!'' proclaimed the
youthful Broadway talents. Their sprightly medley ranged from love
songs such as ``They Say That Falling in Love is Wonderful,'' to
the torch song ``What'll I Do,'' to the humorous ``You Can't Get a
Man With a Gun.''
   In the latter, from the 1946 musical ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' the
hungry-for-love sharpshooter laments, ``You can't shoot a man in
the tail like a quail.''
   After rallying around a grand piano played by ``Chorus Line''
conductor Jerry Goldberg, the cast members moved outside to offer
an a cappella chorus of ``God Bless America'' and ``Happy
Birthday,'' then cut loose green helium balloons.
   People from all walks of life got into the act around the city _
and the nation.
   On Staten Island, 15 handicapped Boy Scouts sang ``Happy
Birthday'' and ``God Bless America'' during the dedication of a new
log cabin named for Berlin. He had donated the residuals from the
patriotic tune to the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts.
   Patients in 100 Veterans Administration hospitals and nursing
homes around the nation geared up to sing ``God Bless America''
simultaneously, at 5 p.m. Eastern time.
   The composer, meanwhile, was spending the day ``quietly at
home'' and did not plan to be at Carnegie Hall, said Berlin's
secretary, Hilda Schneider.
   ``He's never made a big thing about his birthdays,'' she said.
``Let's face it, he's not 22 years old.''
   That didn't discourage the 75 New Yorkers who gathered outside
Berlin's Manhattan home to usher in his special day with a midnight
serenade.
   ``Even if he didn't write a thing, to reach 100 is to be part of
American history,'' said John Wiessman, 21, a junior at New York
University. ``But this guy wrote a lot. I love `God Bless America.'
Every American has got to love it.''
   The reclusive Berlin, who lives on exclusive Beekman Place with
his second wife, Ellin, did not appear at his window when Wiessman
and the others crooned ``We'll be loving you, always.'' But he knew
they were there.
   ``When they were there singing, of course he heard them. He was
very thrilled by that,'' said his secretary.
</TEXT>
