<DOCNO> AP880512-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DraytonHall     05-12 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drayton Hall,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Descendants of Colonial Planter To Gather At Homesite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 descendants of colonial
planter John Drayton are expected at his plantation this weekend to
celebrate the 250th anniversary of the family homestead.
   Drayton Hall, a two-story brick Georgian structure northwest of
Charleston, has passed through seven generations of the Drayton
family.
   Now it is one of 13 sites maintained by the National Trust for
Historic Preservation that is open to the public. It attracts more
than 52,000 visitors a year.
   The Thomas Drayton family settled in South Carolina in 1679 _
nine years after the founding of Charleston. The youngest son,
John, began construction of Drayton Hall in 1738. It was completed
four years later.
   His father lived at nearby Magnolia Plantation, which also is a
popular tourist attraction.
   There are an estimated 4,000 descendants of Thomas Drayton
scattered around the world, and at least 100 are expected for the
celebration, which will include dancing under the stars and
workshops on archaeology, said Meg Lavin, curator at Drayton Hall.
   Drayton Hall is the only Ashley River plantation to survive the
Civil War intact. Two small flanking buildings _ one used as a
kitchen and one as a utility building _ were destroyed in the 1886
Charleston earthquake and a hurricane seven years later.
   George Neil, assistant director of Drayton Hall, said that
according to family legend, the house emerged from the Civil War
unscathed because of the quick thinking of its occupant, Dr. John
Drayton.
   As Union troops marched through toward the end of the war,
Drayton had the house posted with flags signifying it was being
used to treat smallpox patients. However, it's not known whether it
actually was used as a hospital.
   ``The story comes down both through the owners and slave
descendants. Whether it was a ruse or not is unclear,'' said Ms.
Lavin.
   The builder of the house was a successful planter who owned up
to 125 slaves and acquired 30 other properties including townhouses
in Charleston.
   The cost of building the manor, located on a 125-acre tract, is
not known, said Neil. However, in the later part of the 18th
Century the house was referred to as ``Mr. Drayton's Palace.''
</TEXT>
