<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-StockMarket-Regan     05-12 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Market-Regan,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donald Regan Calls For Steps to Quell Market Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald T. Regan took time off from discussing
his book on the inner workings of President Reagan's White House to
tell Congress that financial markets and the government must act
quickly to reassure the nation's investors.
   The former Treasury secretary said Wednesday that ``there should
have been more prompt action'' after last October's stock market
crash. ``This thing happened over seven months ago,'' he said.
   Regan told the Senate Banking Committee that a form of
computerized trading called index arbitrage should be prohibited,
and that all transactions involving stock index futures should be
temporarily halted. Both practices, he said, make the markets
excessively volatile and have scared worried individual investors
off.
   ``A stock market whose main participants are speculators and
their programs cannot be a healthy market, and an unhealthy Wall
Street will sooner or later drag down the real economy,'' said
Regan, the former chief executive officer of Merrill Lynch & Co.
   The banking panel has been holding hearings on the dramatic
price swings that have dominated the markets since Oct. 19, when
the Dow Jones Industrial Average fell a record 508 points.
   Regan, who was White House chief of staff for two years after
being treasury secretary, has spent most of his time recently
talking about his new book, ``For the Record: From Wall Street to
Washington.'' In it, he says first lady Nancy Reagan often consults
astrologers when planning the president's schedule and making other
decisions.
   Regan declined to discuss his book Wednesday with reporters.
   But he did blame computer-driven trading, especially index
arbitrage, for the market's problems.
   Traders conducting index arbitrage use computers to profit from
price discrepancies between the stock and futures markets by
simultaneously buying in one market and selling in the other.
   ``In my mind, we should start by banning index option arbitrage,
and then proceed with other reforms which will restore public
confidence in the financial markets,'' Regan said.
   He said problems also have been caused by stock futures, which
are traded in Chicago. In a stock index futures transaction, an
amount of cash equal to the value of a collection of stocks changes
hands, with an agreement that the portfolio will be bought back at
whatever those stocks' values are at a specific future date.
   Opponents of the practice say the massive amounts of money
involved add unpredictability to the stock market when traders buy
or sell equities to protect their futures transactions.
   ``I think there should be a pause'' in index futures trading,
Regan told reporters after his testimony. ``It won't hurt very much
for a three-month or six-month pause here while we take a look at
the instrument itself and how it's used to see whether or not it
should be permitted to continue.''
   Regan told the senators the nation's financial markets, or the
federal agencies that regulate them, should initiate the steps he
recommended. If not, Congress should act, he said.
   At the same hearing, George L. Ball, chairman and chief
executive officer of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said the
abolition of stock index futures should be considered.
   ``Most knowledgeable professionals agree that if it were not for
index futures, stock market moves would be far less wild, sudden or
irrationally large,'' he said.
   Charles R. Schwab, who owns the discount brokerage firm that
bears his name, also told the lawmakers that program trading should
be abolished if other steps to restore market confidence don't work.
   ``In surveys we have conducted, we hear over and over again the
theme that individual investors fear they cannot compete in markets
that are so dominated by the volatility introduced by program
trading and index arbitrage,'' he said.
   Earlier, Leo Melamed, chairman of the executive committee of the
board of governors of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, told
reporters that index arbitrage helps stabilize the markets by
ensuring that stock and futures prices closely track each other.
   ``I'm not going to defend perception,'' he said. ``The reality
is it is not a factor'' in the volatility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0715EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-PlantClosing Bjt   05-12 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Plant Closing, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Reagan Uses Shopworn Argument Against
Plant-Closing</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a creaky plank in the platform
President Reagan stands on when he sounds off against legislation
aimed at protecting workers against sudden plant closings.
   Reagan, speaking against the provision recently, said that ``as
an old labor union president, I suggest that's a matter that
belongs in the management-labor contracts between the unions and
the people.''
   But that suggests organized labor plays a larger-than-life role
in today's economy. Many government statisticians, unionists and
even business executives know better.
   Reagan headed the Screen Actors Guild in Hollywood in the late
1940s, when unions were far more powerful than they are today,
representing roughly a third of all workers.
   Because unions now represent only about 15 percent of all
workers, and about 20 percent in manufacturing, it doesn't
necessarily follow that plant notification protections can be left
for employers and unions to settle.
   Doing that would leave open the question of who takes care of
the interests of the other 80 percent of blue-collar workers.
   What's happened is that the administration has essentially
accepted the boardroom argument that executives must be free to
make their own decisions, Reagan's shopworn argument
notwithstanding.
   And Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin conceded to a manfacturer's
audience Tuesday that this may prove politically costly, especially
if Reagan's expected veto of the bill is sustained.
   ``The polls have indicated that, from the people I've talked to,
62 percent of the people think that plant notification is the right
way to go,'' she said. ``This issue is going to drive us kicking
and screaming for the next five months.''
   The plant-closing provision in the 1,000-page trade bill was the
product of heavy lobbying by the AFL-CIO, and many Democrats were
unwilling to see it pulled from the bill.
   ``The workers who do not have the benefit of a union are treated
like dogs,'' said Brian Turner, assistant to Howard Samuel,
president of the AFL-CIO's Industrial Union Department.
   ``The fact is that, although a lot of companies talk a good game
and a lot of them do a good game, the overwhelming fact is that
many workers do not get sufficient notice,'' Turner said.
   He cited a Government Accounting Office study which found that
workers hit by plant closings but not represented by unions had an
average of only two days warning.
   Mark de Bernardo, special counsel for domestic policy at the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said Reagan is correct in opposing any
move by Congress to legislate worker notification protections.
   ``Eighty-eight percent of the employers do give some notice and
more and more employers are giving more, whether they have unions
or not,'' he said. ``But it's not always possible for businesses in
financial turmoil.''
   Plant closing legislation, he said, ``would handcuff employers
at a time which is particularly troubled and turbulent.''
   Audrey Freeman, a labor economist at the Conference Board, a
business research organization in New York, challenged arguments
used by government, business and labor on this issue.
   Referring to Reagan's statement about leaving plant-closing
protection to companies and unions, she said, ``I think that's a
cynical response that you're getting from the White House.''
   ``The strength of unions tends to be more and more in government
and government-affected employment,'' rather than in manufacturing,
she said.
   ``The whole plant-closing thing is kind of artificial,'' she
said. ``I have the impression that they're (the opponents and
proponents) just acting in front of a painted scenery.''
   Ms. Freeman said she thinks business overstates its concern
about governmental interference and that organized labor merely is
trying to get back a greater say in the decision-making process.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Hartson covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
