<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Politics,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kim Young-Sam Elected President Of Opposition Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Young-sam regained control of the
opposition Reunification Democratic Party on Thursday when he was
elected its president at a special party convention in Seoul.
   Kim's re-emergence at the helm of the party comes only three
months after he resigned from the top party post in an attempt to
forge a merger with the breakaway opposition Party for Peace and
Democracy, led by rival Kim Dae-jung.
   In his acceptance speech, Kim Young-sam said he would reform the
party and lead it to victory in the general elections four years
from now. His party fell from first to second place in the
opposition lineup after the Party for Peace and Democracy gained
more seats in last month's parliamentary elections.
   The two Kims came under public pressure to retire from politics
in the wake of the Dec. 16 presidential elections. The two
opposition leaders both ran on separate tickets, despite widespread
calls for a single opposition candidacy, and lost out to governing
party candidate Roh Tae-woo.
   Kim Dae-jung resigned from his party's leadership post in March,
following the party's poor showing in the presidential election.
