<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Zoo,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Reforms Planned For London Zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The London Zoo will receive an $18.8 million
government grant to modernize and attract more visitors, a zoo
spokeswoman said.
   London Zoo in central London's Regent's Park, and Whipsnade Wild
Animal Park in suburban Bedfordshire, have regularly lost money
despite government subsidies and attempts to boost attendance in
the past, said Sue Copsey.
   The two zoos, with the Institute of Zoology, form the Zoological
Society of England which has been losing up to $3.76 million
annually, Ms. Copsey said.
   She said on Wednesday that the losses were due to a large drop
in annual attendance, which fell from an average of 3 million in
the 1950s to less than 1 million in 1982. She said there had been a
slight increase in recent years.
   The grant will help the zoo draw more visitors by funding new
amusement-park type attractions and new animal housing and
displays, she said.
</TEXT>
