<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NationalService     05-12 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-National Service,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Group to Push for National Service Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of elected officials from a Democratic
Party group plan to campaign in coming months for a voluntary
program that would link federal education, housing and job training
aid to participation in civilian or military service.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said the plan proposed by the Democratic
Leadership Council would say essentially ``that if you're going to
get assistance from society for your education, then you're going
to serve society.''
   The group released its 66-page proposal on Wednesday. It calls
for creation of a ``Citizens Corps'' made up of young volunteers
who would work one or two years at subsistence wages in civilian or
military service.
   For each year of service in the corps a volunteers would earn a
$10,000 voucher that could be used for college, vocational training
or a home down payment.
   Nunn said the vouchers would eventually replace existing federal
grant and loan programs as the primary source of federal aid to
students.
   The proposal also calls for enlistment of volunteers over the
age of 65, who would earn modest wages instead of vouchers and
would perform primarily administrative and supervisory tasks within
the corps.
   Former Virginia Gov. Charles Robb, past chairman of the DLC,
said the proposal is ``an attempt to move away from the politics of
pure entitlement to some sort of system that involves mutual civic
obligation.''
   The DLC is composed primarily of moderate and conservative
Democrats, many from the South, and was a prime mover behind the
creation of this year's ``Super Tuesday'' multi-state primary day.
</TEXT>
