<TEXT>
   British pop singer George Michael is the
first white solo artist to hit the top of the black album chart
with his LP ``Faith,'' in what one Billboard columnist called ``an
amazing achievement.''
   The Bee Gees were the last music group to reach No. 1 on the
black charts with the soundtrack from the disco movie ``Saturday
Night Fever'' in 1976.
   But no white had done so since the charts began in 1965,
although Madonna, Phil Collins, Michael McDonald and Herb Alpert
have come close, Billboard columnist Paul Grein said Wednesday.
   ``It's an amazing achievement because it means he is accepted
(by black audiences) and is credible,'' Grein said.
   Michael's representatives were informed by Billboard on Monday
that ``Faith,'' which has sold 12.5 million copies and produced
three hit singles since its release late last year, will take the
No. 1 spot on the black charts in next week's issue, said Michael's
spokesman, Phil Lobel.
   ``Faith'' currently is No. 1 on Billboard's pop chart, which
lists black and white artists.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Madlyn Rhue says she tried to hide her
multiple sclerosis at first, but these days the actress who needs a
wheelchair to get around is proud of her achievements against the
odds.
   In fact, she'll appear as part of a campaign for the National
Multiple Sclerosis Society this month in an ad that reads, ``Even
With MS, Madlyn Rhue Is On a Roll.''
   The actress, who is one of 250,000 Americans who suffer from the
disease that attacks the muscular system, says she resisted the
campaign at first, thinking it would only inspire pity.
   ``I didn't want to do any of that look-how-I've-been victimized
jazz,'' she said recently.
   But when the society showed her a proposed ad campaign that
showed people with multiple sclerosis doing such activities as
scuba diving and sky diving, she changed her mind.
   ``It says to the world, OK, I'm in a wheelchair,'' Miss Rhue
said, ``but look at what I can do.''
   Miss Rhue's most visible role is the wheelchair-bound ballistics
expert on CBS-TV's ``Houston Knights.''
