<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MaternityLeave     05-12 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maternity Leave,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maternity Leave Dispute Pits Senior Attorney Against Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congresswoman is accusing a Justice
Department official of harassing one of his senior attorneys who is
seeking to extend her maternity leave to seven months instead of
the usual three to four months.
   ``Has war on maternity leave replaced the war on drugs?'' Rep.
Pat Schroeder, D-Colo., wrote Attorney General Edwin Meese III. The
letter was directed against Assistant Attorney General John Bolton,
head of the department's criminal division.
   Bolton has ordered Joan Bernott to return to work May 31 or
submit additional medical information from her doctor giving a
reason why her leave should be extended to mid-August.
   On May 4, Bolton rejected Ms. Bernott's request, which is
supported by a note from her medical doctor, to extend her leave
without pay to Aug. 15. Asked whether she would report to work May
31, Ms. Bernott, who went on maternity leave Jan. 25, said that she
would defer to the advice of her doctor.
   In an interview Wednesday, Bolton responded that ``there was no
intent whatsoever to harass'' Ms. Bernott and that ``the idea that
there is discrimination here is absolutely untrue.''
   He referred to an April 21 comment in which he told Ms.
Bernott's lawyer that ``nobody is going to ask Ms. Bernott to do
anything which would in any way jeopardize her health'' and said he
simply wanted more information from her doctor regarding the
medical basis for the additional leave time.
   Bolton said the civil division faces an enormous workload and
that it was vital that its 25 senior attorney positions _ one of
which is held by Ms. Bernott _ be staffed fully.
   Ms. Bernott obtained a letter from her physician, Dr. Sandra M.
Chase, on March 28 saying that an additional four months of
recuperation from a difficult pregnancy was required.
   ``Return to work now, in my opinion, represents health risk to
this patient,'' the doctor said in a follow-up April 26 letter
submitted as a result of Bolton's request for more information.
   Bolton said Ms. Bernott had told Mary Ann Beck, director of the
office of administration, on March 25 that she didn't want to
return to work before mid-August because she wanted to attend a
wedding of her husband's brother in Geneva, Switzerland, the week
before Aug. 15.
   Ms. Bernott said she did not want to come back earlier in August
and then simply have to ask for another week off to go to the
wedding, he said.
   Ms. Bernott hired a lawyer to represent her after Bolton told
her in a letter April 13 that there was ``evidence that you may
have willfully submitted a fraudulently based claim for excessive
leave.''
   Ms. Bernott, 42, who has three children, was the Justice
Department's lead attorney in successfully defending the government
against litigation surrounding the use of the defoliant Agent
Orange during the Vietnam war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SpySketches     05-12 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spy Sketches,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Spies Penetrated Highest Levels Of British Intelligence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Philby, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following are biographical sketches of the
four British traitors recruited at Cambridge University in the
1930s by a Soviet agent who is still unidentified.
   _ Harold Adrian Russell ``Kim'' Philby was regarded as the most
damaging spy to Western intelligence. The only one of the Cambridge
spy ring who was not a homosexual, he is believed to have become a
Soviet agent in 1933, the year in which he saw fascists fighting
communists and labor unionists in Austria. When entrusted with the
Russian desk of MI6, the British intelligence unit that controls
agents abroad, he told the Soviets who was spying on them. He
served in Washington as liaison officer with the CIA. He betrayed a
British-U.S. plan to land guerrillas in communist Albania in 1946
and 300 were killed. He fled to Moscow in 1963 while working as
journalist in Beirut.
   _ Anthony Frederick Blunt, an art historian, recruited spies for
Moscow during the 1930s. He spied for the Soviets during World War
II while working for the British MI5 counter-espionage service. He
was unmasked in 1964 but was granted immunity in return for telling
all he knew about Soviet intelligence. He was publicly exposed in
1979 and stripped of the knighthood conferred for his services as
royal art adviser. He died in London of a heart attack in 1983.
   _ Guy Francis de Moncy Burgess became a Soviet agent in the
1930s because he believed only Soviet dictator Joseph Stalin could
stop Adolf Hitler. He worked as a British diplomat in Washington
and looked after Far East affairs during the Korean War. He lived
in Washington with Philby, who was also working for the British
Foreign Office. He died in Moscow in 1963 at age 52.
   _ Donald Duart Maclean worked for the Foreign Office and was
posted to Washington in 1944, but recalled because of heavy
drinking. He worked with Americans and Canadians on the Combined
Policy Committee for Joint Atomic Development and gave the Soviets
documents on nuclear planning. It is believed he and Philby gave
atomic bomb secrets to Stalin. Maclean fled to Moscow with Burgess
in May 1951, where he was given the KGB rank of colonel. He died in
Moscow in 1983 at age 69.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
