<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Denton,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Museum Honors Denton Naval, Senate Career</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeremiah Denton, the former Alabama U.S.
senator and Vietnam prisoner of war, is furnishing a museum room in
his honor with souvenirs and mementos of his life _ including
letters from four presidents.
   The upstairs room at the Museum of the City of Mobile was
dedicated last month to commemorate its native son's POW years, his
joyous return from the war prison in Hanoi, his service in the
Senate and his continuing career of public service with the
National Forum Foundation.
   Some of the pieces are gifts to the museum. Others were placed
on loan, including presidential letters from Lyndon Johnson,
Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford and Ronald Reagan.
   Some of the letters were written to Denton's wife, Jane, during
her husband's 7{-year captivity. The most recent, from Reagan, was
dated April 12 and congratulated the 63-year-old Denton on his
``hometown tribute.''
