<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Guatemala     05-12 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guatemala,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Says It Foiled Uprising; Two Officers Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops foiled a rebellion against
President Vinicio Cerezo's civilian government and arrested two
army officers who were halted leading soldiers toward the capital,
the defense minister said.
   The minister, Gen. Hector Alejandro Gramajo Morales, gave no
details of Wednesday's rebellion and would not confirm an earlier
Defense Ministry statement that a coup attempt had taken place.
   He did not say how many soldiers were involved, what kind of
arms they used or if there was any violence.
   Gramajo Morales said the two officers arrested, whom he refused
to identify by name or rank, had staged short-lived ``acts of
indiscipline.''
   Reading a prepared statement, he told a news conference the two
ringleaders met with officers and soldiers at bases in Jutiapa, 75
miles south of the capital, and Retalhuleu, 115 miles southwest of
Guatememala City, and led them toward the capital Wednesday morning.
   ``They were immediately neutralized and the officers involved
immediately changed their attitude,'' Gramajo Morales said, adding
that the rest of the army's 74 bases and installations were not
involved.
   The defense minister said one of the ringleaders temporarily
blocked the road leading from Guatemala City to El Salvador,
prompting the army to deploy extra troops around the capital.
   Guatemala City remained calm throughout the day. Local radio and
television broadcasts said troops involved in the uprising had
returned to their barracks.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
preliminary reports indicated some military units were involved in
a coup attempt, but she had no details. She reaffirmed U.S. support
for civilian government.
   Cerezo, who with his Cabinet were briefed on the uprising by
Gramajo Morales, did not issue any public statement.
   A lawyer and leader of the Christian Democratic Party, Cerezo
was elected in November 1985 in the first election in 16 years in
which the military did not field a candidate.
   Nearly halfway through his term, Cerezo faces discontent over
economic measures and a powerful military.
   While his government has wanted the world to see Guatemala as
safe for the return of exiles, including leftist leaders, the
military has made known it does not welcome them.
   Both the Cerezo administration and military leaders have opposed
a prompt resumption of peace talks with leftist guerrillas, who
have been fighting the civilian government and a succession of
military or military-dominated governments for 27 years.
   Cerezo succeeded Gen. Oscar Humberto Mejia Victores, who seized
power in August 1983 from another military ruler, Gen. Efrain Rios
Montt.
   Rios Montt came to power after young army officers staged a coup
in March 1982 that overthrew the rightist government of Gen.
Fernando Romeo Lucas Garcia.
</TEXT>
