<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-12 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Meets Congressional Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Meeting with Tutu begins 8:30 a.m. EDT; will be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis was holding meetings today with congressional leaders
before heading for Oregon, the scene of the next primary contest.
   The Massachusetts governor had a morning meeting set with
Archbishop Desmond Tutu of South Africa. Tutu told members of
Congress on Wednesday he favors new and harsher economic sanctions
against South Africa to pressure the country to end its policy of
official racism.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., was introducing a measure today
that would require U.S. companies to shed their investments in
South Africa within a year and ban trade in everything but
strategic minerals and agricultural products. A similar bill is
pending in the House.
   Dukakis was also meeting congressional leaders including House
Majority Leader Tom Foley; House Speaker Jim Wright; Rep. William
Gray, D-Pa., the chairman of the House Budget Committee, and Senate
Majority leader Robert Byrd of West Virginia.
   The Massachusetts governor was attending a luncheon with Latin
American ambassadors before leaving for a series of appearances in
Oregon, which holds its primary Tuesday. Dukakis was traveling
tonight to California, which has 314 delegates at stake in its June
7 contest.
   Dukakis widened his delegate lead over Jesse Jackson this week
with wins in Tuesday's Nebraska and West Virginia primaries. He is
more than 600 delegates ahead of his only remaining Democratic
rival, but is still several hundred shy of the 2,081 delegates
needed to nominate.
   As his prospects for being the nominee have steadily improved in
recent weeks, Dukakis has been more aggressive in criticizing his
likely rival, George Bush. The vice president, who has a
mathematical lock on the GOP nomination, received President
Reagan's formal endorsement on Wednesday night.
   That drew a gibe from the Dukakis camp.
   ``We figured it's because Aquarii get along better with Geminis
than Scorpios,'' said Dukakis campaign spokesman Steve Akey,
referring to Nancy Reagan's consultations with an astrologer, as
reported by former White House chief of staff Donald Regan in his
new book.
   On Wednesday, Dukakis rode high-speed trains being tested for
use between Boston and New York and accused the Reagan
administration of failing to promote such service and ``spending
the last eight years without a national transportation policy.''
   He also attended a fund-raiser in New Jersey, whose primary is
the same day as California's.
</TEXT>
