<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     05-12 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Upbeat As He Wraps Up Oregon Campaign Swing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, telling supporters ``I earn
my votes every day'' was campaigning hard for Oregon's primary next
Tuesday, leading an anti-drug march through a crime-ridden city
neighborhood and visiting an Indian reservation.
   Jackson was winding up a three-day campaign swing through the
state today. He dismissed polls showing him behind Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts.
   ``Let the polls catch up to leadership,'' he said, also brushing
aside defeats in Tuesday's West Virginia and Nebraska primaries.
   On Wednesday, Jackson made his trademark anti-drug appeal at a
Portland high school.
   ``You get those guns out of your pockets and the drugs out of
your life and you can make a difference,'' he told about 1,300
students at predominantly black Jefferson High School.
   ``Dope pushers are killers of the dream,'' he said. ``They're
terrorists.''
   Jackson was greeted with thunderous applause on his arrival in
the school's gymnasium and received several standing ovations from
the students. After the rally, he led a 13-block anti-drug march
from the school through one of Portland's highest-crime areas.
   Jackson also traveled to Redmond, where he told leaders of
Oregon Indian tribes he would see that Indian concerns are included
in the Democratic Party platform.
   ``In our government, there will be a secretary of Interior who
is sensitive to your humanity, sensitive to our treaty
obligations,'' Jackson said.
   At Redmond High School, Jackson stopped to embrace Robin Tovey,
13, a seventh-grader born with no arms or legs. Asked what Jackson
said to her when he gave her his Redmond High School cap, she
replied, ``That he loved me.''
   Jackson also went to a hospital to see a teen-aged volunteer
worker in his campaign who was hurt in a riding accident this week.
   In Salem, Jackson told a crowd of 2,500 cheering supporters that
his quest for the presidency is ``winning every day.'' He said he
is ``setting the moral tone for the campaign.''
   ``I earn my votes every day, I'm not inheriting any votes,''
Jackson said. ``When I win, you win.''
