<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Military     05-12 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Military,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hardliner Gets Top Military Command Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By naming a little-known Khomeini
loyalist as armed forces chief of staff, Iran's leaders appear to
be trying to end friction between the regular army and
Revolutionary Guards, Western anaylsts say.
   Brig. Gen. Ali Shahbazi was sworn in Monday, three weeks after
Iraq recaptured the Faw Peninsula in a lightning assault April
16-18 that caught the Iranians by surprise.
   In addition, U.S. warships sank or crippled two Iranian frigates
and four other armed vessels April 18 after knocking out two
Iranian oil platforms.
   Shahbazi's appointment by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini ``is a
direct consequence'' of those defeats, said Hans-Heino Kopietz, a
Middle East specialist with the London-based International
Institute for Strategic Studies.
   Western analysts have speculated that more heads will roll among
military and naval commanders.
   Shahbazi, 42, replaced Brig. Gen. Ismael Sohrabi, who had been
the armed forces' chief of staff since 1984. Promoted from colonel,
Shahbazi had been Sohrabi's deputy for four years. ``It's like this
fellow came out of nowhere,'' Kopietz said in a telephone interview.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Shahbazi has
``an outstanding record in the guerrilla warfare headquarters'' at
Ahvaz in the oil-rich southwestern Khuzistan province, and it
stressed his ``revolutionary and religious commitment.''
   Anthony Cordesman, a Middle East specialist at Georgetown
University, said in a telephone interview that Shahbazi is ``a
Khomeini loyalist, a Khomeini professional, who has close links
with the Revolutionary Guards.''
   That indicated that the Tehran leadership is making a new effort
to end friction _ and often outright hostility _ between the
regular army and the increasingly powerful Revolutionary Guards
Corps.
   The 350,000-strong Revolutionary Guards, made up of Islamic
zealots who outnumber the army, have their own air and naval wings
and get the pick of new hardware.
   When he swore in Shahbazi on Monday, President Ali Khamenei
declared, ``The Revolutionary Guards and the army must work more
closely together and coordinate their operations in every area.''
   Iran had held Faw, a dusty strip of land in the northern gulf,
since capturing it in February 1986, but Iran apparently had
reduced its force in the enclave to about 20,000 men, half the size
of a year ago.
   Faw was the only significant chunk of Iraq that Iran had seized
in the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   While Iran's loss of Faw does not significantly change the
military equation, Iraq's victory was a major psychological blow to
the Iranians.
   The Iranian navy's drubbing by the Americans doubled Tehran's
discomfiture.
   Unconfirmed reports from Tehran said the Revolutionary Guards
commander, Mohsen Rezai, and other hardliners pressed for
retaliation against the U.S. Navy, despite its superior firepower,
after the Americans pounded the two oil platforms April 18.
   The platforms were destroyed to avenge the mining of the missile
frigate Samuel B. Roberts in the Persian Gulf on April 14 during
which 10 sailors were injured.
</TEXT>
