<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Laundering,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ohio Plumber Indicted In Fraud Schemes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former plumber from Ohio was charged in a
federal indictment with money laundering and fraud after a company
he ran in Florida bounced a $500,000 check and failed to deliver a
promised $4 million loan, authorities say.
   Prosecutors contend Walter E. Johnson defrauded unsuspecting
business executives by claiming to control a $3 trillion gold
bullion hoard from World War II. The company, European Arabian
Trust Inc., was shut down by Florida banking authorities in 1986.
   Johnson, the firm's president, and four other people including
its former managing director, Stewart A. Koral, were named in a
federal indictment made public Wednesday.
   Johnson, a former plumber from Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio, and Koral
have said in newspaper interviews that they were entrusted in 1981
with an Indonesian admiral's $3 trillion fortune in gold bullion.
But they have not produced evidence that they actually have the
gold.
   According to the five-count indictment made public in U.S.
District Court here, Johnson, Koral and their co-defendants were
charged with conspiring to launder ``vast amounts of U.S. currency
derived from illicit activities.''
   The indictment described a complicated transaction in which
$100,000 provided by an undercover Internal Revenue Service agent
was transmitted to a Florida bank through a brokerage account in
New Hampshire without complying with U.S. currency transaction
reporting rules.
   The transaction was completed with the unwitting help of an
unidentified stockbroker at the Manchester, N.H., office of
Prudential-Bache Securities who was told that one of the
defendants, James J. Smith, was a CIA agent, according to the
indictment.
   The transaction was made through a Prudential-Bache account
purportedly set up to receive money from an Asian trust set up by
the Indonesian admiral, Seita Darma, the indictment charged.
   Johnson, Koral and two other defendants were also charged with
defrauding Systems Computer Technology Corp. out of $100,000 in
fees they charged to help the Malvern, Pa., company obtain a
subcontract for a fictitious Treasury Department project to create
a multinational currency to stabilize the world economy.
   The company, also known as SCT, paid the monthly retainer to
Kelgre Investment Group Inc., a Gaithersburg, Md. company headed by
Smith, the indictment said.
   SCT officials were led to believe that European Arabian had been
selected as a prime contractor for the fictitious top-secret
project that was aimed at disrupting the underground economy and
recapturing U.S. currency in foreign hands, according to the
indictment.
   Johnson is charged with telling the company it would be hired to
conduct a $1.1 million feasibility study. Johnson allegedly told
SCT that the subcontract award was being delayed while Treasury
Department officials tried to find a way to hide financing for the
secret project in the federal budget.
   The company was also told the project included an effort to help
Third World nations refinance their debt by bartering natural
resources for loans, the indictment says. Company officials were
told this phase of the contract was backed by the Seita Foundation,
according to the indictment.
   To lend credibility to the scheme, SCT officials were shown a
Jan. 14, 1986 letter to European Arabian about the project from
Carrye Elizabeth Maxwell, identified as a special consultant to the
Treasury Department.
   Maxwell, of Arlington, Va., was charged separately with bilking
two investors out of a total of $55,000 for applications for
multi-million loans she falsely represented were guaranteed by the
fictitious ``Project Recycle.'' She was also charged with
impersonating a Treasury Department official in other transactions.
   Also charged were Billy Hugh Blankenship of Gaithersburg Md.,
and Phillip Nicely of Great Falls, Va.
   Blankenship is charged with participating in both the SCT fraud
and money laundering schemes. Nicely, identified in court papers as
an associate of Kelgre Investment, is charged with participating in
the money-laundering conspiracy.
   The indictment follows a nearly two-year investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
