<2ND_LINE>BC-Aloha Transcript,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Aloha Pilots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of pertinent
communications between Aloha Airlines Flight 243 last April 28 as
the plane made an emergency landing at the Maui airport in Hawaii
after suffering an in-flight breakup. The exchanges are between the
co-pilot, Madeline ``Mimi'' Tompkins, and the controller at the
Maui airport tower:
   23:48:33 _ Flight 243: Maui tower, Aloha two forty three, we're
inbound for landing. ... We're just ah to the east of Makena, 10
(miles) east of Makena descending out of 13 (thousand feet) and we
have rapid decompression. Ah we are unpressurized declaring an
emergency.
   (A series of exchanges follow over confusion about the planes
flight number.)
   23:49:03 _ Tower: Aloha two-forty-three, say your position.
   23:49:05 _ Flight 243: We're just ah to the east of Makena Point
descending out of 11 thousand (feet). Request clearance into Maui
for landing. Request the equipment.
   23:49:16 _ Tower: Okay. The equipment is ... on the way.
   (The controller gives Flight 243 a transponder signal code so
that the plane may be fully identified on his radar screen. Further
confusion develops over the flight number because of poor radio
transmission quality.)
   23:49:58 _ Tower: two-forty-three, the equipment is on the roll.
Plan straight in runway two and I'll keep you advised on any wind
change.
   (The controller turns to other traffic and redirects one plane
to another runway so as not to interfere with Flight 243's landing.)
   23:52:11 _ Aloha two-forty-three, you still up (on the radio
frequency) ... Aloha two-forty-three, Maui. ... Aloha two -- (The
controller turns briefly to other traffic and resumes trying to
raise Flight 243.) Aloha two-forty, two-forty-three. If you hear,
ident.
   (Flight 243 then appears in a full data block on the
controller's radar screen, indicating that the pilot programmed his
transponder to the code given earlier.)
   23:53:40 _ Tower: Aloha two-forty-three. I hear you loud and
clear. Go ahead.
   23:53:42 _ Flight 243: Ah, we're gong to need assistance. We
cannot communicate with the flight attendants. Ah, will (there) be
assistance for passengers when we land?
   23:53:51 _ Tower: Okay. Understand you're going to need ah an
ambulance. Is that correct?
   23:53:55 _ Flight 243: Affirmative.
   (Controller turns to other traffic)
   23:54:39 _ Tower: Aloha two-forty-three, can you give me your
souls on board and your fuel on board?
   23:54:46 _ Flight 243: Eighty five, eighty six plus five crew
members.
   23:54:56 _ Tower: Roger, how many do you think are injured?
   23:54:58 _ Flight 243: We have no idea. We cannot communicate
with our flight attendants. (voice begins to show strain, but
control)
   23:55:00 _ Tower: Okay. We'll have ambulance on the way.
   23:55:05 _ Flight 243: (unintelligible) ah we won't have a nose
gear.
   23:56:00 _ Tower: Aloha two-forty-three, wind zero five-zero at
one-five. Equipment is in place.
   23:56:06 _ Flight 243: Okay. Be advised we have no nose gear. We
are landing without the nose gear.
   23:56:10 _ Tower: Okay. If you need assistance, keep me advised.
   23:56:14 _ Flight 243: We'll need all the equipment you got.
   (Controller provides wind information to two other planes.)
   23:58:11 _ Tower: Aloha two-forty-three, just for your
information the gear appears down. The gear appears down.
   (Seconds later Flight 243 touches down on the runway.)
   23:58:45 _ Tower: Aloha two-forty-three, just shut it down where
you are. Everything's fine. The gear _ the fire trucks are on the
way.
   (A Delta Airlines pilot asks the tower for the status of the
runway.)
   0001:41 _ Tower: Ah. I don't have an idea. It's shut down. We're
gonna close the airport now.
   0001:49 _ Delta pilot: Okay.
   End of Transcript.
