<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     05-12 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Says `No Deal' With Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-US-Noriega, Bjt
^By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega has made no deal with Washington about stepping
down and there will be none ``if U.S. aggression and violation of
Panamanian sovereignty continue.''
   The official news agency Panapress reported on Wednesday night
that President Reagan had ``entered in direct contact with Gen.
Noriega.''
   The report came shortly after an administration source in
Washington said the United States would drop drug charges against
Noriega if he agrees to step down as Defense Forces chief and leave
the country, at least temporarily.
   Boris Moreno, director of the government's National Information
System, or SNI, told The Associated Press he did not know if Reagan
had telephoned Noriega in an effort to find a way out of the crisis
between the two nations.
   Moreno also said he did not know if the offer to drop the
charges had been formally presented to the general.
   ``There has been no agreement about anything,'' said a statement
he read to the AP over the telephone. ``Upon being informed of the
existence of such reports, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega told SNI
categorically, `The sovereignty of Panama is not negotiable.'
   ``Such reports only come from sources interested in sidetracking
the conversations and in aggravating the existing situation. These
reports form part of the confusion and confrontation provoked by
certain elements of the Washington establishment.''
   Panapress said on Wednesday night: ``Gen. Noriega has said there
can be no deal if the U.S. aggression and the violation of
Panamanian sovereignty continue.''
   The source in Washington, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said that under the proposed deal Noriega would step down, probably
in August, and would stay out of Panama until after its next
presidential elections.
   The Reagan administration began imposing economic sanctions on
Panama 2{ months ago. Washington hoped the measures would force
Noriega into exile, but he has resisted and appears entrenched.
   The general, as chief of the 15,000-strong Defense Forces, is
the country's de facto ruler. Last summer, he was accused by his
former second-in-command of involvement in political assassination
and electoral fraud.
   On Feb. 5, Noriega was indicted on federal drug-smuggling and
money-laundering charges in Florida. He denies the charges,
contending they are part of an attempt to replace him with a leader
amenable to a strong U.S. presence in Panama into the next century.
   The 1977 Panama Canal Treaty obliges Washington to cede control
of the waterway and U.S. military bases along it by the year 2000.
   Panapress said Reagan ``sent a special mission to Panama to
dialogue with the leader of the Panamanian Defense Forces.''
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Terence Kneebone responded, ``no
comment,'' when asked if State Department envoy Michael Kozak, who
the Reagan administration has sent to Panama in recent weeks to
talk with Noriega, met in Panama on Wednesday with the general or
his representatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
