<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Contras     05-12 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Rebels Meet In Attempt To Resolve Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meeting with their leaders, more
than 4,000 Nicaraguan rebels sought to resolve a simmering dispute
over whether to continue peace talks with the leftist Sandinista
government.
   Also Wednesday, Nicaragua's vice president said at the United
Nations that the rift among the rebels threatened the peace
negotiations.
   Rebel sources said the U.S.-backed fighters, also known as
Contras, met with their civilian and military leaders at the jungle
town of Yamales, 185 miles southeast of Tegucigalpa and six miles
from the Nicaraguan border.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
dissident rebels accuse Contra military commander Enrique Bermudez
of corruption and inefficiency and want him replaced. Unlike the
civilian Contra leaders, Bermudez reportedly opposes forging a
lasting peace with the Sandinistas.
   Bermudez said in a telephone interview there was only
``minimal'' opposition to his command from ``a group of parasites''
within rebel ranks, whom he did not identify.
   Bermudez, 46, was Nicaragua's representative to the
Inter-American Defense Board in Washington, D.C., under President
Anastasio Somoza, the rightist dictator overthrown by the
Sandinistas in 1979.
   He is said to command a total of 8,000 rebels.
   Three civilian leaders of the Nicaraguan Resistance _ Pedro
Joaquin Chamorro, Azucena Ferrey and Bosco Matamoros _ were at the
jungle meeting, the sources said.
   Also present were eight dissident Contra military leaders who on
Sunday publicly accused Bermudez of opposing negotiations for a
more permanent truce with the Sandinistas, the sources said.
   Nicaragua's vice president, Sergio Ramirez Mercado, said on
Wednesday at the United Nations in New York that his government was
not sure if rebel fighters would honor any agreement reached by
their political leaders.
   Ramirez said the ``open rebellion'' against Bermudez
``represents a serious limitation'' to the talks.
   ``We don't know now if what the political leadership of the
Contras is going to discuss with us in the next round of
negotiations is going to be accepted by this military leadership
under the command of Col. Bermudez,'' Ramirez said. He spoke at a
news conference before the opening of a special U.N. session on
economic aid to Central America.
   Bermudez hinted he might use force to bring the dissidents back
into line but expressed hope that he and Adolfo Calero, the top
Contra civilian leader, will find a solution to the problem.
   ``I am sure that once the fighters understand the reality of the
situation, they will change their attitude,'' he said in the
telephone interview.
   On March 23, Sandinista and Contra leaders signed a preliminary
accord aimed at ending the 6{-year-old civil war. A 60-day truce
went into effect April 1, during which the two sides were supposed
to negotiate conditions for a lasting peace.
   Two rounds of high-level negotiations in Managua since have
failed to produce substantial progress. Foremost among issues
dividing the two sides is a Sandinista demand that the Contras lay
down their weapons.
   The date for the next round of talks has not been set.
</TEXT>
