<DOCNO> AP880512-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AleutsCompensation Bjt   05-12 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aleuts Compensation, Bjt,0775</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aleut Compensation Bill May Be `Too Little, Too Late'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNALASKA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Harriet Hope, years of congressional
wrangling over whether to compensate natives of the Aleutian
Islands who were forced into camps during World War II have taken
their toll.
   ``It's just too little, too late,'' she said. ``The old ones who
deserve it the most are gone.''
   Hope and her family were among 110 Aleuts from Unalaska Island
villages ordered from their homes in July 1942 after the Japanese
bombed and strafed the island's Dutch Harbor. They were herded
aboard a steamship that took them to a camp in southeast Alaska,
purportedly to protect them from harm.
   They were not alone. An estimated 880 Aleuts were evacuated from
the Aleutians. Many houses later were ransacked or destroyed by
soldiers and sailors. Photographs, diaries, icons and other
possessions left behind were damaged or stolen, residents say.
   About 10 percent of the Aleuts died in the camps. Some never
went home. It has been estimated that half the camps' survivors
have since died.
   The Japanese seized three of the western Aleutians _ Attu,
Agattu and Kiska _ and occupied them between 1942 and 1943.
   In Washington, conference committee staff members were scheduled
to meet today to work out differences in House and Senate versions
of a measure authorizing reparations to Japanese-Americans and
Aleuts forced from their homes in the opening months of the war.
   The Senate bill, considered likely to be adopted, would pay the
Aleut camp survivors $12,000 each, set up a $5 million trust fund
for the six villages where people were forced from their homes,
authorize $1.4 million to restore and rehabilitate churches damaged
or destroyed in the war and pay the Aleuts between $12 million and
$15 million for the loss of Attu Island, which has remained under
military control.
   Japanese-Americans forced into camps would receive $20,000 each,
and virtually nothing else.
   John C. Kirtland, a Washington lawyer hired in 1978 to represent
the Aleuts before Congress, thinks the legislation, re-introduced
each year since 1983, will make it to the president this year.
   Hope was 5 years old when the Japanese planes arrived. Her
father was English, her mother, Aleut. Her father, the village
postmaster, was allowed to remain behind because of his nationality.
   ``We had 48 hours to get ready. We were told to take nothing but
a very, very few belongings,'' she recalled.
   Hope, her mother, two brothers and a sister joined other Aleuts
from the island's three villages for the voyage. Eventually they
were deposited at a burned-out cannery at Burnett Inlet on the
Alaska Panhandle.
   ``It was nothing but a ghost gown. There was no plumbing, no
heat, just an abandoned old cannery. There was no running water.
You could see through the ceiling.''
   Medical facilities were virtually non-existent. Tuberculosis was
a threat. Village hunters and fishermen used to the treeless
mountains of Unalaska were thrown into a strange environment.
   ``It was like trying to live a subsistence lifestyle in a
foreign country,'' Hope said.
   For the three years the family was held at the camp, Hope's
father was allowed only one 10-day visit, Hope said. Her mother
worked at canneries to earn money, and provided medical care to
camp residents. Her brother left to work on a fishing boat.
   ``I just don't understand why they did what they did,'' Hope
said.
   The Aleut Corp., a regional native corporation, and the
Aleutian-Pribilof Islands Association led the drive for Aleut
reparations.
   Kirtland's firm searched archives and put together reams of
evidence about camp conditions and the wrongs committed during and
after the evacuation.
   At about the same time, a nine-member federal Commission On
Wartime Relocation and Internment of Civilians was appointed by the
president and congressional leaders. ``Nine volumes of documentary
evidence were given to commission,'' Kirtland said.
   The panel held hearings around Alaska, and recommended
compensation for the Aleuts in June 1983.
   Just as the compensation is pending, the scars of war remain on
Unalaska.
   Trench lines cut the mountains. Bunkers, pillboxes and
machine-gun nests dot the landscape. The past is never far away.
   Hope works as a receptionist at Unalaska City Hall, near the
house where she was born.
   ``I don't feel like I deserve anything; it's my mother and
father _ they went through the anguish. They're the ones who really
deserve it.''
   Her father died in 1956; her mother, 10 years later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeefFat     05-12 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beef Fat,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Beef Fat Not As Bad As Experts Once Believed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beef, which for years has been cast as the villain
in the fight against heart disease, may not be so bad after all,
say researchers who found that a major form of saturated fat lowers
cholesterol.
   While too much fatty beef such as hamburger and prime rib will
clearly raise cholesterol levels, most people can eat moderate
helpings of lean meat without fear, the researchers said.
   The researchers cautioned that only men were enrolled in the
study, so the findings might not apply to women.
   But other experts said the study of 11 men is too small and
preliminary to reach a conclusion. All 11 were healthy volunteers,
ranging from their late 50s to early 70s.
   Beef got a bad name because it is high in saturated fat. Until
now, it was assumed that all saturated fats endangered the heart by
increasing cholesterol, which clogs arteries.
   The study, published in today's New England Journal of Medicine,
suggests that the situation may be more complicated. Beef contains
two major forms of saturated fat, and the researchers found that
one raises cholesterol while the other lowers it.
   This means that meat is probably not as bad as health experts
have long believed, said Dr. Scott Grundy, the study's senior
author and a researcher at the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center at Dallas.
   Grundy, who also is a past chairman of the American Heart
Association's Nutrition Committee, said people should still follow
the widely adopted dietary guidelines for avoiding all kinds of
fat, including saturated fat. But he believes beef can be a regular
part of a sensible diet, as long people eat small portions of about
3 ounces and stick to lean cuts, especially select-grade meat.
   ``You don't really have to cut meat out of the diet in order to
keep a low cholesterol (level),'' he said in an interview
Wednesday. ``That's an important message, because beef is rich in
protein and iron.''
   Fats from plants and animals differ in their proportions of
various fatty acids. Safflower oil, for instance, is high in oleic
acid, which lowers the body's cholesterol levels, while palm oil
contains high levels of palmitic acid, which raises cholesterol.
   Beef fat is high in both palmitic acid and stearic acid. Both
are saturated fatty acids. Unlike polyunsaturated fats such as corn
oil, they are solid when cool.
   In the study, the volunteers drank three liquid formula diets
for three weeks each. They were high in palmitic acid, stearic acid
or oleic acid.
   The researchers found that the volunteers' blood cholesterol
levels dropped 14 percent while they consumed stearic acid and 10
percent while on oleic acid, compared to when they used the
high-palmitic acid diet.
   Today's report was accompanied by an editorial by Drs. Irwin H.
Rosenberg and Ernst J. Schaefer of the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Human Nutrition Research Center on Aging at Tufts
University in Boston.
   They wrote that the study ``demonstrates convincingly'' that
stearic acid lowers cholesterol. However, they added, people should
still try to hold down fat consumption, and ``this study should not
change our chief dietary message to the American public.''
   Dr. John C. LaRosa of George Washington University, chairman of
the heart association's Nutrition Committee, agreed. ``It's a nice
little piece of work,'' La Rosa said, ``but it's not the basis for
dietary recommendations.''
   Guidelines adopted by the association and other groups urge
people to limit total fat intake to about 30 percent of total
calories. Saturated fat should be less than 10 percent of the day's
calories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
