<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-12 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Steel Industry Will Benefit from Canada Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter has
told several steel-state senators the American steel industry will
be a clear winner under the proposed U.S.-Canada free trade
agreement.
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that the U.S. steel industry will
be a net beneficiary of this agreement _ no doubt,'' Yeutter said
Wednesday during a joint meeting of the Senate Steel Caucus and the
Senate Judiciary antitrust subcommittee.
   Yeutter said American steelmakers will benefit from the gradual
elimination of the two nations' tariffs because Canadian tariffs on
imported steel are about double the U.S. average.
   And he said they will also gain from the increased economic
activity the free trade agreement, or FTA, is expected to stimulate
between the two countries.
   ``To the degree that we have an expansion of economic activity
and demand, the steel industry wins generally in both countries,''
Yeutter said. ``In the absence of an FTA, that isn't going to
happen.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Film Industry Wants More Controls on Cable TV `Monopoly'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Motion Picture
Association of America says cable television ``is no longer a babe
in swaddling clothes'' and Congress should rein in the industry's
power to control the entertainment marketplace.
   ``Consumers are held hostage to their cable system,'' MPAA
President Jack Valenti told a House subcommittee on Wednesday.
``They have no alternative. They can either commit suicide or go
bowling.''
   Valenti's testimony was part of a lively day of exchanges before
the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on telecommunications,
which is looking into the effects of cable deregulation.
   Valenti, who represents the major Hollywood studios and
independent producers, sparred with Ted Turner, president of Turner
Broadcasting System, and John Malone, president of
Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest cable company.
   ``Before cable, we had the three big networks and they dominated
what people saw. Now there are the three networks and more than 50
cable channels,'' said Malone.
