<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs Nurse's Statue at Viet Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee wants a second statue added
to the Vietnam Veterans Memorial and a supporter insists, ``This
will be the last one.''
   The Senate Energy and Resources Committee on Wednesday passed,
over one senator's objection, a bill that would place a statue of
an Army nurse at the memorial
   The lone dissenter, Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., protested what
he called a threat to the artistic integrity of the memorial. A
statue of three soldiers was added in 1984 by veterans groups who
objected to the starkness of the granite wall, unveiled in 1982,
that lists the names of American war dead.
   The bill, which has 63 cosponsors, contained an amendment that
strengthens a declaration that Congress would not allow any other
statues to be placed at the memorial if the bronze sculpture of an
Army women's sculpture is approved.
   ``This will be the last one,'' said Sen. Bennett Johnston,
D-La., the committee chairman. ``But the last for how long?''
retorted Evans, who stressed that his opposition had nothing to do
with his respect for American women.

