<HEAD>GOP Begins Attacks on Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican National Committee has issued a
booklet on the Democratic presidential candidates that calls
Michael Dukakis ``the biggest spending governor in America'' and
says Jesse Jackson ``has a tendency to confuse public policy with
publicity.''
   The 20-page campaign salvo also attacks House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, alongside its criticism of the front-runner
Dukakis and Jackson.
   A section titled, ``The Dukakis Threat,'' accused the
Massachusetts governor of ``hypocrisy on the balanced budget,''
citing critical media comments about his role in his state's
booming economy.
   Jackson, meanwhile, is taken to task for a trip to Cuba and
another to the Middle East in 1979 to meet with Palestine
Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat.
   The section on Wright quoted media accounts of the House
speaker's actions on behalf of a troubled Texas bank, his dealings
with Nicaraguan leader Daniel Ortega, and Republican accusations of
abuse of power in House debates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study: Poor, Minorities Disenfranchised By Voting Barriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private study says discriminatory voter
registration procedures are disenfranchising the poor, minority and
disabled citizens throughout the country.
   Among the practices are arbitrary registration hours,
inconvenient registration locations, ``mysterious purging of voters
without notice, denial of registration before an election,'' said a
statement from Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who is the author of
legislation to correct such practices.
   The Citizens Commission on Civil Rights in hearings in New York,
Atlanta and Phoenix in 1984 and 1985 ``documented numerous examples
of discriminatory practices,'' the group said on Wednesday.
   Among the specific problems are refusal by local officials to
designate sites in black communities for mobile registration units;
requirement of excessive identification from black applicants;
``undue scrutiny'' of Hispanics and Asian-Americans to determine
their citizenship; sites ``that require extraordinarily long
trips'' and dual registration requirements for tribal and state
elections for Native Americans.
   The commission recommended legislation to permit registration by
mail, election-day registration, and a congressional investigation
into denial of the right to vote for homeless people.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nixon: Don't Invite Me to Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Nixon, aware that his
appearance would spark controversy, has told Republican Party
officials not to invite him to address the party's national
convention in August, a party source says.
   In a letter to Republican Party chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf
Jr., Nixon said he would be writing a column for the London Sunday
Times and so is avoiding any political activity this year.
   The party source, who insisted on anonymity, said there was
sentiment among party officials to invite Nixon to address the New
Orleans convention.
   But Nixon, who was driven from office by the Watergate scandal,
was aware that his appearance would be controversial, said the
source. The former president has not appeared at a Republican
National Convention since he left office.
