<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShipyardAccident     05-12 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shipyard Accident,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Injured In Shipyard Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-ton propeller shaft fell on a group of
shipyard workers as they worked on a Navy destroyer, injuring nine,
including two seriously, officials said.
   Six workers were killed in an accident at the yard last July.
   Wednesday night's accident occurred as workers were installing
the intermediate propeller shaft into the USS Elliot, said Fred
Hallett, vice president of finance at the National Steel &
Shipbuilding Co.
   ``They were in the process of aligning the shaft when the
forward part fell approximately 20 to 25 feet to the deck of the
drydock,'' Hallett said.
   When the shaft fell, it dislodged scaffolding that had been
erected below, Hallett said.
   One worker told Hallett the crew was preparing to drive in the
bolts when the propeller shaft released and fell, Hallett said.
   The most seriously hurt employee received injuries to his head
and arm, Hallett said. The man, who was not identified, was listed
in critical condition at University of California-San Diego Medical
Center.
   One was listed in serious condition, three others in fair
condition, two were released after treatment and two were not
expected to be hospitalized, officials said.
   In the accident July 10, six people were killed and six injured
when a steel basket lifting workers fell 30 feet to the deck of a
Navy ship.
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration cited
the company for 19 safety violations in that accident.
   In March, OSHA accused the company of 100 other violations,
which carried $72,300 in penalties. The company is appealing the
penalties.
   Hallett said 80 percent of the OSHA recommendations were
completed and the rest were in progress.
   The shipyard employs 2,500 workers, Hallett said. Between 150
and 200 were on duty at the time of Wednesday's accident.
</TEXT>
