<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ A Reagan administration source on Wednesday said
the White House offered to drop U.S. drug charges against Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega if he steps down as Panama's military leader
and leaves the country temporarily. U.S. economic sanctions imposed
since Noriega's February indictment have paralyzed Panama's economy
but failed to force Noriega into exile.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ The government said Noriega has made no
deal with Washington about stepping down and there will be none
``if U.S. aggression and violation of Panamanian sovereignty
continue.'' The official news agency Panapress on Wednesday night
said without elaboration that President Reagan had ``entered in
direct contact with Gen. Noriega.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ More than 4,000 Nicaraguan rebels met on
Wednesday with their leaders to try to resolve a dispute over
whether to continue peace talks with the leftist Sandinista
government. Rebels sources said dissidents want to replace military
commander Enrique Bermudez, who reportedly opposes forging a
lasting peace with the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GUATEMALA CITY _ Troops on Wednesday foiled a rebellion against
President Vinicio Cerezo's civilian government and arrested two
army officers who were halted leading soldiers toward the capital,
the defense minister said. The government gave no details and did
not say how many soldiers were involved, what kind of arms they
used or if there was any violence.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ A leftist guerrilla attack on a
hydroelectric dam north of the capital on Wednesday killed 16
soldiers and caused a nationwide power shortage. In San Salvador, a
Soviet journalist was apparently abducted from his hotel and a
military judge fatally shot outside his home.
</TEXT>
