<1ST_LINE>r p PM-People-OlympiaDukakis     05-12 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Olympia Dukakis,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Running As Delegate For Cousin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympia Dukakis says the cry of ``Go Michael!''
she yelled for her cousin, the presidential candidate, at the end
of her Oscar acceptance speech is reverberating around her home
state of New Jersey.
   The actress who won the supporting actress Oscar this year for
``Moonstruck'' is running in that state's presidential primary as a
delegate for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   ``Remember when I said, `Go Michael!'' at the Oscars? Well, now,
wherever I go, people take up the chant,'' she said in an interview
published in today's Daily News. ``It's become the rallying cry of
the campaign.''
   Ms. Dukakis admits that the world of politics is ``all new to
me,'' but she said she is taking the race seriously and is ``boning
up on Michael's position papers.''
   But on June 7, when New Jersey holds its primary, Ms. Dukakis
will be flying to Vancouver to begin filming ``Daddy's Home'' with
John Travolta.
</TEXT>
