<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkylabReunion     05-12 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Skylab Reunion,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skylab Astronaut Says Russians Have Passed America In Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scientist in the Skylab program of the
early 1970s says the ``plodding'' Soviets have since surpassed the
Americans in manned space missions.
   ``All our accomplishments of 15 years ago should be buried in
the dust by now. Unfortunately, there is some dust on them, but it
is not American dust,'' ex-astronaut Edward Gibson said Wednesday
at a reunion with eight other former Skylab crew members.
   ``The Russians are the people who have continuously manned space
stations up there. They are the turtles of the space race. They
kept plodding along.''
   The three Skylab flights, from May 1973 to February 1974, took
almost 183,000 pictures of the sun and more than 40,000 of the
earth.
   ``We learned a lot about solar physics, how the sun works,''
said Gibson, now a space consultant at Reston, Va. ``It is the
largest contribution ever made in that area.
   ``In earth observations, it led into what we currently are doing
_ better monitoring and understanding of our environment and how to
control part of it to some degree.
   ``Also, we learned a lot of the physiological aspects of man
going into space _ important information for future flights and
also for spinoffs for medicine on earth.''
   The United States could regain the lead in space technology,
Gibson said, if the government and nation understand what is
needed, establish long-range goals and make financial commitments
to match them.
   ``We need to find the best way to draw in all the good talent
that exists in our country and a way to retain them in the work
force for many years,'' he said. ``We need to streamline the
organization _ the whole military and NASA infrastructure _ in the
way in which we manage the combined effort, as well as in the
individual agencies themselves and the programs.
   ``There is enthusiasm, capability and knowledge ready to put us
out ahead again, not only for competitive reasons but for practical
benefits and human reasons.''
   At one of the reunion sessions, Jim Odom, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's associate administrator for
its proposed space station, noted that America has been without a
permanent manned orbiting facility for almost 10 years.
   Important research could have been accomplished during that
time, Odom said.
   ``Unlike Skylab, the space station will lend itself to ongoing
modifications,'' he said. ``We will be able to tailor it to meet
the changing requirements of experimenters over its projected
30-year lifespan.''
   Odom said that some parts of the Apollo program ``were scrapped
in the wake of the Apollo 1 fire,'' in which three astronauts died
on the launch pad.
   He added, ``It would be tragic if this should happen again as a
result of the Challenger accident,'' which killed seven astronauts
in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
