<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-12 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Europe, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar gained ground on all other major
currencies in light European trading early today. Gold bullion
prices drifted lower.
   The closure of most European markets for the Ascension Day
holiday brought activity to a near standstill, traders said.
British and Italian markets were the only major centers operating
today.
   The dollar's higher rate reflected gains in New York late
Wednesday after major U.S. banks raised their prime lending rate
from 8.5 percent to 9 percent.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.6839 West German marks, up from 1.6773
   _1.4015 Swiss francs, up from 1.3935
   _5.7100 French francs, up from 5.6912
   _1.8870 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8830
   _1,251.80 Italian lire, up from 1,249.50
   _1.2320 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2315
   The British pound fell to $1.8778 from $1.8870.
   The dollar firmed to 124.39 Japanese yen in Tokyo, up from
Wednesday's close of 124.24 yen. In later London trading today, the
dollar was quoted at 124.70 yen.
   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $448.65 a troy ounce, down from $449.30 late
Wednesday.
   Zurich markets were closed for Ascension Day.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $450.06, down
from $451.68.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.52 a troy ounce,
down from $6.55.
</TEXT>
