<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0635EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Arrests     05-12 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Arrests,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Suspects May Have Been Involved In Past ANC Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four whites charged with
possession of an impressive arms cache may have been involved in
previous attacks carried out by the African National Congress, a
newspaper reported today.
   Police announced on Wednesday they had made their biggest arms
seizure ever in connection with the arrests of three men and one
woman who allegedly were acting on behalf of the ANC's military
wing.
   The four suspects also had a ``hit-list'' of top police
officials, according to police.
   Arms seized included a Soviet-made SAM-7 ground-to-air missile,
limpet mines, hand grenades, assault rifles, pistols, machine guns,
mortars and explosives, police said.
   They said the four had planned to use the missile to shoot down
a police helicopter at a recent fair.
   Police have not released the suspects' names, but have said the
three men are South African citizens and the woman is a foreigner.
The four are college educated and in their 20s and 30s, police
said, adding that two are military draft dodgers and one is a
former journalist.
   The Citizen, a pro-government daily, said without citing sources
that at least one of the four was believed involved in ANC attacks
carried out in the early 1980s.
   The mostly black ANC was outlawed in South Africa in 1960 and
began a sabotage-and-bombing campaign the following year aimed at
toppling white-minority rule.
   Tom Lodge, a leading authority on the ANC and a lecturer at the
University of the Witwatersrand, said the arrests illustrate ``the
continuing trend of young, well-educated liberal and left-wing
whites (to) identify themselves with the ANC.''
   Lodge said white participation in the ANC's military wing
``obviously has a greater impact on the attitudes of white South
Africa than the involvement of blacks.''
   Few whites have been involved in the ANC's military operations,
although there have been several highly publicized cases in recent
years.
   Following a March 17 car bombing that killed three people,
police said the leading suspect was Heinrich Grosskopf, a white
South African and an alleged ANC member who remains at large.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok described the four suspects
as ``a highly specialized terror unit.'' He alleged that the
suspects had been trained in Moscow, Cuba and Angola, and had radio
transmitters which they used to communicate with ANC headquarters
in Lusaka, Zambia.
   He said they were captured Sunday at a farmhouse near Pretoria,
where they had been staying since early this year.
   The South African Press Association, citing unidentified police
sources, said a disenchanted ANC member apparently gave authorities
the tip that led them to the four suspects.
   Vlok said police still were investigating how the weapons were
brought into South Africa, but he said the arms came overland
through Zambia and Botswana.
   Police have announced numerous arrests of alleged ANC members in
recent months and say they have substantially weakened the group's
ability to operate inside South Africa.
   There have been more than 70 bombings in South Africa since a
nationwide state of emergency was imposed in June 1986, but the
frequency has fallen sharply in recent months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
