<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Afghan     05-12 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghan,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper: Weapons Supplies Stepped Up To Guerrillas On Eve Of Soviet
Pullout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Najib in last graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military charged today that foreign sponsors
have stepped up weapons shipments to Afghan guerrillas and sent in
more military advisors, endangering Soviet troops who are about to
march out of Afghanistan.
   The Defense Ministry newspaper Red Star reported in a front-page
dispatch from its military correspondents at Soviet headquarters in
Kabul that there is great anxiety about the withdrawal that begins
Sunday.
   ``They are facing 1,500 kilometers (940 miles) of mountainous,
war-torn roads,'' the newspaper said of Soviet soldiers who will be
among the first to pull out of the Soviet Union's southern
neighbor. ``And we know very well that roads in Afghanistan are on
the forward edge of the undeclared war. It is necessary to be
prepared for the possibility of armed provocations.''
   The newspaper said rebel activity had been stepped up in Kabul,
Kandahar, Ghazni, Paktia and other provinces.
   ``Taking advantage of the pullback of Soviet and Afghan troops
from border areas of those regions in the depth of the country, the
opposition and its foreign patrons have sharply increased the
number of caravans with weapons, delivering them _ not only at
night now but also in the daytime,'' the paper claimed.
   ``In the military formations there has been a noticeable growth
in the number of foreign military advisers, who organize joint
actions by groups from different Moslem parties,'' the newspaper
said.
   The United States has been the insurgents' chief arms supplier.
   Red Star said the preparations for withdrawal were nearly
complete at the Kabul headquarters of the ``limited military
contingent,'' as the 115,000 Soviet soldiers in Afghanistan are
referred to in the state-run press.
   The dispatch did not make clear, however, how many would leave
in the first march north or when headquarters would be evacuated.
   It said the first troops to leave would be motorized rifle
regiments, paratroopers, scouts and pilots, but gave no other
details.
   Afghanistan has been in the throes of civil war since April
1978, when a Soviet-inspired revolution brought a Marxist
government to power.
   Soviet soldiers intervened in December 1979 to install Babrak
Karmal as the Afghan leader and to help troops loyal to him put
down a widespread insurrection. Karmal was replaced by Najib in May
1986 and has since taken refuge in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
