<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Climbs Slightly Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar climbed marginally today against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo, while stock prices also posted a slight gain
after falling sharply in early trading.
   The dollar ended at 124.39 yen, up 0.15 yen from its finish on
Wednesday. After opening the day at 124.35, the dollar moved
little, remaining between the 124.35 and 124.46 yen.
   ``The market was motionless throughout the day,'' said an
exchange dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Trading was quiet lacking incentives to direct the market, he
said, adding the impact on Wednesday's half-percentage point
increase in the prime lending rate of large American banks, which
boosted the dollar in U.S. trading, tapered off quite early.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost a big 251.20 points Wednesday, gained
back 51.53 points, or 0.18 percent, closing the day at 27,212.58.
   The Nikkei index, the main market barometer, lost as much as
194.95 points in the first 15 minutes of trading, dropping below
the 27,000-level for the first time since April 22. The fall,
prompted by the overnight plunge on Wall Street caused by prime
rate hikes and concern over inflation, turned investors to hunt for
bargains, traders said.
   ``There are several factors, such as the result of the upcoming
30-year bond sale in the quarterly U.S. Treasury refunding, and
U.S. trade figures for March, which investors are keeping eyes on
in making major moves,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities.
   The overall buying mood was strong, however, and unless
something really surprising happens, the market will maintain its
bullish trend, he said.
   Popular issues included shipbuildings and machineries.
Chemicals, non-ferrous metals, textiles and rubbers also gained
ground. Lower issues were steels and electricals.
   Volume of the first-section trade stood at an esimated 900
million shares, against 1.1 billion shares changed hands on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
