<HEAD>Associated Press Barred From Covering Afghan Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Afghan
^Eds: One name for Najib is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry has informed The Associated
Press that its correspondents have been barred from traveling to
Afghanistan to cover the scheduled withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   Foreign Ministry officials said on Wednesday the Afghan
government had objected to a question posed by an AP correspondent
during a recent news conference held by Afghan leader Najib in
Kabul.
   Yevgeny B. Isayenko, a ministry press official, said Afghan
authorities would refuse a visa to any AP correspondent, several of
whom had applied to cover the withdrawal scheduled to begin Sunday.
   Michael Putzel, AP chief of bureau in Moscow, had been given
oral assurances Tuesday that an Associated Press reporter and
photographer would be given seats on the official plane carrying
correspondents to Kabul.
   The Afghan government generally permits news coverage by Western
journalists only when they are invited as members of an officially
sanctioned press tour.
   Isayenko said that, during a news conference in Kabul last
month, Carol J. Williams, a veteran AP Moscow correspondent, asked
a question that ``was very insulting'' to Najib.
   Ms. Williams asked Najib whether, if rebel forces in Afghanistan
emerge victorious after the Soviet pullout, he would seek refuge in
the Soviet Union. The pro-Soviet Afghan leader replied he would
never allow such a victory.
   He did not object to the question at the time.
   Isayenko said refusal to grant visas was ``the sovereign right
of the Afghan Embassy in Moscow.''
   Andrei Silantiev, a Foreign Ministry official who serves as
government liaison with foreign news agencies, said the British
news agency Reuters would file pool reports to the AP and other
Western news services.
</TEXT>
