<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardDemonstration     05-12 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Demonstration,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students End Occupation At Harvard Law School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard Law School will renew its
commitment to a diversified faculty under an agreement reached
between the dean and about 50 students, most of them black, who
staged an overnight ``study-in'' at his office.
   ``We feel we were very successful over the last 24 hours,'' said
Robert Wilkins, a second-year law student who is president of the
Black Law School Association, which staged the protest. ``This is a
great step forward.''
   But Dean James Vorenberg said Wednesday the administration had
only agreed ``to look into'' seven of the students' 12 demands.
   ``I don't think there's any major commitments on either side,''
he said. ``It's more of a sharing of understanding how issues
look.''
   However, Vorenberg said, a policy statement on diversity first
issued in 1982 would be ``updated and reissued'' and an effort to
interest minority students in teaching would be made.
   The students camped out at Vorenberg's office Tuesday night in
their protest for more black professors and for Vorenberg, who is
retiring, to be replaced by a tenured black professor.
   After a meeting Wednesday, the dean ``specifically agreed to
going ahead with commitments on seven'' demands, Wilkins said.
   He said the demands included establishing a fellowship to entice
black professors to teach at Harvard; issuing a policy statement
expressing a commitment to diversity as part of the school's hiring
policy; and allowing students a broader role in the hiring of
minority faculty.
   The students also failed to bring about a commitment to
``diversify the curriculum to reflect the experience of people of
color'' and a request that a black assistant professor receive
tenure.
   Harvard Law School has 61 tenured positions, two of them held by
blacks. There are three black assistant professors and no black
women on the staff.
</TEXT>
