<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Owner Of Car That Exploded Near Israeli Embassy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with owner in court, additional
details. EDITS to conform, tighten. No pickup.
^By ALEX EFTY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today ordered a young Lebanese
held in custody for eight days after police said he was the owner
of a dynamite-packed car that blew up near the Israeli Embassy and
killed three people.
   The car exploded Wednesday about 200 yards from the embassy
after police prevented it from parking outside the building and the
car sped off.
   Police said they suspected the owner, Omar Ahmad Hawillo, 28, of
being involved in the bungled attack, which killed the driver and
two bystanders.
   Police said the car was rigged with 300 pounds of dynamite, and
Interior Minister Christodoulos Veniamin said the embassy was the
intended target.
   Witnesses reported seeing Hawillo running from the scene, police
said, adding that there was also evidence linking him to a
remote-control detonating device found nearby.
   There was speculation that the attempt to blow up the embassy
was to avenge the assassination of Khalil Wazir, the PLO's military
chief.
   But the Palestine Liberation Organization's office in Nicosia
issued a statement denying involvement.
   Five of the 15 people hurt in the fiery blast remained
hospitalized today and were listed in serious but stable condition
with burns and cuts.
   Hawillo, who arrived from Lebanon on March 21, was brought to
court under heavy security. With the hand that wasn't handcuffed,
he covered his face so it could not be photographed.
   Detective Takis Komodikis said Hawillo was arrested four hours
after the explosion. Police earlier reported he was picked up
shortly after the blast.
   The judge remanded the suspect to police custody for eight days,
pending the investigation's completion.
   A detective who spoke on condition of anonymity said Hawillo had
admitted to owning the car but denied any involvement in the
attempt to bomb the embassy, claiming he had lent the vehicle to a
friend.
   Komodikis told the court that the driver, who was blown to
pieces, had not been identified yet.
   A police statement said the driver had tried to park outside the
Israeli Embassy building twice before the blast, but was told to
move on by police. When asked for his identification, he sped away
and rammed another car at an intersection.
   Adamos Markides, one of the injured Cypriots, said he saw the
car coming out of a side street near the embassy. ``He was driving
so fast he didn't even stop at the traffic lights and hit another
car,'' Markides said.
   He said his was the second car behind the one that exploded.
``Suddenly there was this flash and boom with a black cloud of
smoke enveloping everything and a terrible heat. I staggered out of
my car with my face and arms on fire.''
   An anonymous caller telephoned a Mideast bureau of the American
television network NBC to claim responsibility for the explosion in
the name of the Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal. Abu Nidal, whose
real name is Sabri Banna, has been blamed for a series of terrorist
attacks around the world.
   Wazir, the PLO's deputy commander, was killed April 16 in Tunis.
Israeli sources have said he was killed by an Israeli squad of
agents. Palestinian groups have pledged to avenge the his death.
   Police said the two Cypriots killed in the blast were a woman
who was trapped in her burning car and a pedestrian, Andreas
Frangos, a retired diplomat. The woman was not identified.
</TEXT>
