<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Spill,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poisonous Spill Kills Truck Driver, Hundreds Evacuated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army helicopters rescued hundreds of civilians
today from the reach of poisonous fumes after a tractor-trailer
carrying bromine overturned in southern Israel, killing the driver,
police said.
   Nine people were treated at hospitals for burns and breathing
difficulties after the accident on a main highway about 65 miles
south of Jerusalem, said Amos Dahari, a spokesman for southern
Israel's Negev district police.
   The driver, who was not identified, was pulled out of the cabin
dead after police and soldiers struggled for seven hours to reach
him, he said.
   Police closed a 72-mile stretch of road as clouds of the orange
smoke billowed above the spill, witnesses said.
   Bromine is a poisonous, reddish-brown chemical used in making
dyes and photographic solutions.
   ``There was a huge orange cloud of chemicals in the sky,'' one
of the injured, taxi driver Shlomo Azulai, told Army radio.
   Azulai said he tried to pull the driver from the truck for about
45 minutes before being overcome by the gas and flown by helicopter
to Soroka Hospital in nearby Beersheba.
   Rescue workers also evacuated hundreds of civilians from three
settlements, a school, and bedouin Arab encampments, Dahari said.
   Workers also sprayed the road with a solution of ammonia to
neutralize the corrosive liquid, he added.
   Dahari said it was unclear what caused the early morning
accident just south of the Dead Sea and near the Jordanian border.
</TEXT>
