<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfRdp     05-12 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says It Raided Ships Off Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said today its warplanes raided two
ships off Iran during the night, bringing to eight the number of
attacks on commercial shipping in the Persian Gulf it claimed in
two weeks.
   Only one of the reported attacks has been confirmed by the
London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which monitors
maritime traffic around the world.
   Gulf-based shipping executives had no local independent
information for any of the attacks since April 29. Such attacks
normally would precipitate an Iranian retaliatory blow in the
so-called tanker war, an offshoot of the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   Lloyd's said the Iraqis fired two French-made Exocet missiles at
an Iranian tanker on Tuesday, causing considerable fire damage to
the vessel.
   The vessel, whose name was not known according to Lloyd's, was
owned by the National Iranian Oil Tanker Co. and was sailing from
Iran's key oil loading terminal at Kharg en route to the Larak
terminal in the southern gulf.
   The attack took place about 40 miles off the northern Iranian
coast, according to the Lloyd's report.
   The Baghdad high command on Wednesday reported the sixth attack
and today, the seventh and eighth attacks in two weeks on ``large
maritime targets'' off Iran. The term usually means a tanker
sailing to or from Kharg.
   Kharg accounts for 90 percent of Iranian oil exports and Baghdad
has vowed to block the Iranian oil flow as long as the Tehran
rulers refuse to accept a negotiated end to their war.
   Ship attacks claimed by Iraq often are not confirmed until some
time later because they occur inside the maritime war zone. Some
ships maintain radio silence to avoid being targeted again. Some of
the raids are never confirmed.
   The Lloyd's report would be the first confirmed ship attack in
the gulf since the U.S. Navy was empowered to defend any vessel
attacked by either belligerent outside exclusion zones off enemy
coastlines, if a U.S. warship happened to be in the area at the
time of the attack.
   Iran retaliates for the Iraqi raids by striking at neutral
commercial shipping. The Iranians have not hit any vessel since
April 24 and before the U.S. Navy rules in the gulf were broadened.
</TEXT>
