<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MilitaryAIDS     05-12 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military AIDS,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Man Says He's Not Surprised By His Acquittal In AIDS Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy avionics technician acquitted of
assault for having sex with his former fiancee despite knowing he
carried the AIDS virus said he was not surprised by the verdict.
   ``It was what I felt was right,'' Petty Officer 2nd Class John
E. Crawford said after the verdict was announced Wednesday.
Crawford, 27, was accompanied by his present fiancee, Karen
Skavdahl.
   Crawford's family and friends applauded after the seven-member
jury announced their verdict before Military Judge Richard Mollison
at the Treasure Island Navy Station.
   Jeannie Elmer, Crawford's former fiancee and accuser, said she
was upset by the verdict and fears it will encourage others not to
reveal to sex partners that they are infected with the deadly virus.
   ``That's why AIDS is probably going to be carried on and on and
on, because people will not tell their partner,'' said Elmer. ``And
now this will prove they can probably get away with it.''
   Elmer has tested negative for the AIDS virus three times.
   Crawford stood at attention in a packed courtroom as the jury,
which deliberated 4{ hours, also acquitted him of charges of
adultery and of exposing his former girlfriend to the AIDS virus
wrongfully and in wanton disregard for human life.
   He was convicted of the minor charge of having a visitor in his
room after hours, for which the jury gave him 15 days in the brig
and reduced his rank by one grade, from E5 to E4.
   If convicted of the primary charges, Crawford could have been
stripped of his rank, dishonorably discharged and sentenced to a 10
years behind bars.
   The charges stemmed from a sexual encounter Crawford and Elmer
had on April 15, 1987.
   Crawford, a native of Magnolia, Ark., testified he told Elmer
about his test results and wore a condom when the couple made love
in his barracks room. He said Elmer, 28, was bitter that he had
broken off their brief engagement and filed the charges for revenge.
   Lt. Cmdr. Jane Gilliland, the prosecutor, countered in her
closing statement that Crawford simply didn't care enough about
Elmer to tell her about the tests.
   The case was unprecedented in the Navy, although there have been
similar cases in other military branches.
   In Arizona on Wednesday, the AIDS-related court-martial of
Adrian G. Morris Jr. resumed after a nine-month delay.
   Morris, a 28-year-old Army private from Caseyville, Ill., is
accused of having threatened the health of three soldiers by not
using condoms during sex and failing to warn them he had tested
positive for the AIDS virus.
   The national Centers for Disease Control estimates that 20
percent to 30 percent of those who test positive for exposure to
the virus will develop AIDS within five years. It is not known
whether everyone with the virus will eventually develop the
incurable disease.
</TEXT>
