<HEAD>Boxing Champ Gives Rolls To Two Cops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Port Authority police officers were the
proud owners of a slightly damaged $150,000 Rolls Royce _ at least
until their boss found out.
   The windfall began when heavyweight boxing champ Mike Tyson and
his new wife, actress Robin Given, were involved in a fender-bender
Sunday near the Manhattan entrance to the Holland Tunnel.
   When the officers, whose names have not been released, went to
see if they could help, Tyson _ according to police reports quoted
in today's New York Post _ told them: ``I've had nothing but bad
luck and accidents with this car. You guys take this car and keep
it.''
   Port Authority police said the officers at first resisted, but
the nearly 6-foot, 216-pound Tyson, whose ring record stands at
34-0, insisted.
   The officers drove the gift to a private garage in Jersey City,
N.J., where it stayed until Monday morning when the commander of
the Holland Tunnel police detail heard about the incident.
   The Port Authority's Internal Affairs unit sent detectives to
retrieve the car and return it to the company that handles Tyson's
business interests.
   ``I've got real problems with this behavior,'' said Port
Authority Police Superintendent Henry DeGeneste. ``The main
difficulty is that we had to ask. They should have told us about
the situation first and faster.''
   DeGeneste said the two would be disciplined.
   The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey operates the
bridges and tunnels between New York City and New Jersey.
