<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-MysteryWriters     05-12 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Mystery Writers,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giuliani to Writers: Pay More Attention To White Collar Crime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. prosecutor surprised an audience of
mystery writers with an impersonation of Marlon Brando in ``The
Godfather,'' then urged the authors to devote less ink to murders
and more to white collar crime.
   ``We have to pay more attention to white collar crime,'' U.S.
Attorney Rudolph Guiliani told the International Congress of Crime
Writers as he catalogued some of the criminals he has prosecuted,
including Wall Street insider traders, income tax evaders, corrupt
government officials.
   He then shifted gears, offering his opinion of fictional
prosecutors.
   ``A lot of my collegues are not portrayed fairly,'' he said
Wednesday. ``And the same could be said about the police. But then,
even journalists complain that they're not portrayed accurately.''
   The writers asked for a little help in the accuracy department.
   What common characteristic did white-collar criminals have?
   Aside from basic greed, ``When they get caught, they all find
God at or about the time they go to prison,'' he responded.
</TEXT>
