<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoPhones     05-12 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Phones,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phones Still Out in Chicago Suburbs Five Days After Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telephone outage in Chicago's western suburbs
dragged into a fifth day today as Illinois Bell officials tried to
find out why an hour went by before firefighters arrived to fight a
blaze at a switching station.
   Sunday's fire at the unmanned Hinsdale station left 35,000
customers without telephone service in Du Page County, west of
Chicago, and there was no indication when they would get normal
service back.
   Adjusting to life without telephones has been difficult, say
those affected.
   ``You don't miss it until you don't have it,'' said Bill Saad,
one of more than 100 people waiting in line Wednesday for 17 phones
provided free of charge outside the fire-damaged switching station.
   Bell learned of the fire at 3:59 p.m., when alarms at a
monitoring station reported a fire and power failure, said Bell
spokeswoman Pat Montgomery. The alarm is not designed to sound at
the Hinsdale Fire Department, which arrived at the fire at 4:58 p.m.
   She said an Illinois Bell worker arrived at the station at 4:20
p.m., and flagged down a car and asked the driver to alert
firefighters.
   ``We're still trying to find out why there was the big
difference in the time (the Bell worker) came and when the fire
department came,'' Ms. Montgomery said.
   She had little encouragement for customers.
   ``We don't know when we will be able to bring back local
service,'' she said Wednesday. ``And when we do, it will be a slow
process of a few thousand customers a day. We can't estimate when.
We just don't know.''
   Between 150 and 200 Illinois Bell employees have been working to
restore operations, and some local calls between suburbs and some
long-distance calls that normally run through the Hinsdale station
were finally ringing phones, Ms. Montgomery said.
   Cable and high-tech equipment were badly damaged by flames and
the water sprayed by firefighters. The cause of the fire has not
been determined, Ms. Montgomery said.
   Saad, a resident of Downers Grove, was standing in line for the
second time to make the same business call to Kansas City. The
operator had cut off Saad's first call, but under rules set up at
the center, that still forced to go him back at the end of the line
before another try.
   ``It has definitely been a headache,'' said Gloria Telander,
president of Print Media Services Ltd. in Elk Grove Village, whose
business publishes campground guides for travelers around the
country.
   She said her customers calling from outside Illinois get a
recorded message: ``Due to mechanical difficulties, we cannot
complete your call. Please try again.''
   ``Well, they've been trying now for three days and they're
hysterical. ... Why doesn't the phone company just say what's going
on?''
</TEXT>
