<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Punjab 1stLd-Writethru a0478 05-12 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0478,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Militants Killed In Temple Siege, Head Priest Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with two militants killed in
afternoon firing, police chief's news conference. Picks up 13th
graf pvs, `All shops and ...' Edits threafter to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the Golden Temple's five top
priests and about 30 followers were arrested today when police
blocked their attempted march on the Sikh shrine which was ringed
by government security forces.
   Among those arrested was head Sikh priest Jasbir Singh Rode. His
talks Wednesday with government officials to try to end the
four-day confrontation at the 400-year-old temple were inconclusive.
   Two Sikh militants were killed this afternoon in a heavy
exchange of fire with security forces on the temple's perimeter,
police said. A third was seriously injured.
   The deaths raised to at least 14 the number of people killed
since shooting broke out Monday at the temple, Sikhism's holiest
shrine. Eleven others have been injured.
   Rode has called for the estimated 100 Sikh extremists inside the
temple complex to dismantle their bunkers and for the 2,500 police
and paramilitary forces ringing the shrine to withdraw.
   The priest and his followers were arrested at another Sikh
shrine about a third of a mile north of the Golden Temple as they
were about to start marching in defiance of a police ban.
   Deputy Police Commissioner Sarbjeet Singh asked the group to
call off the march because two bursts of gunfire inside the temple
were reported this morning after an overnight lull.
   Punjab Police Chief K.P.S. Gill told a news conference that
there were no plans to end the siege. Asked where it was leading,
Gill said: ``We are waiting to see how the situation develops.''
   ``We want the militants to stop firing so that normalcy can be
restored,'' he added.
   ``We take responsibility for any firing from inside the
temple,'' Rode responded. ``You take responsibility for firing from
outside.''
   Sikh militants placed a medium-sized machine gun atop a tower
inside the complex and were in a position to fire down on anyone in
the area.
   The Sikhs have also built fortifications on the northern edge of
the complex, from which police Tuesday evacuated 800 pilgrims to
keep them out of the crossfire.
   All shops and businesses in the old, walled sector of Amritsar
which surrounds the temple remained shuttered today and people
stayed off the streets as a police-imposed curfew entered its
fourth day.
   State-run All India Radio said the government was trying to
ensure that milk and other supplies reach civilians in curfew-bound
areas.
   Police had hoped to lift the curfew Wednesday, but the effort
failed.
   The temple complex covers an area equivalent to more than five
city blocks, and includes offices, hostels and dining halls.
   The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus.
   Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1983
for more autonomy for an independent homeland in Punjab state.
Sikhs make up less than two percent of India's 800 million people
and Punjab is the only state where they are a majority.
   More than 940 people have been killed this year in Punjab in
attacks blamed on the extremists. Most have been Hindus or moderate
Sikhs opposed to the separatist campaign.
   The Indian army was sent into the Golden Temple complex in June
1984 to drive Sikh extremists from the shrine. More than 1,200
people were killed in the attack, including Jarnail Singh
Bhindranwale, a militant Sikh preacher.
   Later that year, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was assassinated
by two of her Sikh bodyguards in revenge.
</TEXT>
