<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PortraitProtest     05-12 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portrait Protest,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caricature of Late Mayor Sparks Confrontation</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A painting of the late mayor Harold Washington
wearing women's lingerie was impounded by police after the City
Council condemned the work and aldermen stormed the prestigious art
school where it was displayed.
   Students yelled ``Fascists!'' and ``Chicago is a communist
state!'' after nine alderman removed the caricature of the city's
first black mayor, who died of a heart attack in November, from the
School of the Art Institute.
   ``Half the city is still mourning,'' said Alderman Bill Henry.
``You're going to tell me it's art?''
   The City Council contingent charged the work was racist and an
insult to the Washington family.
   ``The painting has been arrested,'' Alderman Ernest Jones said.
The portrait, wrapped in brown paper, was carried off in a squad
car that left the school with sirens wailing.
   Students at the school, a four-year college affiliated with the
Art Institute of Chicago, argued that the work was artistic
self-expression and protected by the First Amendment.
   ``This has nothing to do with race, it has to do with art,''
said student Kevin Landers. ``Don't tell us what to draw.''
   The painting depicted Washington clad in a frilly white bra,
panties and stockings, holding a pencil and frowning at viewers. It
was displayed in a school hallway with dozens of others in a
student competition closed to the public.
   The students repeatedly restored the painting to the wall after
aldermen took it down. The aldermen eventually took the work to
school president Tony Jones, who agreed to allow police to impound
the work.
   ``We got complaints about the painting. We came down here and
... found it insulting, inciting and causing unrest,'' Ernest Jones
said.
   Tony Jones, who signed a statement at the aldermen's request
indicating the work would not be displayed again at the school,
later said police were concerned the painting ``would lead to
riots.''
   ```Incitement to riot' was the phrase they actually used,'' he
said.
   Artist David Nelson left the school hours before the
confrontation, Jones said, adding he had tried unsuccessfully to
reach the student to seek voluntary removal of the painting before
the City Hall delegation arrived.
   A school statement said the artist ``chose this work himself''
and noted, ``Students bear the sole responsibility for selection of
their work in this exhibition.''
   Nelson could not be reached to explain what the painting was
intended to represent. School spokesman Kevin Frech would not
provide his telephone number, and calls placed to listed telephone
numbers for that name went unanswered or were answered by people
who denied any knowledge of the painting.
   The exhibit also included a self-portrait of Nelson, showing a
young white man embracing people of various races and titled, ``I'm
sensitive and I love all humanity.''
   The City Council passed a resolution Wednesday calling for
withdrawal of city subsidies to the school unless the painting was
removed, and demanding a public apology.
</TEXT>
