<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-WWII     05-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-WWII,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Parties To Call Non-Confidence Vote Against Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties today agreed to call a
no-confidence vote in Parliament against a Cabinet minister who
claimed Japan was not an aggressor in World War II.
   A resolution condemning National Land Agency chief Seisuke Okuno
was expected to be submitted to the Lower House of the Diet on
Friday, said an official of the opposition Komeito (Clean
Government Party).
   But the measure was almost certain to fail because the governing
Liberal Democratic Party has a 302-seat majority in the 512-seat
Lower House.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Okuno's comments and previous
lapses by other officials have ``severely damaged'' relations with
Asian nations.
   Okuno came under fire from China, South Korea and North Korea
for an April 22 statement that Japan was not an aggressor in World
War II and ``fought to protect itself at a time when the white race
had turned Asia into a colony.''
   He made the remark after visiting Yasukuni Shrine, where war
heroes and convicted war criminals are enshrined. Other countries,
including China, have protested official visits to the monument in
central Tokyo.
   Okuno said the objections were ``unfortunate.''
   In separate policy committee meetings, the Japan Socialist Party
and the Komeito agreed to call a no-confidence vote against the
75-year-old minister, said the Komeito official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Japan's two largest opposition groupings were supported by the
Democratic Socialists and the Communist Party.
   News reports said the opposition was privately pressing Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita to dismiss Okuno, widely regarded as the
third-highest ranking official after Takeshita and Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa.
   Okuno's comments and his refusal to apologize have embarrassed
the government. Spokesmen have stressed that his views do not
reflect official policy.
   Takeshita, fielding questions from opposition Diet members
Wednesday, said: ``Our country feels deep responsibility for the
grave damage Japan inflicted on the Chinese people during the past
war. We believe the government should fully recognize that our
country's actions during the war have been criticized severely as
aggression.''
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno, who tried to soothe China's anger
on a trip to Beijing last week, said today he had telephoned Okuno
and urged him to withdraw his comments.
   Today, North Korea termed the comments ``an expression of a
sinister intention to open a chapter of a new history of militarist
aggression.''
   Beginning in 1937, China and Japan fought an eight-year war that
killed 571,000 Japanese and 1.3 million Chinese soldiers and an
untold number of civilians.
   The dead included an estimated 42,000 Chinese civilians and
captured soldiers killed by the Japanese in the Nanking massacre in
the winter of 1937-38.
   China and Japan signed a treaty in 1972 that says in part, ``The
Japanese side is keenly aware of Japan's responsibility for causing
enormous damages in the past to the Chinese people through war and
deeply reproaches itself.''
</TEXT>
