<2ND_LINE>PM-Capitol Bombings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Indicted in Capitol Bombings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 28, She is also, to make clear that ``she'' refers
to Ms. Evans.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven members of a leftist terrorist group
linked to two bloody Brink's armored truck robberies in 1981 face
new charges of setting off bombs at the U.S. Capitol and three
military facilities.
   The charges were made public here Wednesday just hours after one
of the defendants, Marilyn Buck, was convicted in New York of
murder and armed robbery in two 1981 Brink's truck holdups that
left four dead.
   Ms. Buck, Linda Sue Evans, and Laura Whitehorn were charged with
conspiring to wage a campaign of ``armed propaganda'' against
``imperialist rule'' by setting off bombs in the Capitol and seven
other locations in Washington and New York City.
   Susan Rosenberg, Timothy Blunk, Dr. Alan Berkman and Elizabeth
Duke were named as participants but not charged with conspiracy.
   All seven were charged with malicious damage of government
property by placing bombs in the Capitol and at three military
buildings here.
   The midnight explosion in a corridor outside the U.S. Senate
chambers on Nov. 7, 1983, blasted a large hole in a wall and
shattered four windows. It damaged several paintings and knocked
doors off the hinges outside the office of Senate Majority Leader
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., then the minority leader.
   Bombs were also detonated at the National War College at Ft.
McNair on April 26, 1983, the Washington Navy Yard Computer Center
on Aug. 18, 1983, and the Navy Yard Officer's Club on April 20,
1984.
   The bombings injured no one but caused considerable property
damage.
   All the defendants except Ms. Duke _ a fugitive _ are serving
time for various federal weapons convictions stemming from alleged
terrorist activity.
   The group variously called itself the Armed Resistance Unit, the
Revolutionary Fighting Group and the Red Guerrilla Resistance in
communiques issued to claim credit for the blasts, the indictment
said.
   After the Capitol bombing, the Armed Resistance Unit sent a
communique to National Public Radio saying it set off the bomb to
protest the U.S. invasion of Grenada and the deployment of Marines
in Lebanon.
   ``We purposely aimed our attack at the institutions of
imperialist rule rather than at individual members of the ruling
class and government,'' the communique said. ``We did not choose to
kill any of them at this time. But their lives are not sacred.''
   The various groups also claimed responsibility for bombs set off
at four buildings in New York City at:
   _The Federal Building in Staten Island on Jan. 18, 1983.
   _The Israeli Aircraft Industries Building on April 5, 1984.
   _The South African Consulate on Sept. 26, 1984.
   _The Patrolmen's Benevolent Association on Feb. 23, 1985.
   Documents seized by federal agents indicated that the group also
targeted the Old Executive Office Building next to the White House,
the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., and Aberdeen Proving
Ground, Md., for surveillance.
   Other potential targets were the Washington offices of a law
firm, the American Israel Public Affairs Committee, the Cuban
American National Foundation and Summit Aviation in Middletown,
Del., the indictment charged.
   The group amassed an arsenal of dynamite, explosive gels,
blasting caps and firearms that was kept in a garage in Doylestown,
Pa. and a rented storage bin in Cherry Hill, N.J.
   The indictment charged that members of the group obtained
aliases from death certificates to obtain passports, driver's
licenses and to get jobs. Berkman and Blunk staged a Sept. 2, 1984,
armed robbery at a supermarket in Cromwell, Conn., the indictment
said.
   Ms. Buck and Mutulu Shakur were convicted Wednesday in New York
of murder and armed robbery in connection with the Oct. 20, 1981,
attempted robbery of a Brink's truck carrying $1.6 million in
Nanuet, N.Y.
   A Brink's guard and two Nyack, N.Y., policemen were killed in a
shootout.
   They were also convicted of the June 1981 robbery of a Brink's
truck in the Bronx, N.Y., in which a guard was killed.
   Both face life sentences.
   Federal authorities here said they waited until after Ms. Buck's
trial was over to unseal the indictment, which was returned last
month by a grand jury.
   Ms. Evans, 41, was convicted of harboring Ms. Buck when she was
a fugitive wanted on charges stemming from the attempted Brink's
holdup.
   Ms. Evans is also serving a five-year term for illegal weapons
possession plus a 40-year sentence for illegally buying weapons in
New Orleans in 1983.
   Rosenberg, 32, and Blunk, 30, are serving 58-year sentences for
possession of 600 pounds of explosives found when they were
arrested in Cherry Hill, N.J., almost three years ago.
   Berkman, a physician, and Ms. Duke were arrested in 1985 outside
Pittsburgh. At the time, both were linked by law enforcement
officials to M-19, a radical leftist group.
   Berkman is serving a 10-year prison term for possession of
explosives and weapons that were stored in the Doylestown, Pa.,
garage allegedly rented by Ms. Duke. She fled while awaiting trial
on similar charges.
   Whitehorn is already serving time for possession of weapons and
false identification cards.
   Ms. Rosenberg has been linked to the attempted holdup of the
Brink's truck as well as the 1979 prison escape of Joanne Chesimard.
   Ms. Chesimard, a leader of the Black Liberation Army, was
serving a life sentence for murdering a New Jersey state trooper.
   The federal court jury also convicted Shakur and Ms. Buck of
helping Ms. Chesimard escape from state prison at Clinton, N.J.
</TEXT>
