<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0518,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighting Stops Between Shiite Factions In South Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with woman killed today, other
details. Pick up 6th graf pvs: `The final...' Edits thereafter to
trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After six days of fighting, guns fell
silent in south Beirut's slums today as rival Shiite Moslem
militias observed a cease-fire arranged by the presidents of Syria
and Iran.
   Police said the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
controlled 70 percent of the 16-square-mile slums before the
cease-fire went into effect at 11 p.m. (5 p.m. EDT) Wednesday.
   Tension remained high in the slums as both sides, armed in their
positions, exchanged occasional sniper and machine-gun fire. One
woman was killed by a sniper's bullet in the Ghobeiri district
today.
   Police said 33 people were killed and 160 wounded Wednesday
before the truce began. The overall toll from nearly a week of
violence was 188 killed and 532 wounded.
   A police spokesman said the Syrian-backed Amal, Arabic for hope,
had lost most of its positions in south Beirut's narrow alleys and
redeployed its militiamen along the disputed terrain's southern,
western and northern edges.
   ``Amal controls all the gateways to south Beirut and Hezbollah
controls most of the area from inside,'' said the spokesman, who by
regulation cannot be identified.
   Reporters who toured the embattled slums saw Amal militiamen at
those positions in south Beirut.
   Hezbollah fighters, in light green fatigues and green headbands,
controlled most of the area from inside.
   Bullet scars appeared on nearly every building in the area.
Smoke billowed from several shell-pocked apartment blocks and shops
that were hit during Wednesday's battles.
   Several Amal jeeps were seen destroyed along the side roads of
districts under Hezbollah's control.
   Dozens of cars were damaged. Several others were burned beyond
recognition. Glass shards and rubble littered the dusty streets and
alleys of the embattled slums.
   Iranian flags rose from at least 15 Amal positions overrun by
Hezbollah.
   The ``final cease-fire'' was ordered by President Hafez Assad of
Syria and his Iranian counterpart, Ali Khamenei, after telephone
consultations late Wednesday evening. The two presidents also set
up a four-man committee to supervise implementation of the accord.
   The committee groups Iran's deputy foreign minister, Hussein
Sheikholeslam; the head of Syrian military intelligence in west
Beirut, Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud; Ayoub Homeyed of Amal; and Hassan
Khalil of Hezbollah.
   Four observer teams formed by the committee entered south Beirut
early today to supervise evacuation of the wounded from both rival
factions, the police spokesman said.
   He said a convoy of about 10 ambulances from the Lebanese Red
Cross also drove across Amal lines into the bomb-scarred slums to
evacuate the wounded.
   However, the evacuation was delayed because ``at the last minute
Hezbollah demanded guarantees that its wounded will be safe in
hospitals of west Beirut outside its area of influence,'' the
spokesman said.
   He said ``the Syrians agreed to guarantee safety of wounded
Hezbollahis.''
   At the height of the fighting, doctors said militiamen forced
surgeons at a hospital to operate at gunpoint, and that there were
gunbattles inside the hospital.
   Syria deployed 7,500 troops in west Beirut 14 months ago after a
month of bloody clashes between Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal
and the militia of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party.
   The Syrians, however, did not deploy in south Beirut, a
traditional stronghold for Iranian-backed underground factions
holding most of the 18 foreign hostages.
   The truce was reached after Amal lost most of south Beirut to
the pro-Iranian radicals.
   The truce calls for withdrawal of all militiamen from the
streets of the southern suburbs this afternoon. ``The withdrawal
will be the big test,'' the police spokesman said.
   Four previous cease-fire accords have collapsed due to
Hezbollah's refusal to withdraw to positions it held before the
confrontation broke out Friday.
   An Amal official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said his
militia ``insists on returning to the districts we controlled
before the clashes started.'' He refused to say whether Amal would
try to regain its lost positions by force if Hezbollah refuses to
withdraw.
</TEXT>
