<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson'sContention 1stLd-Writethru a0425 05-12 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson's Contention, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Officeholders Cool To Jackson's Call To Support Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 18th graf bgng ``Not only'' to CORRECT to Natalie sted
Patricia</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's call to white Democratic
legislators who benefited from black votes to back him for the
presidential nomination has failed to attract much support from
those who count at the national convention.
   Since the days leading up to the Super Tuesday primaries on
March 8, Jackson ha said that white Democratic legislators,
especially those in the South who were elected with a major share
of the black vote, should be willing to support him based on that
basis.
   He recently renewed that call and added a new twist _ Jackson
named names.
   ``It's reasonable to expect that Sen. (Terry) Sanford will
endorse my campaign. That's a reasonable expectation,'' Jackson
said during an appearance in Greensboro, N.C.
   Sanford, who was elected to the Senate in 1986, is one of the
unpledged public officeholders who will attend the Democratic
National Convention as a ``super delegate.''
   Earlier in the campaign, Sanford backed Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr., who captured North Carolina on Super Tuesday. In the wake
of Gore's decision to suspend his campaign, Sanford moved into the
uncommitted ranks.
   ``He wants to enjoy his uncommitted status for a little bit,''
said Sanford's spokesman, Tom Lawton. Sanford chose not to comment
on Jackson's call for his support, Lawton said.
   Back in 1986, when Sanford sought the Democratic nomination for
the Senate seat, he did not have the backing of Jackson. Ted
Kinney, a black candidate seeking the Democratic nod, picked up
Jackson's endorsement instead.
   Kinney ``was not a serious candidate by any stretch of the
imagination,'' said Merle Black, a political science professor at
the University of North Carolina.
   In the general election, Sanford edged James T. Broyhill, 52
percent to 48 percent, with a major share of the black vote and
nearly half of the white vote _ about 45 percent.
   ``By the early '70s, the late '60s, the percentage of white
votes began dropping precipitously,'' said Larry Sabato, a
political science professor at the University of Virginia.
``Democrats don't need a majority (to win the election) thanks to
the black vote, but they need a healthy slice of the white vote.''
   Black says that in the South the white vote has become the swing
vote.
   ``The Achilles heel for Republicans is they get little support
from blacks so they have to get a landslide of whites. The
Republicans need a landslide to make it close,'' he said.
   The ability to capture a large share of the white swing vote,
combined with strong black support, made the difference for a
number of Southern senators elected in 1986.
   Wyche Fowler of Georgia has been elected for nine years to
represent the black majority fifth congressional district in his
state. In the general election, Fowler won his old district by
nearly a 2-to-1 margin but he also won the support of 4-out-of-10
white voters.
   Fowler, who also is a super delegate, remains uncommitted.
   Louisiana Senator John Breaux did well in the Cajun parishes but
also carried or finished even in the white Baptist parishes for his
1986 victory. Breaux also remains uncommitted.
   Not only did these candidates target the white swing vote, but
they had to battle the staunch white voters who refuse to support a
candidate who has the backing of black voters, according to
pollster Natalie Davis.
   ``It's hard to document but about one-fifth of the typically
Democratic voters will not back a candidate with black voters,''
Ms. Davis said. ``Democrats are caught perenially between a rock
and a hard place.''
   Some of these Southern senators who managed to capture both the
black vote and a large enough share of the white vote have decided
not to endorse a presidential candidate before the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta, July 18-21.
   In fact, 11 of the 12 Southern senators who will be attending
the convention as super delegates have chosen the uncommitted
ranks. Only Bennett Johnston of Louisiana remains steadfast in his
support of Gore.
   Jackson has also hinted that his supporters might stay away from
the polls in November if they perceived that he was being treated
unfairly.
   ``We define our friends by their willingness to be fair and to
be just,'' Jackson said. ``One thing about politics, it does not go
up and down. It goes round and round. Anything that goes around
comes around.''
   Jackson's indication of possible party problems in the general
election presents a real dilemma for Democrats, who are treading
carefully on the issue.
   ``If Jackson is not treated well, there could be a low turnout
for the ticket,'' Black said. ``If it's not as high, they need a
larger share of the white vote.''
</TEXT>
