<HEAD>Viewers Abuzz Over Pending `Marriage' between Characters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, ``We thought xxx, to CORRECT spelling of
actresses name, Sonia sted Sonai, add that show was taped in
January</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big Bird and scads of preschoolers are delighted
and Oscar the grouch is predictably unimpressed. Perhaps the only
ones nervous about Friday's ``wedding'' of Maria and Luis are the
creators of ``Sesame Street.''
   The marriage of two of the show's longtime characters represents
the first attempt by the public television program, now in its 19th
season, to show how romantic love works.
   Valeria Lovelace, the show's director of research, said the
staff found ``no books for preschoolers on love and marriage, only
death and divorce.''
   When interviews with 90 Manhattan preschoolers showed that young
children did not make the connection between love and marriage, the
general outline of the theme was born.
   ``We wanted the wedding to make that connection for them,'' said
Ms. Lovelace.
   The message has been carefully cultivated since last December,
when Maria and Luis, longtime friends and partners in the show's
Fix-It Shop, realized that their feelings were changing as they
cared for a sick kitten together.
   ``I saw them kiss,'' said Vicky Velasquez, a 4-year-old on a
Brooklyn playground full of chatter about the impending match. ``So
I know they're happy.''
   ``We thought, `What could we say to 3-year-olds about love?'''
said Sonia Manzano, who plays Maria and writes for the show. ``And
since kids see love in terms of physical things like kissing,
hugging, giving flowers, we showed Maria and Luis doing a lot of
that.''
   Dulcy Singer, executive producer, said Ms. Manzano, who was
married two years ago, inspired the wedding when she told her she
was thinking about having a baby. The show was actually taped last
January.
   Ms. Singer declined to say whether Maria and Luis, who is played
by Emilio Delgado, would have a child after the wedding.
</TEXT>
