<1ST_LINE>r i Cambodia-Fighting     05-12 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Cambodia-Fighting,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Claim They Forced Vietnamese Into Interior</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian guerrillas say they have
broken Vietnam's control of thousands of villages in Cambodia,
forcing Vietnam to send soldiers to defend the villages.
   The claim came in a Khmer Rouge radio broadcast in which
guerrilla Commander-in-Chief Son Sen reported on fighting from
October 1987 to April 1988, the region's dry season. A text of the
broadcast was obtained today.
   The communist Khmer Rouge, with about 30,000 guerrillas, is the
strongest of three groups opposing Vietnam's 9-year-old occupation
of Cambodia. Khmer Rouge claims are widely regarded as exaggerated.
   In the broadcast, a text of which was obtained today, the
guerrillas claimed they killed 11,200 Vietnamese soldiers and
``repeatedly attacked and dismantled or dispersed the Vietnamese
administrative networks in 4,033 villages and 236 communes and
attacked 23 townships and seven district towns.''
   Vietnam responded by transferring an important part of its
troops from the western battlefields bordering Thailand _ the
traditional area of fighting _ to the interior for village defense,
the broadcast said.
   That allowed the Khmer Rouge, who are based along the Thai
border, to infiltrate more men into the interior, it said.
   ``Therefore, the Vietnamese enemy's strategy to seal off the
western border of Cambodia and prevent the (Khmer Rouge) from
attacking it inside Cambodia suffered a total setback,'' the
broadcast said.
   A coalition of three Cambodian groups is fighting to drive out
the Vietnamese, who invaded Cambodia in 1979 to drive out the Khmer
Rouge. The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of people
during their 1975-79 reign of terror.
   The United States had assisted the republican side against the
Khmer Rouge during the 1973-75 civil war.
</TEXT>
