<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pacific-France     05-12 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pacific-France,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Explodes Nuclear Bomb in Pacific, New Zealand Objects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France today detonated its first
underground nuclear bomb this year in the South Pacific. New
Zealand protested the explosion and said it could not have happened
at a worse time.
   The 50-kiloton device, equivalent to 50,000 tons of dynamite,
went off at 5 a.m. at a nuclear test site on the French-controlled
Mururua Atoll, about one-third of the way between New Zealand and
the Central American coast.
   The explosion was the 92nd underground test there since France
abandoned atmospheric testing in 1975, said to Warwick Smith,
director of the New Zealand Seismological Observatory in Wellington.
   ``The New Zealand government will keep expressing its strong
concern about French nuclear testing whenever it occurs,'' said New
Zealand Foreign Mnister Russell Marshall. ``The timing could not be
worse.''
   The testing has strained France's relations with countries of
the South Pacific, which have declared the region a nuclear-free
zone.
   The French government in 1985 ordered the bombing of the
Greenpeace flagship Rainbow Warrior to prevent the vessel from
leading a protest flotilla from the New Zealand harbor of Auckland
to the Mururua nuclear test site.
   French relations with New Zealand were severely strained by the
bombing, in which one crew member died. The two French agents
responsible for the attack were sentenced to exile on the Hao Atoll
in the South Pacific, but since have returned to France despite of
strong objections from New Zealand.
</TEXT>
