<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Harold Philby</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold ``Kim'' Philby, an upper-class Englishman
who turned traitor and became a double agent for Moscow for 26
years, died Wednesday in the Soviet Union. He was 76.
   The Soviet Embassy in London disclosed the death but gave no
cause.
   Philby, whose unmasking as a Soviet agent in 1963 rocked the
British establishment, was the notorious ``Third Man'' who tipped
off fellow spies Donald Maclean and Guy Burgess that they were
under investigation by British authorities. Philby fled to Moscow
that year and was later reported to be a highly regarded adviser to
Soviet intelligence agencies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Tabatha Foster</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tabatha Foster, 3, the world's longest
survivor of a five-organ transplant, died Wednesday after an
infection caused her heart, kidneys and liver to fail.
   Tabatha received a new liver, small intestines, pancreas and
parts of a stomach and colon during a 15-hour experimental
operation that ended Nov. 1.
   The feisty little girl won the hearts of hospital staff with
good-natured teasing, playing peek-a-boo, giggling each day at
``Sesame Street'' and singing ``The Itsy-Bitsy Spider.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Pete Homer Sr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARKER, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pete Homer Sr., former chairman of the
Colorado River Indian Tribes and a movie actor, died Tuesday. He
was 83.
   Homer, a Mohave Indian, during his 1955-1964 chairmanship led
moves to solve land title problems, gained the tribes leasing
authority and water rights, and saw the annual family income rise
to $5,000 from $164.
   He worked for the Bureau of Reclamation for 21 years and for the
Bureau of Indian Affairs for eight years. After retiring, he served
on the Senate Indian Policy Committee, the National Indian Safety
Council, the National Congress of American Indians, the governor's
advisory council on vocational rehabilitation and the Committee on
Indian Affairs in Arizona.
   His movie career began at Paramount Pictures, where he was known
as Chief Lightfoot and appeared in ``Annie Oakley'' with Barbara
Stanwyck. He appeared with stars like Tony Curtis, Jeanette
MacDonald and Nelson Eddy.
</TEXT>
