<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons-Safety     05-12 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Weapons-Safety,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Finds Safety Lacking in Biological Weapons Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has ``serious deficiencies'' in
the way it manages the safety of its research programs into
chemical and biological warfare, a Senate subcommittee's staff
report maintains.
   The review found ``inadequate regulations, lax safety
enforcement and documented safety lapses,'' said the report by the
majority staff of the Senate Governmental Affairs oversight
subcommittee.
   The study, released Wednesday, noted that it did not examine
``the current safety practices of particular facilities conducting
... research. Nor does it reach final conclusions as to whether ...
research is being conducted in a safe manner.''
   Air Force Maj. Randy Morger, a Pentagon spokesman, said today
that Defense Department officials hadn't seen the report. ``We need
to look at it carefully, but we're greatly concerned when there are
questions from any corner about possible safety issues in programs
overseen by the Department of Defense.''
   The United States recently began building new chemical weapons,
after halting the program in 1969. The nation produces no germ
weapons and has unilaterally renounced the use of biological
weapons, but does conduct research into chemical weapons that might
be used against American troops.
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., chairman of the subcommittee, said he
plans to hold hearings later this year to discuss the Pentagon's
safety practices in the two research fields.
   The study noted that U.S. spending on the programs has increased
sharply during President Reagan's two terms, from about $63 million
in 1980 to $348 million in 1986.
   The number of laboratories involved in research has also
increased, the study found. There are about 150 labs doing
Pentagon-sponsored research in chemical and germ weapons.
   The subcommittee staff said it was ``unable to locate a
comprehensive safety program ... , that is, a readily identifiable
set of safety regulations and an office with overall safety
responsibilities.
   In the biological weapons area, the review found that ``there is
no comprehensive set of safety regulations for research'' with
biological warfare agents and toxins, ``no emphasis on safety in
the contractor program and no office that monitors contractor
safety.''
   For chemical weapons, the approach is better, although it also
``appears to have major shortcomings,'' the study said. The
military has a wide number of safety steps, but many are violated,
the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
