<2ND_LINE>PM-Bowlers-Booze,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women's Bowling League Sues Over Being Dropped in Favor of Men's
League</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A women's bowling league has sued a country club
for sex discrimination over cancellation of its bowling night by a
bowling alley manager who allegedly said women don't drink enough
alcohol.
   The suit, filed Wednesday in Macomb County Circuit Court by the
American Civil Liberties Union, asks that the Clinton Township
league of 60 bowlers be allowed to retain the Wednesday night time
slot it has held for four years.
   Officials of Fern Hill Country Club booted the women from the
slot in March, saying the women don't drink enough alcohol,
reducing revenues for the club, according to the suit. The time
slot has been filled by a men's league.
   Bowling alley Manager Jimmy Walker said Wednesday he doesn't
remember making the remark about the cancellation at a league
banquet.
   Fern Hill co-owner Fred Severini Jr. denied that less drinking
was the reason for the change and said the women had refused a
bowling alley offer to return next fall to the same time slot.
   However, state ACLU executive director Howard Simon called
Severini's statement ``an outright falsehood.''
