<HEAD>One Rare Bird Departs, Another Arrives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of cormorant</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare spotted redshank that drew bird
watchers to Lake Perry last week apparently has flown the coop. But
the news is not all bad for ornithologists.
   A olivaceous cormorant, a Gulf bird seen in Louisiana and Texas
but uncommon to Kansas, was recently spotted in the area, said
Richard Rucker, a ranger for the Army Corps of Engineers at Lake
Perry.
   The big one got away, however. The spotted redshank, a
Euro-Asian bird that is one of the few black sandpipers, was first
spotted at the lake May 1.
   Rucker, who last saw the bird Saturday, believes it may have
left the area that night. ``We did get a change of birds between
Saturday night and Sunday morning,'' he said Wednesday.
   One experienced bird watcher spent four hours at the lake Sunday
hoping for a glimpse of the rare bird and left disappointed, Rucker
said.
</TEXT>
