<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeacherPoisoned     05-12 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teacher Poisoned,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Arrested After Allegedly Putting Ammonia In Teacher's Iced
Tea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old student was arrested for putting
ammonia into a glass of iced tea his teacher left in a classroom,
police said.
   Jerome Felton, a ninth-grader at Booker T. Washington Junior
High School, was arrested Wednesday at school and charged with
poisoning and aggravated assault, both felonies, said detective
Julio Moreiras.
   Sue Niles, 40, whose mouth, throat and esophagus were burned,
was hospitalized but received no serious injury.
   Ms. Niles said she left the classroom April 22 where Felton was
with two other students to go to the bathroom and returned five
minutes later. She said she had a glass of iced tea near her desk
that was about a quarter full.
   ``I just took a big gulp,'' she said. ``I realized it was
bitter. It felt like my mouth was on fire. I knew something was
wrong.''
   Niles, who is in charge of the school's detention program, said
Felton was upset at being put on indoor suspension for cutting
classes.
   Moreiras said the teen denies he poured the ammonia in the tea.
He is in the custody of Health and Rehabilitative Services.
   If tried as an adult, the youth could get a maximum sentence of
45 years in prison, Moreiras said.
</TEXT>
