<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmnestyDenials     05-12 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty Denials,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys Say Just One-Quarter of Immigrants Appealing Amnesty
Denials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of public interest lawyers say they
are alarmed that only one-quarter of the illegal aliens whose
amnesty applications have been denied are filing appeals.
   Many of the rejected applicants may be confused by the letters
of denial from the Immigration and Naturalization Service, attorney
Susan Alva said Wednesday.
   ``These denial letters are three pages, all in English,'' said
Ms. Alva, an attorney with the Public Counsel, an organization
financed by the Los Angeles County and Beverly Hills bar
associations. ``For many immigrants, they're just about impossible
to understand.''
   But Joe Thomas, director of the INS regional processing facility
in Laguna Niguel, said many of those denied amnesty under the 1986
immigration reform act may be choosing not to appeal because they
realize they will not succeed. The deadline for seeking amnesty was
midnight May 4.
   Many denials were issued because applicants were ineligible,
disqualified by criminal records or because of fraudulent
applications, he said. To qualify, illegal aliens had to prove that
they had lived in the United States continuously beginning Jan. 1,
1982.
   As of May 7, 4,047 denials had been sent to amnesty applicants
in the agency's Western region, which includes California, Nevada,
Hawaii, Arizona and Guam. Of those, 1,001 have appealed.
   Those rejected have just 30 days to appeal, a process that costs
$50.
   Federal officials argued the applicants were able to fill out
English applications and should be able to deal with denial letters
in English.
   ``They've been treated fairly,'' said William S. King Jr.,
director of immigration reform for the Western region.
   ``If they (amnesty applicants) have a problem with
interpretation of their denials, they can get help from the same
people who helped them file their applications,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
