<1ST_LINE>u w PM-PreventiveHealth 1stLd-Writethru a0426 05-12 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preventive Health, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,550</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 6-7 with 3 grafs to update with remarks at press
conference; subs last graf with 2 grafs with margin of error and
other methodology.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans have become more casual about
cholesterol and good nutrition in general, according to a
Prevention magazine survey issued today that shows a decline in
health practices for the first time in five years.
   ``We don't know whether this year's score represents a temporary
setback on the way to further progress or whether it is an early
warning sign,'' said Thomas Dybdahl, director of the private
publication's so-called prevention index.
   The 1988 score is 64.8 out of a possible 100 _ down from 65.2
last year, but still 3.3 points above 1984, when the first index
was compiled.
   The latest sampling found that more Americans are using smoke
detectors and getting strenuous exercise, but falling behind in the
area of good nutrition.
   For example, the number saying they are making efforts to limit
high-cholesterol foods fell from 46 percent in the 1987 report to
42 percent and there also was a four-point decline in the number
who said they make an effort to get adequate vitamins and minerals
_ from 63 percent to 59 percent.
   ``One clear message from this year's survey is that the spread
of good health habits is not automatic,'' Dybdahl said at a news
conference.
   ``People may know more than ever about good health, but they may
not be acting on what they know. In key areas such as diet,
exercise and weight control, there is still much room for
improvement.''
   Dr. James Michael McGinnis, director of the federal government's
Office of Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, said the survey
is the only one to track the same data over a five-year period.
   The sharpest gains from the 1984 report were the 57 percent who
reported wearing seat belts now compared with 19 percent then and
the 82 percent who say they have a smoke detector in their home
compared with 67 percent then.
   The biggest drop was in those who said they obey the speed limit
_ from 61 percent in 1984 to 55 percent.
   The Emmaus, Pa.-based magazine has retained Louis Harris &
Associates for the past five years to poll Americans on their
practices in 21 health-related areas ranging from not smoking to
exercising to using a smoke detector in the home and wearing auto
seat belts.
   The same questions have been asked each year to give an accurate
year-to-year comparison and relative weights assigned to each of
the 21 areas. For example, not smoking is assigned the highest
ranking _ a 9.78 on a scale of one-to-10.
   The current year's report was based on telephone interviews
conducted with 1,250 randomly selected adults Nov. 11-25. Humphrey
Taylor, president of Louis Harris and Associates, acknowledged the
survey's 3 percent margin of error could call into question
year-to-year changes that are within that margin.
   Taylor said, however, that the theoretical chance for error is
largely overriden because consistent trends tracked over the
five-year sampling period give added credence to the figures
reported in any one year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CabildoFire 1stLd-Writethru a0498 05-12 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cabildo Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Damages Historic New Orleans Landmark</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with fire chief's comments
today. Picks up in 5th graf, ``There's all ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that gutted the top floor of the
building where the Louisiana Purchase was signed in 1803 was
apparently touched off by workers doing repair work, a fire
official said today.
   Wednesday's fire, which raged out of control for two hours,
destroyed or damaged priceless artifacts and threatened the
nation's oldest Roman Catholic cathedral next door.
   The blaze destroyed 18th century French furniture stored in the
upper floor and consumed the cupola atop the three-story Cabildo, a
Spanish-style gray stucco building with a slate roof, officials
said.
   No injuries were reported.
   Fire Chief William McCrossen said today that workers repairing
the roof and waterproofing the stucco walls apparently touched off
the fire. ``We think it's tied up to the restoration,'' he said.
   There was speculation that a soldering iron, used in repairing
metal flashing, touched off timbers that originally came down the
Mississippi River as flatboats. The mansard roof and the top floor
were added in 1847 using timbers salvaged from the river barges.
   ``There's all the cultural heritage of Louisiana in that
building. It makes me want to cry,'' said James F. Sefcik, museum
director of the 193-year-old landmark in New Orleans' French
Quarter.
   Smoke and water stained and soaked contents of the first and
second floors, where paintings, tapestries, doll and fan
collections, Mardi Gras memorabilia, pottery and other items were
on display, officials said.
   ``Next to Independence Hall in Philadelphia, this is the most
historic building in America,'' said Sam Wilson, a New Orleans
architect who renovated the Cabildo's interior 20 years ago.
   The cause of the fire remained uncertain, but Wilson said the
building remained structurally sound and could be repaired.
   An estimate of damages was not immediately available. The
building alone was assessed at $50 million and is insured, said
Sefcik.
   ``Every painting, every artifact suffered some water or smoke
damage,'' Sefcik said.
   France and the United States signed the Louisiana Purchase
inside the three-story building in 1803. It also was the repository
for a death mask of Napoleon and other priceless antiques and
artifacts. The bronze death mask was saved.
   The Marquis de Lafayette stayed at the Cabildo as a guest, and
Pierre Lafitte, brother of the notorious buccaneer Jean Lafitte,
was jailed there for smuggling.
   Firefighters managed to keep the flames from spreading to the
adjacent St. Louis Cathedral, which remained undamaged except for
some melted copper on the outside.
   Built in 1794, St. Louis Cathedral is the oldest active Roman
Catholic cathedral in the United States. Pope John Paul II
celebrated Mass there when he visited New Orleans last September.
   The Cabildo was built a year later and served as the seat of
Louisiana territorial government for France, Spain, the Confederacy
and the United States. The building, which has been used as a
museum since World War I, was closed recently to tourists because
of exterior renovations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
