<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-AgaKhan     05-12 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Aga Khan,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aga Khan Relative To Head Afghan Refugee, Humanitarian Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
has appointed Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan to coordinate the
international relief effort for the return of Afghan refugees under
an accord signed in Geneva.
   Sadruddin, appointed Tuesday, is the son of the late Aga Kahn
III and uncle of the current Aga Khan IV. The Aga Khan is spiritual
leader of the world's 15 million Ismaili Moslems.
   Sadruddin, 55, was U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees from 1965
to 1977. He will hold the rank of under secretary-general.
   The United Nations has not divulged details of the massive
program which he will oversee. His salary was not reported.
   The United Nations mediated an agreement between Afghanistan and
Pakistan providing for the nine-month withdrawal of 115,000 Soviet
troops from Afghanistan beginning Sunday. It also provides for the
return of 5 million Afghan refugees, 3 million of them in Pakistan
and 2 million in Iran.
   Sadruddin was born in Paris to a family known for formidable
wealth and philanthropy. He is of Iranian origin and lives in
Switzerland.
   Sadruddin Khan was graduated from Harvard University in 1954 and
did postgraduate work at the Center for Middle Eastern Studies at
Harvard until 1957.
   In 1958 he was a special consultant to the United Nations
Educational, Social and Cultural Organization (UNESCO). He was
active in the preservation of Nubian monuments.
   As commissioner for refugees, Sadruddin oversaw operations to
help displaced persons in Bangladesh, Uganda, Sudan, Chile and
Cyprus.
   Since 1983 he has been co-chairman of the Independent Commission
on International Humanitarian Issues.
</TEXT>
