<HEAD>Communist Leadership Offers Resignation Over Poor Investments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The entire 11-member politburo of
Finland's Communist Party offered to resign after the party
treasury lost an estimated $2.25 million last year in poor
investments, the media reported Thursday.
   The politburo, led by party chairman Arvo Aalto, offered its
resignation at its meeting Wednesday. It will be considered at the
party's Central Committee meetng later this month.
   The Central Committee was not expected to accept all of the
resignations.
   The Independent Helsinki daily Helsingin Sanomat said in an
editorial that there was ``no reason to feel malicious pleasure
outside the party.''
   Aalto was not available for comment Wednesday or Thursday.
   The failed foray into the investment market meant a further loss
of face for the party after a steady loss of voter support over the
past 10 years. Internal quarrels led to a party split before last
year's parliamentary elections.
   In 1958, the party had 50 seats in the 200-seat parliament. In
the 1987 election, the two Communist factions won a total of 20
seats.
