<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WHO-Polio     05-12 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WHO-Polio,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Launches Effort To Root Out Polio By Year 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Health Organization on Thursday endorsed
a massive immunization campaign to protect all children against
polio and eradicate the crippling disease by the year 2000.
   Only half the world's children are immunized, and 275,000 new
cases of polio occur each year, mainly in developing countries,
according to WHO.
   A committee of the 166-nation U.N. agency passed by consensus a
resolution calling for the eradication program. Approval by WHO's
full assembly is expected Friday at the final session of the
agency's annual meeting.
   Polio is the major disease with the best chance of being stamped
out, the resolution said. It asked WHO's director general to seek
funds needed for the campaign and urged all countries to step up
surveillance to permit quick identification of outbreaks.
   Eradication is expected to require doubling the $500 million the
organization spends each year on immunization programs against six
major childhood diseases in the Third World, including polio. The
others are measles, diphtheria, whooping cough, tetanus and
tuberculosis.
   About 10 million people worldwide have been crippled by polio,
and one patient in 10 dies of the disease, WHO said.
   India has reported the most cases of polio in recent years _
14,629 in 1986. Afghanistan reported 1,843 cases, Vietnam 1,600,
China 1,537, Bangladesh 810 and Brazil 665.
   WHO estimates that only one case in 10 is reported to its
headquarters in Geneva, Switzerland.
   Eliminating polio will be ``an appropriate gift, together with
the eradication of smallpox'' to the next century, the resolution
said.
   WHO led a global drive that eradicated smallpox by the late
1970s.
   Polio became rare in developed countries after U.S. scientists
developed two vaccines in the 1950s. WHO expects to eliminate the
polio virus from the Americas, Europe and the Western Pacific by
1990.
   The organization says it costs $10 to immunize a child against
polio and other major diseases, although the cost can be higher to
reach children in remote areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
