<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FugitiveCaptured     05-12 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Captured,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Escaped 10{ Years Ago Captured in Maryland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEVERN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who walked away from a South Carolina
prison work-release program 10{ years ago has been arrested in
Maryland, where she had become a successful businesswoman,
authorities said.
   Pamela A. Rogers, 36, who served three years of a 12-year
sentence for armed robbery, was arrested Tuesday at her home in
Severn, where she had lived under a different name with her husband
and two sons from an earlier marriage.
   ``Ten-and-a-half years, 10{ years, 10{ years, why now?'' the
woman, a successful real estate broker, asked as she was arrested,
according to Rodney Johnson, warrants supervisor with the U.S.
Marshal's Office in Baltimore.
   Johnson said Ms. Rogers had lived in Severn since shortly after
the escape and had assumed the name Kay Kathalena Smith and a
birthdate five years prior to her real birthdate.
   She worked as a waitress and about 18 months ago obtained her
real estate license. Johnson said the woman had more than $1
million in sales last year and apparently lived an honest life
since her escape.
   Ms. Rogers, convicted in the armed robbery of a Columbia, S.C.,
jewelry store, had been wanted since Jan. 7, 1978, when she failed
to return to Goodman Correctional Institution near Columbia from a
work-release job, said state Department of Corrections spokesman
Hal Leslie.
   An old phone number and information provided by her former
husband, who recently was arrested on a murder charge in Idaho,
helped authorities uncover Ms. Rogers' new identity, authorities
said. Officials in South Carolina forwarded a picture of her to
Maryland.
   Upon locating the woman, police placed her under surveillance to
check for a small scar on the left side of her face that they felt
would further substantiate her identity.
   ``She looked the same as the picture, only older,'' Johnson
said. Ms. Rogers, who was alone in her home, did not resist arrest.
   She appeared Wednesday in Annapolis District Court and was freed
on $25,000 bond, Johnson said. She declined to waive extradition
and a hearing was scheduled June 10.
   A co-worker praised Ms. Rogers as a good worker and mother.
   ``I wish I had 20 Kay Smiths,'' said Fred Fischer, office
manager at Gary Hart & Associates in Glen Burnie.
   ``Everyone liked and respected her, he said. ``She took an
active part in her children's schoolwork and athletics. When she
wasn't with her family, she was working in the office.''
</TEXT>
