<HEAD>Rebels Launch Attacks Days Before Papal Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed guerrillas today seized a seminary where
Pope John Paul II is scheduled to speak this weekend, news reports
said. Police said suspected rebels bombed a police bus and
seriously wounded seven officers.
   The violence followed a mortar attack late Wednesday on the
Interior Ministry and a car bombing near a Lima military
installation, according to police reports.
   The violence comes just two days before the pope is scheduled to
arrive in Peru. It was the heavist round of attacks in the capital
this year.
   Police did not provide details, but news reports said a soldier
guarding an officers' school was killed and two policemen wounded
in the attack on the Interior Ministry.
   Police said suspected guerrillas hurled a bomb at the bus, which
was carrying police troopers on a downtown avenue during morning
rush hour traffic.
   Eight armed members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement
seized the Santo Toribio Seminary during a morning Mass and
demanded that seminarians, priests and others attending join their
insurgency, according to Radio Programas, Peru's leading news
station.
   The guerrillas fled when police arrived, and police launched a
search, the radio said. There were no injuries.
   The pope, on a 13-day tour of Latin America, is to arrive in
Lima Saturday from Bolivia. He is scheduled to meet cultural and
business leaders at the seminary Sunday. The pope is to leave for
Paraguay Monday.
   There was no indication which guerrilla band carried out the
other attacks. The Tupac Amaru group is smaller and considered less
violent that the Mao-inspired Shining Path.
   The Shining Path's eight-year insurgency against the government
of President Alan Garcia has claimed 10,000 lives.
</TEXT>
