<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForestRules     05-12 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Rules,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time-Consuming Paperwork Will Be Shaved From Forest Service
Appeals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the time-consuming paperwork will be
shaved from appeals resulting from Forest Service decisions
involving wildfires and other natural disasters, the Agriculture
Department said today.
   Forest Service Chief F. Dale Robertson said a newly adopted
interim rule primarily concerns future natural disasters in the
national forests.
   However, he said the agency also ``needs to speed up appeal
procedures for recovery and rehabilitation activities that resulted
from 1987's severe fire season in California and Oregon. It was
this natural disaster that brought to our attention the need for
special appeal procedures.''
   Under the interim rule adopted today, anyone may appeal
decisions on recovery and rehabilitation activities that result
from natural disasters, such as wildfires, flooding, earthquakes
and high winds, he said.
   Those who appeal will be entitled to a ``one-level appeal
process'' which must be completed within 90 days, Robertson said.
Previously, appeal processes could be reviewed at two
administrative levels.
   An estimated 2.2 billion board feet of national forest timber
were destroyed or damaged in California and Oregon in the 1987 fire
season, with about 40 percent of that volume offered for sale, he
said.
   ``A delay in fire-caused salvage sales and related
rehabilitation activities in California and Oregon could result in
unnecessary losses of valuable natural resources,'' Robertson said.
   The fires disrupted the timber sale programs of several national
forests, he said. As a result, the economies of timber-dependent
communities in the burned areas could suffer from delays in salvage
and rehabilitation work.
</TEXT>
