<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--HistoricStatues     05-12 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Historic Statues,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bunyan, Babe Statues Make National Register</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEMIDJI, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Huge statues of Paul Bunyan and his ox,
Babe, have been listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
   ``It's about time Paul got the recognition he deserves,'' said
Doug Peterson, mayor of this northwestern Minnesota city.
``Everyone has had their pictures taken with them,'' he said
Wednesday.
   The statues of 18-foot-tall Paul and 23-foot-long Babe became
eligible for the National Register after passing their 50th
birthday last year, according to National Park Service guidelines.
   Inclusion is made for historic or aesthetic merit.
   According to Susan Roth of the state historical society, the
National Register listing was awarded to the steel and concrete
statues in March because of their long-time role in promoting
tourism in the area.
   Peterson said Bemidji is planning to celebrate the statues' new
significance with the unveiling of a plaque at the end of the month.
</TEXT>
