<1ST_LINE>r p AM-California-Underdogs Bjt   05-12 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-California-Underdogs, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Strong in California, But Demographics Good for Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California Democrats are likely to go for the
favorite next month, abandoning their longtime penchant for backing
underdogs in presidential primaries, pollsters say. But the
tradition may not succumb without a fight.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis is substantially ahead of
Jesse Jackson in opinion polls, most recently in a Gallup survey
this week giving Dukakis 67 percent to 26 percent for Jackson and 7
percent undecided.
   But if Dukakis is the heavy favorite to win, pollsters said in
recent interviews, Jackson still may do better than his recent
finishes, perhaps well enough to boost his influence at the party's
convention in Atlanta.
   ``I would be extremely surprised if Jackson got over 40
percent,'' said I.A. Lewis, chief of polling for The Los Angeles
Times.
   While that strong a showing is by no means assured, pollsters
say there are several reasons Jackson could do well in California
on June 7. One is demographics: Many of the voters fit the profile
of Jackson supporters. Another is history: Jackson, who has found
support from whites elusive, did his best on that score in his 1984
campaign with California whites.
   Yet another factor is a decreased expectation that Jackson can
win the nomination. Several analysts said dissatisfied Democrats
may be more likely to cast a protest vote for Jackson when it
appears he cannot actually win.
   ``When you don't think Jackson is a viable nominee he gets a
better vote than when you do,'' said Lewis. He noted that Jackson's
support from whites fell off after the Wisconsin primary, when he
looked strong. But after losing a series of landslides, Jackson got
24 percent of the white vote in Nebraska this week, his second-best
showing among whites all year.
   Given the liberalism of many California Democrats, ``there's a
number of people that would like to give him bargaining chips in
Atlanta by his showing well here _ people who may not want him to
be president but want to give him some clout,'' Lewis said.
   Any added clout from second place would stem from vote totals
rather than the delegate count; the primary is a winner-take-all
contest, with delegates awarded only to the first-place finisher in
each congressional district.
   Pollsters stressed that a victory by Jackson in California would
be exceedingly difficult, even with his plans to campaign heavily
in the state. Blacks, who have been giving him support in the
90-percent range, made up only about 15 percent of the primary
electorate in 1984, and Jackson has not increased blacks' share of
the vote in most other states.
   Jackson in 1984 won four of the state's 45 congressional
districts and received 21 percent of the vote statewide.
``Conventional wisdom is that Jackson should do better than four
years ago, but not dramatically,'' said California-based pollster
Mervin Field. He said Jackson may be hurt by his recent losses
while Dukakis is fueled by his run of wins.
   Still, Lewis noted that California Democrats have a history of
backing the anti-establishment candidate. California went for Gary
Hart over front-runner Walter Mondale in 1984, Edward Kennedy over
President Carter in 1980, favorite son Gov. Jerry Brown over Carter
in 1976, and George McGovern over Hubert Humphrey in 1972.
   Added pollster Gordon Black: ``The Democratic Party there is
more liberal than the Democratic Party in the rest of the country.''
   John Brennan, a poll analyst for ABC News, noted that four years
ago 45 percent of the Democratic voters in California identified
themselves as liberals, 24 percent were under 30 and 40 percent
were college graduates _ all groups in which Jackson has done his
best among white voters.
   ``It's got good demographics for Jackson,'' Brennan said. He
said a 1984 ABC News exit poll found that Jackson got 13 percent of
the white vote in California, the only state that year in which he
reached double digits.
   That poll said 7 percent of the vote in 1984 was Jewish, and
Jackson has fared poorly among Jews because of concern about his
position on Israel.
   But homosexuals could make up 5 percent of the vote and may
favor Jackson because of Dukakis' resistance to homosexual couples
as adoptive parents.
   Hispanics made up 9 percent of the electorate in 1984 in the ABC
poll. Jackson lost Hispanics badly to the Spanish-speaking Dukakis
in Texas this year, with 60 percent for Dukakis and 20 percent for
Jackson in an ABC poll.
   Still, Brennan noted that the 1984 California electorate was
only 25 percent Catholic and one-third blue collar, groups that
Dukakis has been winning. And the primary is closed, meaning
independents, who have backed Dukakis, can't vote.
   If the black vote reaches 20 percent and goes entirely to
Jackson, he still would need 31 percent of the remainder to beat
Dukakis _ a level of non-black votes that he has achieved only in
one state this year, Vermont.
</TEXT>
