<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PotholeSettlement     05-12 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pothole Settlement,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pothole Settlement Costs Dallas Nearly $1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A potholed street has cost Dallas almost $1
million in a settlement that nearly wiped out its litigation
reserve fund, officials said.
   City Council approved, by a 5-2 vote Wednesday, a $969,000
settlement with a man whose wife was killed three years ago by a
motorist who swerved after hitting a pothole.
   In a suit in state district court, the family of A. Glennie
Mayer of Rowlett had sought $2.4 million from the city for failing
to fill the pothole, which was about 8 inches deep and 3 feet
across.
   The suit contended the city had been negligent because it failed
to properly maintain the street despite a complaint filed with the
Streets and Sanitation Department.
   City Attorney Analeslie Muncy said the city's litigation fund
has ``just a little'' more than $1 million, which must last until
Sept. 30, the end of the fiscal year.
   In 1985, there was no state limit on death claims resulting from
faulty street maintenance. The state's 1987 tort reform law set a
$250,000 limit.
   The lawsuit, filed by Robert E. Mayer, stems from a Nov. 18,
1985, accident that killed Mrs. Mayer, 48.
   Under Texas law, a city may be held liable for an accident
caused by a pothole only if a complaint has been filed and there
was time for crews to fill it.
</TEXT>
