<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LehderTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0507 05-12 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Ends Closing Arguments</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with defense ending closing
arguments. Picks up in 10th graf, `The issue ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense ended its closing
arguments today in the cocaine-smuggling trial of Carlos Lehder
Rivas, ridiculing prosecutors for trying to make the Colombian
appear responsible for the nation's drug problem.
   ``If that is true, you could lock up the doors to this
courthouse and tear down all the `Just Say No,' signs,'' defense
attorney Edward Shohat said, referring to a national anti-drug week
campaign.
   Shohat urged the jury to make an independent judgment about the
charges against Lehder, saying ``The government does not own the
jury _ noboby owns the jury.''
   Counsel for Lender's co-defendant, Jack Carlton Reed, also was
expected to finish his closing arguments today, followed by a
rebuttal from U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle. The case was scheduled
to go to the jury Friday.
   Lehder, 38, and Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., are charged with
conspiring to smuggle about 3.3 tons of cocaine into the United
States from Colombia via Lehder's private Bahamian island, Norman's
Cay, from 1978 to 1980.
   A separate Miami indictment accuses Lehder of being one of the
leaders of the so-called Medellin cartel, a violent Colombian
smuggling ring believed to be responsible for a major portion of
the cocaine entering the United States.
   Shohat spent this morning hammering again at what he said were
inconsistencies in the testimony of government witnesses, many of
whom were admitted smugglers given immunity for their testimony.
   On Wednesday, Shohat said chief prosecution witness, convicted
smuggler Ed Ward, was ``given the break of a lifetime'' for his
testimony against Lehder.
   By agreeing to cooperate with the government, Ward was able to
reduce a possible 215-year sentence and $5.9 million fine to less
than six years in prison, Shohat said.
   Shohat reviewed what he termed ``the litany of lies'' testified
to by several members of Ward's group of American smugglers.
   ``These people planned to dump on Mr. Lehder. These people knew
how to get an American Express card to freedom,'' he said.
   ``You can't believe any of these people without hesitation,''
the defense attorney said.
   Shohat urged the panel to focus on the actual charges listed
against Lehder in the indictment and not what he called the
government's attacks on his character.
   ``The issue is not whether Mr. Lehder was good or bad. The issue
in this case is the 11 counts in the indictment,'' said Shohat.
   He said the actual charges were discussed in only five weeks of
the 22-week case.
   ``Mr. Lehder has no burden of proof. It is the obligation of the
prosecutors to prove Lehder guilty beyond a reasonable doubt,'' he
said.
   Winding up his prosecution arguments Wednesday, Merkle referred
to testimony that Lehder used bribes, charm and threats to run a
smuggling empire. For once, Merkle said, Lehder couldn't use such
tools.
   ``He cannot buy his way out of a just verdict. He cannot charm
his way out of a just verdict. And he cannot force his way out of a
just verdict,'' Merkle said.
   The prosecutor said Lehder was responsible for smuggling 19 tons
of cocaine into the United States, earning him $20 million.
   Lehder was captured in February 1987 at a mansion near the town
of Medellin after a shootout between Colombian army troops and his
bodyguards. He was whisked onto a U.S. Air Force plane for the
United States.
   The prosecution called 115 witnesses in the trial, which began
in October. Last week, defense attorneys surprised the courtroom by
announcing they would call no witnesses.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. Reed is charged with conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
