<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House will quickly follow up
President Reagan's veto of the wide-ranging trade bill with
attempts to get another form of the legislation passed, President
Reagan's spokesman said today.
   ``We wil seek to get a new bill,'' Fitzwater said as the bill
was being analyzed by administration officials in advance of
Reagan's promised veto. ``At the moment, the plan is to talk to the
(congressional) leadership and see what happens.''
   Fitzwater, as he has previously, refused to say what form the
administration believes a trade bill should take, although he
indicated there is no White House interest in trying to salvage a
plant-closing provision.
   Democrats had sent their 1,000-page bill toward the against international
trade violations.
   At the rally, House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., warned
that if Reagan vetoed the measure, Democrats will attempt to
override the action ``and we have the votes to do it.''
   The measure cleared the House by a 312-107 margin, more than the
two-thirds needed to override a presidential veto.
   But it passed the Senate only by 63-36, three votes short of the
two-thirds needed. Democrats conceded they remained unsure of just
where the remaining support could be found.
   ``We'll consult the stars,'' cracked Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.
   Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., the former presidential
candidate, appeared at the rally and declared: ``The president
should sign the bill.''
   When reminded that he had voted against the legislation,
Gephardt said that was due to special circumstances _ House-Senate
conferees had dropped his plan for mandatory trade retaliation
against countries running large trade surpluses with the United
States.
