<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--AirForceBase     05-12 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Air Force Base,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arkansas Air Force Base Renamed After Aviation Pioneer, Ira C.
Eaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force announced Thursday it would
change the name of Blytheville Air Force Base in Arkansas later
this month to honor aviation pioneer and World War II hero Gen. Ira
C. Eaker.
   The change in name to Eaker Air Force Base will occur during
ceremonies May 26 at the facility, the Air Force said. Gen. Larry
D. Welch, the service's chief of staff, will preside.
   The Blytheville base was first established as an Army Air Force
pilot training school in 1942. The Strategic Air Command assumed
control of the facility in 1958 and it currently is the home of the
97th Bombardment Wing and the 42nd Air Division.
   Eaker, who died last August, received a Congressional Gold Medal
for his accomplishments in aviation and the military. He
established a world record for flight endurance in 1929 and then
participated in the first transcontinental flight using aerial
refueling techniques in 1930.
   During World War II, he commanded the Eighth Air Force and later
all U.S. Army Air Forces in Britain. Eaker became
commander-in-chief of the Mediterranean Allied Air Forces in 1944.
   Eaker retired from the Air Force in 1947 and worked later as the
head of the Hughes Aircraft Co. and as a vice president and
director of the Douglas Aircraft Co.
</TEXT>
