<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cover of Prince's new album,
``Lovesexy,'' reveals most of the rock star, but it may not be easy
to find.
   ``Between 75 (percent) and 90 percent of our customers are going
to take a pass on it,'' said David Lieberman, chairman of
Bloomington-based Lieberman Enterprises, which stocks record
departments in such department and discount stores as Sears,
Wal-Mart, Pamida and ShopKo.
   ``They find it objectionable. They sell general merchandise.
They're very sensitive to their customers' sensibilities,''
Lieberman said.
   He declined to specify which stores would not sell ``Lovesexy,''
which has a cover photo of Prince in the nude, his legs
strategically placed.
   The album was scheduled to arrive in record outlets Tuesday, but
many stores nationwide, including the Target chain, have rejected
it, the Star Tribune of Minneapolis reported Thursday. Other shops
will stock the album but keep it behind the counter, the newspaper
said.
   ``We're surprised at the reaction,'' said Alan Leeds, operations
manager for PRN Productions, Prince's Chanhassen-based business
operation. ``The cover represents what he wants it to represent. If
it's misconstrued, it's just part of the risk of being an artist.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disc jockey ``Cousin Brucie'' Morrow, fight
announcer Don Dunphy and ``The Inner Sanctum'' producer Himan Brown
will relive some of their radio days Tuesday when they are inducted
into the first Emerson Radio Hall of Fame.
   In the ceremony at the Empire State Building, the three will be
honored along with 15 others, from radio pioneers like CBS Inc.
founder William S. Paley to the late Orson Welles of the ``Mercury
Theater on the Air.''
   Morrow, whose peppy voice introduced millions of American
teen-agers to groups from the Beach Boys to the Beatles, will share
the radio personality category with Martin Block of ``The
Make-Believe Ballroom.'' Dunphy will share honors in the
sportscasters category with Bill Stern, while Brown will hold down
the mystery-suspense award on his own.
   There will be an exhibition, including radio memorabilia, at the
Empire State Building in June. Then Emerson Radio Corp. will move
the exhibition to its headquarters in New Jersey until a permanent
location is found.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jerry Lewis will be honored at
a dinner June 23 for his efforts to raise money to battle muscular
dystrophy.
   Lewis, host of an annual Labor Day telethon to generate funds
for ``Jerry's kids,'' will receive the Harry Zimmerman Memorial
Award.
   Zimmerman was the founder of Nashville-based Service Merchandise
and was active in fund-raising and educating the public about
muscular dystrophy. A dinner last year raised $550,000 to benefit
the Muscular Dystrophy Association.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secrets of success aren't secrets
anymore to a group of eighth-graders who went right to some of
America's most famous figures for advice.
   ``To me, what makes someone successful is managing a healthy
combination of wishing and doing,'' Fred Rogers, of ``Mr. Rogers''
television fame wrote to the class at Roosevelt Middle School.
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca had other suggestions.
   ``I have found that in order to become successful, you must
determine what you want, and then be willing to work tirelessly to
reach your goal,'' he wrote.
   Decatur native James B. Parsons, the first black federal judge,
advised students they should always have ``a readiness to grasp and
hold on to the hand of someone stronger, a hand held out to help
me.''
   The class wrote to celebrities seeking advice. They put together
copies of the responses and excerpts from interviews they conducted
in a booklet titled ``Successfully Yours,'' distributed to all
Roosevelt eighth-graders.
