<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie ``Dead Heat'' might be dead meat by
the time actor Joe Piscopo gets done promoting it.
   ``It's an interesting thing because it's not really my kind of
film. I want to just wholeheartedly say, `It's the greatest thing
in the world,' but there's too much blood and violence in it for
me,'' Piscopo said during a West Coast visit.
   The movie, about a live police officer and a dead one who try to
catch the man who killed and resurrected the dead cop, opened
Friday to poor reviews. The dead character, portrayed by Treat
Williams, decomposes during the film.
   Piscopo, who rose to fame on television's ``Saturday Night
Live'' and now stars in a number of beer commercials, said most
comedy roles are those of losers.
   ``I don't want to be another (jerk) on the screen. That's why I
did `Dead Heat,' because it's a real (physical) role,'' he said.
   But it wasn't the right role for him, he said, noting that even
``a guy as brilliant as Robin Williams'' did half a dozen films
before he found the right role in ``Good Morning, Vietnam.''
