<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Norco-Asbestos     05-12 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norco-Asbestos,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norco Blast Scattered Asbestos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORCO, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shell Oil Co. workmen with respirator gear
Thursday were gathering asbestos scattered by last week's refinery
explosion that killed seven people, state officials said.
   Mike McDaniel, a Department of Environmental Quality assistant
secretary, revealed Wednesday that asbestos, which has been linked
to lung cancer and lung disease, was dispersed with other debris by
the blast at the Shell plant.
   Debris containing asbestos has been found near the plant on the
east bank of the Mississippi River, as well as on the west bank in
Boutte, McDaniel said.
   Residents who find debris should leave it alone and contact
Shell, he said.
   Gus Von Bodungen of the state's air quality division said he
doubts any public exposure to asbestos from the blast has been
serious.
   But the Department of Environmental Quality does not know how
much asbestos was scattered or how many people may have come in
contact with it.
   State personnel are surveying both sides of the river to
determine how wide dispersal of the fibers has been.
   The pre-dawn explosion at the refinery plant injured 42 people
and damaged homes in Norco. It was felt as far as 40 miles away and
caused minor damage in New Orleans, 20 miles away.
</TEXT>
