<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Matti Viio takes a flying leap, he's just
advertising.
   Viio, 49, was showing off a new safety vest and tether he
designed in front of police, Coast Guardsmen, city River Rescue
officials and passers-by.
   The Swedish inventor climbed atop a 10-foot ladder Wednesday on
the Sixth Street Bridge. When a co-worker leaned the ladder to the
edge, Viio allowed himself to fall until the tether and vest broke
his plunge about 20 feet below the bridge.
   Hanging over the water, Viio then pulled out a newspaper and
pretended to read it.
   ``I always prove my products. I never release a product if I am
not willing to wear it myself,'' Viio said, adding that he also
wanted to draw attention to his recently opened U.S. manufacturing
plant in nearby Butler.
   Viio's safety vest is sold in Europe, but is not yet sold in the
United States. His jump had the approval of the city's Department
of Public Safety.
   ``We were kind of curious to see it,'' said public safety
official Craig Merritt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surfing could become an endangered sport
in this affluent community.
   Surfers have lost privileges to park in two popular spots where
they've gathered for years because of complaints about public
nudity and disturbing the peace.
   The Town Council on Wednesday banned surfers and other
beachgoers from parking along a 250-foot stretch of road a block
from the beach. The surfers recently lost parking privileges at
another popular spot.
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said Garrett Andrews, 19, who has been
surfing in the area for six years. ``It's getting so that we can't
go anywhere.''
