<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Attack Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with identity of base,
details. Pick up 5th pvs, `Forty-nine people...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes blasted a Palestinian
guerrilla base south of Beirut today in the eighth air raid on
Lebanon this year, police said.
   They said six fighter-bombers rocketed the targets near the
Kharroub region town of Barja in three bombing runs. Barja is 16
miles south of Beirut.
   The raid began at 6:05 p.m. and lasted 10 minutes. There was no
immediate report of casualties or damage.
   Police said the target appeared to be a base of the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   They said from the Lebanese port of Sidon, nine miles south of
Barja, that smoke could be seen billowing from the bombed base.
   In Jerusalem, the military command said Israeli warplanes raided
guerrilla bases north of Sidon. The brief statement said all
Israeli planes returned safely to their bases and that pilots
reported accurate hits on their targets.
   The attacking planes drew anti-aircraft fire, but no hits were
claimed, the Lebanese police said.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command, headed by former Syrian army Captain Ahmed Jibril, is
based in Syria and bankrolled by Libya.
   The group has claimed responsibility for an attack into northern
Israel last November in which a guerrilla flying a motorized hang
glider killed six Israeli soldiers and wounded eight before he was
shot dead.
   Forty-nine people were killed and 71 wounded in the seven
previous Israeli air raids this year. In the last raid May 9, which
Israel never confirmed, helicopter gunships pounded the southern
Lebanese village of Kabrikha, destroying a house.
   Security sources said the house might have been used by
guerrillas to launch cross-border attacks into northern Israel.
</TEXT>
