<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PlantFire 1stLd-Writethru a0608 05-12 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead, Eight Injured In Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout, one dead, more details on blast</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire at a metals plant today
killed one person, injured at least eight others and prompted the
evacuation of neighboring businesses, officials said.
   Fire Chief James McNamee said the fire started in a metal dust
collector at the Mineral Met Inc. plant on the city's east side.
   ``The dust collector blew up and spread these flaming metal
chips and debris all over and started the fire,'' said McNamee.
   ``The whole building shook,'' said Clark Oil & Chemical Co.
sales representative Linda Weiss, in a building across the street.
``It (fire) was shooting out of the top of the building.''
   Denise Sobola, a secretary at Mineral Met, said there were 29
people in the plant when the blast hit. The dead man was identified
only as a temporary worker hired from an employment service.
   The plant processes powdered metal into a substance used in
metal rod coatings, workers said.
   ``I think my ceiling fell in _ I'm not sure _ behind me. But I
just ran out the side door,'' said Ms. Sobola. She said workers
were ``just running out and collapsing outside the doors.''
   A hazardous materials team of the Cleveland Fire Department was
at the scene. The fire was controlled about noon.
   ``The dust was so heavy you couldn't see in front of your
face,'' said Mark Eakman, a chemist for Clark. He described the
Mineral Met building as a one-story concrete block structure.
   Kim Chambers, a supervisor at Precision Coating, next door to
Mineral Met, said he saw a cloud of smoke before the explosion.
   ``It just went boom. It shattered the windows upstairs in the
(Precision Coating) building,'' he said. Chambers said he helped a
truck driver off the street who hurt his leg running from the
Mineral Met building.
   Sue Dawson, spokeswoman for Cleveland Metropolitan General
Hospital, said six people were being treated there. Two were in
fair condition and one was in good condition; the conditions of the
other three were not released.
   Maria Tayek, spokeswoman for St. Vincent Charity Hospital, said
two men were being treated there. She said the victims included a
34-year-old man in stable condition with an injured left foot and a
40-year-old man in good condition with injuries to his right leg
and back.
</TEXT>
