<DOCNO> AP880512-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Philby     05-12 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Philby,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Eulogize Philby As Super-Spy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Spy Legacy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tass news agency eulogized Harold ``Kim''
Philby on Thursday as a master spy who carried out heroic and
seemingly impossible feats to protect the Soviet Union from Western
agents.
   Philby died Wednesday in Moscow, where he had lived since
defecting to the Soviet Union in 1963. As a rising star in British
intelligence, the upper crust Englishman spied for the Soviets for
26 years. He eventually became a decorated KGB officer.
   ``On May 11, 1988, in the 77th year of his life, the remarkable
Soviet intelligence officer Kim Philby died,'' the official news
agency reported in a brief dispatch.
   Tass did not elaborate on the circumstances of Philby's death or
say where it occurred. The British Foreign Office said Wednesday
that Philby had died in Moscow.
   With three colleagues, Donald Maclean, Guy Burgess and Anthony
Blunt, the Cambridge-educated Philby turned Britain's most precious
secrets over to the Kremlin.
   ``For a long time, Kim Philby was engaged in exceptionally
delicate work, or, better said, a struggle directly within the
special services of the capitalist countries whose thrust was
spearheaded against the Soviet Union and the world's progressive
movement,'' Tass said.
   ``These were years of truly Titanic nervous stress which
required the whole of his spiritual and physical forces,'' Tass
said. ``Not infrequently Philby was able to accomplish things which
seemed well-nigh impossible to achieve.''
   Tass called Philby's activities ``heroic'' and ``multifaceted
and vast in their geographic sweep.''
   ``In 1963, having successfully accomplished a regular
assignment, Kim Philby came to Moscow, where he continued the work
that had become the reason and content of his entire life,'' Tass
said.
   ``Being an internationalist, Kim Philby loved his own English
people, valued their spiritual richnesses and believed in their
happy future,'' Tass said.
   While spying for Moscow, Philby sent many Western agents to
their deaths. He was even able to head off the defection of a
Soviet diplomat who threatened to expose him.
   For his services to Soviet intelligence, Philby was awarded the
nation's highest decoration, the Order of Lenin, and other awards
including the Red Banner and the Order of the Patriotic War, First
Class, Tass said.
   After an initial hero's welcome in Moscow, Philby sank into
obscurity and confessed in an interview with a British newspaper
earlier this year that he went through depression and began
drinking heavily when he believed that the Soviet KGB had no
further use for him.
   But Philby told Phillip Knightley of the Sunday Times in his
first and only interview with a Western publication since his
defection that he had no regrets, except for personal friends he
had lost.
   Asked ``Would you do it all again?'' Philby replied,
``Absolutely.''
   Philby said then that he had found peace, was happy in his
fourth marriage, to a Soviet woman, and that he felt at home in the
Soviet Union.
   He told Radio Moscow last November he wanted to be buried in the
Soviet Union, ``which I considered to be my country since the
1930s.''
   The Tass announcement of his death gave no details of funeral
arrangements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0145 </DOCNO>
