<1ST_LINE>u a PM-WorkersShot 1stLd-Writethru a0654 05-12 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Workers Shot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Shoots Two Workers At Food Distribution Company</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New thruout, CORRECTS that man arrested is an independent
trucker, not employee and that authorities still are investigating
the cause of the truck fire; fixes byline; adds quotes, new details</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck driver shot two workers at a
food distribution company at close range today, critically injuring
both before he gave himself up, officials said.
   Police said the gunman, an independent trucker from Missouri,
went to the Wilson Certified Express company and shot Larry Fritz
Meyer, 30, of Des Moines, and Jack Jones, 39, of Friendswood,
Texas, with a .380-caliber pistol.
   Charged with two counts of attempted murder was Sam Lacy, 48, of
Blue Springs, Mo., police said.
   As he was being led away, Lacy yelled to reporters that the
company had discriminated against him and taken everything away
from him.
   Authorities said that just before the shooting, Lacy's truck
tractor was found destroyed by fire in a parking lot behind a
nearby store. The state fire marshal's office was investigating the
cause of the fire.
   The sheriff's office said a load of oranges and lemons that Lacy
was supposed to be driving from California to Wisconsin had not
been located.
   Glenn McDole, chief of the Polk County Patrol Division, said
that after the shooting, Lacy handed ammunition to a receptionist
and put his gun down on a bookcase. After his arrest Lacy said he
would not talk to anyone but his wife, McDole said.
   ``The company called us. We had an officer near by. He (the
suspect) laid the gun down, and went and sat down and gave up,''
said McDole.
   ``We kind of locked our doors and stayed inside,'' said a
receptionist at Mid-Continent Bottlers, a company which shares the
office building with Wilson.
   Meyer was reported in critical condition at Iowa Methodist
Medical Center, suffering from two gunshot wounds to the chest,
while Jones also was in critical condition at Mercy Hospital
Medical Center with a single chest wound.
   A man answering the telephone at the company said there would be
no immediate comment. As employees left the building, they told
reporters they had been instructed not to comment.
</TEXT>
