<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MultipleKillings 5thLd-Writethru a0664 05-12 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Multiple Killings, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0664,0886</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simmons Convicted In Christmas Holiday Slayings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs, exact length of deliberations, reaction,
packed courtroom, picking up 6th graf pvs, ``Simmons, 47 xxx; SUBS
10th graf, ``The state rested xxx, to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of the Christmas holiday
slayings of 14 relatives and two other people was convicted today
of capital murder and five counts of attempted capital murder.
   R. Gene Simmons' defense had rested this morning without
presenting any evidence. The jury deliberated for 84 minutes.
   Simmons was on trial for a Dec. 28 rampage that left two people
dead and four injured. He is to be tried in the other 14 killings
in July.
   Capital murder applies to crimes involving multiple killings
under Arkansas law, and the jury was to consider the sentence this
afternoon. There are only two sentences for a person convicted of
capital murder _ life imprisonment without parole or death.
   The circuit court jury also reduced a kidnapping charge to
first-degree false imprisonment and convicted Simmons on that
charge. The attempted murder charges referred to the four people
Simmons wounded, plus another person who was fired at but was not
hit.
   Circuit Court Judge John S. Patterson read the jury's verdicts
to a standing room only crowd of about 100.
   Viola O'Shields, and her husband, Roger, relatives of some of
the Simmons' family victims, were pleased. Tears welling in her
eyes, Mrs. O'Shields displayed a photograph of Simmons' late
17-year-old Loretta and said, ``Isn't it a shame.''
   Simmons, 47, had no immediate reaction to the verdict.
   ``The evidence in this case is strong; it's stout,'' said
Prosecutor John Bynum during a 32-minute closing statement this
morning.
   The defense's closing argument lasted 34 minutes, most of it by
Robert E. ``Doc'' Irwin, who contended that there was a lack of
evidence to support a contention of premeditation and deliberation.
   Irwin also said there were no tests to link Simmons to the
murder weapons and other evidence. Bynum said such tests were
unnecessary when witnesses testified about details and the police
chief had testified that Simmons handed him the murder weapon.
   The state rested late Wednesday and Patterson denied defense
motions for directed verdicts and dismissal of the charges. The
defense rested this morning.
   A route salesman who chatted with Simmons testified Wednesday
that a month before the Christmas-time killings began, Simmons was
talking about settling some scores.
   Simmons ``said he had a few people in town he would like to get
even with,'' Paul Epperson, 49, told the jury. ``Rusty Taylor was
the only name he called.''
   The state contends that on Dec. 28, 1987, Simmons shot six
people, including Taylor; two of the six died. After Simmons
surrendered, police searched his home and found the bodies of 14
family members, all shot to death or strangled.
   Epperson was the last of 30 state witnesses who testified in
Franklin County Circuit Court in the trial of Simmons on a charge
of capital murder for the slaying of two people plus five counts of
attempted capital murder and one count of kidnapping. Simmons could
face the death penalty if convicted.
   Epperson said his talk with Simmons, 47, took place in a small
Russellville market where Simmons was a cashier and to which
Epperson delivered bread and cake on a daily route.
   A state ballistics expert, Paul McDonald, testified that
markings on bullets taken from the two murder victims showed they
had been fired by the same nine-shot revolver that Simmons handed
to police when he surrendered.
   Killed were Kathy Kendrick, 24, at a Russellville law firm where
she worked and James Chaffin, 33, at a Russellville oil company. A
man also was wounded and a woman shot at, but not hit, at the oil
company.
   Police said Ms. Kendrick once refused Simmons' amorous
attentions.
   Bullets recovered from the market, where Simmons had quit his
job 10 days before the shooting, came from the same pistol,
McDonald said. Two people were wounded at the market.
   Simmons also allegedly shot a former co-worker at a freight
company, Joyce Butts.
   Mrs. Butts, whose husband assisted her to and from the witness
box, said she and Simmons once had a bad encounter while they
worked together. Later, after she told him to do a better job with
some of the accounts he was handling, ``he got angry,'' she said.
``He screamed. He shouted acrss the office that he didn't get paid
enough,'' which led to a discussion about how he had treated her on
that previous occasion.
   Mrs. Butts was shot in the back of the head and the bullet went
into her heart, for which she underwent open heart surgery. The
shooting let her unable to bend her left leg and with poor vision.
   Vicki Jackson, who the state says was taken hostage at the
freight company after Mrs. Butts was shot, testified earlier
Wednesday.
   ``Vicki, I'm not going to hurt you,'' Ms. Jackson said Simmons
told her as he held a gun to her temple. ``I came to kill Joyce. I
got everybody that hurt me. I'm not going to hurt you.''
</TEXT>
