<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SpyLegacy 1stLd-Writethru a0645 05-12 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spy Legacy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0855</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Archtraitor is Dead, but Questions Linger</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th `His network' to include Anthony
Blunt, the ``fourth man''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold ``Kim'' Philby is dead, but the bitter
aftertaste of his colossal betrayal still lingers in Britain.
   Even 25 years after the privileged English gentleman was
unmasked as Moscow's highest-placed mole in Western intelligence,
central questions remain unanswered:
   Were there others of higher rank? Were the operations of Western
intelligence agencies compromised more seriously than they realize?
When Philby gave his only interview to a Western journalist four
months before he died, was it part of a new plot by his KGB masters
to discredit the British and undermine their relationship with
Washington?
   A tribute to Philby came Thursday, the day after he died at age
76, from Peter Wright, a former British intelligence officer.
   Wright has done much to keep the scandal alive with his
allegation that an even higher mole existed: the late Sir Roger
Hollis, who directed the MI5 security service from 1956 to 1965.
Wright's claim is in his volume of memoirs, called ``Spycatcher,''
which is banned in Britain.
   In a statement from Australia, where he now lives, Wright called
Philby ``an outstanding man in the intelligence world.''
   Philby became a Soviet agent while at Cambridge University in
the 1930s, joined the secret service and rose to high rank. He was
believed to be in line to head MI6, the sister service of MI5.
   His network unraveled in 1951 with the defection of Guy Burgess
and Donald Maclean to Moscow, but Philby escaped exposure for 12
more years. In 1963 he, too, defected.
   In 1964 the ``fourth man,'' Anthony Blunt, confessed he had
worked for the Soviets while in MI5 and received immunity in
exchange for information about the other three. His treason was
kept secret and he eventually became art adviser to Queen Elizabeth
II, receiving a knighthood.
   Blunt's past was made public in 1979 and he was stripped of his
honors. He died in London in 1983.
   The damage to British security, which shared secrets with
Washington, is incalculable. Now that all four of ``Stalin's
Englishmen'' finally are dead, the suspicion persists that there
were five.
   Wright's claim about Hollis, whether true or not, illustrates
the doubt that still eats at the British security services because
of Philby's treachery.
   ``It's bad for morale, and it's actually bad for operations,''
said Rupert Allason, a Conservative member of Parliament and who
writes histories and analyses of espionage under the name Nigel
West.
   He said the suspicions mean intelligence analysts must ask
themselves constantly whether the files they use contain ``tainted
information'' left by the traitors.
   Philby still was a KGB officer when he died, and intelligence
experts here believe the lengthy interview he gave in January to
Phillip Knightley of The Sunday Times was a KGB operation.
   ``The Soviets had things in mind that they wanted to
accomplish,'' said Miles Copeland, a retired CIA officer living in
England.
   Copeland and Allason, in separate interviews, said the purpose
was to revive U.S. suspicions of British intelligence generated by
the Philby affair.
   They pointed to remarks by Philby to Knightley in which he
hinted that other traitors remained in British intelligence and
that the British could not be trusted to keep secrets.
   Allason said Philby had clearly hinted to Knightley that there
were other moles, still undiscovered.
   He also saw hidden purpose in letting Knightley see how
comfortable and privileged Philby was in his adopted homeland. ``It
was a carrot to other people'' who might want to defect, Allason
said.
   Copeland noted Philby's recollection of a British intelligence
official taking classified files with him when he retired. The
traitor's aim, Copeland thinks, was to show once again that secret
British files are not leakproof.
   Apart from all this is the question of what possessed this
epitome of the English gentry to devote himself to communism and
treachery.
   Author Malcolm Muggeridge, once a close friend, blamed the
double agent's father Harry St. John Philby, the celebrated
explorer and expert in Arabic.
   ``Kim could never be the towering figure his father was, so he
compensated for it by defying him and all he stood for in the most
appalling manner,'' Muggeridge told The Times of London.
   He called Philby ``a cad's cad.'' Allason called him ``a
grotesquely unpleasant man who betrayed everyone he came in contact
with, including his close friends and family.''
   Philby, born in India and raised in the Middle East, wrote that
he felt little conventional English patriotism. He said he embraced
communism at Cambridge because Britain was not challenging German
militarism, and communism alone seemed to offer resistance.
   An editorial in the conservative Daily Telegraph said he
deserved only contempt.
   ``The convention whereby the dead should be judged charitably
demands suspension in the case of Kim Philby,'' it said. ``He has
died impenitent, glorying in his own treason.''
</TEXT>
