<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Schools Bjt   05-12 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Schools, Bjt,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Children Attend Underground Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIR ZEIT, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers closed Arab schools
months ago, but children are back in class, reciting lessons in
unfinished buildings, mosques and churches with the added spice of
defying the Israeli occupiers.
   About 60 youngsters aged 6 to 12 study math, English, Arabic,
history and geography in bedrooms of an incomplete villa on a rocky
hillside _ peering out during the multiplication tables, as
children do, at yellow flowers in the valley.
   Secret schools are different, and to many students an adventure.
The children do not have to wear uniforms, classes are
coeducational, and some children from private Moslem and Christian
schools are studying together.
   The army closed all 820 West Bank schools Feb. 2, sending home
300,000 elementary and secondary students. Schools in the Gaza
Strip have been closed for days at a time, but the army has not
shut down the entire system.
   Israeli officials said schools had become assembly points for
the anti-Israeli rebellion that began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million
Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Leaflets issued this week by the uprising's clandestine
leadership urge more secret schools to get started. Those already
operating include half a dozen in Bir Zeit, 12 miles north of
Jerusalem.
   The underground schools symbolize the transformation of the
5-month-old revolt, which has claimed the lives of 186 Arabs and
two Israelis. There is far less street violence now, but the air of
defiance is little diminished.
   Teachers and students interviewed at the ``people's schools''
agreed that challenging Israel's authority was a significant reason
for organizing the classes.
   ``Because the Israelis closed the schools, we come here to show
that we can break their rules,'' said Amjad Shibli, 16. His school
``uniform'' was brown jeans and yellow and black running shoes.
   Amjad was among about 75 teen-agers attending high school
classes in an unfinished building behind the city hall. He said he
had spent the past three months working in his father's cafe and
sometimes joined other youths in throwing stones at Israeli
soldiers.
   Rocks intended to slow Israeli vehicles are scattered in streets
leading to the makeshift high school. The pavement near another
school had been blackened by bonfires of tires burned as protest
barricades.
   The military government, known as the Civil Administration,
closed four universities as well as the lower schools because many
protests began on the campuses.
   ``Schools were closed because the children didn't want to study.
They had become a place for disturbances and violence,'' said
Olivier Rabovitch, a spokesman for army administration.
   He said protests had decreased dramatically in recent weeks and
the schools might be allowed to reopen if the situation remained
calm.
   An Arab teacher who identified himself only as Professor M.
said: ``The Israelis have kept the schools closed as a general
punishment of the population.'' He is a lecturer at the shuttered
Bir Zeit University and organized most of the underground schools
that opened here two weeks ago.
   Thirty-seven parents, university graduates and laid-off
university teachers were recruited to conduct classes for several
hundred volunteer students in Bir Zeit, Professor M. said.
   He said regular teachers, who are Civil Administration
employees, refused to help because Israeli authorities threatened
to dismiss them.
   Professor M. acknowledged ``an element of challenge'' to the
army in organizing the schools, but he and other teachers said
their main concern was seeing that the children did not fall too
far behind in their studies.
   Although many classes are coeducational, some Moslem families
send their children to study in mosques, where boys attend in the
morning and girls in the afternoon.
   At the unfinished villa on the hill, Assad Sayegh, a 26-year-old
economics graduate of Bir Zeit University, was teaching math to 14
pupils aged aged 8 and 9 who sat in small chairs against the
unpainted concrete walls. His blackboard and textbooks were
spirited from the government school.
   Sayegh said the youngsters were taught the politics of the
``intefadeh,'' or uprising, but a reporter saw no evidence of
indoctrination in the classes visited.
   ``The government wants to keep the Palestinian people
empty-headed,'' Sayegh said. ``That way Palestinians can't make
bombs or fly airplanes. They want all the knowledge for themselves
so Palestinians can't destroy the Jewish government.''
</TEXT>
