<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HypnotizedBrain     05-12 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hypnotized Brain,0584</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Hypnosis Blocks Pain By Changing Brain's Functioning, Study
Suggests
^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who can make their hands go numb through
hypnosis show a marked change in brain waves, suggesting that a
trance blocks pain by altering the brain's processing of
information, a new study says.
   Hypnotized people who create a pain-blocking hallucination may
essentially be reducing the signal on normal sensory circuits and
turning instead to imagination-linked circuits, said researcher
David Spiegel.
   ``These findings provide evidence for the objective as well as
subjective reality'' of hypnotic hallucinations that affect the
sense of feel, Spiegel said Wednesday at the annual meeting of the
American Psychiatric Association.
   Hypnosis is a state of aroused and concentrated attention,
similar to getting lost in a good book. Scientists have known for a
century that hypnotism can reduce pain, but they do not know how.
   Spiegel said the new findings provide a starting point for
further exploration of the cause.
   He and two Stanford University colleagues studied 10 highly
hypnotizable people and 10 with little ability to enter a trance.
The brain waves were studied while a series of electrical impulses,
not quite strong enough to cause discomfort, was applied to their
left wrists.
   Each person went through the experience four times. Without
hypnosis, they were told at one time to simply pay attention to
what they felt, and at another time to press a button when they
felt slightly longer pulses.
   Another time, after a procedure to induce a trance, they were
told again to push a button when they felt the longer pulses.
   The fourth time, they were put into a trance and told to imagine
that a local anesthetic was spreading from the fingers of their
left hand up through the forearm. They were told to make the arm
cold, tingling and numb. Then they were told to press the button if
they felt any long electrical pulses.
   The hallucination was more effective in the highly hypnotizable
subjects, who pushed the button after only 38 percent of the long
pulses, than in the low hypnotizables, who felt 80 percent of the
long pulses.
   Without the hallucination, both groups responded to 86 percent
or more of the long pulses either with or without hypnosis.
   The brain waves studied are called ``cortical event-related
potentials,'' which reflect the brain's reponse to a stimulus.
   When researchers looked at the behavior of brain waves about a
tenth of a second after each electrical impulse, they found that in
highly hypnotizable people, the hallucination reduced brain wave
strength by about 45 percent from the level seen without hypnosis.
   In contrast, when the highly hypnotizable people were asked
under hypnosis to pay attention to the impulses, but not create the
numbness in their arm, the wave strength at the one-tenth second
mark rose 35 percent over the level without hypnosis.
   Brain waves in the low hypnotizables showed no such changes.
   The flexibility that the highly hypnotizable people showed in
adjusting the sensory input in the brain fits in well with the
ability of such people to reduce or eliminate pain with hypnosis,
Spiegel said.
   The results are ``a very interesting finding,'' said Fred
Frankel, psychiatrist in chief at Beth Israel Hospital in Boston
and psychiatry professor at Harvard Medical School.
   Previous work has shown brain wave differences in visual
hallucinations, he said Thursday in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
