<DOCNO> AP880512-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CloggedFreeways Bjt   05-12 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clogged Freeways, Bjt,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Governor Reports Firsthand on Massive Jams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dubbed ``Delta Duke,'' Gov. George Deukmejian
took to the roads and to the airwaves Thursday pushing a $1 billion
bond to unclog the nation's most congested roads.
   ``Today the governor is a Los Angeles commuter and a traffic
tipster,'' said anchorman Bill Zorn of KNX-AM, one of three radio
stations to broadcast Deukmejian's live traffic reports.
   During his hourlong, 32-mile commute from a hotel near his Long
Beach home to Beverly Hills, the governor crept through the West
Los Angeles junction of the San Diego and Santa Monica freeways,
which traffic officials have labeled the nation's busiest
interchange. Some 513,000 vehicles use it daily.
   The Republican governor wanted to demonstrate how California's
freeways, once the idyllic image of wide-open roadways ideal for
cruising, are now the nation's busiest.
   Transportation officials confirmed this week that nine of the
nation's 10 busiest freeway interchanges are in California.
   ``Just traveling along now on the San Diego Freeway, I'm taking
note of the fact there's only one person in each car. If we can
just increase that to 1.4 persons, we can relieve congestion during
the peak traffic hours,'' Deukmejian said.
   Deukmejian traveled in a telephone-equipped van, provided by the
state Office of Emergency Services, to a transportation hearing to
dramatize his support for a $1 billion bond issue on the June 7
ballot.
   Proposition 74 is the first phase of a $2.3 billion package of
supplemental financing for California highway improvements which
Deukmejian first proposed two years ago.
   He averaged 35 mph during the commute, but slowed to 5 mph at
one point where the Century Freeway is being constructed near Los
Angeles International Airport.
   ``We are approaching the El Segundo Boulevard exit. We're almost
at a standstill, moving 5 mph,'' he said.
   KNX-AM traffic reporter Bill Keene gave Deukmejian the handle
``Delta Duke'' for his traffic reporting stint, which was also
heard on KABC-AM and KGIL-AM.
   Deukmejian laughed, saying, ``Well, I've been called a lot
worse.''
   Hundreds of thousands of people move to the nation's
second-largest city each year. Roadway congestion became so bad
last summer that flare-ups among commuters resulted in a rash of
freeway shootings killing five and wounding 11.
   ``I'm aware of the frustration people have in the peak hours,''
Deukmejian said.
   California transportation officials who worked with the Federal
Highway Administration in Washington, D.C., said this week that six
of the country's 10 busiest interchanges are in Los Angeles County.
Two of the other top 10 spots were claimed by neighboring Orange
County.
   ``I looked at the numbers and said, `Holy mackerel!''' said
transportation engineer Chuck Pivetti. ``Ten years ago, all the top
spots would have been in New York, New Jersey and Chicago. Now we
have nearly all the spots. We're talking about some tremendous
volumes of traffic.''
   Behind the Santa Monica-San Diego freeway junction is the East
Los Angeles interchange of the Santa Monica, Golden State, Pomona
and Hollywood freeways, with 509,000 vehicles per day, and the
Santa Monica junction with the Harbor Freeway in Central Los
Angeles with 502,500 vehicles per day.
   The point where the Ventura and San Diego freeways meet in
Sherman Oaks claimed the fourth busiest spot with 480,000 cars per
day.
   The junction of the Eastshore, MacArthur and Nimitz freeways in
Alameda County in Northern California placed fifth in the
congestion lineup because it serves 455,000 vehicles per day.
   Another 444,000 drivers use the junction of the Harbor and San
Diego freeways in Carson, making it the sixth busiest interchange
in the country.
   The Santa Ana, Garden Grove and Orange freeways in Orange County
took seventh place with 441,000 vehicles a day, while the Orange
and Riverside freeways in Anaheim claimed ninth place with 421,000
vehicles a day. Both are in Orange County.
   The eighth spot was claimed by the Artesia and San Gabriel River
freeways in Cerritos, Los Angeles County, where 425,500 vehicles a
day pass through.
   An interchange in Chicago placed 10th.
</TEXT>
