<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     05-12 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truce Holds with Occasional Sniper Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truce ordered by Syria and Iran ended a
six-day battle between rival militias Thursday in which the radical
Hezbollah captured most of south Beirut's Shiite Moslem slums.
   Sniper fire was heard in the ramshackle 16 square miles adjacent
to the Beirut airport, but the howitzers and tank cannons were
silent. Police reported a woman killed and two other civilians
wounded in the Ghobeiri neighborhood.
   Police said 188 people were killed and 534 wounded in the battle
that began last Friday between the mainstream Amal militia, backed
by Syria, and Hezbollah, or Party of God, which is loyal to Iran.
   South of the capital, the Israeli air force blasted Palestinian
bases in its eighth raid into Lebanon this year. Police said six
fighter-bombers made three passes to rocket targets near Barja, 16
miles from Beirut. There were no reports of deaths or serious
injuries.
   The truce was ordered for 11 p.m. Wednesday after telephone
conversations between President Hafez Assad of Syria and President
Ali Khamenei of Iran.
   Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, spiritual leader of Hezbollah,
said he had no information about the 18 foreign hostages in
Lebanon, most of whom are believed held in the slums by groups
linked to Hezbollah. There has been no word of the foreigners, who
include nine Americans, since the fighting began.
   Although its fighting force was outnumbered 2-1, Hezbollah
appeared to have won the contest for supremacy. Police said it
controlled 70 percent of the slums when the fighting ended,
compared with about one-third when it began.
   Police estimated Hezbollah's fighting force at 3,000 men. They
said Amal put about 6,500 men into the field, about 2,000 brought
in from the Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley in east Lebanon.
   Syria has 25,000 soldiers in Lebanon and sent 7,500 of them to
Moslem west Beirut in February 1987 to stop factional war. Although
they patrol west Beirut, the Syrians have not entered the southern
Shiite slums.
   After 13 years of civil war, Assad was the undisputed power
broker in Lebanon until Iran began challenging Syrian influence
among the 1.2 million Shiites, the country's largest sect.
   Hezbollah denied police reports that 500 Iranian Revolutionary
Guards joined them in the slum war.
   A police spokesman said Amal lost ``most'' of its positions in
south Beirut. He said Amal moved its fighters to the edges of the
disputed area and Hezbollah took over the inner neighborhoods.
   Most of the 250,000 people who normally live in the southern
slums fled during the battle and more were planning to go despite
the truce.
   ``We don't trust cease-fires,'' a man who identified himself
only as Hussein told a reporter. ``I have five children and I've
already lost my home. I don't know where to go now. I don't think
the fighting will ever stop unless one side exterminates the
other.''
   Fadlallah spoke with journalists at his home, which was damaged
by artillery fire, in the Haret Hreik neighborhood. ``I think it's
over now because of the high-level solutions that are being worked
out by the presidents of Syria and Iran,'' he said.
   Asked about the foreigners, he replied: ``I have no information
about the hostages and I don't know anything about them. I don't
know where they are and, therefore, I can't answer your question.''
   He called Amal ``a local force that represents American
interests in the area.''
   Posters stuck on walls in districts Hezbollah had conquered
depicted Nabih Berri, Lebanon's justice minister and the Amal
leader, with vampire teeth over the slogan: ``The war criminal who
sold himself to the Great Satan,'' Iran's standard term for the
United States.
   Iranian flags were hoisted on positions formerly held by Amal.
   A four-man committee was formed to supervise the cease-fire,
under which the combatants were to withdraw from the streets and
free prisoners by Friday.
   Its members are Deputy Foreign Minister Hussein Sheikoleslam of
Iran; Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud, Syria's intelligence chief in west
Beiut, and one representative each of Amal and Hezbollah: Ayoub
Homayed and Hassan Khalil.
</TEXT>
