<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlantFire     05-12 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Fire,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant Explosion Kills One, Injures Eight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion spewed flaming metal chips
throughout an industrial plant Thursday, killing one worker and
injuring eight others, officials said.
   Businesses near the plant on the city's east side were evacuated
while firefighters worked to keep flames from spreading to a
warehouse containing powdered metals, including magnesium, titanium
and aluminum.
   ``The dust collector blew up and spread these flaming metal
chips and debris all over and started the fire,'' said Fire Chief
James McNamee.
   Firefighters found one worker's body in the Mineral Metals Inc.
plant after the fire was brought under control about noon, three
hours after it was reported.
   The victim's identity was not immediately available.
   Plant secretary Denise Sobola said there were 29 people in the
plant when the explosion occurred. The plant processes powdered
metal into a substance for welding rod coatings, workers said.
   Ms. Sobola said her office filled with dust and she ran out a
side door. She said workers were ``just running out and collapsing
outside the doors.''
   Ms. Sobola said there have been minor explosions at the plant in
the past that have spread dust throughout the plant. ``I knew this
time (it was worse). I heard glass busting and everything,'' she
said.
   Chemalloy Co. of Bryn Mawr, Pa., is the parent company of
Mineral Metals. Chemalloy President Anthony Demos was en route to
Cleveland on Thursday and not available for comment, his office
said.
   Six workers were treated at Cleveland Metropolitan General
Hospital for burns and smoke inhalation, said hospital spokeswoman
Terri Manns. One man was unconscious and in critical condition, she
said. Two men were treated at St. Vincent Charity Hospital,
spokesman Maria Tayek said.
</TEXT>
