<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AARPPresident     05-12 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AARP President,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Health Insurance Program Priority for AARP President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should direct its efforts
to providing health care for the chronically ill, says the new
president of the American Association of Retired Persons.
   ``We contend that national legislation based on a social
insurance approach is required so that the risk can be spread over
millions of working and retired persons,'' said Louise Crooks, 76,
who ascended to the presidency Wednesday during the biannual
meeting of the 28 million-member association.
   ``We must find a way to assure adequate health care for the
estimated 37 million Americans, who have no health care insurer
whatsoever, and expand and improve private pension plans so that
future generations of older Americans will have more adequate
retirement income,'' the West Lafayette, Ind., woman said.
   Among the health issues discussed at the convention was
Alzheimer's disease, a form of dementia that afflicts about 2
million elderly Americans. The disease's cure and cause remains
unknown.
   Dr. Gene Cohen, director of the Program on Aging at the National
Institute of Mental Health in Bethesda, Md., said the federal
government is spending $90 million a year to research the disease,
up from $4 million in 1974.
   ``Alzheimer's has emerged as one of the great mysteries of
medical science,'' Cohen said.
   The conference also looked at the needs of those who care for
the elderly. Those people, mostly women, often are burdened by
unrelenting demands and develop health problems of their own, said
Rhonda Montgomery, director of the Institute of Gerontology at
Wayne State University. She said twice as many senior citizens are
being cared for in private homes as in nursing homes.
</TEXT>
