<2ND_LINE>AM-Carson Ratings,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Viewers Stay Up Late for Fresh Carson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first new ``Tonight Show'' since the
writers' strike started two months ago was a sight for sore eyes
for millions of viewers who boosted the show's ratings by 36
percent, according to A.C. Nielsen Co.
   Host Johnny Carson, who is not a member of the striking Writers
Guild of America, got back on the air by writing his own material,
beginning with Wednesday night's show.
   According to overnight ratings from the country's 16 largest
television markets, ``Tonight'' got a rating of 8.7 and a 27 share
on Wednesday night, a 36 percent rise over its average rating since
the strike began.
   The rating is a percentage of homes with televisions. The share
is a percentage of sets in use.
   The 2-month-old strike over royalties and creative control
forced reruns of ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson'' and
``Late Night with David Letterman,'' both on NBC, and caused an
early end of the season for some series. CBS has announced it is
delaying the start of its fall season due to the strike.
