<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1728EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SentencingCommission     05-12 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sentencing Commission,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Declares U.S. Sentencing Commission Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has declared
unconstitutional a commission that sets federal sentencing
guidelines, saying the president's authority to remove commission
members violates the separation of powers between the executive and
judiciary branches of government.
   Chief U.S. District Judge W. Brevard Hand also threw out the
sentencing guidelines themselves.
   Hand's ruling Wednesday on a motion in a cocaine case was
similar to one issued by U.S. District Judge Marvin Shoob in
Atlanta; challenges to the guidelines also have been filed in other
jurisdictions and many federal judges have criticized them.
   Under the commission's guidelines, federal judges must impose
sentences within prescribed ranges unless special circumstances
exist that are not adequately considered by the commission's rules.
   The guidelines, Hand said, substantially restrict the
traditional discretion allowed judges in sentencing.
   Hand said the commission, created by Congress in 1984,
improperly includes three federal judges. Members of the commission
are appointed by the president and may be removed by him for
neglect of duty, malfeasance in office or for other causes.
   ``Federal courts must carefully abstain from exercising any
power that is not strictly judicial in its character, and which is
not clearly confided by the Constitution,'' Hand ruled.
   He said the job of setting guidelines is essentially an
administrative rule-making task, legislative in nature, and ``not a
proper function of the judiciary.''
</TEXT>
