<HEAD>Sober Singer Proves She Still Can Sing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Natalie Cole, a three-time Grammy winner,
says she has come to terms with her late father's fame and now
wants to do an album of Nat ``King'' Cole ballads.
   Miss Cole successfully battled drug and alcohol dependence in
the early 1980s with the help of a therapist and overcame her
hostility toward her father, according to the May 30 issue of Us
magazine.
   ``My whole theme was, `I'll never be as good as my father,'''
Miss Cole said. She said the time was right to record her father's
songs ``because I have confidence in my own talent.''
   Miss Cole, who is riding high with a hit single ``Pink
Cadillac,'' was frank about her problems.
   ``I was a human garbage disposal,'' she said, speaking of her
years on cocaine, methaqualone and alcohol. Then, after her
rehabilitation, ``people wanted to know if I could stay sober. Then
they wanted to know if I could still sing. It was humiliating and
scary and just plain hard work, but I proved that I could do both.''
