<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-House-Immunity     05-12 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House-Immunity,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes To Make Itself More Immune To Civil Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House unanimously approved a resolution
Thursday that asserts the right of its members to be immune from
civil lawsuits when they issue news releases, hold news conferences
or communicate with government officials.
   The 413-0 vote was triggered by a federal appeals court decision
that limited lawmakers' immunity to activities such as speaking and
voting on the House or Senate floor.
   The resolution requested that the Supreme Court hear an appeal
of the case, in which the need for a broader interpretation of
immunity would be argued.
   The House expressed ``deep concern'' with the ruling ``because
of its impact on the necessary and proper functioning of the House
of Representatives.''
   The dispute began in 1985 when Rep. Don Sundquist, R-Tenn.,
wrote to the attorney general and the president of the Legal
Services Corp. about a controversy over expenditure of federal
money by Memphis Area Legal Services.
   Sundquist, who released the letters to the news media, made a
reference to a staff attorney for the Memphis group, who sued the
lawmaker for defamation of character.
   In April 1986, a U.S. district judge in Washington dismissed the
suit on grounds that members of Congress are entitled to immunity
while acting in good faith within the scope of their official
duties.
   Last November, a panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington voted 2-1 to reverse the ruling. The appellate court
said immunity was limited to that granted by the Constitution's
speech and debate clause, which has been held to apply only to
activities such as floor action.
   Sundquist then appealed to the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
