<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FosterCare     05-12 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foster Care,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Accuse Administration Of Failing To Enforce Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen accused the Reagan
administration Thursday of ruining children's lives and wasting
taxpayer's money by failing to enforce a 1980 law meant to improve
the foster care system.
   ``Children are being abused beyond our wildest expectations.
Millions of dollars are being misspent,'' Rep. George Miller,
D-Calif., told three federal officials responsible for children's
programs.
   The children ``don't have permanency. They don't have services.
They can't get back to their families. ... What you're really
engaged in is state child abuse,'' Miller said.
   Miller, chairman of the House Select Committee on Children,
Youth and Families, and Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., chairman of the
Ways and Means public assistance subcommittee, led the attack on
the trio at the last of three hearings on the foster care system.
   ``It appears to me that we're doing a reasonably adequate job.
It's not an exceptional job,'' said Sydney Olson, assistant
secretary for human development services at the Department of
Health and Human Services. ``We're trying to improve.''
   Earlier witnesses had charged that neither the federal
government or the states were enforcing the 1980 law, which
stresses preserving and reuniting families, and finding permanent
homes for children who cannot be with their parents. Case plans and
case reviews for children in foster care are required at specific
intervals.
   The American Public Welfare Association said ``many positive
changes'' had occurred as a result of the law. The Children's
Defense Fund said that without the changes, ``the crises facing the
child welfare system today would be even more overwhelming.''
   Those and other groups said there remain serious problems
ranging from patchwork services and inadequate federal funds to the
increasingly disturbed children entering the foster care system as
a result of unemployment, poverty, drug abuse, homelessness and
family violence.
   Downey and Miller aimed their fire at the administration,
contending officials are failing to penalize states no matter how
bad their records are.
   ``As one of our witnesses told us, you'd have to work overtime
to flunk your audit,'' Miller said. He said the department is
relying on a checklist filled out by states themselves, plus sample
cases that don't reflect the serious problems pinpointed by
lawsuits and studies across the country.
   Those problems have included child abuse by foster parents,
slipshod monitoring by authorities responsible for the child's
future, and failure to refer children for adoption or return them
to their families where that is appropriate.
   Downey said a lawsuit in New York City revealed that child
welfare offices were being used as shelters and 1,000 children had
been subjected to multiple one-night placements. He said a suicidal
12-year-old was sent to 17 placements in 28 working days. Despite
this information, he said, New York is one of seven states that has
not been audited since the law was enacted.
   Olson said she was not aware of the lawsuit, probably because
the federal government is not a party to it.
   ``You are a party to it,'' Miller rejoined. ``You're paying the
bill for the care of these children... When states are out of
compliance, they're not supposed to get the money. Somehow, that
doesn't happen.''
   Miller and Downey also scored the administrators for failing to
help states cope with soaring rates of homelessness, drug abuse and
child abuse. They said thousands of children are in foster care
because their parents are homeless or the social services their
families need are unavailable.
</TEXT>
