<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     05-12 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Tells Palestinians to Behave, Extra Security In Jerusalem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
urged Palestinians in this Arab city Thursday to stop their
uprising against Israeli occupation and said if they did, the
bloodshed would cease.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, Israeli troops opened fire on
Palestinian protesters, wounding five, Arab reports and hospital
officials said. The army reported three wounded.
   About 3,000 police were deployed in Jerusalem as the Moslem fast
of Ramadan drew to a close.
   The Israeli air force made its eighth raid into Lebanon this
year, blasting Palestinian targets south of Beirut. Police said six
fighter-bombers took part in the attack at Barja, 16 miles outside
Beirut. There were no reports of deaths or serious injuries.
   Israel's Police Commissioner David Kraus said ``all necessary
measures'' would be taken to prevent disturbances at the close of
Ramadan, the Moslem holy month due to end Monday or Tuesday with
the sighting of the new moon.
   Thursday marked Laylat Al Kadr, Arabic for ``Night of Fate,''
which falls on the 27th day of Ramadan and marks the giving of the
Koran to the prophet Mohammed. Police were on patrol to prevent
rioting by Moslems gathering at Jerusalem's sacred Temple Mount for
all-night prayers.
   Officials also are concerned about possible violence on Sunday,
when Israelis mark the 40th anniversary of their state as well as
the 21st anniversary of the seizure of Arab east Jerusalem.
   Shamir visited Hebron, the second largest West Bank city, for
the first time since unrest broke out in the occupied territories
Dec. 8. He toured the narrow stone-paved streets of the Qasbah, or
open-air market, passing surprised vendors selling meat, vegetables
and donkey saddles.
   Speaking through a translator, Shamir urged Palestinian
residents of the city to stop violence. One Arab told him ``the
government should start treating the Palestinians as human beings,
especially now, during religious celebrations.''
   Shamir responded that ``the population should start to behave,
and not only during holidays.''
   ``If there would be quiet and order, nothing would be done
against the population,'' Shamir said.
   Asked by Shamir what he was doing to promote peace, one merchant
said: ``We are praying and hoping.'' But an Arab youth shouted:
``There won't be peace. We want Jerusalem, Jaffa and Haifa!'' He
was quickly pushed away by troops.
   Arab witnesses said the prime minister's party was preceded by
dozens of troops who banged on shop doors and used megaphones to
order striking shopkeepers to open.
   After touring Hebron, Shamir was taken by army helicopter to the
neighboring Beit Hagay Jewish settlement, where about 90 Jewish
settlers live in the barren hills south of Hebron.
   Shamir said the land was ``thirsty for Jewish settlement'' and
promised settlers that Israel would ``march forward'' with the
settlement drive.
   Throughout the West Bank, many shops remained shuttered all day
due to conflicting PLO and army orders. PLO leaders have ordered
shops to open in the morning and close in the afternoon, and the
army has tried to thwart the organization's control by issuing the
opposite orders.
   The clash in the open-air market of Nablus started after troops
ordered shops in the city closed and youths began throwing stones,
Arab reports said.
   An official at the city's Ittihad Hospital said five youths,
including one 13-year-old, were brought in with gunshot wounds.
Four were wounded in the legs and one was wounded in the stomach.
   Since the uprising began, 186 Arabs have died in clashes with
Israelis. An Israeli soldier and a Jewish teen-ager also have been
killed.
</TEXT>
