<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   05-12 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Hit Noriega Deal; Reagan `Mortified' by
Endorsement Flap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson joined the chorus of
criticism Thursday against reported U.S. plans to drop drug charges
against Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega, while President Reagan
was ``mortified'' that his endorsement of George Bush was viewed as
less than enthusiastic.
   Dukakis made his first visit to the Capitol as the presumed
Democratic nominee and won backing from several congressional
leaders before heading to the West, where Bush and Jackson were
campaigning.
   The White House acknowledged U.S. officials were trying to coax
Noriega to surrender power, but refused to say whether dropping the
drug charges might be part of the deal.
   In New Mexico, Bush refused to discuss the matter except to say,
``I favor getting Noriega out. ... When negotiations are going on
that are sensitive, you don't discuss them.''
   The Republican vice president called the fuss over the terseness
of Reagan's endorsement ``much ado about nothing.''
   ``I couldn't have been more pleased,'' he said.
   Reagan devoted three brief sentences at the end of a speech to a
GOP fund-raising dinner Wednesday night to declare his backing for
Bush, who clinched the Republican presidential nomination more than
two weeks ago.
   Dukakis still is short of the majority he needs at the
Democratic convention, but the string of primary victories put
together in recent weeks by the Massachusetts governor has ended
any doubt that he will be the party's candidate against Bush in the
general election.
   With his new status, Dukakis met privately in Washington with
South African Bishop Desmond Tutu and then with Democratic
congressional leaders. He picked up endorsements from Senate
Majority leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia and Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski of Illinois, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee.
   Dukakis won nearly 80 percent of the vote in the West Virginia
primary earlier this week and Byrd, the state's senior senator,
said he was endorsing the governor ``without any reservations,
because I'm confident, based on our conversation, we're going to
have a president who will work with the Congress.''
   Byrd also said, ``It's time now that we unite ... We need now to
begin to close ranks, and that's what we're doing today.''
   Rostenkowski called Dukakis ``the candidate best able to lead
our nation.''
   After meeting with Tutu, Dukakis said he ``very strongly''
supported tougher sanctions against the white supremacist regime in
South Africa.
   ``It's time to change our policy and I assure you if all goes
well ... there will be a fundamental change in policy,'' Dukakis
said. ``This country has got to lead in human rights.''
   In recent days, the Massachusetts governor has hammered away at
Bush on the question of what the vice president knew about
Noriega's involvement in drug trafficking.
   At the Capitol, he focused on the reports the administration
might drop the drug charges.
   ``I think before we start talking about dropping indictments and
making deals, the American people deserve a full explanation of
what kind of relationship this administration has had with Noriega
... Just exactly what has been going on for the past 7{ years,'' he
said.
   ``I don't believe you drop indictments against suspected drug
runners and murderers.''
   Jackson sounded a similar theme during a Portland, Ore., news
conference.
   ``They want to exonerate him altogether,'' Jackson said. ``It's
not just Noriega. Others are dealing in drugs. We can't indict them
one day and exonerate them the next day. That is no policy at all.''
   Marlin Fitzwater, Reagan's press secretary, told reporters the
president was ``mortified'' about the endorsement flap. ``He
thought the speech was terrific. He wrote it himself,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Reagan issued a statement later that said, ``I was surprised by
the news reports that have said my endorsement last evening of the
vice president was `lukewarm.' I am enthusiastic, fully committed
and, as I have said, will go all out to make Vice President Bush
the next president of the United States.''
   Bush said he and Reagan talked about the endorsement in advance.
   ``He showed me those remarks he had handwritten,'' said the vice
president. ``I still have them.''
   In other political developments:
   _ The three major television reaffirmed their support of
legislation to set a uniform poll closing time during presidential
election years. The legislation, which has passed the House and is
pending in the Senate, would order a 9 p.m. EST poll simultaneous
poll closing time.
   _ Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York embarked on a political trip to
the West Coast and said he planned to ``have some fun'' attacking
Bush. Cuomo, who resisted entreaties he get into the Democratic
race, said he thought the contest for his party's nomination had
strengthened Dukakis.
   ``Dukakis is already a favorite in the polls and I'm not
surprised,'' said Cuomo.
</TEXT>
