<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-SovietJewry     05-12 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Soviet Jewry,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Promises To Push Human Rights Issues at Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish leaders said Thursday that President
Reagan had assured them he will press Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev at the Moscow summit to make good on promised human
rights gains.
   Morris B. Abram, chairman of the National Conference on Soviet
Jewry, quoted Reagan as saying, ``In no way are the Soviets going
to get us to retreat from these principals and from the insistence
to their obedience to their obligations.''
   Abram, accompanied by Simcha Dinitz, former Israeli ambassador
to the United States, told reporters outside the White House that
the meeting ``went extremely well.''
   Reagan will travel to Helsinki, Finland, on May 25 and make a
presummit speech en route to his May 29-June 2 summit with
Gorbachev.
   Abram credited the president with having ``absolutely
institutionalized the use of summitry to advance the cause of human
rights and Soviet Jewry in a way that it can never be ignored by
any subsequent administration.''
   ``And the proof of that is that on Oct. 10, 1987, prior to the
Washington summit last year, Chairman Gorbachev for the first time
joined the president of the United States in a statement that human
rights and humanitarian affairs would be on the agenda _ something
they had never admitted before as a matter that was rightfully on
the agenda.''
   Dinitz was asked whether he thought Gorbachev would be willing
to make major headway in improving Jewish emigration rights, given
the Kremlin leader's boast during the Washington summit that ``I'm
not on trial here.''
   ``I might say he might not be on trial,'' said Dinitz, chairman
of the World Zionist Organization and the Jewish Agency, Israel,
``but the action and behavior with regard to human rights are on
trial. And the prosecutor, so to speak, is not the president of the
United States but the conscience of mankind.''
   ``We are all aware of the fact that at the last summit meeting,
Mr. Gorbachev said to the president, `By what right do you have to
challenge us on those questions''' Abram said. ``The right is
derived from documents they themselves signed.''
   ``And to be fair about it, there has been an improvement of the
emigration figures in the last few months under Mr. Gorbachev,''
Abram said. He said there had been about 1,100 emigrations in the
first four months of 1988, compared with about 1,000 in an entire
year before Gorbachev's ascension to power.
   But Abram said the figures were even higher under Leonid I.
Brezhnev, before the advent of Gorbachev and his ``glasnost''
society.
   ``We welcome improvement, and with every improvement, we will
say, on behalf of the National Conference on Soviet Jewry, `Things
are improving,' but they are a long way from fulfilling their
obligations under international undertakings,'' he said.
</TEXT>
