<HEAD>Cuomo Making Rounds Of Democratic Fund-Raisers In West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo headed for the
West Coast on Thursday to ``have some fun'' attacking Vice
President George Bush, the likely Republican presidential nominee,
and help raise money for Democrats.
   ``Since I'm never going to leave the bullpen, I may as well get
out there for some scrimmaging,'' said the former minor league
baseball player who was once considered a potential 1988 Democratic
presidential nominee. ``I may as well have some fun.''
   Cuomo said he would use a Friday night appearance in San
Francisco on behalf of Rep. Nancy Pelosi and one in Seattle on
Saturday night for Washington Gov. Booth Gardner to go after Bush.
   In between, Cuomo was to stop in Portland, Ore., to deliver a
foreign policy speech.
   Cuomo said the battle for the Democratic nomination, now
expected to go to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, had been good
for the party.
   ``They had virtually no contest,'' said Cuomo of the
Republicans, offering a preview of his attacks on Bush. ``They
would have us believe that it was because they were all eager to
speak with just one voice, the voice of George Bush. I think it's
because they have nothing to say.''
   ``...We will ask him (Bush) to use his voice to tell us why he
hasn't used his voice for eight years,'' said Cuomo.
   The New York governor's West Coast trip, planned months ago, was
once viewed as possible evidence that Cuomo had hopes of a
deadlocked national convention turning to him with its presidential
nomination.
   Cuomo's Portland speech on Saturday comes just three days before
the Oregon presidential primary. The California primary is June 7.
   However, that was all before the April 19 New York presidential
primary when Dukakis stormed ahead of Jesse Jackson in the delegate
count and buried Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s faltering
campaign _ with no help from Cuomo.
   Cuomo said Thursday that his address Saturday to the Oregon
World Affairs Council would focus on U.S.-Soviet relations. The
governor spent a week in the Soviet Union in September.
   ``One need not be a candidate to have an opinion,'' said Cuomo.
   And what if he's asked about a possible 1992 presidential
campaign?
   ``Please, forget '92. I have the state to deal with,'' said
Cuomo.
