<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CookieCrumbles     05-12 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cookie Crumbles,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Scout Cookies Leave For Japan For Second Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shipment of Girl Scout cookies
winged out of Texas on Thursday on its second trip to U.S. sailors
in Japan after a Brownie troop got a taste of the power of politics.
   Sailors aboard the USS Midway, stationed in Atsugi, bought the
402 boxes from Brownie Troop 807 in Beeville. But the plan crumbled
when the the girls were told that the cookies faced a stiff customs
tariff in Japan.
   The cookies were sent back and sat in an American Airlines
office at the Corpus Christi International Airport for more than a
week.
   The sweets finally left Thursday morning on a flight to Dallas,
where the Thin Mints, Golden Yangles, Scot Ts, Savannahs, Jubilees,
Classic Cremes and Hoedowns caught a connecting non-stop flight to
Tokyo, said officials for the airline, which provided free
transportation.
   ``They're on the way, and the red tape should be turning to
green by now,'' Marchetta White, the troop's leader, said Thursday.
The shipment was to arrive Friday afternoon in Japan.
   Mrs. White said U.S. Navy personnel originally told her the
Japanese demanded a tariff of more than $2,000 before releasing the
cookies from customs.
   But the consulate-general of Japan in Houston last week
attributed the cookie misfortune to ``insufficient communications
among those who are involved with customs clearance.''
   A spokesman for the consulate said the import fees amounted to
about 20,000 yen, or about $150. According to a statement issued by
the consulate, there would have been no customs fee ``if the U.S.
armed forces had taken necessary procedures.''
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, worked through diplomatic channels
to get the cookies to the sailors without a customs fee, and sent a
telegram to the Brownies on Wednesday.
   ``This all happened because you wanted to do something nice for
some sailors serving our country on the other side of the the world
...,'' the telegram said. ``Now everyone has seen how helpful
Brownies in Texas are.''
   He added that he was ``sure the `Cookie Monster' is pleased,
too.''
   The 18-member Brownie troop first started corresponding with the
sailors at Christmas, then sent a Valentine's Day package and
finally the April 26 shipment of cookies, Mrs. White said.
   They could not send the cookies by mail because it would have
been too expensive, Mrs. White said, and the airline offered free
shipment.
   ``Everybody who was supposed to be getting the cookies was
really upset when they didn't get them,'' said Petty Officer 3rd
Class Sid Woolford, Mrs. White's son-in-law, who is stationed on
the Midway and on leave in Beeville.
   The girls prepared another gift for the sailors Wednesday by
posing on the steps of the Bee County Courthouse for a color photo
they will send the sailors, said Mrs. White.
   Meanwhile, she added, the troop will wait to hear how the
sailors liked the cookies: ``They're waiting for the letters that
will be coming to them again.''
</TEXT>
