<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PortraitProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0701 05-12 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portrait Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Removal of Painting Showing Late Mayor in Lingerie Sparks
Controversy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 11th, `But Miller...' to update with
student's comment. Deletes now-outdated last graf.
^LaserPhotos CX3,10</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Washington ``would not have been amused''
by a painting showing him in women's lingerie, but the late mayor
wouldn't have gone along with aldermen who stormed the exhibit and
had the work removed, a longtime friend said Thursday.
   ``He would have been the first one to say the artist has a right
to do whatever the artist does,'' former mayoral press secretary
Alton Miller said a day after the outraged aldermen had police
confiscate the painting from the School of the Art Institute.
   Officer Patrick Camden said police removed the painting ``for
safekeeping because of the possibility of inciting civil unrest.''
He said it would be returned Thursday.
   The painting by student David K. Nelson depicts Washington
wearing a frilly white bra, panties and stockings, holding a pencil
and frowning out at viewers. It had been displayed in a school hall
with dozens of others in a student competition.
   The school offers a four-year bachelor of arts program and a
two-year master's degree, said Kevin Frech, a spokesman for the
private school whose sister institution is the adjacent art musuem.
   The exhibit is closed to the public, but the aldermen say they
got involved after receiving numerous complaints from angry
constituents who had seen the painting.
   They contend the work titled ``Mirth and Girth'' is an insult to
Washington.
   But a group of students argue the painting is artistic
self-expression and protected by the First Amendment.
   Washington would have agreed with both assessments, Miller said.
   ``He would not have been amused,'' and would have seen the
painting as ``aiding and abetting'' a campaign waged by his
detractors to raise questions about his character, Miller said in a
telephone interview.
   But Miller added, Washington would have strongly felt that ``in
terms of either ordinance statute or constitutional law ... there's
absolutely no way that it can be suppressed.''
   ``I don't think it's the most tasteful portrait, but I don't
think that matters,'' Nelson told radio station WLUP.
   ``Nobody said when I went to the Art Institute that I had to
produce tasteful artwork. In fact ... that goes against everything
the institution is about,'' he said. ``It's like saying you have to
produce artwork in a certain way.''
   At the school, a group of about 15 people marched peacefully
outside Thursday to protest the painting as the board of directors
met inside to discuss the matter.
   Frech said he did not know what options the board was
considering.
   Civil liberties experts and legal scholars took the students'
side.
   ``We're against censorship and this seems to be a form of
censorship,'' said Jay Miller, executive director of the American
Civil Liberties Union of Illinois.
   Daniel Polsby, a Northwestern University law professor, called
the aldermen's behavior ``constitutionally indefensible.
   ``They behaved like a lynch mob and very seriously violated the
civil rights of (the artist) as well as the Art Institute.''
   Alderman Allan Streeter, who was among those who stormed the
school and helped draft a resolution demanding that the painting be
removed, said he's aware of the constitutional issues involved.
   ``There's a moral question that outweighs the constitutional
question,'' he said Thursday.
   The city of Chicago gives the Art Institute, which oversees the
school, subsidies of $5 million a year ``as well as other public
and private funds, and we don't feel that any institution, private
or public, has a right to portray a leader of any community ... in
such a derogatory fashion,'' he said.
   Alderman Robert Shaw, who sponsored the resolution, said police
removed the painting because ``it posed a threat to the safety to
the school and the general community.''
   ``People, particularly from the black community, are highly
perturbed _ using it mildly _ about this particular portrait,''
Shaw said. Washington, who died in November, was the city's first
black mayor.
   Miller said the ACLU was looking for the student and would
represent him if he chose to protest the case in court.
</TEXT>
