<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WrightAide     05-12 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright Aide,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide Hired To Help Speaker Staying On Indefinitely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright is keeping on
indefinitely a press aide who was the focus of controversy due to
angry letters he wrote to newspapers and revelations he was the
author of a sex book.
   Wright and George Mair, 59, originally had agreed to a six-month
contract that was due to expire at the end of May.
   But Wright decided Tuesday after talking to Mair that he would
keep the press aide on his staff ``as another hand at the oar,''
Mair said Thursday.
   Mair and Wright are working together on a book on the 200-year
history of Congress, which celebrates its bicentennial in April
1989. Mair said he will concentrate on media liaison work, helping
the speaker research material for newspaper opinion columns and
revive the Democratic congressman's newsletter to the constituents
in his Texas district.
   Rumors circulated in January, a month after Mair was hired, that
he would be resigning following revelations he was the author of a
book of reviews of 113 books on sex, love and romance.
   ``We're two honorable men who stick by our word,'' Mair said.
``We both told everyone I would have a six-month trial period and
everyone became astonished when we kept our word and I was
astonished that everyone was astonished.''
   Wright in January had distanced himself from a series of
intemperate letters written by Mair to 19 newspapers, including one
to the Los Angeles Times suggesting two reporters had engaged in
plagiarism in their profile of the speaker.
   The Los Angeles Times angrily protested Mair's letter.
   Other recipients of angry letters included the Wall Street
Journal, Newsweek and U.S. News & World Report.
   Wright apologized for the letters, saying at the time: ``While I
am as concerned as George over lack of balance in some of this
coverage, angry letters obviously do little to correct it.''
   ``I wrote 19 letters, but only five were reported on,'' Mair
said of criticism of him. ``Then I wrote a book on love and
intimacy and relations between men and women. I just wrote 113 book
reviews. It was originally titled `A Guide to Books on Love and
Intimacy.' But it was changed to `The Sex Book Digest.'''
   Mair, an author of numerous books, a former columnist for the
Los Angeles Times Syndicate and a former editor and publisher of
the Alexandria (Va.) Gazette, said his letters did not reflect that
he is ``against my fellow journalists.'' He said his letter
outlined ``patent, outright lies.''
   ``I talked to almost all of those people I wrote letters to and
several said they checked back the story and found the reporter did
not have the facts straight, and that's all I asked,'' he said.
</TEXT>
