<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrunkDonation     05-12 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drunk Donation,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drunken Driving Charge Reduced for $20,000 Donation to Drug Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with drunken driving
was allowed to plead guilty to speeding in exchange for a $20,000
donation to a drug task force, a plea bargain that has angered some
residents.
   District Attorney General David Crockett said the benefit to the
public outweighed the mandatory 48-hour jail term, $250 fine and
yearlong driver's license suspension for first-time drunken driving
convictions.
   Tom Donihe of Kingsport pleaded guilty Friday to the reduced
charge.
   Donihe was arrested in April 1986 after he was clocked driving
at 78 mph and had a blood alcohol level of 0.15 percent, police
said. Legal intoxication in Tennessee is 0.10 percent.
   The leaders of two area chapters of Mothers Against Drunk
Driving criticized Crockett for accepting the offer by Donihe's
lawyer.
   Elizabeth Price, head of the Johnson City MADD chapter, is
calling for Crockett's resignation.
   ``If I wasn't a Christian, I could tell you what I really
think,'' she said. ``I feel that the people who let him off are the
real criminals.''
   Lynda Fortner, president of the MADD chapter in Kingsport, said
the decision to accept a plea bargain in the case ``almost sounds
like a bribe.''
   ``I've weighed the criticism and I'm willing to take it,''
Crockett said. ``We have successfully prosecuted several thousand
drunk drivers. ... If we made a mistake in the case then my batting
average is still 999.99 of doing the right thing.''
   Criminal Court Judge Arden Hill, who approved the plea bargain
expressed some reservation before accepting the plea, saying, ``It
bothers my conscience.''
   Crockett, whose teen-age son was killed in a 1986 traffic
accident, has been a vocal opponent of drunken driving.
   He said the contribution to the First Judicial Drug Task Force,
which he helped found, was ``a proper disposition of the case.''
   The unit, made up of officers from various agencies,
investigates drug cases in four counties. It is funded with court
fines, private donations and tax dollars from local governments.
</TEXT>
