<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Prisons     05-12 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Prisons,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watchdog Group Blasts AIDS Policies In New York Prisons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State prison inmates with AIDS sometimes get
improper medical care and are being unnecessarily denied freedom
for the final days of their lives, a prison watchdog group charged
Thursday.
   The Correctional Association of New York said an 18-month
investigation demonstrated that the prison system and state
government have not responded adequately'' to AIDS in the prisons.
   ``AIDS and prison is proving to be a devastating combination,''
said Cathy Potler, author of the report.
   Among other things, the association urged mandatory education
about AIDS for prisoners and staff, expanded and better-supervised
medical care, and new provisions to allow the release of terminally
ill prisoners.
   New York, which has more AIDS cases than any other state, also
has more prisoners with AIDS.
   As of the end of last year 597 AIDS cases had been confirmed
among New York's prison inmates, said state prison system spokesman
James Flateau. Of those, 346 inmates died while in prison, 152 had
been released and 99 remained in custody. He said about 100 AIDS
cases and 120 cases of AIDS-Related Complex, are in the
42,000-inmate system.
   There is no known cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
which is fatal.
   The association had medical consultants and non-medical
investigators visit several prisons to prepare its report.
   The group said it also found that inmates suffering from AIDS
are often shunned by other inmates who are afraid of even casual
contact. Inmate barbers at one prison refused to give haircuts to
men with AIDS, said the report.
   And while prison officials told the association that ``the
hysteria initially expressed by the security staff has subsided
considerably'' over the last three years, the watchdog group still
found evidence of fear.
   State Corrections Commissioner Thomas Coughlin said the
association's medical team should have spent more time in the
prisons.
   ``Much of the report consists of the opinions of non-medical
researchers, supported by unattributed comments by staff and
inmates, the content of which may or may not be accurate,''
Coughlin said.
</TEXT>
