<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Florida, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge, Prosecutors Question Dismissal of Noriega Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `I am...' with 2 to update with Kellner's
comment.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Noriega Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge questioned Thursday whether the
government alone can drop the drug indictment against Panama's Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, and local prosecutors inisted they want to
try the case.
   ``My understanding and knowledge of the law is that the
presiding judge is not required to dismiss an indictment on the
motion of the government,'' said U.S. District Judge William
Hoeveler, who is handling the case. ``However, I am having the law
researched further.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that the
Reagan administration is discussing a deal that could result in the
dropping of drug trafficking charges against Noriega in exchange
for his agreement to relinquish power.
   The lead prosecutor in the case, Chief Assistant U.S. Attorney
Richard Gregorie, said Thursday he strongly opposes any deal.
   ``I am against the dismissal, and right now I am ready to try
this case,'' said Gregorie. Gregorie's boss, U.S. Attorney Leon
Kellner, released a statement through his executive assistant Ana
Barnett following his meeting with Attorney General Edwin Meese III
in Washington.
   ``He would not discuss the details of his talk with Mr. Meese,
but he said, `I presented my views,''' Ms. Barnett said. ``I am
authorized to say his views haven't changed, and he wants to
proceed with the case and he's ready to proceed with the trial.'''
   Kellner has previously vowed not to dismiss the indictment, but
Noriega's attorneys said the government has little choice.
   ``General Noriega believes, and always has believed, that the
indictment against him was a political indictment,'' his attorney,
Neal Sonnett, said Thursday. ``So a dismissal of the indictment
would have to be a pre-condition to any discussions.''
   Sonnett's associate, attorney Raymond Takiff, was called back to
Panama on Thursday following the revelations about a possible deal.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, who brought a separate indictment
in Tampa against Noriega, refused comment Thursday on reports he
has threatened to quit if the charges are dropped.
   Merkle was in Jacksonville prosecuting Carlos Lehder Rivas,
alleged to be a member of the same Medellin Cartel that prosecutors
say paid Noriega to protect its interest.
   Noriega is charged in a 12-count Miami indictment with accepting
$4.6 million in bribes from the cartel; in Tampa, he faces three
marijuana importation counts.
   The possibility of a deal was good news for Noriega's
co-defendants.
   Brian Davidow, the only defendant arrested in the Miami case,
also should have his case dismissed, said his attorney, Richard
Sharpstein.
   Gregorie agreed.
   ``If they made me dismiss this case, I would dismiss against Mr.
Davidow and all the other defendants,'' the prosecutor said. ``It
would be a travesty of justice to proceed against any of the
defendants if the case against the chief defendant was dismissed.''
</TEXT>
