<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SafeKids     05-12 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Safe Kids,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign To Fight Preventable Injuries In Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children's advocates on Thursday announced a
``Safe Kids'' campaign designed to combat the leading killer of
America's children _ injuries that can be prevented.
   ``Preventable injuries are epidemic in this country ... (these)
things are preventable and that's what people have to be made aware
of,'' actress Markie Post of NBC-TV's ``Night Court'' said at a
press conference.
   ``We've got to change our vocabulary and priorities with
children now,''she said. ``We need to become more child-oriented.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who has scheduled hearings on
the issue, said surveys show that most parents would identify drug
abuse and kidnapping as the major concerns about their child's
safety.
   Dodd said 67 children in the United State were abducted last
year and 57 died from drug abuse, while nearly 8,000 children aged
14 and under were killed and 50,000 were permanently disabled as a
result of avoidable accidents.
   According to the Department of Health and Human Services, nearly
half the deaths of children aged 14 and under are caused by
unintentional injuries.
   The Safe Kids campaign was developed by Children's Hospital in
Washington, and is supported by Johnson & Johnson Co. and the
National Safety Council. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop serves as
honorary chairman of the national campaign.
   More than 40 health, corporate and children's organizations have
joined the campaign, with President Reagan expected to sign a
proclamation designating May 16-22 as National Safe Kids Week.
   Public service announcements featuring Ms. Post will begin
airing nationwide on Monday, inviting listeners to call
800-365-KIDS to request a 16-page safety booklet.
   The publication advises parents on how to protect children from
injury in five leading risk areas: traffic accidents, drownings,
burns and scalds, choking and poisoning, and falls.
   The booklet also urges parents to take first aid and
cardiopulmonary resuscitation courses to enable them to provide
immediate proper care if an injury does occur.
   Safe Kids groups in 24 cities will host injury prevention
activities next week.
   ``This campaign has set an ambitious goal _ to change the way
America thinks about and deals with the epidemic of preventable
injuries to children,'' said Herta Burbach Feely, executive
director of the campaign.
   ``The fact is we have not done and we are not doing everything
that we can to prevent childhood injuries either as individuals,
the community or as a nation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
