<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NASABudget     05-12 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NASA Budget,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Appropriations Subcommittee Cuts NASA Budget By $780 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House appropriations panel cut more than
$780 million out of the NASA budget Thursday and agency officials
said the reduction could seriously affect the civil space program.
   In the markup of appropriations for the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, the Appropriations Committee's subcommittee
on housing and urban development and independent agencies approved
a total budget for fiscal year 1989 of $10.706 billion. NASA had
asked for $11.488 billion.
   While that subcommittee was cutting the budget, the full House
Committee on Science, Space and Technology authorized the total
dollars that NASA had requested, making only minor changes in
distribution of the funding. But this action will have little
effect if the funds are not appropriated.
   The budget reduction by the Appropriations subcommittee ``is
really going to hurt the program. There is no more slack left in
NASA,'' said shuttle astronaut Jon McBride, on assignment in NASA's
congressional relations office. ``Something will have to be cut.
There's nothing left. If they do make these cuts, some serious
things will happen to the civil space program.''
   In one of the largest reductions, the Appropriations
subcommittee cut NASA's request for the struggling space shuttle
program by more than $200 million. The language of the bill would
let NASA decide what shuttle program activities will be eliminated.
   NASA had asked for $3.610 billion to improve and start flying
the shuttle again, but the subcommittee agreed to appropriate only
$3.4 billion.
   ``This will be one of the toughest cuts to accommodate,'' said
Terry Dawson, a staff member of the House subcommittee on space
science and applications.
   Dawson said some of the shuttle program items that could be
affected include manufacture of spare parts, an effort to enhance
the performance of the rocket engines and fuel pumps on the orbiter
and the scheduling of missions. It would not, however, affect the
resumption of shuttle flights.
   ``It's going to hurt them no matter what they do,'' said McBride.
   The space shuttle has been grounded since January 1986 when the
explosion of the Challenger shuttle killed seven crew members. The
winged spacecraft fleet is scheduled to resume flights in August.
   Appropriations subcommittee members also cut $65 million from
the $967 million NASA had requested for development of the space
station. Dawson said the $902 million allocation would allow the
space station program to continue will little effect.
   Other cuts, with the original NASA request in parenthesis,
include:
   _Advanced X-ray astrophysics facility, an astronomy satellite,
$16 million ($27 million).
   _Commercial Development Space Facility, a privately built
orbiting factory that NASA was to lease, zero. (A $25 million
appropriation from last year was rescinded).
   _Titan 4 launch rocket, $23 million ($43 million).
   The subcommittee also cut NASA plans to buy a Delta II and a
Titan 3 launch rocket.
   The marked-up bill is expected to go to the full Appropriations
Committee, where it could be changed, later this month. It then
must go to the full House for a vote before it can be considered by
the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CovertAction     05-12 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Covert Action,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Intelligence Committee Approves Notification Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Intelligence Committee said Thursday
it has approved and sent to the full House legislation that would
require the president to notify Congress within 48 hours when he
authorizes covert intelligence missions.
   The bill, which grew out of the recommendations of the
congressional panels that investigated the Iran-Contra affair, was
approved Wednesday on an 11-to-6 party-line vote and announced
Thursday by the committee.
   It is similar to a covert-action measure passed March 15 by the
Senate on a vote of 71 to 19.
   A central dispute in the Iran-Contra affair was the approval by
President Reagan of a secret arms-for-hostages swap which was not
discovered for 10 months after it was authorized, even though the
law requires notification of Congress ``in a timely fashion.''
   The congressional Iran-Contra committees recommended that the
law be changed to eliminate all ambiguity.
   The House and Senate bills would require the president to make a
written ``finding'' that any covert action is required on national
security grounds, and to provide copies to the congressional
intelligence oversight committees.
   The committees would have to be given prior notice of such
actions, unless an emergency prevented notification. In such cases,
the president would have up to 48 hours to get word to Congress.
   The president also would have to tell Congress which agencies
are to be involved in the covert action and disclose whether
private third parties are to be involved, as they were in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Under the bill, a covert action is any U.S. activity, other than
traditional military, diplomatic and law enforcement actions,
designed ``to influence political, economic or military conditions
abroad so that the role of the United States government is not
intended to be apparent or acknowledged publicly...''
   As it considered amendments to the measure, the
Democrat-controlled panel rejected an effort by Rep. Dick Cheney,
R-Wyo., to leave an exemption from the 48-hour notice requirement.
The committee also rejected an effort by Rep. Bob Livingston,
R-La., to provide for fines up to $20,000 and up to five years in
prison for unauthorized disclosure of classified information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
