<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Plane-CrashLanding     05-12 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane-Crash Landing,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Narrowly Misses Students on Field as It Crash Lands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane that ran out of gas
barely missed a football field full of students before making an
crash landing on the grounds of a high school Thursday.
   The two men in the plane suffered minor injuries, but none of
the students at Bishop Denis J. O'Connell High School was hurt,
said Steven Hynson, a spokesman for the Arlington Fire Department.
   ``The pilot did his very best and did an excellent job of
getting around them,'' said Hynson. ``He was extremely low when he
came in.''
   The pilot of the plane was identified by the Fire Department as
Ed Sanchez, 45, and his passenger as Dick Scheeringa, 44, both of
Toronto, Canada. They were taken to Arlington Hospital for
treatment of minor injuries.
   Hynson said the single-engine Piper Cherokee came in from the
east about 2:30 p.m. and circled the football field full of
students as it descended.
   The aircraft knocked down a 40-foot flagpole, touched down on
the surface of the track surrounding the field, leapfrogged at an
awkward angle down the length of the field, and slammed to a stop
in an embankment. It was prevented from going any further by an
eight-foot chain-link fence at the top of the small hill that faced
a residential road and a house across the street.
   The crash landing broke the plane's landing gear and smashed the
aircraft's nose.
   ``The pilot did a fine job of getting past the football field
into the bank,'' said Col. John Gutter, assistant principal at
Bishop O'Connell. ``We had a class of girls out on the (football)
field and a class of boys playing softball.''
   ``They were fortunate in three things,'' said Hynson. ``One is
that he (the pilot) could maneuver the plane. Two is that he didn't
hurt anyone. And three is that there wasn't any fuel that could
have caused an explosion or fire when he crashed.''
   The plane had taken off from Toronto and was bound for Raleigh,
N.C., Hynson said.
   Hynson said Virginia State Police and the Federal Aviation
Administration were investigating the accident.
</TEXT>
