<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PandaSuit 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panda Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Attempt Fails To Block Panda Exhibition in Toledo</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with judge turning down TRO. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday refused to halt the
shipment from China of two giant pandas to help celebrate the 150th
anniversary of Toledo, Ohio.
   U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson refused to grant a
temporary restraining order sought by the World Wildlife Fund to
prevent the two giant pandas from being shipped by air from
Shanghai to this country on Friday.
   The fund and the American Association of Zoological Parks and
Aquariums charged that the exhibition of the pandas would violate
an international convention that prohibits trafficking in
endangered species for commercial purposes.
   But the judge ruled that the plaintiffs failed to demonstrate
``a substantial likelihood of success on the merits'' to warrant
issuance of a temporary restraining order.
   The denial of a temporary restraining order cannot be appealed,
so the judge's ruling cleared the way for the shipment of the
pandas.
   The pandas, which are set to arrive in Seattle on Friday
afternoon, will spend 100 days to 200 days at the Toledo Zoo.
   The plaintiffs claimed Toledo zoo officials were interested in
the pandas only for their fund-raising potential.
   ``The Toledo Zoo does not plan to and indeed would not be
authorized by the People's Republic of China to breed the pandas or
to study them scientifically,'' the filing said.
   Instead it wants to use the estimated $1.9 million to be earned
from the exhibition to improve a building, parking lots and other
facilities, they added in a memorandum to the court.
   ``This is precisely the kind of commercial activity condemned by
international law (and) U.S. law,'' the memorandum said.
   Zoo attorney Randal C. Teague Sr. said his client had spent $1.9
million to build a panda house plus another $1.1 million for ramps
and other improvements at the zoo.
   The plaintiffs called the giant panda one of the Earth's most
critically endangered animals, with fewer than 1,000 surviving in
the wild.
   The suit named as defendants Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel
and Frank H. Dunkle, director of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service, because they issued an import permit.
   The memorandum called the decision to grant the permit
``arbitrary, capricious, an abuse of discretion and not in
accordance with the law.''
   Earlier, the fund asked that permits be denied for exhibitions
of pandas in Atlanta, Cincinnati and Detroit, as well as Toledo.
   One potential exhibitor denied that the purpose was commercial.
   ``Certainly, we are not a circus, or a carnival, or even a zoo
for that matter,'' said Tom Washington, executive director of the
Michigan United Conservation Clubs. ``There is a whole string of
hypocrisy involved here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0205 </DOCNO>
