<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Sematech     05-12 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sematech,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Seals Deal Between Consortium, Defense Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sematech sealed its pact with the Defense
Department Thursday, with officials saying that the research
consortium is poised to help the United States claim the
competitive edge in the semiconductor industry.
   The memorandum of understanding between the Pentagon and
Sematech, based in Austin, Texas, allows Sematech to begin
receiving the first allotment of a $100 million federal
appropriation.
   Sematech should receive $15 million of those funds in about two
weeks, officials said.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said at a news conference after the
signing that the federal funds ``were a good buy for American
taxpayers'' and that the technological advancements by Sematech
researchers would create jobs and opportunities.
   Rep. Jake Pickle, D-Texas, in whose district Sematech is
located, said it had created a ``new and exciting partnership''
that will help the United States ease its dependence on foreign
technology.
   Sematech is a consortium of 14 semiconductor manufacturers,
including IBM Corp., Texas Instruments Inc., American Telephone and
Telegraph, Rockwell International Corp. and Motorola.
   It will develop advanced semiconductor manufacturing processes,
materials and equipment and will transfer research results to
member companies. The Department of Defense will be treated as a
member, although it will not have a seat on the board of directors
and does not have the power to approve individual contracts.
   Sandy Kane, chairman of the Sematech executive committee and a
vice president of IBM Corp., said new technology and tools
developed by Sematech can be passed on to defense contractors for
defense contracts but not commercial use.
   Sematech now has 70 employees and ``assignees'' from member
companies, and Kane says 700 staff members are anticipated by next
year. It expects to be operating its clean room facility in October
and to produce its first silicon in early 1989, Kane said.
   Kane called it an unprecedented partnership between business and
government, and said it was a significant undertaking because there
will be sharing of technology between traditionally staunch
competitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
