<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugTesting     05-12 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather Service Employees Union Files Suit Against Drug Test Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit challenging plans to randomly test
National Weather Service employees for illegal drug use was
announced Thursday by a group representing 4,000 agency workers.
   The National Weather Service Employees Association said its
lawsuit, filed in federal court in San Francisco, challenges plans
to test 1,800 meteorologists, 1,700 meteorological technicians and
200 hydrologists for illegal drug use.
   The random testing is part of the Reagan administration's
program for a drug-free work place. The suit is the latest in a
series of court challenges to the government-wide drug testing
program.
   The Reagan administration last week submitted to Congress a list
of positions subject to random drug testing. Employees in those
so-called sensitive positions were singled out for testing because,
the administtation contends, their work affects the public safety.
   The suit, brought on behalf of 16 National Weather Service
employees in California, disputes that claim and charges that drug
testing would be an illegal invasion of privacy.
   The suit said that for at least three years, the agency has
reported no incidents of drug use or impairment by illegal drugs of
employees on the job.
   The suit seeks an injunction to bar the testing.
</TEXT>
