<DOCNO> AP880512-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleKillings 1stLd-Writethru a0779 05-12 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0779,0879</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Simmons Convicted, Sentenced to Death in Holiday Shooting Spree</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS wiht 14 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from Simmons'
statement, comment from judge, lawyer; type of execution in
Arkansas, other detail, picking up 10th graf, `Simmons was...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XOS2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of slaying 16 people was
convicted Thursday and sentenced to death in the holiday season
shooting rampage that left a man and a woman dead. He immediately
asked that the sentence be carried out as soon as possible so that
the ``torture and suffering within me'' would end.
   A Franklin County Circuit Court jury deliberated less than 1{
hours before convicting R. Gene Simmons of capital murder and five
counts of attempted capital murder. They then heard arguments on
whether to sentence him to death or to life in prison without
parole, and later returned the death penalty.
   This trial, which started Monday, stemmed from a 45-minute
shooting spree in Russellville on Dec. 28.
   Simmons, 47, is scheduled to stand trial again in July in the
deaths of his wife, seven children, four grandchildren, and two
in-laws whose bodies were found in and around his house after the
rampage ended. They had all been shot or strangled.
   After Circuit Judge John S. Patterson ratified the death penalty
verdict, Simmons put on his glasses and in a calm voice read a
brief statement asking that the sentence be carried out as soon as
possible.
   ``It is my wish and my desire that absolutely no action by
anybody be taken to appeal or in any way change this sentence,''
Simmons said.
   ``It is further respectfully requested that this sentence be
carried out expeditiously. I want no action that will delay, deny,
defer or denounce this very correct and proper death sentence.''
   ``I only ask for what I deserve,'' he said. ``Let the torture
and suffering in me end. Please allow me the right to be at peace.''
   Afterward, the judge said it was not clear whether Simmons had
the legal right to cancel the automatic appeal provided for death
sentences in state law.
   Under Arkansas law, the death penalty would be carried out by
lethal injection.
   Earlier, prosecutor John Bynum, arguing for death for the
retired Air Force master sergeant, had said ``there is nothing in
the record that says this man is entitled to a break _ nothing.''
   Defense attorney Robert E. Irwin, who had rested his case
without calling any witnesses, asked the jury for mercy.
   ``One thing is certain _ Ronald Gene Simmons is going to die in
prison,'' Irwin said. ``The only question is whether it is by our
hand or by some act of providence or by a merciful God.''
   Later, another defense attorney, John Harris, said they had
urged Simmons not to ask for the death penalty but now felt duty
bound not to oppose him.
   ``He wanted the death sentence; he felt like he deserved it,''
Harris said. ``And he wanted us as his attorneys to do everything
within our power to see that he could get the death sentence, if
you can imagine that.''
   Simmons was found guilty of capital murder _ the deaths of two
people made it a capital crime _ and of five counts of attempted
capital murder for the four people who were wounded and a fifth
person who was fired at but not hit.
   Jurors reduced a kidnapping charge to first-degree false
imprisonment and also convicted Simmons of that charge.
   In addition to the death penalty on the murder charge, the
jurors sentenced Simmons to 30 years for each of four attempted
capital murder counts, 20 years for the fifth attempted murder
count, and seven years for first-degree false imprisonment.
Patterson ordered that those sentences be served consecutively.
   In his closing statement, Irwin argued that the state did not
support its contention the murders were premeditated and that there
were no tests to link Simmons to the murder weapons and other
evidence.
   But Bynum said such tests were unnecessary because of the number
of witnesses and the testimony from Russellville Police Chief Herb
Johnston that Simmons handed him the murder weapon.
   ``The evidence in this case is strong; it's stout,'' Bynum said.
   Among the spectators in the standing-room-only courtroom were
Viola O'Shields, and her husband, Roger, relatives of some of the
Simmons' family victims.
   Tears welling in her eyes, Mrs. O'Shields displayed a photograph
of one of the victims, Simmons' 17-year-old daughter, Loretta.
``Isn't it a shame?'', she said.
   Killed were Kathy Kendrick, 24, who reportedly had spurned
Simmons' advances a year before the shooting; and James Chaffin,
33, described by police as a chance victim. She was shot at the law
office where she worked, while he was shot at an oil company.
   A state ballistics expert, Paul McDonald, testified that bullets
that killed Kendrick and Chaffin, and bullets found at a market
where two people were wounded, had been fired by the same nine-shot
revolver that Simmons handed to police when he surrendered.
   The trial was moved to Ozark because of extensive pretrial
publicity.
</TEXT>
