<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     05-12 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arguments To Finish Friday In Cocaine-Smuggling Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Was Carlos Lehder Rivas responsible
for smuggling tons of cocaine into this country from his native
Colombia, or was he victimized by a group of deceitful American
smugglers who are cooperating with prosecutors to reduce their own
legal problems?
   Those are the contrasting points of view advanced by attorneys
for the government and defense in closing arguments in Lehder's
trial on cocaine-smuggling charges.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, in his rebuttal arguments Thursday,
said Lehder wore masks ``that have been stripped away by the
evidence.''
   Merkle was scheduled to finish his arguments Friday morning and
the jury was expected to get the case later in the day.
   He blasted closing arguments by defense attorney Edward R.
Shohat, saying it was an ``attempt to plant a seed of doubt in your
mind that is not there.''
   ``All he wants to do is to create doubt in one person's mind
because your verdict has to be unanimous,'' Merkle told jurors.
   Lehder, 38, and co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, are on trial
on charges they conspired to smuggle some 3.3 tons of cocaine into
the United States from Colombia via Lehder's private Bahamian
island, Norman's Cay, from 1978 to 1980.
   The prosecutor contends the Colombian was responsible for
smuggling 18,000 kilograms into the United States and had earned
$20 million.
   Merkle challenged arguments by defense attorneys that Lehder was
victimized by convicted drug smuggler Ed Ward and members of his
American organization.
   ``Ward was just another pilot,'' Merkle said.
   Shohat ended his arguments for Lehder on Thursday by telling the
jury to ``do what you feel is right.''
   The jury must not condemn Lehder based on the prosecution's
attacks on his character, said Shohat, but must stick to the
specific charges contained in the 11-count indictment.
   Shohat spent the morning again hammering away at what he said
were inconsistencies in the testimony of government witnesses, many
of whom were admitted smugglers given immunity for their testimony.
   Later, Merkle said, ``The attack on the credibility of the
witnesses is this case is so much sound and fury.''
   Shohat had said the chief prosecution witness, convicted
smuggler Ed Ward, was ``given the break of a lifetime'' for his
testimony against Lehder, getting a possible 215-year sentence and
$5.9 million fine cut to less than six years in prison.
   Shohat went through what he termed ``the litany of lies''
testified to by several members of Ward's group of American
smugglers.
   ``These people planned to dump on Mr. Lehder. These people knew
how to get an American Express card to freedom,'' he said.
   Lehder, who officials have said was a key member of Colombia's
violent Medellin cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession of
cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and
operating a continuing criminal enterprise. He was arrested near
the Colombian town of Medellin in February 1987 after a shootout
and was immediately flown to Florida for trial.
   Reed, of San Pedro, Calif., is charged with smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
