<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TreasureScam     05-12 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasure Scam,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Accused Of Fleecing 700 of $1.7 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people were arrested Thursday on
charges of running a treasure-hunting scam that fleeced 700
investors of $1.7 million.
   ``This was a treasure salvage company, but the only treasure
found was the money that was taken from the pockets of investors,''
state Comptroller Gerald Lewis said.
   The three companies accused of wrongdoing traded on the success
of the treasure-hunter Mel Fisher, who found Spanish treasure ships
off the Florida Keys and retrieved gold and jewels worth millions
of dollars, Lewis said.
   ``The people bought a ship from Mel Fisher and they bought
apparently a small amount of treasure so they could show this and
use it and use Mel Fisher's name,'' Lewis said.
   Lewis said the operators falsely claimed they found three
wrecks. No treasure-hunting was ever done and no treasure was
found, he said.
   Instead, the defendants pocketed investors' money, and it is
unlikely they will get any of it back, the comptroller said.
   Fisher is not involved in any of the operations and is not
accused of any wrongdoing, Lewis said.
   The five people arrested were indicted by a grand jury May 5 on
charges of fraud, sale of unregistered securities and racketeering.
   The three agencies that announced the arrests also are
investigating as many as 15 other treasure-hunting operations
seeking investors with ``treasure fever,'' Lewis said. Most of the
bogus operations are in Florida, but a few are out of state.
   Most of those under investigation also have been trading on
Fisher's success.
</TEXT>
