<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Noriega 3rdLd-Writethru a0778 05-12 1077</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Noriega, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0778,1040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega `Plea Bargain' in the Works, White House Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 15th graf pvs, bgng: ``In Panama, ...'' to UPDATE with
Noriega comments; INSERTS 1 graf after penultimate graf pvs, bgng:
``Sen. Alfonse ...'' to UPDATE with additional D'Amato comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said Thursday the United
States was immersed in diplomatic ``plea bargaining'' aimed at
coaxing Panama's Gen. Antonio Manuel Noriega from power, while a
U.S. attorney urged that the drug indictments against the
Panamanian ruler be prosecuted rather than dropped.
   ``We're still talking,'' chief presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said. ``What this amounts to is a plea bargain.''
   ``Maybe something will come of it and maybe something will
not,'' he said.
   At the Justice Department, U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner of Miami,
whose office obtained an indictment against Noriega, met with
Attorney General Edwin Meese III and later issued a statement
saying he wants to carry out the Noriega prosecution.
   ``I am authorized to say his views haven't changed and he wants
to proceed with the case and he's ready to proceed with the
trial,'' said Ana Barnett, Kellner's executive assistant. Meese
declined to comment on the Noriega situation. Kellner said through
Barnett, ``I presented my views,'' but he refused to discuss
details.
   Administration sources said Wednesday the indictments against
the de facto Panamanian ruler would be dropped if he stepped down
and left the country for a year. The sources, declining to be
identified publicly, said the Justice Department objected to the
offer, which was approved at a White House meeting.
   When reporters pressed Fitzwater on Thursday on the legal and
other ramifications of such a deal, he said, ``I offer no
definition of plea bargaining.''
   He said no direct negotiations have taken place with Noriega on
the matter.
   The administration move reflected increasing frustration with
the failure to dislodge Noriega after weeks of diplomatic, economic
and political pressure. But it was criticized immediately.
   ``I don't think you drop indictments against drug pushers and
people suspected of murder,'' Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis said.
   Fitzwater appeared in the White House briefing room not long
after chief of staff Howard Baker talked sympathatically of
arranging a deal to win Noriega's removal. Baker told CBS-TV such a
legal arrangement ``would be the most fruitful and productive plea
bargain.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan ``obviously has directed the negotiations
that have gone on there, but I won't go further.'' He stressed that
there have been no direct talks between Reagan and Noriega.
   An administration source said Wednesday that if Noriega accepts
the deal, he would step down probably in August and would stay out
of Panama until after the next presidential elections there in 1989.
   The deal was approved Tuesday at a White House meeting over the
objections of Meese, the source said.
   In Panama, Noriega was quoted as saying in the army newspaper
Critica, one of his propaganda organs: ``There cannot be and will
not be a deal while aggression against Panama and plans for
dismantling the popular forces continue'' to form part of the
administration's plan.
   Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Michael G. Kozak went to
Panama early last week and has been conferring with Noriega and his
representatives ever since, according to administration sources who
spoke on condition they not be named.
   Fitzwater refused either to name the U.S. contacts in the
negotiations with Noriega or say what sorts of incentives were
being offered by this country.
   ``You may characterize it as plea bargaining, but I'm not saying
what's on the table,'' he said. ``We won't discuss who's directly
involved.''
   In Miami, the federal judge handling the Noriega case questioned
whether the government alone can drop the drug indictment.
   ``My understanding and knowledge of the law is that the
presiding judge is not required to dismiss an indictment on the
motion of the government,'' U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler
said. ``However, I am having the law researched further.''
   Noriega's attorney, Neal Sonnett, said the Panamanian ruler
``always has believed that the indictment against him was a
political indictment. So a dismissal of the indictment would have
to be a precondition to any discussions.''
   Noriega, a onetime close associate of the late Panamanian leader
Omar Torrijos, has headed the Panamanian Defense Forces for nearly
five years. In February, he refused an order from President Eric
Arturo Delvalle to resign, and then fired Delvalle, who has been in
hiding since.
   There were earlier reports of a U.S. willingness to allow
Noriega to go into exile without pursuing his extradition, and in
early April, there were reports that the State Department was
advocating kidnaping.
   Baker acknowledged April 9 that an array of economic sanctions,
including the freezing of Panamanian assets in this country and the
withholding of U.S. payments to the Panama Treaty Commission, have
``hurt the people more than they have hurt'' Noriega.
   NBC News, quoting an American official it did not identify, said
Wednesday night that Reagan had decided to support dismissing the
indictments after National Security Council advisers warned that
further delay in getting Noriega out could lead to a political
alliance between Noriega and Cuban leader Fidel Cstro. Fitzwater
would not comment on that.
   Dukakis wasn't alone Thursday in reacting to the possibility of
dropping the indictments.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said if descriptions of the offer were
accurate, it would appear to be a victory for Noriega, allowing his
loyalists to retain control while he spent ``a year's vacation on
the Riviera.''
   ``If I was a cop in Boston or Miami or somewhere, I'd sit there
and say this administration has sent a signal that crime does
pay,'' Kerry said in a CBS interview.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said, ``I think it'd be a terrible
mistake to take the word of a drug-dealing killer dictator that
he's going to get out and allow free elections sometime next year,
and he'd be allowed to stay in until August. And the only thing
you're going to have is a transferance of power to his cronies.''
   D'Amato said of the administration's dealings with Panama:
``What we have here is an administration that's set its hair on
fire and is trying to put it out with a hammer.''
   Ambassador Juan Sosa said Noriega's opponents cannot accept the
dropping of charges without any arrangements made for next year's
election, the restructuring of the defense forces Noriega controls
or the setting up of a government of reconciliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
