<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Panama-Chronology     05-12 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama-Chronology,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chronology of Major Evens In Panamanian Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Noriega, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the Panamanian crisis:
   FEB. 25 _ Panama's president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, announces
dismissal of defense chief Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who had
been indicted in the United States on drug charges.
   FEB. 26 _ Noriega-dominated National Assembly ousts Delvalle.
Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma named head of state. Noriega
opponents call for general strike.
   MARCH 1 _ General strike gains support. Locally owned banks
close. International banks limit withdrawals.
   MARCH 3 _ Organizers end general strike. U.S. federal courts
block withdrawal of Panama funds from American banks.
   MARCH 4 _ National Bank of Panama says it cannot meet cash
demands. International banks fearing a run on deposits close their
doors.
   MARCH 11 _ President Reagan imposes economic sanctions,
including eliminating trade preferences for Panama and placing
Panama Canal fees in escrow.
   MARCH 14 _ Public employees stage work stoppages and riot when
government is unable to pay wages. Riot police use tear gas and
truncheons to disperse demonstrators.
   MARCH 16 _ Noriega survives coup attempt by dissident officers.
Demonstrations and strikes at state-run utility companies, ports
and government ministries.
   MARCH 17 _ Government declares ``state of urgency'' and soldiers
patrol capital.
   MARCH 18 _ Noriega meets with U.S. State Department officials
who say the United States will not extradite him on the drug
charges if he seeks asylum in third country. Noriega reportedly
says he wants to remain in Panama and take part in formation of
transitional government.
   MARCH 20 _ U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz says
indictments against Noriega will not be dropped and Noriega cannot
have say about government after his departure.
   MARCH 21 _ General strike paralyzes nation. Solis Palma
announces Noriega offers to resign before May 1989 elections if
opponents agree to talks. Opposition leaders and United States
reject offer.
   MARCH 30 _ Nation's three biggest supermarket chains open,
signaling rupture in general strike. Government announces banks
will reopen with limited service.
   APRIL 8 _ Reagan bans payments from American citizens or
companies to Panama's government, including bills, fees or fines.
   APRIL 20 _ Government lifts state of emergency.
   APRIL 28 _ White House backs away from insisting Noriega leave
Panama, saying he just has to resign. Panamanian opposition
protests change in stance.
   APRIL 30 _ United States relaxes order prohibiting payments by
Americans to Panama.
   MAY 7 _ Noriega rejects U.S. ultimatum to resign and leave
Panama and says he is considering Guatemalan offer to mediate end
to crisis.
   MAY 9 _ Banks let customers make limited cash withdrawals.
   MAY 11 _ Reagan administration sources say Washington has
offered to drop drug charges against Noriega if he steps down and
leaves country. Panamanian government says there has been no deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
