<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0728 05-12 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Hebron</HEAD>
<HEAD>Army Prohibits Residents from Leaving Gaza</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with closing of Gaza, Moslem crowds
praying in Jerusalem, other detail</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers prohibited residents from
leaving the occupied Gaza Strip on Thursday, trying to reduce the
violence expected in Jerusalem at the close of the Moslem holy
month of Ramadan.
   In the West Bank, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told the people
of Hebron bloodshed would end if they stopped the 5-month-old
rebellion against Israeli occupation. The violence has taken the
lives of 186 Palestinians and two Israelis.
   The Israeli air force made its eighth raid into Lebanon this
year, attacking Palestinian targets south of Beirut. Lebanese
police said six fighter-bombers took part in the attack at Barja,
16 miles outside Beirut.
   An Israeli army spokesman said the ban on leaving the coastal
Gaza Strip, where 600,000 Palestinians live, began at 10 p.m. and
would last ``until further notice.''
   He said the closure did not apply to the West Bank, home to
about 900,000 Palestinians, but police spokesman Alex Lapidoth said
extra soldiers were at roadblocks between the West Bank and Holy
City and they were being ``more strict.''
   Closing off Gaza was intended to to lessen the potential for
violence during the period beginning with the Moslem ``Night of
Fate'' Thursday and continuing through Friday, the last Moslem
sabbath of Ramadan.
   Israeli officials have expressed fear that mass prayer services
Thursday and Friday on sacred Haram al Sharif would lead to riots
in Arab east Jerusalem. Haram al Sharif means Noble Enclosure and
is the Arab name for Temple Mount.
   The ban also might run through the last day of Ramadan early
next week. The holy month ends Monday or Tuesday, depending on when
the new moon is sighted.
   Tens of thousands of Moslem worshipers traditionally come to
Jerusalem for the ``Night of Fate,'' marking the revelation of the
holy Koran to the Prophet Mohammed. More come for sabbath prayers
on the final Friday of Ramadan.
   Israel radio said about 10,000 worshipers prayed Thursday night
at Temple Mount, site of the Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa mosques.
It said several hundred raised the outlawed Palestinian flag,
chanted slogans and threw stones at military police, who responded
with rubber bullets.
   Reports by the state and army radios said a policeman was hit in
the head by a stone and 38 Palestinians were arrested. There were
no reports of Arab wounded.
   Israel television said police and troops would turn back groups
of Palestinians trying to enter the city Thursday and Friday in an
effort to reduce the crowds on Temple Mount, which also is sacred
to Jews.
   About 3,000 police began patrolling the hill and surrounding
areas. Residents reported a huge police presence in east Jerusalem.
   Israel's police commissioner, David Kraus, said ``all necessary
measures'' would be taken to prevent disturbances.
   Officials also are worried about violence Sunday. Israelis will
honor both the nation's 40th anniversary and the 21st anniversary
of the seizure of Arab east Jerusalem in the 1967 Middle East war,
when the West Bank and Gaza were captured.
   Israel radio said the army had decided to begin re-opening West
Bank schools early next week. It said elementary schools would open
first, followed by the higher levels if no disturbances occurred.
   An army spokesman said he could not comment on the report. The
schools were closed Feb. 2 because they had become rallying points
for protesters.
   Israel radio said about 200 prisoners in the occupied
territories would be freed Friday as a goodwill gesture for the
close of Ramadan. The army spokesman confirmed prisoners would be
released but said he did not know how many.
   Soldiers fired on Palestinian protesters in Nablus, wounding
five, Arab reports and hospital officials said. The army reported
three wounded.
   Shamir visited Hebron, the second largest city in the West Bank,
for the first time since violence began in the occupied territories
Dec. 8, and toured the open-air market.
   He appealed through an interpreter for an end to the violence
and an Arab rejoined: ``The government should start treating the
Palestinians as human beings, especially now during religious
celebrations.''
   The prime minister's reply: ``The population should start to
behave, and not only during holidays. If there would be quiet and
order, nothing would be done against the population.''
</TEXT>
