<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending 3rdLd-Writethru a0772 05-12 0933</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0772,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Considers Plans To Use Military To Fight Drug-Runners</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead with 2 grafs to UPDATE with prospects for passage
slipping to Friday; INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs bgng,
`Another proposal,' to UPDATE with later comments from Nunn,
D'Amato; ADDS new last graf with Persian Gulf vote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday was trying to find a
way to increase U.S. military involvement in the war against
illegal drugs, but bogged down in a dispute over whether to give
the Navy new powers to arrest drug traffickers in international
waters.
   The dispute centered around a Pentagon budget bill, which the
Senate is trying to finish. The argument over the anti-drug
provision is the major remaining hurdle and Senate leaders said
they don't expect to pass the bill before Friday.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci attended a closed-door
series of meetings at the Capitol to discuss the anti-drug plans,
which have been proposed in response to what legislators say is
public demand to do more to halt drug-trafficking.
   ``We're all looking for a way to have the military more involved
in a meaningful way in the war against drugs,'' said Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee and the chief
author of one anti-drug proposal.
   The bill authorizes defense spending in the fiscal year starting
Oct. 1 of $299.5 billion, the same total contained in a separate
Pentagon budget bill passed Wednesday by the House. Differences
between the measures will be worked out later by a House-Senate
conference committee.
   The House bill contains a provision ordering President Reagan to
have the military ``substantially halt'' the penetration of U.S.
borders by ships and planes carrying illegal drugs.
   The plan proposed by Nunn is not as far reaching, but it would
make the Pentagon the chief federal agency in halting illegal
drug-trafficking, and also would have the Pentagon provide more
coordination and communications to other drug-fighting agencies
such as the Drug Enforcement Administration and the Coast Guard.
   Making the Defense Department the chief federal agency for
anti-drug efforts would mean it would have to approve actions by
all other federal agencies.
   Another proposal authored by Sens. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., would allow U.S. military personnel to
make anti-drug arrests outside U.S. borders, such as beyond the
three-mile limit recognized by the United States.
   Nunn, D'Amato and Wilson said they were trying to craft their
separate proposals into a single bill, but the main sticking point
was over whether to give the military arrest powers in
international waters.
   The plan will not be approved before Friday, Nunn said.
   Asked about the reaction of Pentagon officials, D'Amato said,
``They're not happy. ... They're not doing cartwheels.''
   The military is now barred from enforcing civilian laws by the
Posse Comitatus Act, an 1878 law enacted to halt the practice of
having the Army enforce laws in the post-Civil War southern states.
   That law was amended in 1981 to permit the military to provide
some aid, and U.S. military surveillance information is now passed
along to some civilian agencies. In addition, Coast Guard officials
now travel aboard Navy ships patrolling the Caribbean Sea.
   Carlucci has offered to have the Pentagon do more in the
anti-drug effort, although he opposes having the military make
arrests.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said Thursday that the military
can slow, but not halt, the flow of drugs.
   ``If the effort here is to reduce the amount of drugs coming
into this country, it can be done,'' Howard said. ``If the effort
is expected to stop drugs coming into this country, it cannot be
done. Unless you do it on the demand side, ways will be found.''
   The military can track planes, Howard noted, but ``it's
difficult to tell the difference between a civilian flight and one
that is engaged in drug smuggling.''
   ``We have ample military resources to be able to stop every
aircraft at our border, but in fact that's a much more complex
problem than I think most people realize,'' he said.
   As it worked through the bill Thursday, the Senate:
   _Voted 57-39 to kill an effort to ban most U.S. underground
nuclear testing. The House, in its version of the bill, approved an
underground test ban, meaning the issue will have to be resolved by
the conference committee.
   _Voted 64-32 to restore a ``Buy America'' requirement which
requires the Petnagon to buy U.S. products, including anthracite
coal. The Pentagon says it already has a four-year supply of the
coal and doesn't need any more.
   _Killed, on a 60-37 vote, a proposal that would have halted the
sending of any U.S. combat troops to leftist-ruled Nicaragua or its
neighbor, Honduras. The troop ban was approved last week by the
House, meaning the issue will have to be decided by the conference.
Reagan has said repeatedly the United States has no intention of
sending combat troops to Nicaragua.
   _Killed, on a 61-36 vote, a plan to reduce spending for the
railroad version of the MX nuclear-tipped missile from $700 million
to $200, using the extra $500 million to buy more non-nuclear
weapons. The House proposes to spend only $100 million for the rail
version of the MX.
   _Rejected, 82-13, the latest proposal to have the Senate express
a formal opinion on Reagan's Persian Gulf policy. The amendment
would have required a detailed report from Reagan outlining his
plans for Navy involvement in the war-torn region, and would have
given Congress 15 days after that to formally vote on the policy.
</TEXT>
