<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoPhones     05-12 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Phones,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Bell Says Weeks Required To Restore Service After Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phone service to Chicago's western suburbs will
not be fully restored until late in June following a fire at a
switching station that caused the worst service disruption in the
company's history, Illinois Bell said Thursday.
   James Eibel, Illinois Bell's vice president of operations, said
``significant progress'' has been made in restoring telephone
circuits passing through its west suburban Hinsdale switching
center, which was heavily damaged by fire Sunday.
   But he told a news conference it would take at least until the
third week in June before all 35,000 customers affected by the
outage have full service. Phones in all or parts of six western
suburbs have been dead since the fire.
   ``This was the most severe service disruption Illinois Bell has
had in its history,'' Eibel said of the 107-year-old company. ``The
scope and complexity of the repair work far exceeds anything we've
had in the past ... and that includes any natural disasters.''
   Illinois Bell investigators have still not determined the cause
of the fire.
   By overhauling damaged local switching equipment as a stopgap
measure, the phone company hoped to restore 21,000 service lines by
Sunday, Eibel said. But he cautioned that this was the most
optimistic projection.
   Eibel said he could not guarantee the old equipment would hold
up against corrosion caused by the chemical reaction from smoke and
water sprayed by firefighters.
   Emergency service to hospitals, police and fire departments, the
company's first priority, may be back in service in the next couple
of days, Eibel said.
   Illinois Bell employees were working round-the-clock Thursday to
install new equipment, which should be in place by June 1, although
it will take another three weeks to restore service to all local
residents, Eibel said. It normally takes 50 weeks to install a
completely new system.
   The telephone company was having more success in repairing
damage to 13,000 special lines used by businesses and the
``trunking service'' knocked out by the fire at the Hinsdale
station.
   About half of the trunking service had been restored by
Thursday, and all 118,000 circuits connecting the western and
southwestern suburbs with the rest of the Chicago metropolitan area
and long distance providers should be back in service by late
Sunday, Eibel said.
   He expected that the business service lines would be fully back
in operation by the end of next week. Special service lines are
used by business customers for a variety of purposes, including
data transmission.
   Eibel acknowledged a considerable delay in the time between when
the fire was first reported at the unmanned switching station and
the arrival of firefighters to fight the blaze.
   Bell received an alarm at 3:50 p.m. at a monitoring station in
Springfield, more than 150 miles away, but it was not until 4:20
p.m. that a full fire alarm sounded, Eibel said.
   After another 30 minutes, an employee arrived to check out the
alarm, but he had to hail down a passing motorist to alert
firefighters because the phones were already out of service.
Firefighters did not arrive at the scene until after 5 p.m.
   The phone company was reviewing its fire prevention measures in
light of the fire, Eibel said.
   Meanwhile, residents were trying to cope as best as possible
with the lack of phone service. People lined up at mobile trailers
with public coin phone stations at six locations in the western
suburbs.
   ``I'ts been very inconvenient,'' said Sandy Barthick, assistant
editor of a telecommunications trade paper in Hinsdale. ``I've been
doing all my phone work from my home in Chicago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
