<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ContraAid     05-12 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Official Says Humanitarian Aid To Rebels OK</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan Vice President Sergio Ramirez said
Thursday his government is willing to allow immediate delivery of
humanitarian supplies to rebels in Nicaragua and he denied his
government is trying to starve the Contras into submission.
   ``We are in full disposition to accept that the Contra forces
could receive humanitarian aid inside Nicaragua tomorrow, if
possible,'' Ramirez told reporters after a 1{-hour meeting with
House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and other Democratic
congressional leaders.
   ``We are not trying to gain this war through starvation,''
Ramirez said.
   The visit appeared to be in part an effort to counter Reagan
administration accusations that Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government is dragging its feet in peace talks to delay food and
medical supplies destined for the rebels under a $48 million aid
package passed by Congress earlier this year.
   ``There were some things necessary to clarify here about the
serious attitude of the government of Nicaragua'' toward permitting
the rebels to receive non-military supplies, Ramirez said.
   A temporary cease-fire agreement in Nicaragua's seven-year war
reached March 23 called for aid to the Contras to be delivered by a
neutral agency, but there has been no agreement on who that
delivery agent should be.
   The Sandinistas have proposed the Red Cross _ ``the very symbol
of neutrality in the world,'' according to Ramirez _ but the rebels
have rejected that idea.
   Ramirez said he was meeting later in the day with Secretary
General Joao Baena Soares of the Organization of American States to
hear his proposals for delivering the aid and said he would take
that information back to Managua.
   ``I'm sure we can agree without problems'' on some way to
deliver the aid, he said. ``If they don't want to accept (the Red
Cross), we are willing to discuss other proposals.''
   Ramirez also said he was confident talks aimed at reaching a
long-term peace accord would resume soon. The rebels have proposed
resumption of formal talks on May 19, but the Sandinistas want to
schedule one or two preliminary private rounds of talks first.
   The 60-day temporary cease-fire runs out at the end of the
month, and Ramirez reiterated his government's belief that some
extension of the temporary truce will be necessary, perhaps for
another 30 to 60 days.
</TEXT>
