<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-PersianGulf     05-12 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Persian Gulf,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Rejects Attempt to Express Formal Opinion on Persian Gulf
Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday easily rejected the
latest attempt to have the chamber express a formal opinion on
President Reagan's expanded policy of protecting shipping in the
war-torn Persian Gulf.
   The Senate voted 82-13 to table, and thus kill, an amendment to
a Pentagon budget bill that would have required a report from
Reagan outlining his policy.
   The proposal would have required specifics about the U.S. goals,
anticipated length of deployment and the rules under which U.S.
weapons would be fired.
   The plan was offered by Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., who again
criticized his colleagues for refusing to vote on whether the
Senate approves of Reagan's year-old policy.
   Adams, a critic of the administration policy, told his fellow
senators that ``for over a year we have danced around the issues.''
   Reagan's policy involves having the Navy protect 11 reflagged
Kuwaiti tankers in the gulf, which has been the scene of fighting
in the long Iran-Iraq war. Kuwait is an Iraqi ally.
   The U.S. policy recently was expanded to provide American
protection to neutral merchant ships who are attacked and who seek
U.S. help from Navy warships.
   That expanded policy came in the wake of an April 18 clash
between the Navy and Iran, in which the Navy sank or damaged six
Iranian vessels. It was the latest in a series of military fights
between the Navy and Iran.
   Congress has yet to vote formal approval or disapproval of
Reagan's policy. The Senate also has rejected Adams' repeated
efforts to invoke the War Powers Act. That is the 1973 law that
would, under some circumstances, require the withdrawal of U.S.
forces from situations of ``imminent danger.''
   Reagan has refused to invoke the War Powers law, arguing that it
is an unconstitutional restriction on his authority. Adams and 110
other legislators have sued to invoke the law, but a federal judge
rejected the suit and they are appealing that rejection.
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., a former secretary of the Navy, led the
opposition to Adams' proposal.
   ``I think it would be ill-advised for the Congress to single out
any particular military operation and say, on an annual basis, that
we're going to appropriate money for that operation.''
   Adams' proposal rejected by the Senate would have required the
report from Reagan and then would have provided 15 days for
Congress to disapprove the policy. If no disapproval vote were
taken, the policy would have been considered approved.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, criticized Reagan's policy as ``foolish
... stupid'' but he opposed Adams' plan. He said it might mean that
U.S. forces would be pulled out of the region.
   ``I don't want to see us take an action in the Persian Gulf that
would really mean we are willing to pull out,'' said Glenn.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., opposed the plan because ``this would
require the president to be a prophet. ... I'm not sure the
president can provide a plan, given the fluid nature of events in
that part of the world.''
   Adams said his proposal ``isn't a withdrawal from the Persian
Gulf. ... I do not want to withdraw our forces.''
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said the plan ``is another example
of what Congress is criticized for. ... You can't have 535
secretaries of state,'' referring to the total number of House and
Senate members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
