<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthAfricaSanctions     05-12 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa Sanctions,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislation Proposed To Strengthen Sanctions Against South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of senators introduced legislation
Thursday to impose a virtual ban on economic dealings between the
United States and South Africa.
   ``The United States has indulged the apartheid regime for 40
years,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the primary Senate
sponsor of the bill. ``It is time to chart another course.''
   The bill, similar to one pending on the House calendar, would
force U.S. businesses to divest their holdings in South Africa
within a year and would ban most trade with and lending to that
country.
   Other supporters included Sens. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., Paul Simon, D-Ill., Carl Levin and Donald
Riegle, both D-Mich., Bill Bradley and Frank Lautenberg, both
D-N.J., and Barbara Mikulski, D-Md.
   ``This will end once and for all time American complicity in,
and support for, apartheid,'' Kennedy said in announcing the bill
at a news conference.
   While supporters of the sanctions are optimistic about House
passage, the bill's fate in the Senate is unclear, in part because
moderate Republicans who were key to the passage of limited
sanctions in 1986 are reluctant to go along with harsher measures.
   The Reagan administration opposes the sanctions and a
presidential veto is likely if Congress should pass the bill.
Efforts are under way in the House to enlist the two-thirds support
that would be needed to override a veto, but that effort would be
more difficult in the Senate.
</TEXT>
