<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Punjab     05-12 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Golden Temple Fighting; Priests Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested four of Sikhism's five
high priests and 26 followers as they prepared to march Thursday to
the Golden Temple, officials said. Security forces killed at least
three people at the besieged shrine.
   Indian commandos backed by paramilitary troops captured a
strategic water tank on the temple complex grounds, where an
estimated 100 Sikh militants have been holed up since Monday,
officials said.
   About 2,500 police and paramilitary troops surrounded the
militants at the temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine. They have been
fighting intermittently since Monday.
   The Punjab government ruled out new negotiations with the
militants and demanded they surrender.
   ``If they do not do so the state government will continue its
pressure on them,'' Punjab Governor S.S. Ray said in a statement
issued in the state capital, Chandigargh.
   Talks Wednesday on ending the temple standoff were inconclusive
and a cease-fire that took effect that day ended Thursday morning.
   The militants have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1983
for more autonomy or an independent homeland for the Sikhs in
Punjab.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but are a majority in Punjab.
   Three more people, two Sikh militants and an unidentified man,
were shot and killed by security forces on Thursday, raising the
death toll in the fighting to at least 15, said A.A. Siddiqui,
state police deputy chief.
   United News of India said as many as seven Sikhs died inside the
shrine Thursday.
   Indian commandos captured the water tank in the living area of
the temple complex, said witnesses who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The priests were arrested as they attempted to march on the
Golden Temple from another Sikh shrine about a half-mile to the
north, Siddiqui said. The priests were placed in custody for 15
days on charges of violating curfew orders, Siddiqui said.
   Among those arrested was Jasbir Singh Rode, the temple's head
priest, who held talks Wednesday with government officials to try
to end the confrontation. Rode has called for the militants to
dismantle their bunkers and for the security forces to withdraw.
   Deputy Police Commissioner Sarbjeet Singh had asked them to call
off their march because two bursts of gunfire were reported inside
the temple Thursday after an overnight lull.
   ``We take responsibility for any firing from inside the
temple,'' Rode told Sarbjeet Singh, insisting that the march should
be allowed to proceed. ``You take responsibility for firing from
outside.''
   Firing from the temple increased as the morning wore on.
   Police lifted a curfew in most parts of Amritsar on Thursday,
but it remained in force within 200 yards of the Golden Temple,
Indian television said.
   Most of the shops and businesses in the old sector of Amritsar
which surrounds the temple remained shuttered even after curfew was
withdrawn in the area.
   Security forces for the first time Thursday began blocking
reporters from approaching the temple. They said Sikh militants
might shoot the journalists.
   More than 940 people have been killed this year in Punjab in
attacks blamed on the extremists. Most have been Hindus or moderate
Sikhs opposed to the separatist campaign.
   The confrontation at the Golden Temple began Monday when
militants inside the shrine opened fire on security forces who had
gone to a nearby rooftop to look at fortifications the Sikhs were
building on the northern edge of the complex.
   The temple complex covers an area equivalent to more than five
city blocks. The temple sits in the center of a pool.
   The Indian army was sent into the Golden Temple complex in June
1984 to flush out Sikh extremists. More than 1,200 people were
killed in the attack. Later that year, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi
was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards.
</TEXT>
