<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-AfghanRelief     05-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghan Relief,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Afghan Relief Boss Says Hundreds of Millions Needed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghan Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan, head of U.N.
relief for Afghanistan, said Thursday an international appeal will
be launched in three weeks for hundreds of millions of dollars for
refugee aid and reconstruction.
   ``We must see to equitable distribution and certainly relief
would be without strings attached and should not be used for
political manipulation,'' he told a news conference.
   ``The important thing is that the aid gets to the people who
need it.''
   The amount has not been set.
   The prince, a U.N. high commissioner for refugees from 1965-77,
said he hopes to meet all parties concerned, rebels included. The
rebels control much of the Afghan countryside and he indicated they
could play an important part in relief distribution.
   ``I am concerned about the Afghan people as a whole and we need
to find ways to get help where it is needed,'' he said.
   The 55-year-old prince was named Wednesday as
undersecretary-general to coordinate all international relief
efforts in Afghanistan and resettlement of 5 million refugees.
   Facing him is the task of insuring that a vast amount of aid
will be distributed fairly by U.N. and other agencies. He must see
aid is not exploited or manipulated by the pro-Soviet government in
Kabul or by the anti-Marxist rebels, who reject the political
accord on withdrawing Soviet troops.
   The United Nations mediated the Geneva agreement between
Afghanistan and Pakistan providing for the 115,000 Soviet troops in
Afghanistan to withdraw over a nine-month period.
   The prince emphasized that U.N. relief efforts are separate from
the political agreement.
   Answering a question, he said he could not give the amount of
aid needed for relief, reconstruction and rehabilitation, but it
would amount to ``hundreds of millions of dollars.''
   He said Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar probably will
launch the appeal to donor countries in three weeks.
   Sadruddin Aga Khan said he will shuttle between Kabul and
Islamabad from his base in Geneva and that he will go to the area
next week.
   He said his work will involve coordinating the work of many U.N.
agencies _ including the World Health Organization, the United
Nations Development Program, the Food and Agriculture Organization
and others _ as well as the International Red Cross; the Red
Crescent, its Islamic counterpart, and other groups.
   He said many governments already have indicated their
willingness to make generous contributions and have been awaiting a
U.N. mechanism for distribution. He said his immediate task is to
formulate an appeal and assure donors how their money will be spent.
   He said repatriation of refugees will be a major task and
reception centers must be set up for displaced people wanting to
return.
</TEXT>
