<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlantBlast 1stLd-Writethru a0793 05-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0793,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerr-McGee Shuts Down Ammonium Perchlorate Production Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Friday to Thursday in 5th graf pvs, `Earlier Friday
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket fuel manufacturer Thursday
blamed a natural gas leak for a series of earthquake-force
explosions May 4 that demolished a plant, killing two people and
injuring 326.
   Fred Gibson, chairman of the Pacific Engineering and Production
Co., said the high-pressure gas line passing through the plant had
been leaking for at least 30 minutes before a fire broke out May 4
at the plant.
   ``All of the subsequent destructive events were caused by the
gas leak, the gas fire and the gas explosion,'' he said.
   Gibson said the leak is believed to have saturated the earth
below the paved surfaces of the plant and ignited ``as a result of
circumstances unrelated to PEPCON operations.''
   Earlier Thursday, Kerr-McGee Corp. bowed to pressure from the
state and halted production at the only other U.S. plant making the
fuel component ammonium perchlorate until an independent inspection
determines its plant is safe.
   Southwest Gas Corp. vehemently denied the allegation, saying gas
mains under the plant ruptured only after the initial explosions.
   ``As far as we're concerned, our facilities are a victim of the
explosion and not the cause,'' said spokesman Dennis Hetherington.
   Fire Chief Roy Parrish said Wednesday that the Fire Department
would withhold judgment until it completes an investigation of the
blast, which caused an estimated $73 million in damage.
   A Kerr-McGee official said he hoped the company's own plant
could resume manufacture within a few days of ammonium perchlorate,
an oxidizer used in the space shuttle and in missiles.
   ``A prolonged shutdown is not helpful to any of us,'' said Paul
Gaines, Kerr-McGee director of governmental relations.
   ``I think Kerr-McGee has done the responsible thing in agreeing
to suspend production,'' said Gov. Richard Bryan, who had met with
company executives two hours Wednesday.
   Bryan said ``legal work was being prepared'' to force the plant
to suspend production at McKerr-McGee before it agreed to the
shutdown.
   Gaines said the company, which will continue to manufacture
other chemicals at the Henderson plant, has contracted with an
unidentified safety consultant to study the plant. He said the
inspection could begin by Monday.
   Local and state officials had expressed outrage when the plant
resumed production Tuesday of ammonium perchlorate. Plant officials
had said last week they would not reopen until authorities
determined the cause of the Pacific blast.
   Gaines said the Kerr-McGee plant is completely safe. ``We are
blameless here,'' he said. ``It is not our plant that exploded.''
   Meanwhile, Bryan announced the appointment of seven people to a
panel charged with reviewing health, safety, zoning and insurance
standards for industries with highly combustible materials.
   Lt. Gov. Bob Miller will be chairman of the the panel, which
Bryan said will complete its work within 90 days.
</TEXT>
