<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Sketches     05-12 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Sketches,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Sketches of Seven New Cabinet Ministers in France</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Premier Michel Rocard on Thursday named
26 Cabinet ministers. Here are sketches of seven key members of the
Cabinet.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, 65, is a longtime friend of
President Francois Mitterrand who has served as his emissary on
delicate diplomatic missions. Dumas has been elected to the
National Assembly four times and was foreign minister from 1984-86,
when the Socialist government was replaced by the conservative
Cabinet of Premier Jacques Chirac. He is an attorney, a scholar in
Oriental languages and an art collector.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Defense Jean-Pierre Chevenement, 49, served as
minister of research and technology from 1981-83, when he quit in
protest over economic austerity measures adopted by the Socialist
government. He was education minister from 1984-86. He is known as
a hardline Socialist.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Interior Minister Pierre Joxe, 53, served briefly as industry
minister before becoming interior minister from 1984-86. Joxe
implemented a plan for modernizing the police force. A member of
the Socialist Party's executive committee, he led the Socialists in
the National Assembly from 1981-84. His father was a minister under
Gen. Charles de Gaulle.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy, 62, also served as finance
minister from 1984-86, after first serving as social affairs
minister from 1982-84. Known as a pragmatist, he won praise from
financiers and industrialists for his steps to modernize French
markets.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Culture Jack Lang, 48, served as culture minister
from 1981-86. Only Andre Malraux held the post longer. His dynamic,
passionate style and dark good looks made him a media darling. A
fan of American culture, Lang created the National Orchestra of
Jazz. A jurist and former professor of international law, he held a
number of posts in the Socialist Party.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Education Lionel Jospin, 50, replaced Mitterrand as
Socialist Party chief after Mitterrand was elected president in
1981.
   The education post is seen as key and sensitive. Mitterrand
promised that education would be a priority during his next seven
years in office. Reform of the educational system has brought
hundreds of thousands of demonstrators into the streets on at least
two occasions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Overseas Territories Olivier Stern, 52, is to the
right of the mainstream Socialists and is a former member of the
conservative Rally for the Republic. He served as minister of
overseas territories from 1974-78 under the Chirac government.
Stern's problems include resolving the political crisis in France's
Pacific territory of New Caledonia.
</TEXT>
