<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-CentralAmerica     05-12 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Central America,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Endorses Blueprint for Central American
Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly on Thursday endorsed
a plan calling for $4.3 billion in economic development programs in
Central America aimed at fostering peace and democracy.
   The 159-nation body approved the resolution by consensus only a
day after a military rebellion was put down in Guatemala. That
country represented the region during the U.N. debate.
   Nealy half the money, $2 billion, would be debt relief.
   The resolution puts the assembly's stamp of approval on an
ambitious and wide-ranging program for regional reconstruction,
emergency relief and long-term development that depends on the
generosity of the international community.
   U.N. officials have not indicated exactly how they plan to raise
the money for the program. However, its coordinator, Augusto
Ramirez Ocampo, has been trying to line up donors, particularly in
Western Europe.
   More than 45 nations, including most of the European Community,
signed on as sponsors of the resolution. Britain, concerned about
the plan's call for debt relief, was an exception.
   ``We take the view that the matter of bilateral commercial debt
is a matter between creditor governments and creditor banks,'' said
Stephen Smith, a spokesman for the British mission.
   The United States, which did not commit itself to contributing
any money to the U.N. plan, shared Britain's reservations about
debt relief.
   Ambassador Lester B. Korn reminded the assembly that the United
States has given $4 billion in direct aid to El Salvador,
Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica since 1985 and contributed an
additional $1 billion to international organizations active in the
region.
   ``The United States is pleased that the General Assembly is on
record as supporting what the United States has been doing for the
past decade in this troubled area of the world,'' Korn said.
   Korn criticized the plan for being vague about sources of
funding.
   Work on the development plan began shortly after five Central
American presidents signed a regional peace accord last summer.
   The U.N. development plans calls for $392 million to resettle
the estimated 830,000 people displaced by the civil wars in
Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala, and to provide emergency food
and energy assistance.
   About $1.4 billion would be earmarked for long-term projects
running the gamut from rebuilding roads to vocational training for
the handicapped to encouraging tourism.
   The plan also calls for spending $600 million to revive a
Central American common market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
