<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-US-Soviet 2ndLd-Writethru a0673 05-12 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0673,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Soviets Settle Differences on Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 5 grafs SUB for grafs 17-21 pvs, The Soviet ... UPDATING with
details on sticking point, solution. Picks up 22nd graf pvs,
Regarding missile ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Soviet Union settled their
differences Thursday on a historic treaty to scrap medium-range
missiles and sent the agreement to the U.S. Senate in an effort to
speed ratification of the pact before the Moscow summit.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, winding up two days of
talks with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, told
reporters: ``We have reached a completely satisfactory agreement on
all of these issues.''
   The Senate postponed debate on the treaty Monday while some
members accused Moscow of backsliding and leaving loopholes for
cheating. But Shultz said the differences over verifying compliance
with the pact were a result of implementing an unprecedented system
of on-site inspection.
   ``Occasionally, they'll have an argument,'' Shultz said of the
technicians who will carry out the agreement to destroy 683 Soviet
missiles and 364 U.S. missiles with a range of 315 to 3,125 miles.
``That's life.''
   He called the settlement he reached with Shevardnadze
``absolutely satisfactory.'' It was initialed by Maynard Glitman,
who negotiated the treaty, and Col. Gen. Nikolai Chervov, the
senior arms control adviser to the Soviet military.
   Shultz said Glitman and Lt. Gen. Colin Powell, the U.S. national
security adviser, would fly to Washington on Thursday night to
report to the Senate on Friday.
   ``I think it will be well-received,'' Shultz said.
   The Moscow meeting between President Reagan and Mikhail S.
Gorbachev is scheduled to begin May 29.
   Chief U.S. negotiator Max Kampelman and Soviet negotiator Viktor
P. Karpov signed another document at the Soviet mission that
guarantees any futuristic weapons developed in the
intermediate-range also would be banned under the treaty.
   Two of the principal stumbling blocks to verification of the
treaty dealt with U.S. demands to inspect Soviet missile containers
big enough to hold only a stage of a rocket and the issue of how
much access U.S. inspectors will have to Soviet missile plants and
bases.
   Other issues dealt with photographing equipment, updating data
exchanged between the two sides and the size and weight of vehicles
that can be inspected leaving Votkinsk, where Soviet SS-20 missiles
are assembled.
   The pact on intermediate-range missiles is unprecedented in its
provisions for on-site inspection to guard against infractions. It
also is the first U.S.-Soviet agreement to eliminate an entire
category of nuclear weapons.
   The document on futuristic weapons was aimed at convincing Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, and other critics that the ban would apply to
intermediate-range weapons that have not been developed yet.
   Glitman and Powell were taking the second document to the Senate
as well. While Shultz obviously was satisified with the results, he
said ``what the Senate does is up to the Senate.''
   With evident relief, however, he told reporters: ``I hope I've
heard the last of INF (Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces) at these
ministerials.''
   Shevardnadze, at a separate news conference, said the Soviets
did not view the differences as technical but as ``very serious
problems that required political decisions.'' He added: ``And such
solutions were found.''
   Shultz and Shevardnadze declined to provide specific details of
how the dispute was resolved.
   Senior U.S. officials, however, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the Soviets wanted the United States to destroy
West German Pershing 1-A missiles, but were satisfied the Bonn
government itself would scrap them.
   After a telephone call to Bonn, the U.S. side told the Soviets
where the missiles are stored and how many there are _ 21.
   ``We got back to everything we wanted,'' an official said,
referring to the range of disputes on INF.
   Another official, while not criticizing the Senate, said all the
issues could have been resolved quietly with the Soviets if they
had not been made public in newspaper accounts.
   Regarding missile canisters, the official said American
inspectors will be able to look inside, but not take the parts out.
``They gave in enough,'' he said.
   Shultz said, ``I think when the senators see it (the agreement)
I think they will see that it was worked out satisfactorily.''
   On a related subject, Shultz ruled out quick completion of
another treaty to reduce U.S. and Soviet long-range nuclear weapons
arsenals by 30 to 50 percent.
   Reagan had hoped to make the accord the centerpiece of his four
days of talks with Gorbachev.
   Negotiations are moving slowly on how to verify the scrapping of
mobile missiles as well as cruise missiles carried on warships and
fighter planes.
   There is also a nagging dispute over the U.S. program to develop
a space-based defense against Soviet ballistic missiles. The
Soviets are trying to constrict the program, known as Star Wars.
   ``It's now clear,'' Shultz said, ``there is no way these
questions can be shaped up and ready in time for the summit.''
</TEXT>
