<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 2ndLd-Writethru a0764 05-12 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0764,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Reacts To Paraguay Challenge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 20th graf ``He was...'' with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
final appearance of day. Pickup 21st graf pvs ``John Paul...'';
minor editing thruout to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUCRE, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican said Thursday it was shocked
by the sudden cancellation by Paraguay's military government of a
meeting between Pope John Paul II and civic leaders, including
opposition politicians.
   ``For now, I must clearly state the astonishment caused by a
decision without precedent in the exercising of the pastoral
mission by the Holy Father,'' chief Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro said in a written statement.
   It was the first time in 37 foreign papal tours that a
government had scratched a meeting after it was announced.
   The Vatican statement was released as the pope arrived in this
9,150-foot- high university city. John Paul is on a 12-day,
four-country visit to South America.
   Police in Paraguay interrupted a Mass Thursday and arrested the
country's top opposition leader, Domingo Laino, and six others
including a journalist with the Roman Catholic Catholic radio
station Caritas, an opposition party spokesman said.
   Laino, head of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party, and the
others were taken into custody in Arroyito, 185 miles northeast of
Asuncion, said party spokesman Luis Wagner.
   Police gave no reason for the arrests.
   The pontiff is due to arrive in Paraguay on Monday and was
scheduled to meet the next day with the Builders of Society, a
church-sponsored group of about 350 intellectuals, union leaders,
business leaders and politicians.
   Those scheduled to meet with John Paul included representatives
of political parties that are opposed to Paraguay's president, Gen.
Alfredo Stroessner. The parties are not recognized by Stroessner.
   In all, about 3,000 people were expected to attend the meeting
at a government-owned sports complex.
   But Stroessner, South America's longest-ruling military
dictator, canceled the meeting Wednesday, citing security reasons
and charging that the encounter would be used for political
purposes.
   An official traveling with the pope said the Vatican statement
was issued in hopes the government would change its mind.
   The Vatican official, briefing reporters on condition of
anonymity, said the church was pursuing discussions with Paraguayan
authorities on the conflict.
   In Asuncion, Catholic Church officials vowed Thursday to hold
the meeting at another location.
   Tensions between the church and government in Paraguay have been
building for some time. Bishops there have been increasingly
critical of the human rights record and authoritarian style of
Stroessner, who took power in a 1954 coup.
   Through such groups as Builders of Society, the church has been
campaigning for a pluralistic system of politics. The Catholic
radio station, Caritas, has given air time to opposition figures.
   In Sucre, John Paul celebrated a Mass and visited a hospital. In
his homily at the outdoor Mass, attended by more than 100,000
people, the pope praised European missionaries who have worked in
this predominantly native Indian country.
   The pope ended his day in the tropical city of Santa Cruz, where
he met with cultural and intellectual leaders.
   Santa Cruz, a farming and ranching center of 377,000 near the
Brazilian border, is an important transit point for cocaine.
   In his meeting with the intellectuals, the pontiff said the
Third World's ``brain drain'' _ the emigration of trained
professionals _ is ``a reason for serious concern.''
   John Paul added, however, ``we do not want to deny the
legitimate right ... to emigrate.''
   Simon Reyes, first secretary of Bolivia's legal Communist Party
and executive secretary of the country's principal union
federation, told the pontiff: ``You give us hope so the people can
continue their struggle.''
   Reyes gave the pope a letter describing the plight of Bolivia's
workers and acknowledged the local church's support of workers'
rights.
   John Paul, on his ninth Latin American tour, flies Saturday from
Bolivia to Lima, Peru, for a regional religious conference.
   In a Lima seminary where the pope is due to speak this weekend,
armed pro-Cuba rebels disrupted a Mass Thursday, news reports said.
   Eight armed members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement
seized the Santo Toribio Seminary, demanding that seminarians,
priests and others join their insurgency, according to Radio
Programas, Peru's leading news station.
   There were no injuries, the radio said.
   During the pope's last visit to Peru in February 1985, the
Maoist Shining Path guerrilla group caused a power outage that cut
airport lights as the pontiff's jet was landing in Lima. The jet
landed safely.
</TEXT>
