<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Taiwan-Hijack 1stLd-Writethru a0755 05-12 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Hijack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0755,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Chinese Hijack Jetliner, Granted Asylum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-13 UPDATE with further confirmation on arrival
back in China, other details. Picks up 8th graf pvs, The hijackers
... editing to conform, tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHINGCHUANKANG AIR FORCE BASE, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Chinese men
hijacked a domestic airliner from the mainland to Taiwan, where
they were granted asylum, and the jet took the other 116 people
aboard back to China early Friday.
   It was the first piracy of a Chinese commercial airliner to
Taiwan. The two air pirates carried two bombs and handguns.
   Some foreigners, but no Americans, were aboard.
   The Boeing 737 left Chingchuankang military airport in central
Taiwan at 2:55 a.m. (2:55 p.m. Thursday EDT) after refueling, a
litle under six hours after it landed there, said Wang Pao-hua,
spokesman for the air force base.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency later confirmed that the
plane landed just over an hour later _ at about 5 a.m. (4 p.m.
Thursday EDT) _ in Xiamen, a coastal city in China's Fujian
province where the hijacking ordeal began Thursday evening.
   Xiamen is just across the narrow Taiwan Strait which separates
the communist mainland from the Nationalist Chinese island bastion
of Taiwan.
   An official at the Xiamen office of China's national airline,
the Civil Aviation Administration of China, said the passengers
were in good condition. The plane was operated by Xiamen Aviation
Co., a subsidiary of the national carrier.
   Xinhua said the mayor and other officials met those returning on
the plane and extended sympathy to them from Premier Li Peng.
   There are no air links between Taiwan and mainland China.
Taiwan's Nationalist government claims to be the legitimate ruler
of China and maintains no official contacts with the Beijing
government.
   Taiwan's Government Information Office said the hijackers were
granted asylum, and also said the government was opposed ``to any
threats affecting commercial flight safety.''
   It said the plane carried 107 passengers and 11 crew, including
the hijackers. They were identified as Chang Ching-kuo, 27, an
arsenal worker in southern Yunnan province, and Lung Kuei-yun, 26,
a steel mill employee in Guizhou province, also in the south.
   Hu Yizhou, head of China's national airline, sent a request
before the asylum announcement that Taiwan ``assist in a quick
return of the crew members and all the passengers to Xiamen, and
hand over the hijackers at the same time,'' Xinhua reported.
   Taiwan did not mention Hu's request, but said merely that the
plane was ``allowed'' to fly to Hong Kong _ apparently trying to
avoid any impression of cooperating with the communist government.
The plane actually flew to Xiamen.
   The hijackers commandeered the plane soon after it left Xiamen
at 7:27 p.m. Thursday for Canton, capital of neighboring Guangdong
province. Wang said they carried two bombs and handguns, although
initial reports had said the explosives were fake.
   Several Japanese and a French passenger were aboard, as well as
many Taiwanese who were visiting relatives under a new policy that
eases restrictions on unofficial contacts with the mainland.
   Reports on Taiwan's official television and radio said the
hijackers gave themselves up after the plane landed at the
Chingchuankang base. They raised their hands in ``V'' for victory
signs as they walked out of the aircraft.
   Television said radar detected the hijacked plane when it
crossed the Penghu islands held by Taiwan, and two air force F-104
jets went aloft as escorts.
   It was the first hijacking of a Chinese passenger airliner to
Taiwan but several military pilots have defected to the island
since Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists retreated to Taiwan 1949 after
losing a civil war to the Communists.
   A Chinese air force squadron commander flew his MiG-19 jet
fighter to Taiwan in November, becoming the sixth pilot defector
since 1960.
   Thursday's hijacking was the second time a Chinese domestic
airliner was forced to land outside the mainland. In May 1983, six
Chinese who initially demanded to be taken to Taiwan landed in
South Korea.
   On Feb. 22, a Taiwanese man said to be seeking better relations
between Taiwan and China tried to hijack a domestic China Airlines
to Beijing. China Airlines is Taiwan's major carrier.
   Four stewards and two passengers overpowered him, and on
Saturday he was sentenced to 10 years in prison.
</TEXT>
