<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CabildoFire     05-12 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cabildo Fire,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Repair Work May Have Sparked Blaze in Historic Building, Official
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers repairing the exterior of the Cabildo
apparently touched off a blaze that destroyed a roomful of antique
furniture in the building where the Louisiana Purchase was signed,
investigators said Thursday.
   The fire Wednesday raced through the third floor of the
wood-and-stucco French Quarter landmark that has served as a museum
since 1911, destroying a painting and causing water damage to
artworks and other items.
   Napoleon's death mask and the bulk of other historic artifacts
survived, said museum director James F. Sefcik.
   Offficials refused to give a damage estimate for the
193-year-old, three-story building, which was undergoing
renovation, and the contents.
   Fire Superintendent William McCrossen said that workers
repairing the roof and waterproofing the walls apparently touched
off the fire.
   An investigator who spoke on condition of anonymity said a spark
from a welding torch being used on a gutter on the front of the
Spanish baroque building could have started the blaze in the
building's old timbers.
   McCrossen said he expected to have a report on the cause of the
fire Friday.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer said the building, the seat of government in
Louisiana under three nations, would be restored ``as soon as
humanly possible.''
   ``It's like somebody said: `Louisiana was burning last night.'
So it's important,'' Roemer said.
   Lt. Gov. Paul Hardy said he expected repairs to take between one
and two years.
   Lost to the blaze was an 1802 portrait of Luis Penalver y
Cardenas, first Roman Catholic bishop of Louisiana, on loan from
the Archdiocese of New Orleans. Furniture from the 18th-century
French colonial period was stored on the gutted third floor.
   Roemer said officials were trying to determine how to preserve
historic state records kept there and were considering short-term
measures such as erecting a temporary roof.
   The Cabildo was built in 1795 and served as the seat of
Louisiana government under France, Spain, the Confederacy and the
United States.
   It was there that America and France signed in 1803 the
Louisiana Purchase that doubled the size of the United States. Only
a copy of the document is at the Cabildo, Sefcik said. Originals
are in France and Washington, D.C.
   The Cabildo was the third such building on the site to bear the
name. The two earlier buildings were destroyed by fire, in 1788 and
1794.
</TEXT>
