<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0777,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palace Names New Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT that minister a former union leader.
SUBS 17th graf ``Jacques Chereque...'' with one graf to CONFORM;
SUBS 9th graf, ``The government ... with 1 graf to CORRECT eight
non-Socialists to nine; INSERTS graf after 11th graf ``But
Chirac...'' with negative reaction from leader of Chirac's party.
SUBS last grafs, ``Mitterrand has ... with 3 grafs to CONFORM and
to ADD that Poperen named a minister. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Elysee Palace on Thursday announced new Premier
Michel Rocard's Cabinet, dominated by members of a previous
Socialist government but containing non-Socialists, non-politicians
and a former union leader.
   Jean-Louis Bianco, secretary-general for the Elysee, read a list
of 26 ministers to replace the conservative government of Premier
Jacques Chirac.
   Chirac was defeated in May 8 presidential elections, which
returned Socialist President Francois Mitterrand to a second
seven-year term.
   Among the top new ministers is Lionel Jospin, who has just
resigned as head of the Socialist Party. He was appointed minister
for national education and research. Mitterrand had called
education and training a top priority for the new administration.
   Pierre Beregovoy, a finance minister under the Socialist
government of 1981-1986, was returned to the post.
   Similarly Roland Dumas returned to his post as foreign minister,
replacing Jean-Bernard Raimond, and Pierre Joxe to his old post as
interior minister, replacing Charles Pasqua, who had been known for
his law-and-order command of the ministry.
   The Socialist government was defeated in March 1986 legislative
elections which brought Chirac to power.
   Jean-Pierre Chevenement, education minister in the earlier
Socialist government, was named minister of defense, replacing
Andre Giraud.
   The government, expected to reflect the spirit of
``enlargement'' on which Mitterrand campaigned, contained at least
nine non-Socialists but only two figures who could be called
centrists.
   Mitterrand, whose Socialist Party has moved toward the right,
had made a point of appealing to centrists.
   But Chirac spokesman Alain Juppe said Mitterrand's talk of
reaching beyond the ranks of the Socialists was but a
``pre-electoral trap for fools.''
   Jacques Toubon, secretary general of Chirac's conservative Rally
for the Republic party, said the Cabinet was ``a hard-core
Socialist government.''
   The announcement of the Cabinet, originally expected Wednesday,
was reportedly delayed because of last-minute hesitation on the
part of centrists wary of joining a Socialist government.
   Sen. Jacques Pelletier was named minister for aid and
cooperation and Sen. Michel Durafour was appointed minister of
public works. Both were ministers under former President Valery
Giscard d'Estaing, who is from the centrist Union for French
Democracy. They are both part of the center-right parliamentary
majority.
   Among the non-politicians is judge Pierre Arpaillange, named
justice minister, replacing Albin Chalendon.
   Roger Fauroux, who had been director of the prestigious Ecole
Nationale d'Administration where most French politicans study, was
named minister of industry and foreign trade.
   Jacques Chereque, a former union leader, was named minister for
territorial management.
   Bianco said the rest of the Cabinet members would be announced
Friday.
   The announcement of the new government came two days after
Rocard's appointment by Mitterrand.
   Rocard said earlier Thursday that he would not rush the process.
   ``I intend to do my work in a spirit of calm and serenity,
listening to everyone concerned,'' he told reporters.
   He met twice Thursday with the president, who must approve his
Cabinet proposals.
   Most prominent centrists who supported Chirac's conservative
government have said they would decline Cabinet ministries in a
Socialist-led government.
   Rocard would be assured of only the votes of the 211 Socialists
in the 577-member National Assembly, but the center-right
opposition parties have said they would not necessarily vote to
bring down the new government.
   Mitterrand has the power to dissolve the assembly, and public
opinion polls show an early election would likely produce a
Socialist majority. Officials of Chirac's party as well as leaders
of most of the centrist parties are saying they think legislative
elections should wait at least until autumn.
   Pressure is mounting within the Socialist Party, however, for an
election next month.
   Jean Poperen, a member of the party executive committee, said in
a radio interview Wednesday that ``logic and coherence'' argue for
an immediate election. He was named minister for parliamentary
relations.
</TEXT>
