<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EasterTrial     05-12 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Easter Trial,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant, Officer Argue On Tape Played for Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman on trial with her three sons in the
slayings of three policemen who came to arrest her at a motel was
heard on tape Thursday vowing not to leave her room ``unless they
take me out on a stretcher.''
   The tape was played during opening arguments in the murder trial
of Alberta Easter, 69, and her sons, George, Roy and William
Lemons. The July 9 shooting in Inkster killed Officers Daniel
Dubiel and Clay Hoover and Sgt. Ira Parker.
   With at least 115 witnesses due to testify and several hundred
exhibits to be presented, the trial is expected to last three
months.
   Wayne County Assistant Prosecutor Douglas Baker played a tape
made when Dubiel and Hoover, sent to the Easters' rooms to serve a
bad-check warrant, telephoned Parker, their supervisor.
Conversation in the room was also picked up on the taped telephone
call.
   Easter and her sons have said that the shooting erupted when
Parker arrived at the motel after the telephone call, was abusive
toward Easter, grabbed her arm, drew his gun and fired.
   ``You will be asked to judge who sounds reasonable, who sounds
out of control, and who sounds ready for a fight,'' Baker told the
jury.
   On the tape, the voice identified as Easter's insisted that the
bad check charge is a mixup and asks an extra day to straighten it
out. The speaker identified as Parker said, ``I'd like to do that
but they won't give me that kind of leeway.''
   ``Talk to somebody before I call President Reagan or somebody,''
Easter said, adding, ``I'm not going to go out of here unless they
take me out on a stretcher.''
   Baker said witnesses would testify that less than 10 minutes
later Parker arrived at the motel, knocked on the Easters' door and
walked in. ``Before the door is shut a barrage of shots is heard,
maybe 30, according to witnesses,'' Baker said.
   In their opening arguments, defense attorneys told jurors they
should not be swayed by publicity in the case and talked about the
prosecution's obligation to prove the defendants guilty beyond a
reasonable doubt.
   ``We all know that Alberta Easter has been convicted,'' said
Gerald Evelyn, Easter's attorney. ``The press has convicted her.''
</TEXT>
