<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsTreaty 2ndLd-Writethru a0789 05-12 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0789,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Says No INF Debate Before Committees Act</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3, 5, 16 to CORRECT spelling of Shevardnadze.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Soviet Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd,
D-W.Va., insisted Thursday he will schedule debate on the US-Soviet
medium-range missile treaty only after three Senate committees
examine and approve a new anti-cheating agreement.
   But some senators of both parties objected, declaring it is
imperative the Senate begin work on the pact immediately so that
President Reagan can take a ratified treaty to Moscow on May 29 for
his summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas reported to the
Senate that Secretary of State George P. Shultz believes he struck
a ``completely satisfactory'' bargain with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze in Geneva on the outstanding disagreements
involving the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty.
   Dole said White House national security adviser Colin Powell
will fly back from the meeting Friday to brief Senate leaders on
what has been accomplished.
   If Powell can report that Shevardnadze has confirmed Moscow will
live up to the letter of the treaty, Dole said debate on
ratification should begin on Monday with the aim of taking a final
vote before the Moscow summit.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee, said Shultz will testify before his panel Monday
afternoon and that Senate's bipartisan leadership and the chairmen
and the ranking Republican members of the Armed Services and
Intelligence committees have been invited to attend.
   Pell suggested that if no further snags are uncovered, Senate
debate could open on Tuesday.
   But Byrd insisted he will not be ``driven by a calendar date''
and will not permit floor debate to begin until the on-site
inspection plan is reviewed and approved by the Foreign Relations,
Armed Services and Intelligence committees.
   ``We were told all the I's were dotted and all the T's were
crossed,'' Byrd said. ``It was through the examination of these
committees that it was found that this was not the case.''
   ``If we make a mistake in this treaty and we find we have been
hoodwinked or outsmarted, then you can kiss the next arms treaty
goodbye,'' he declared. ``Let's do this thing right.''
   But Byrd said: ``I want our committees which have the
responsibility for taking the microscopic look at the fine print to
have the opportunity to go carefully into this and advise the joint
leadership if these agreements adequately resolve the problems.
   ``Briefings are fine but the final word will be what these
committees have to say,'' he declared
   But Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said the Senate must do nothing
to cause further delay and prevent ``this American president from
being able to present before the Soviet people this historic
agreement.''
   ``If he goes to Moscow and faces the question of why he can't
get ratification, I think we place the presidency in jeopardy so
far as the success of future negotiations is concerned,'' Stevens
said.
   ``Time is the commodity that's scarce now,'' he said.
   Byrd on Monday shelved debate on the new treaty to give Shultz
and Shevardnadze time to resolve a serious dispute over the
implementation of anti-cheating provisions.
   The dispute centers on what U.S. inspectors will be permitted to
see and what they will be permitted to do as they seek to learn
whether the Soviets are living up to the requirements of the treaty
to eliminate all medium-range missiles.
   Earlier, Byrd told reporters a go-ahead for debate ``depends on
who's giving the answers and what they look like,'' Byrd said.
   ``I'm going to depend on the committees with jurisdiction to
determine whether these matters have been resolved in the proper
way... whether these things that need to be fixed are really
fixed,'' Byrd said.
   ``We need to stand firm on these things,'' Byrd told the Senate.
``The Soviets cannot realistically expect us to now compromise away
decisions which already have been negotiated and closed between the
two parties.''
   Calling the on-site inspection provisions of the new treaty the
single most important aspect of the pact, Byrd said that what
happens in the next few days ``could be the beginning or the end of
arms control.''
   ``If the verification system is sound and stands the test of
time, then the negotiations for future treaties will be given added
chance of support and success,'' Byrd said.
   ``But if now, when we are just on the verge of approval of the
INF treaty, we allow its verification provisions to be unraveled by
the Soviets, then the prospects of sound future arms control
agreements will be dismal, very dismal indeed.''
   Byrd said the last-minute snag justifies the searching
examination to which the Senate put the new treaty since it was
signed last December by Reagan and Gorbachev.
   The process, he said, uncovered a number of flaws and unanswered
questions, including whether or not the pact covered futuristic
weapons such as those using laser or particle beams.
   ``If we had rushed in and approved the treaty, say a month ago,
and then discovered these ambiguities and contradictions, the level
of confidence of the country in our ability to reach good, solid
agreements with the Soviets would have plummeted,'' Byrd said.
</TEXT>
