<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolChauffeurs     05-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Chauffeurs,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Board Refuses State Demand To Drop Chauffeurs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Board of Education say they'll
risk the loss of thousands of dollars in aid and take the state to
court if necessary to keep the taxpayer-paid chauffeurs who drive
two of its members to meetings.
   On Wednesday, the state Senate voted 36-1 to prohibit schools
from spending money for chauffeur-driven cars for board members.
The measure was sent to the House.
   Board president Gloria C. Cobbin, who does not use a chauffeur,
called the legislation ``racist _ another example of
Detroit-bashing at its worst.''
   ``We challenge the state's authority to impose these
restrictions on how we run our school system,'' she said. Detroit,
with an 11-member school board, is the only Michigan district known
to use drivers.
   Wednesday's action reinforced steps taken by the Senate last
year, when it told the district that unless it stopped issuing cars
to its members or paying for their drivers, it would withhold money
used for that purpose.
   The action reduced the amount of state money the district is
scheduled to receive in June by $270,000.
   In addition, state Treasurer Robert Bowman said that until the
drivers are dropped, he will not sign $30 million in notes for the
district _ a move that could mean teachers in the 181,000-student
district will not get paid May 31.
   The district has a $25 million payroll.
   ``The notion that the state will send money to local governments
no strings attached is an outdated notion,''' Bowman said Wednesday.
   Board member Rose Mary Osborne said that without a chauffeur,
she would be unable to attend evening functions because she cannot
to drive at night.
   ``I'm not backing down,'' Osborne said. ``I don't think he
(Bowman) has the authority to do this. This is a legitimate
expense. I only use the board driver for board-related activities.''
   According to a study by The Detroit News in 1987, the drivers
for the district earned an average of $35,060. The average salary
for a teacher in the district is $32,930.
   Nine of the board members stopped using drivers after the
state's action last year.
</TEXT>
