<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CyanideTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0819 05-12 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0819,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juror Admits To Own Tampering Incident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to CLARIFY that juror sued for alleged
product contamination, not necessarily tampering. PICKS UP 5th graf
pvs, `Mrs. Nickell's ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the jury that convicted a woman in
the nation's first death-by-product-tampering case has admitted
settling a product-contamination suit of her own less than two
months before she was selected as a juror.
   Laurel Holliday told the Seattle Times she did not think her
suit was relevant and did not reveal it during jury selection for
the trial of Stella Nickell on charges of killing two people with
cyanide-laced Excedrin capsules.
   Mrs. Nickell, 44, of Auburn, was found guilty Monday in the
death of her husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Susan Katherine Snow,
40, of Auburn. She could receive up to life in prison at sentencing
June 17.
   Court records show that Ms. Holliday had settled a lawsuit
against a company she alleged made a cracker containing the aspirin
substitute ibuprofen.
   Ms. Holliday said that she did not raise the matter during jury
selection because she believed the suit involved a manufacturing
mishap, not product tampering.
   Mrs. Nickell's attorney, Thomas Hillier II, did not return calls
for comment Thursday.
   On Monday, before the verdict in the Nickell case, Ms. Holliday
reported receiving an anonymous call during deliberations last week
telling her that Mrs. Nickell had failed a polygraph test. That
information was not admitted as evidence.
   U.S. District Judge William Dwyer, with Hillier's concurrence,
allowed Ms. Holliday to remain on the jury after she said could put
the information out of her mind.
   Three days earlier, the jury had reported it was hopelessly
deadlocked at 11-1. Soon after the verdict was announced several
jurors identified Ms. Holliday as the holdout.
   Hillier, after the verdict, suggested that another juror may
have influenced Ms. Holliday or that she ``contrived'' the
anonymous call to end the pressure of being the holdout vote,
hoping to be excused.
   At Hillier's request, Dwyer ordered the jury back to court
Friday to ask members if they were improperly influenced.
   Ms. Holliday has said she reached the verdict of her own accord.
   Repeated calls to Ms. Holliday's home went unanswered or were
not returned Thursday.
   In her own tampering incident, Ms. Holliday, a real estate
agent, told police her mouth started burning after she ate a
cracker in 1986. She said she found half of a pill in the uneaten
portion of the cracker and vomited.
   A year later, Ms. Holliday sued the manufacturer, Pepperidge
Farm Inc. The case was settled for $500. There were no witnesses,
and Pepperidge Farm attorneys questioned whether the event ever
took place.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
