<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AmtrakSmoke     05-12 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amtrak Smoke,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 150 Suffer Smoke Inhalation at Train Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 125 children and 30 adults suffered from
smoke inhalation Thursday night after someone pulled the emergency
brakes on an Amtrak train while it was in a tunnel near Union
Station, sending exhaust fumes spewing into the cars, officials
said.
   The first and second cars of the Crescent, which operates daily
between New York and New Orleans, were evacuated.
   Approximately 125 school children and about 30 adult chaperones
who occupied the first two cars were taken to several area
hospitals where they were treated for possible smoke inhalation,
said Paul Harvey, supervisor for the District of Columbia's
Emergency Ambulance Division.
   The children and their supervisors had been planning to depart
the train in Birmingham, Ala., said Amtrak spokesman Clifford
Black. Amtrak officials said the students are from Long Leaf
Elementary School.
   The Crescent departed Washington at 6:40 p.m. EDT going
southbound with about 400 passengers and 18 crew members on board.
It had two engines and 16 cars.
   ``At 6:45 p.m., as the train was in the tunnel, an unknown
person for unknown reasons pulled the emergency brake,'' Black
said. ``The train stopped with its emergency brakes applied in the
tunnel'' as the second engine stalled or died.
   The train crew, thinking that an air hose that controls the
brake system had parted accidentally, ``walked the train'' looking
for such a problem, he said.
   After finding none, the crew searched the train's interior and
found that the emergency brake handle in the first passenger car
had been pulled, he said.
   Unable to release the brake, the crew shut down the remaining
lead engine which was spewing out diesel smoke that entered the
cars.
   Trains that leave Washington going south immediately enter a
3,900 foot tunnel that roughly goes under the grassy mall
stretching from the Capitol to the Lincoln Memorial, Black said.
   Another Amtrak engine pulled the train back to Union Station, he
said. By 9 p.m. buses were ordered to retrieve the children from
the hospitals and take them to hotel for the night.
</TEXT>
