<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     05-12 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Announce Biggest Arms Seizure, Including Missile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Wednesday announced
their biggest arms seizure, including a ground-to-air missile, and
arrested four whites who purportedly planned to carry out attacks
for the African National Congress.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok described the three men and
one woman as ``a highly specialized terror unit.'' He said they
were captured Sunday at a farmhouse near Pretoria, where they had
been staying since early this year.
   Police said the four had an assassination list of top police
officials and planned to use the missile to shoot down a police
helicopter at a recent fair.
   They said that besides one Soviet-made SAM-7 ground-to-air
missile, the weapons seized included limpet mines, hand grenades,
assault rifles, pistols, machine guns, mortars and explosives.
   In his statement, Vlok alleged that the suspects were trained in
Moscow, Cuba and Angola and had radio transmitters which they used
to communicate with ANC headquarters in Lusaka, Zambia.
   The predominantly black African National Congress, outlawed in
South Africa since 1960, began a sabotage-and-bombing campaign the
next year aimed at toppling white-minority rule.
   Vlok did not release the names of the four. He did say the men
were South African citizens and the woman was from another country
he did not specify.
   He said two of the men were armed forces deserters and one was a
former South African journalist. They had university degrees and
were in their 20s and 30s, he added.
   The minister said police were investigating how the weapons were
brought into South Africa.
   The South African Press Association, citing unidentified police
sources, said a disenchanted ANC member apparently tipped off
authorities.
   Police said the four apparently had no connection with Heinrich
Grosskopf, a white South African and an alleged ANC member who is
the leading suspect in a March 17 car bombing that killed three
people. Grosskopf remains at large.
   Apartheid by law and custom establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
