<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     05-12 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Bars Top Vietnam Economists From Visiting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States refused visa
applications from six leading Vietnamese economists as part of a
policy to pressure the Hanoi government to end its occupation of
Cambodia, U.S. officials said Wednesday.
   The group included Nguyen Xuan Oanh, a Harvard-educated
government advisor who visited several Asian capitals earlier this
year to try to attract capital and technology, officials said.
   Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, said
the State Department denied the visa requests on April 16 because
the group was ``deeply involved in Vietnamese economic policy
planning and the U.S. government policy is to isolate Vietnam
politically and economically to force its withdrawal from
Cambodia.''
   The Christopher Reynolds Foundation invited the group to visit
Harvard, the University of Michigan and other institutions to talk
about Vietnam's economy and efforts to attract Western investment,
said a U.S. source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The United States does not have diplomatic relations with
Vietnam.
   David Lyon, consul general at the Embassy, said Washington was
acting under Section 212A27 of the Immigration and Nationality Act,
which says the government can bar aliens whom it ``knows or has
reason to believe seek to enter the United States solely,
principally or incidentally to engage in activities which would be
prejudicial to the public interest or endanger the welfare, safety
or security of the United States.''
   Communist Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and maintains
125,000 troops there, according to U.S. estimates.
   Petzing said Oanh submitted a second application on April 19,
this time for him to travel alone, and that application is being
reviewed.
   The spokesman said that since Oct. 1, the United States has
approved applications for a half-dozen Vietnamese government
officials to visit the United Nations and other international
organizations.
   A larger number of private Vietnamese citizens have gone to the
United States to attend medical conferences and the like, Lyons
said. He said he did not know of any other Vietnamese visa
applications denied in the past 10 months.
   In the past few years, Vietnam has played host to many U.S.
congressmen, relief agency officials, journalists and others in an
effort to break its isolation.
</TEXT>
