<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Takeshita-SixMonths Adv19   05-12 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Takeshita-Six Months, Adv 19,0570</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs May 19 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Leader Trying to Break Pro-U.S. Mold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After six months in office, Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita still faces trade disputes with the United States and
Western Europe and has been unable to break the pro-U.S. mold set
by his predecessor, Yasuhiro Nakasone.
   His critics call his devotion to Nakasone's policies his one big
failure, while at least one admirer, Seizaburo Sato, an adviser to
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party, said it is only natural for
Takeshita to remain committed to them.
   ``Takeshita occupied many important positions in the Cabinet and
the party, and he is committed to the policies of Nakasone,'' Sato
said.
   But others see signs that Takeshita finally is beginning to head
off on his own course.
   ``I think he has not yet found his own way of solving problems,
but he is on his way,'' said Rei Shiratori, professor of political
science at Tokai University.
   But he added that one of Takeshita's biggest problems is ``the
heavy burden left by former Prime Minister Nakasone, especially
with the United States.''
   Many Japanese feel Nakasone was too closely allied with the
United States.
   Takeshita himself has said the time had come for a change in
Japan-U.S. relations.
   ``The international economic framework so long sustained by the
overwhelming economic might of the United States is being
transformed, and there is a need for Japan and Western Europe to
join forces with the United States in supporting the international
economy,'' he said in a policy speech.
   An editorial in the Asahi Shimbun in late April called on
Takeshita to assert Japan's independence from U.S. policies.
   ``We want the prime minister to be aware that Japan has become
an important pillar for the West,'' the independent liberal
newspaper said. ``It is now time for Japan to assert its own
diplomacy, independent of the United States.''
   On resolving major policy issues, Takeshita has a slim record so
far. He achieved limited success in resolving a trade dispute with
the United States over lack of access to Japan's construction
market, primarily because of the major influence of one of his
Cabinet officials on Japan's construction industry.
   However, talks with U.S. officials on liberalizing Japan's beef
and orange imports broke down, and the United States is seeking a
resolution through the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   Takeshita's administration was also unsuccessful in persuading
President Reagan to lift sanctions imposed last year on some
Japanese products because of alleged violations of an agreement on
U.S. access to Japan's computer chip market.
   Takeshita also was unable to prevent the U.S. Congress from
passing a sweeping trade bill that includes sanctions against
Japanese companies. He is relying heavily on Reagan to veto the
bill.
   The prime minister's major test at home will come later this
year, when the Diet, Japan's national legislature, considers a tax
reform package that Nakasone desperately wanted, but was unable to
get.
   Many Japanese say the current tax system is unfair. New
proposals call for taxes on capital gains from the sale of
securities, the elimination of tax privileges for doctors, the
cutting of provisions that allow some people to estimate their
income, and taxation of farmland.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
