<1ST_LINE>a i PM-SouthAfrica-Town Adv20   05-12 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Town, Adv 20,0738</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs May 20 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Black Community Refuses To Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OUKASIE, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government accustomed to getting
its way has met its match in this ramshackle black township, which
officially doesn't exist.
   For years, white authorities have been trying to coax or coerce
the people of Oukasie into moving to a newer township 12 miles away.
   Officials legally abolished Oukasie in 1986, but about 8,000
residents remain and are determined to stay.
   In April, the government declared the 55-year-old township an
``emergency camp'' subject to severe new regulations. Rents were
raised by 50 percent, unauthorized visitors will be barred as of
June 1, and permits are required to renovate homes, keep pets or
take in lodgers.
   Members of the community believe the government seeks to
demoralize them so they will give up and move. That would enable
the authorities to eliminate Oukasie without resorting to forced
removal, a policy the government claims to have abandoned.
   Oukasie residents say they won't give in to the pressure.
   ``Sometimes in life you get tired of being harassed and moved
about,'' said Sello Ramakobye, a spokesman for Oukasie's civic
association. ``You decide it's time to resist.''
   The official reason for Oukasie's intended demise is that the
government considers it an unhealthy slum, beyond rehabilitation
because of ``astronomic costs.''
   Residents commissioned a study of their own that found upgrading
would cost 3 million rands ($1.4 million). They say this would be
cheaper than relocating all of them at the new township,
Lethlabile, and they believe the government's real reason for
wanting Oukasie shut down is that it is just a few hundreds yards
from Brits, a white suburb 30 miles west of Pretoria, South
Africa's capital.
   Brits is a stronghold of the far-right Conservative Party. Its
white residents have displayed little sympathy for their black
neighbors, who are able to walk to their jobs in Brits but would
have to pay for transport if they moved to Lethlabile.
   Because of government funding, Lethlabile has advantages over
Oukasie, and some of the 5,000 former Oukasie residents who have
moved there are pleased with their choice. The new township's
streets are smooth, its homes have electricity and plumbing. A few
houses are relatively lavish, with patios and two-car garages.
   Oukasie is overcrowded and dilapidated. Many homes are in ruins,
demolished by former owners as a prerequisite for getting state
compensation to move to Lethlabile. The only services provided are
water from communal taps and removal of waste from bucket toilets.
   But Oukasie has certain charms. Trees, a rare sight in many
townships, are abundant, and well-tended gardens adjoin even some
of the sorriest-looking metal shacks. Two soccer fields are
maintained diligently by local youths.
   ``Everything we want to do, we do it ourselves,'' said Elias
Sithole, a 39-year-old former carpenter. He is one of an estimated
50 percent of the adult population that is unemployed, and says
job-seeking from Lethlabile would be costly and difficult.
   Other jobless residents don't want to move because they have
improved their homes in Oukasie over the years and can't afford
houses in Lethlabile, except for the small metal huts allocated to
newcomers.
   ``The social structure in Oukasie is so coherent,'' said
Ramakobye. ``It's wrong to destroy it. In Lethlabile, everybody is
for himself.''
   Oukasie residents also are wary of Lethlabile's proximity to the
nominally independent black homeland of Bophuthatswana. They fear
the new township will be incorporated into the homeland, thus
depriving residents of South African citizenship.
   ``No one is going to volunteer to go to Lethlabile,'' said
Sithole. ``The government thinks everybody is going to be scared
into going, but it will take force. You should see the unity of
these people.''
   Sithole guided visitors to the edge of the nearby white suburb,
where a concrete moat filled with dark green muck separates
handsome, new hillside homes from a dirt road leading to Oukasie.
   ``How can they say it's too expensive to upgrade Oukasie when
they upgrade their mountain?'' he said.
   Raw sewage from whites' homes runs into a gully next to the
township.
   Sithole said Oukasie residents are somewhat cynical about white
complaints that the black community smells.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs May 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
