<1ST_LINE>a a PM-APonTV-Mythology Adv13   05-12 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Mythology, Adv 13,0942</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, May 13, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Joseph Campbell's Mythology Featured on PBS</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Campbell made his career teaching about
life, as comprehended in the myths or stories people tell about
themselves and the universe.
   Half a year after his death, public television offers a
stimulating seminar with the great teacher starting May 16 with
``The Hero's Journey,'' a one-hour documentary about Campbell.
   A week later, PBS begins a six-week series of Bill Moyers'
conversations with Campbell in ``Joseph Campbell and the Power of
Myth.''
   ``The Hero's Journey'' is a useful introduction to Campbell's
ideas about mythology and his core conviction: ``There is one
mythology in the world,'' with variations called Christianity,
Islam, Buddhism and so on.
   A myth, in this sense, is not a lie, but a metaphor for the
experience of life.
   So, to Campbell, the idea of God is not true or false. ``God is
a metaphor for a mystery that absolutely transcends all human
categories of thought, even the categories of being and non-being.''
   The metaphor is valid, he says, if ``it is putting you in touch
with the mystery that is the ground of your own being. If it isn't,
it's a lie.''
   Though ``Joseph Campbell and the Power of Myth'' is simply the
two men talking, it may be the most compelling television series
this year.
   The conversation is strewn with ideas that will be enlightening,
provocative and at times maddening. The success of the series may
be measured by the number of times a viewer will want to argue, and
by the conversations that begin after the TV is switched off.
   Campbell, who taught at Sarah Lawrence College for 38 years,
died Oct. 30 in Honolulu at age 83. He left an extensive record of
his work in books, including ``The Hero with a Thousand Faces'' and
``The Masks of God.''
   ``He is a writer of important scholarship, but you don't find
the person in the writing,'' Moyers said in a recent interview.
   ``You find the mind there, but not the personality, not the
power of the individual that comes through any great teacher.
That's why I wanted to do so much with him. We would have his
works, but we wouldn't have his teaching. Teachers have to be
experienced, they can't be read.''
   Moyers didn't know much about Campbell when they met in 1979 for
an interview that appeared two years later on ``Bill Moyers'
Journal'' on PBS.
   ``We had over 14,000 requests for a transcript, so I knew I had
touched a chord,'' Moyers said. ``Even without the requests, I knew
he had touched a chord because he moved me. He opened my eyes. He
connected what had been unrelated phenomena in my own experience in
life.''
   For this series, Moyers taped 23 hours of interviews and spent
many more hours in informal conversations.
   ``We became pretty good friends, more so than I usually do with
somebody I put on the air because I don't have that much time with
them,'' Moyers said. ``I was his perpetual student, his graduate
student for life.''
   Campbell was raised as a Roman Catholic and fondly recalled that
experience as ``powerful, life-supporting and beautiful.'' But,
like many another believer, his faith was derailed by Charles
Darwin.
   ``The thing that saved me,'' he says, ``was the Upanishads _
Hinduism.''
   In those texts, he says in ``The Hero's Journey,'' he found the
same mythology as in Christianity, without the insistence that the
stories were historically true.
   Campbell ``is the most spiritual man I ever met,'' Moyers said,
but he knows that this series will not be welcomed by
fundamentalists.
   ``What I took him as saying is that all religion is true, and if
it works for you, fine,'' said Moyers.
   ``If it does in fact lead you to love the lord thy god with all
thy heart, with all thy soul, with all thy mind and thy neighbor as
thyself, fine. You don't have to move on to this other angle of
seeing ...
   ``Faith,'' Moyers added, ``is an excruciatingly personal choice
or rejection. Your idea of God may be terribly dissatisfying to me,
which is why I love the democratic way which is that you can't
impose it on me.''
   Moyers' interviews with Campbell are also the basis for a book,
``The Power of Myth,'' compiled by Betty Sue Flowers, a professor
at the University of Texas. It will be published this month by
Doubleday.
   Moyers said the book was initiated by Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis, an editor at Doubleday.
   Moyers said Mrs. Onassis had been impressed by the earlier
interviews in which Campbell talked about the mythic significance
of John F. Kennedy's funeral and of the ``ancient mythological
symbol, the widow who helps us all come to terms with our grief
when the ruler is killed.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BACK TO UNREALITY _ Due to the veritable abyss left in the
entertainment world by the absence of ``That's Incredible!'' from
the airwaves, hyperbolic hosts John Davidson, Cathy Lee Crosby and
Fran Tarkenton will engage in a reunion special on ABC on May 22.
ABC promises the one-hour special will include a man kissing a
deadly cobra on the mouth, another putting a red-hot metal bar into
his mouth and yet another blowing bubbles ``into unique and unusual
shapes.'' Not to be mythed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 13</NOTE>
