<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv13   05-12 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 13,0632</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, May 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Roman Catholic bishops have consistently
opposed U.S. military aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua, but
the bishops applaud humanitarian aid.
   It is ``a sign of hope that all sides may now be workng to forge
a lasting and just peace,'' says Archbishop John L. May of St.
Louis, president of the National Conference of Bishops.
   He said in a letter to Nicaragua's Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo that the aid both would help war victims and sustain the
contras while the peace process goes forward.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``Bible Card,'' about the size of
a business card, has on it the entire Bible in microfilm form, says
its producer, ThemeCards, Inc.
   It says 100,000 copies are being turned out for people to carry
as a reminder of faith, although immense magnification would be
required to read the contents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although studies have indicated that most
successful career women are single, divorced or childless, a study
of successful Jewish career women finds that most are married and
have children.
   In the study sponsored by the American Jewish Committee and
Lilith Magazine, a Jewish feminist quarterly, questionaire
responses from 944 Jewish career women showed 603 had married and
had children.
   Most ``were embedded in a `superwoman' syndrome, daily juggling
multiple role obligations,'' the findings say.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Methodist Publishing House
has developed a policy on AIDS in the workplace, saying the disease
is not spread by casual contact and protecting the jobs and privacy
of any employes who have it.
   If ``unable to perform their normal job duties because of their
illness,'' workers with AIDS would be given disability leaves, the
policy says. Employees who refuse to work alongside people with
AIDS could go on unpaid leaves or apply for other publishing house
jobs.
   The policy is ``to protect the rights of all our employees,''
says Stephen C. Tippens, a vice president, who adds that so far, no
cases of AIDS have been reported among the agency's 1,300 employes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several countries reportedly have
dropped broadcasts of defrocked TV evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, who
was involved in a scandal with a prostitute.
   Among stations or networks cited as dropping his program were
those in Trinidad and Tobago, South Africa, Jamaica and Swaziland.
   Swaggart has said he will begin broadcasting again May 25,
defying orders of is former denomination, the Assemblies of God,
which had suspended ihm from preaching for at least a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Bible Society reports that its U.S.
distribution of Scriptures in 1987 totalled 116,155,119 copies, up
16 million or 15.6 percent over the year before.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHEATON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A theologian for the National Association
of Evangelicals says carbon-14 tests on the Shroud of Turin will
not affect evangelical belief in Christ's resurrection, whatever
the results.
   ``It is no more than an interesting investigation,'' says the
Rev. Arthur Climenhaga, chairman of NAE's theological committee.
``Even if proof could be offered that the Shroud of Turin was the
shroud of Christ, that would be no more than an additional artifact
in the historical evidences of Christ's resurrection _ already so
well attested.''
   The Vatican is allowing the carbon-14 tests on bits of the
shroud, preserved in Turin, Italy, and bearing the image of a
crucified man, to determine its age, and whether it dates to the
time of Christ.
   Results of the tests are expected later this year.
   End Adv for Fri AMs, May 13
</TEXT>
