<1ST_LINE>a i AM-TwoAfghanistans Adv18   05-12 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Two Afghanistans, Adv 18,0671</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, May 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Two Educations of Afghanistan's Young</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen-year-old Noorieh Mazloumpoor
has had two educations in her young life _ one Moslem, the other
Marxist.
   She got her Marxist education in her homeland, Afghanistan.
   As a refugee with her family in Pakistan for the past two years,
her education has been based on Islam, her religion.
   She is typical of Afghan children who have been taught two
conflicting ideologies over the past decade of war in their country.
   Now with the Soviet military withdrawal from Afghanistan, the
children who have had an Islamic education in Pakistan will be
returning home to join those whose education was wholly Marxist.
   The gap may be wide, but students interviewed here were
confident it won't deter them from reuniting their country in the
long run.
   Noorieh went to school in Kabul, Afghanistan's capital, until
she was 12.
   In Pakistan, she enrolled in a Moslem school run by the
guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed Afghan government.
   Like many of her classmates, she has had to switch from courses
that taught Communist doctrine to interpretations of the Koran, the
Moslem holy book.
   In Kabul, she said, she was taught that it was her ``duty to
serve the country, the masses, the revolution and the fruits of
history.''
   At her refugee school in Peshawar, the blue cover of her Persian
language text book has a map identifying her country as ``Moslem
Afghanistan.'' Another map in the book carries the Koranic verse,
``There is no god but Allah. Mohammed is his prophet.''
   Refugee books published by the guerrillas' Afghan education
council also teach: ``The future of Afghanistan should be
reconstructed on the principles of Islamic culture.''
   ``Eventually we will have to reconcile the two,'' said
Ehsanollah Poopal, 17-year-old 10th grader.
   ``It's going to take a lot of effort, patience. They have their
reasons and we have ours.''
   Poopal, however, said he will not accept the Communist teachings
and will try to explain to his classmates back home why his beliefs
are different.
   Another refugee student, 15-year-old Mehrafsa, said he thinks it
is going to be difficult in the beginning.
   ``We are going to suffer first, especially to see our friends
are led toward a corrupt path, taught bad values. But I don't think
it will be too long before we understand each other. I don't think
the gap will affect the country in the long run.''
   Wassimeh, 24, a teacher at one of the refugee schools, believes
Moslem education will continue when the children among the 3
million refugees in Pakistan return home.
   Maliheh Malekzad, 28, an mathematics teacher, said she taught at
a Kabul school until two years ago. She added that unless a teacher
was a member of the Communist Party, there was no hope of promotion.
   ``It is very difficult for a Moslem not to be able to express
her religious viewpoint and to be taunted for her belief,'' she
said.
   Schools in Afghanistan, according to the teachers and students
here, have their own party recruitment bodies _ the scouts, the
first stage of Communist ``indoctrination,'' and the youth
organization, where Russian culture and language are taught, and
where some are given schoolarships to study in the Soviet Union.
   The third stage is the older youth organization where advanced
Communist books are read outside the school curriculum.
   Ms. Malekzad said the refugee schools here are good at teaching
theories but poor in practical education.
   The walls and classrooms are adorned with guerrilla posters, and
during class, the students sing: ``I cry for my motherland, I cry
for its martyr. Wherever I turn, I see broken limbs.''
   But 9-year-old Godsiyeh Amir Mohammad said she likes studying
Islam because it will ``make me go to heaven.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, May 18</NOTE>
