<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:SummerMovies Adv16   05-12 0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Summer Movies, Adv 16,0905</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rambo, Crocodile Dundee and a Dwarf Head Summer Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rambo, Crocodile Dundee and a dwarf named
Willow begin the summer movie season this month with a blast that
industry analysts expect to help propel the nation's theaters to a
record year.
   ``It looks like another record,'' said Art Murphy, financial
writer for the entertainment trade paper Daily Variety. ``The first
four months are already $100 million more than last year's record.
If the pace is continued at the same rate, the year will easily
exceed 1987's $4\ billion.
   ``The 15 weeks of summer, which amount to 40 percent of the
year's total, look very promising. First sequels of big hits are
always strong, and you've got `Crocodile Dundee II,' plus `Rambo
III,' which is really a first sequel since the original film was
`First Blood.' Plus you have a George Lucas film which is not in
the same `Star Wars' mold.''
   ``Crocodile Dundee II'' and ``Rambo III'' open on May 27, while
the Lucas epic, ``Willow,'' was moved ahead to May 20 in an
apparent attempt by MGM-UA to beat the crowd. The company is
understandably nervous about the $35 million film _ plus $20
million for advertising and promotion _ which has no stars, and the
hero is a dwarf who protects a baby from an evil queen.
   ``Rambo III'' also seems a perilous investment in view of its
reported $63 million cost, including $20 million to Sylvester
Stallone. Also, Stallone's last two releases failed to ignite the
box ofice.
   Other repeats of past hits will be offered for the summer trade:
``Poltergeist III,'' the last film of young Heather O'Rourke;
``Caddyshack II,'' with Jackie Mason replacing Rodney Dangerfield;
``Arthur 2 on the Rocks,'' again with Dudley Moore and Liza
Minnelli, and a ghostly appearance by John Gielgud; ``Short Circuit
II''; plus ``Phantasm II,'' ``Deathstalker III,'' Angel III'' and
``Barbarian Queen II.''
   Once again comedy is the strong suit of summer. The original
offerings include:
   _ ``Big Business,'' Bette Midler and Lily Tomlin as a pair of
twins who are switched in the maternity ward and find out 30 years
later.
   _ ``Punchline,'' Sally Field and Tom Hanks as stand-up comic
hopefuls who fall in love.
   _ ``Me and Him,'' Griffin Dunne as an architect who suffers a
sexual crisis.
   _ ``Funny Farm,'' Chevy Chase and Madolyn Smith as a fast-lane
pair seeking tranquility in a small town.
   _ ``Hot to Trot,'' comic Bob Goldthwaite and a talking horse.
   _ ``Big,'' Tom Hanks as a 13-year-old whose wish to grow up in a
hurry is granted.
   _ ``Big Top Pee-wee,'' Pee-wee Herman as a country clod who
falls for a circus star.
   _ ``Coming to America,'' Eddie Murphy as an African prince in
search of a bride.
   _ ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' John Cleese, Jamie Lee Curtis and
Kevin Kline in a comedy about United States-British relations.
   _ ``Married to the Mob,'' Michelle Pfiefer and Matthew Modine in
a Mafia comedy.
   _ ``Bull Durham,'' the lighter side of baseball with Kevin
Costner and Susan Sarandon.
   _ ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' a Steven Spielberg-produced
Disney fantasy starring Bob Hoskins and a host of Hollywood cartoon
stars.
   _ ``The Great Outdoors,'' Dan Aykroyd and John Candy as
brothers-in-law on a disastrous summer vacation.
   _ ``Midnight Run,'' Robert De Niro in a comedy about a bounty
hunter for the Mob.
   _ ``Moon over Parador,'' Richard Dreyfuss as an actor who
impersonates a Caribbean dictator.
   _ ``Vibes,'' Cyndi Lauper in her film debut, with Jeff Goldblum
and Peter Falk.
   The macho men will be back for summer. Besides Stallone,
theaters will be offering Clint Eastwood (``The Dead Pool''),
Arnold Schwarzenegger (``Red Heat''), Chuck Norris (``Hero and the
Terror''), Michael Dudikoff (``Nam'') and Charles Bronson
(``Messenger of Death'').
   Summer will also bring Bruce Willis as a New York cop fighting
terrorists in ``Die Hard,'' and Sean Connery and Mark Harmon as
investigators of murder in ``Presidio.''
   A handful of dramatic films offer hope for adult audiences.
Francis Coppola returns with his long-planned ``Tucker,'' with Jeff
Bridges as the inventor who tries to revolutionize the automobile
industry. Tom Berenger and Debra Winger star in ``Betrayed,'' about
an FBI agent who infiltrates a Midwest hate group.
   That nearly extinct species, the Western, gets another chance
for revival with ``Young Guns,'' whose cast include Emilio Estevez,
Charlie Sheen, Kiefer Sutherland and Lou Diamond Phillips.
   And for the small fry: ``The New Adventures of Pippi
Longstocking,'' and a revival of Disney's ``Bambi.''
   How does the summer season look to movie buyers?
   ``I think it's going to be `Willow,' `Rambo' and `Crocodile
Dundee,''' said Todd Zsmania, booker for the 75-screen Mescop chain
in Michigan and Wisconsin.
   ``I saw a rough cut of `Willow' that was a little slow getting
started, then picked up speed. I assume they made some cuts, and I
think it will be a winner. I also saw a rough cut of `Crocodile,'
and the ending was confused, but I think they'll take care of that.
`Rambo,' I think, will be big for a couple of weeks, then drop
off.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
