<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Chile-Watchers Adv20   05-12 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Watchers, Adv 20,0725</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, May 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>200,000 Volunteer To Watch Presidential Balloting in Chile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a little financial help from abroad
and a lot of enthusiasm from 200,000 volunteers, opponents of
Chile's military government have launched a campaign they say will
keep fraud out of this year's presidential election.
   Ten opposition parties, from left to right, have united in the
campaign of door-to-door voter education, poll-watching on election
day and independent vote counting afterward.
   Leaders of the National Election Command for Democracy maintain
that the system is necessary because they believe fraud tipped a
1980 plebiscite to approve a government-drafted constitution.
   Genaro Arriagada, secretary general of the command, said the
1980 plebiscite, in which the government received 67 percent of the
vote, ``lacked the minimal conditions necessary to guarantee any
honest election.''
   That vote took place without voter registries, because the old
ones had been destroyed by the military shortly after they seized
power in 1973. Polling stations were manned only by
government-appointed officials, without any opposition or
independent supervision.
   Arriagada said a national census taken two years after the vote
showed that in several cities the number of people who voted in the
plebiscite was higher than the number of residents in the cities.
   The government has denied accusations of fraud.
   ``The upcoming presidential plebiscite will be very different,''
Arriagada said. He said voter registries now have reopened, ``and
this time we have the capacity to guarantee a clean vote.''
   In the plebiscite scheduled for an unspecified date later this
year, Chileans will be able to vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on a single,
military-appointed candidate for the 1989-97 presidential term. If
the candidate is rejected by voters, a competitive election will
take place a year later.
   President Augusto Pinochet, the 73-year-old army commander who
has ruled since 1973, is considered the most likely candidate.
   Ricardo Lagos, leader of the Socialist Party and a key member of
the National Election Command, said 700 specialists are training
the 200,000 volunteers throughout the country to work as
poll-watchers on election day.
   He added in an interview that the opposition will be able to
have three to five monitors at each of the 20,000 or so voting
places.
   ``We can guarantee to every citizen that his vote will be
properly accounted for, and that it will remain secret,'' Lagos
said.
   Some volunteers have already visited hundreds of thousands of
voters in the door-to-door campaign to ``explain to them that this
time the vote will be totally clean,'' he said.
   Lagos added that part of the financing for the campaign has come
``from groups abroad interested in the restoration of democracy in
Chile.''
   He said the cost is relatively low, however. He estimated his
Socialist Party will spend the equivalent of around $100,000.
   Lagos did no identify the foreign groups sending money, but the
National Endowment for Democracy of the United States and several
West European foundations, especially in West Germany, Italy and
Sweden, have been officially reported in the past as granting
financial aid to Chilean democratic dissident groups.
   The National Election Command also has organized a nationwide
computerized vote-counting system to operate independently of the
government system.
   Eduardo Arriagada, an engineer in charge of the Vote Counting
Center said ``we will be able to quickly deliver a projection of
the vote and complete returns.''
   Eric Campana, a leading electoral expert of the Christian
Democratic Party, the largest in the opposition, said, ``The system
we are implementing fully guarantees a clean vote. There will be no
fraud this time. Chileans can rest assured of that.''
   Campana said volunteers trained as poll-monitors show ``an
enormous enthusiasm.''
   ``Many of them are paying for their travel and other expenses
connected with the campaign out of their own pockets.''
   Juan Gabriel Valdes, who works at the Vote Counting Center,
said, however, old legislation granting the government emergency
powers could still be invoked.
   ``That legislation, for example, would allow the government to
prevent us from announcing the returns we will be gathering,''
Valdes said.
   That, said Lagos, is ``the only fraud possibility that remains
open.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 20</NOTE>
