<1ST_LINE>s w BC-Signal-Chronology Adv22   05-12 1059</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Signal-Chronology, Adv 22,1084</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-The Moscow Signal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology, from public records,
declassified documents and interviews, of major developments
concerning the Soviet microwave bombardment of the U.S. Embassy in
Moscow:
   October 1953: Embassy security officers initially detect
intermittent Soviet-source microwave transmissions.
   Late 1962-early 1963: Electronic measurements confirm that the
signal, code-named TUMS (Technically Unidentified Moscow Signal),
is a directional microwave beam aimed at the back of the embassy
from a fifth-floor window of an apartment building 100 yards to the
west. TUMS is a mix of frequencies ranging from 2.5 to 4.1 GHz
(gigahertz) and operates at typical maximum power levels of 1 to 3
microwatts per square centimeter.
   April 4, 1965: The State Department asks doctors at the Naval
Medical Center, Bethesda, Md., to conduct special eye examinations
and electroencephalogram tests on personnel departing for and
returning from Moscow.
   April 16, 1965: The U.S. Intelligence Board Technical
Surveillance Countermeasures Committee meets to discuss the
microwave problem. It requests all member agencies to review
medical records of personnel assigned to Moscow since 1953 for
``possible clinical changes'' that may be linked with exposure to
the radiation.
   March 29, 1966: The State Department signs a contract with
George Washington University for cytogenetic testing of blood
samples from Moscow and control group personnel. The program is
conducted under the cover story of a ``Moscow Viral Study.''
   June 23-25, 1967: Secretary of State Dean Rusk lodges a protest
over the Moscow radiation with Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei
Gromyko during a summit meeting in Glassboro, N.J.
   Dec. 20, 1968: A scientific review panel begins to evaluate
results from the Pandora Project, a secret research effort
involving irradiation of monkeys with a ``synthetic Moscow signal.''
   April 21, 1969: The Pandora review panel recommends that the
experimental program be expanded to include testing of human
volunteers exposed to low-level microwaves for six to eight months.
   June 27, 1969: The State Department decides to terminate the
cytogenetic testing program, on the grounds that the test results
were not confirmed by outside medical specialists.
   Jan. 12, 1970: The Pandora review panel recommends that the
research project, conducted primarily at Walter Reed Army Institute
of Research, be phased out because re-evaluation of the
experimental data showed ``no clear and strong effects.''
   March 1972: Another signal, code-named SMUT, goes on the air at
power levels of less than 1 microwatt and operates intermittently
until June 1975. With frequencies of 3.2 to 3.7 GHz, it is beamed
from a transmitter about one-half mile northeast of the embassy.
   May 26, 1975: TUMS ceases operation.
   May 28, 1975: A Soviet signal code-named MUTS-1 begins daily
operation from a transmitter on the roof of an apartment building
80 yards east of the embassy. It is a complex, broadband signal
with frequencies in the range of 0.6 to 9.6 GHz and typical maximum
power levels of 10 to 12 microwatts.
   Oct. 16, 1975: Another microwave beam, dubbed MUTS-2, is
detected coming from the top of a building 80 yards south of the
embassy, with a frequency range comparable to MUTS-1 but lower
power levels of 1 to 2 microwatts. While TUMS had operated for
about five to eight hours a day, MUTS-1 and MUTS-2 are in operation
for up to 14 hours daily, with one or both the signals irradiating
the embassy for a total of 18 to 20 hours a day.
   Jan. 26-30, 1976: A team of U.S. experts meets with Soviet
officials in Moscow in an effort to persuade the Russians to cease
irradiating the embassy. The talks prove fruitless, with the
Soviets contending that the microwaves detected at the embassy are
simply background radiation from broadcast and industrial sources.
   Feb. 6, 1976: Ambassador Walter J. Stoessel begins a series of
classified briefings on the microwave problem for Moscow embassy
employees and dependents. Word of the briefings leaks to American
correspondents. Security officers and military personnel start
installing window screening to reduce penetration of the microwave
beams into the building.
   Feb. 12, 1976: Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger tells a
news conference that ``this issue is a matter of great delicacy
which has many ramifications.'' He declines to go into detail.
   Feb. 19, 1976: Members of the American Foreign Service
Association (AFSA), a union representing Foreign Service officers,
express concern over the problem and the State Department's failure
to brief personnel earlier.
   July 7, 1976: The State Department announces that the intensity
of the microwave radiation beamed at the embassy has been ``greatly
reduced,'' down to 2 microwatts per square centimeter outside the
building and a fraction of a microwatt inside. Also announced is
the signing of a contract with Johns Hopkins University for an
epidemiological study of personnel assigned to Moscow and other
posts in Eastern Europe.
   Jan. 4, 1977: A notice posted at the Moscow embassy discloses
that about one-third of individuals tested have shown abnormally
high white blood cell counts. It says the cause for this
lymphocytosis condition is unknown.
   Nov. 20, 1978: Results of the Johns Hopkins epidemiological
study are released and come under criticism by AFSA. In a report
with numerous caveats and limitations, the study team says ``no
convincing evidence'' was found that would directly link exposure
to microwave radiation in Moscow with adverse health effects.
   April 1979: The Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and
Transportation issues a report criticizing the State Department's
handling of the microwaves affair _ particularly its failure to
inform employees from 1953 to 1976.
   June 1981: A 14-member panel, the Electromagnetic Radiation
Management Advisory Council, concludes ``there is no scientific
evidence, nor are there any theoretical grounds to suggest that
biological effects would be expected to occur from the type and low
levels of exposure presented'' in Moscow.
   Nov. 10, 1983: Ambassador Arthur Hartman tells reporters in
Moscow that he made a protest to the Soviet Foreign Ministry over a
microwave beam aimed at the embassy between July 14 and Oct. 19,
with a power level of 2 microwatts.
   March 3, 1988: A statement released by the State Department's
Bureau of Diplomatic Security says that ``microwave signals in the
5-11 GHz range continue to be detected at the Moscow embassy
chancery.'' Typical power levels, it says, are 0.1 microwatt per
square centimeter outside the building and 0.01 microwatt inside.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
