<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv15   05-12 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 15,0859</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Milk Producers Seek New Solution to Production Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Milk Producers Federation says
dairy farmers have been squeezed enough by the administration's
price strategy to trim surplus production.
   It's time to try an alternative short-term remedy such as
another dairy termination program (DTP), or a diversion program, at
least until some basic changes in the dairy program can be worked
out with Congress, the federation says.
   A DTP could be designed to offer dairy farmers another chance of
selling all or part of their herds, thereby reducing U.S. milk
production. Or a diversion program could provide payments for
reductions in milk sold on the market.
   Both programs have been tried in recent years, but neither has
provided permanent solutions to the surplus problem. Indeed,
according to the Agriculture Department, milk production probably
will rise to another record level in 1988 after declining slightly
last year.
   Tom Camerlo, a Canon City, Colo., dairy farmer, is president of
the 72-year-old federation, which represents virtually all of the
nation's dairy farmer cooperatives and their members.
   ``Enough is enough,'' Camerlo said here last week. ``Dairy
farmers are tired of suffering continual price reductions after
having done more to address federal policy concerns than any
segment of U.S. agriculture.''
   Camerlo referred to a string of reductions in the national price
support level of milk since it rose to a peak of $13.10 per 100
pounds in 1983. In January, under a formula provided by the 1985
farm law, the support was reduced again by 50 cents to the current
level of $10.60 per hundredweight.
   The law also provides for an additional 50-cent cut to $10.10
next Jan. 1 if USDA again projects that it will have to buy the
equivalent of more than 5 billion pounds of surplus milk in 1989 to
prop up prices.
   If the surplus continues beyond next year, the law provides for
another 50-cent reduction to $9.60 on Jan. 1, 1990.
   Last year, when milk output was 142.5 billion pounds, the
department's Commodity Credit Corp. bought butter, cheese and
non-fat dry milk equivalent to more than 6.7 billion pounds of
milk. That was down dramatically from CCC purchases, or
``removals'' from the market in 1986 of 10.6 billion pounds out of
the year's production of 143.4 billion pounds.
   Milk production in 1988 is expected to rise 2 percent to 3
percent this year, according to USDA's revised estimates, and net
removals by CCC are expected to be in the range of 7 billion to 9
billion pounds, milk equivalent.
   Camerlo and other federation officials want to head off the
further reduction in milk supports on Jan. 1, 1989, by pressuring
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng to design an alternative,
which is also authorized by the 1985 farm law. And that could be
another DTP, also called a whole-herd buyout, or a diversion
program.
   In the past programs, dairy farmers were helped finance their
own payments through assessments on milk marketed. In the case of
the $1.8 billion in whole-herd buyout payments, for example, about
38 percent was provided by assessments.
   But Lyng has been steadfast in opposing another buyout or
diversion program, federation leaders say. Therefore, dairy farmers
are being asked to put pressure on members of Congress, as well as
on Lyng, to avoid the next 50-cent cut in supports.
   One of the arguments used by the federation is that part of the
recent slide in dairy supports has been accompanied by an easing of
production costs, mainly lower feed prices. But now, with grain
exports and the economy rebounding, costs are going up again.
   Thus, the federation says it makes sense to put brakes on the
slide in milk supports, or else see thousands of dairy farmers hurt
economically.
   According to USDA economists, the price of ``manufacturing''
milk used to make butter, cheese and other products averaged $12.27
per hundredweight in the first three months of 1988, down 63 cents
from a year ago.
   The department's Economic Research Service said in a new outlook
report that milk prices paid to farmers ``probably will remain
below a year earlier and average 5 percent to 7 percent lower for
all of 1988.''
   But the report also noted that the average value of dairy feed,
or concentrate, was $7.09 per 100 pounds as of April 1, up about 40
cents from a year earlier.
   For all of 1988, the cow ration value may average 25 to 45 cents
higher than last year's $6.75 per hundredweight, the report said.
   Alfalfa hay prices also are higher, averaging $69 per ton at the
farm in the first quarter, compared with $61 a year ago.
   Meanwhile, consumer prices of dairy products ``continue to show
smaller year-to-year increases'' than the government's all-food or
all-item index of retail prices, the report said. Dairy prices will
probably decline through midyear, followed by some seasonal
increase in the second half.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
