<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-12 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0529</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major banks have raised their prime lending
rates for the first time since the October stock market crash,
heralding a period of more expensive loans for purchases ranging
from plant machinery to homes and cars.
   The banks, pressured by increased costs of borrowing money
themselves, raised their prime lending rates Wednesday to 9 percent
from 8.5 percent, nearly erasing the results of three rate
decreases over the past seven months. Chase Manhattan Bank led the
move and was followed by competitors.
   The prime rate is used to calculate business and consumer loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local union members narrowly have ratified a
United Auto Workers contract covering 66,000 Chrysler Corp.
workers, according to union officials.
   The contract was approved nationally Wednesday by about 54
percent of those voting at local union halls in 15 states, said
union officials who spoke on condition they not be identified.
   Union officials said the narrow margin apparently stemmed partly
from rank-and-file displeasure over a number of factors surrounding
the contract, which established job-protecting provisions similar
to those in effect at General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. has claimed victory in a proxy battle,
saying shareholders had voted for a management-backed directors
slate over one supporting an investor group's $2.2 billion hostile
takeover bid.
   The vote for six seats on the 15-member board of the building
materials company could prove a turning point in the nearly
8-month-old battle for control of USG being waged by Desert
Partners L.P. of Midland, Texas.
   Robert J. Day, USG's chairman and chief executive, said proxies
received before the close of balloting at Wednesday's annual
shareholders meeting indicated the management-backed slate would
get more than 50 percent of the votes. The official ballot results
will be announced May 20.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staley Continental Inc. has met
with British sugar refiner Tate & Lyle PLC, which announced a
one-day extension of its $1.38 billion buyout bid for Staley.
   But Staley, a major U.S. producer of corn syrup and food-service
supplies, said Wednesday the talks with its English suitor did not
mean it was ready to sell out. Staley spokesman David Satterfield
said his company was continuing negotiations with other parties as
well.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers' confidence rebounded in April,
suggesting consumer spending will remain strong in coming months, a
private study said.
   The report Wednesday by the Conference Board, a business
research organization, indicated its index of consumer confidence
rose to 114.6 in April from 112.7 in March, leaving it just below
its level of 114.9 in February.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board has issued rules
requiring banks, savings institutions and credit unions to meet
strict deadlines in making funds from check deposits available to
customers.
   The new rules, effective Sept. 1, require financial institutions
to give customers access to deposited funds within one, three or
seven days, depending on the type of check deposited. The rules
were issued Wednesday.
