<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-12 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unleaded gasoline futures prices have moved
higher in a mixed market, following a report showing heavy stock
drawdowns last week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, June contracts for
wholesale unleaded gasoline closed up 0.63 cent at 52.25 cents per
gallon Wednesday, while June wholesale heating oil dropped 0.28
cent to 47.46 cents per gallon.
   The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude grade, closed at $17.49 per barrel, up 3 cents from
Tuesday's close.
   Trading was extremely light, said Peter Beutel, assistant
director of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc. He said many
traders were reluctant to get too involved in the market until the
June 7 meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The cartel scheduled the meeting after failing several weeks ago
to reach agreement on a proposal by several major non-OPEC
producers for joint production cuts.
   Unleaded gasoline moved strongly higher because of weekly
statistics issued late Tuesday by the American Petroleum Institute,
a Washington-based trade organization, Beutel said.
   The figures showed domestic gasoline production dropping by a
half-million barrels, inventories slipping by 3 million barrels and
imports dropping by 344,000 barrels in the week ended Friday.
   The shrinkage of supplies encouraged traders to buy in
anticipation that shorter supplies might lead to higher prices,
Beutel said.
</TEXT>
