<DOCNO> AP880512-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CBSMeeting     05-12 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS Meeting,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tisch Says Goal Is Making CBS a Ratings Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief executive of CBS Inc. says the company
is trying to come up with programming that will regain the CBS
Television network's leadership of the prime time audience ratings.
   But Laurence A. Tisch was criticized Wednesday by some
shareholders, one of whom said Tisch had destroyed a company that
was the ``class of the industry'' by selling off several of its
major businesses.
   Tisch responded by telling the company's stockholders at their
annual meeting that the recent sales of the CBS magazine and music
businesses had produced ``excellent returns'' and allowed the
company to focus on its core broadcasting business.
   Tisch also said he was looking for opportunities to use some of
CBS' $3 billion cash hoard to buy television or radio stations.
   CBS has four TV stations that cover about 20 percent of the
country and, under federal rules, can buy additional stations
extending that coverage up to 25 percent.
   Tisch also repeated earlier assertions that neither the CBS
television network nor Loews Corp.'s 24.9 percent stake in the
company were for sale. In addition to heading CBS, Tisch is
chairman of Loews, which has interests in insurance, tobacco and
hotels.
   He said CBS had no plans to sell its New York headquarters
building, nicknamed Black Rock, a move that had been rumored for
weeks.
   Since the last shareholders meeting, CBS sold its magazine group
for $650 million and its CBS records operation for $2 billion. The
CBS television network finished in third place in prime time
ratings for the first time during the season that just ended.
   Tisch noted that asset sales had boosted the company's capital
and that net interest income reached $51.7 million in the first
quarter in contrast to net interest expense of $9.3 million in the
same period of 1987.
   But Ralph Colin Jr., a longtime CBS shareholder and an executive
with the Columbia House division that was sold as part of the CBS
records group sale, told Tisch he seemed more interested in
``running a closed-end mutual fund with the revenues derived from
CBS assets'' than in broadcasting.
   He said the asset sales might have pleased Wall Street, but had
demoralized remaining CBS employees and ``effectively destroyed
something that was very near and dear to many of us _ a once great
company, a company that many considered to be the gem, the class of
the industry.''
   Colin is among a group of CBS records executives who have sued
CBS, claiming they were wrongfully denied more than $1 million in
bonuses for 1987.
   While Tisch did not comment directly on Colin's statement, he
said later in the 2{-hour meeting that the network had some
``exciting new programs'' for the next TV season and that employee
morale was ``very high.''
   ``We are ready to take on the world in the battle to regain the
No. 1 position,'' he said.
   William S. Paley, CBS chairman, didn't attend the meeting, but
sent remarks in which he said he had reviewed the pilots for next
season and found them ``imaginative and exciting. I believe that
they represent the first step in our recovery of our premier
position in the industry.''
   Assessing the outlook for broadcast advertising, Tisch said the
first half of 1988 has ``not proved to be as strong as originally
estimated, and the industry outlook for the third quarter is less
optimistic than anticipated.''
   He said this and the delay in the start of the fall television
season due to the Writers Guild strike made it impossible to
estimate CBS earnings for the year. But he added the company did
not anticipate a severe drop in profit.
</TEXT>
