<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PrimeLayoffs     05-12 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime Layoffs,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Company To Lay Off 700 Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. is laying off about 700
employees because of job redundancies and attrition following its
February acquisition by Computervision Inc., the company has
announced.
   The reduction amounts to about 5 percent of Prime's worldwide
workforce of 13,500, the company said Wednesday in a prepared
statement. The layoffs will occur over the rest of the year.
   Prime attributed the layoffs to the conclusion of its
integration with Computervision, including a new management
structure, new product strategies and excess production capacity.
   Prime jumped to second place in the computer-aided design and
computer-aided manufacturing market behind International Business
Machines Corp. after its merger with Computervision.
   The company reported first quarter net income of $14.5 million
on revenue of $363.7 million, including Computervision operations.
   Prime reported a profit of $64.8 million last year, a 38 percent
increase over 1986, on revenue of $960.9 million.
</TEXT>
