<DOCNO> AP880512-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USG-DesertPartners     05-12 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG-Desert Partners,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Appears to Win Proxy Battle, But Takeover War May Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. appears to have the won the proxy
battle, but Desert Partners L.P. isn't ready to concede the
takeover war.
   ``We believe our slate has been elected,'' USG Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Robert Day said Wednesday, claiming
shareholders had supported a management-backed slate over a rival
one supporting Desert Partners' hostile takeover bid.
   The vote for six seats on the Chicago-based company's 15-member
board of directors was seen as a turning point in the nearly
eight-month battle for control of USG, a building-materials
producer.
   Official results won't be announced until May 20. But Day told
reporters after the annual shareholders meeting that proxies
received before the close of balloting indicated the
management-backed slate would get more than 50 percent of the votes.
   The proxy battle pitted a slate led by Desert Partners' two main
investors, Texas oilmen Jack E. Brown and Cyrus Wagner Jr., against
the USG slate that included three members of the current management.
   ``We're going to continue to pursue our acquisition,'' said Joel
L. Reed, Desert Partners' chief financial officer, maintaining it
was too early to predict the election's outcome.
   Day said the vote reflects ``stockholder confidence in
management's ability,'' adding that USG would not pay out any
``greenmail'' to the Midland, Texas-based investment group.
   Greenmail is a premium price paid by a company for the stock of
a would-be acquirer that is not offered to other shareholders.
   Some investment analysts have predicted Desert Partners might
start selling off its nearly 10 percent stake in USG if it
decisively lost the proxy battle. But Reed said, ``We'll cross that
bridge when we come to it.''
   In the takeover battle marked by lawsuits on both sides, USG
executives have contended Desert Partners launched its bid only to
recoup losses in their USG holdings following October's stock
market crash.
   ``We've thought all along that Desert Partners wanted to recover
the investment they made at a bad time,'' Day said.
   Desert Partners has accused USG executives of trying to entrench
themselves with a ``poison-pill'' defense designed to hinder the
takeover bid.
   Earlier this month, USG announced a defensive recapitalization
plan and business restructuring plan to counter the Texans' offer.
   The USG plan, to be submitted to a shareholders' vote June 24,
will pay stock owners $37 in cash, debentures with a face value of
$5 and a share of stock in the recapitalized corporation for each
of the 51.5 million common shares. The company would sell off two
subsidiaries to finance the deal.
   In March, Desert Partners offered $42 per share in a hostile
tender offer for 39 million USG shares, or a 76 percent stake in
the company. That bid has a value of about $2.2 billion and remains
in effect.
   Desert Partners subsequently indicated it was willing to pay $45
per share, and Reed told the shareholders' meeting the Texans might
be willing to pay up to $50 a share.
   USG stock, which dropped below $30 per share after the market
crash, is currently selling in the $44-$46 per-share range.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0279 </DOCNO>
