<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FirstRepublicBank     05-12 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First RepublicBank,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Casey Says `Workout Bank' Will Be Used In Reorganization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Chairman Albert V. Casey said
he does not plan to remain at the troubled holding company after
its restructuring begins, and said a search for his replacement has
already begun.
   Casey said Wednesday one of the candidates for the chairmanship
is RepublicBank President Joseph R. Musolino, who is not seeking
re-election to the board of directors at the company's annual
meeting next month.
   The company's restructuring is not likely to be completed before
a review of First Republic's loan portfolio is finished in late
June.
   He also said the Dallas-based bank holding company, Texas
largest, hopes to present a restructuring plan by mid-July that
will include creation of a ``workout bank'' containing troubled
loans.
   In a meeting with reporters, Casey said officials believe the
$1.5 billion loss the bank holding company suffered in the first
quarter of this year should prevent any further huge writedowns.
   ``The big body blow is over,'' Casey said, while adding that the
company ``will continue with some loan losses.''
   First Republic is working with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to
establish the workout bank. That bank would be secured by junk
bonds sold to investors.
   The workout bank would repay notes from the disposition of its
holdings, and could include a mechanism that would allow investors
to share in an appreciation of real estate holdings from their
current market value.
   Casey's comments came a month after he took over from Gerald W.
Fronterhouse and almost two months after the company received a $1
billion cash infusion from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   The chairman said the institution has heard two expressions of
interest from investors. The FDIC, which is handling other
inquiries, said it also has heard from several possible investors.
   First RepublicBank's asset base shrunk from $33.2 billion at the
end of 1987 to $28.4 billion as of March 31.
   Holders of First Republic's $1.3 billion in long-term debt will
likely settle for a fraction of face value in the form of new debt
that will be issued by the restructured company, Casey said.
   ``If you look at the balance sheet, (small holders) have been
wiped out,'' Casey said.
   First Republic, whose non-performing assets totaled $4.5 billion
as of March 31, has stopped making real estate loans ``even with
the biggest and the best in the real estate business,'' Casey said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
