<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Up 15.3 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were broadly higher, at the day's
best levels, at midday Thursday in what dealers called a technical
reaction to the previous day's abrupt drop.
   But trading volumes remained low. Other than a ``little dribbly
buying,'' most of the gains came from price mark-ups, a dealer
said. An absence of selling also underpinned prices, he said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 15.3
points, or 0.9 percent, at 1,772.1 at about 12:30 p.m. (1130 GMT).
The index fell 35.8 points on Wednesday.
   Volume was light at 191.1 million shares compared with 355.7
million at the same time Wednesday.
   The market also was helped by belated response to some some
favorable corporate earnings reports. Shares in some companies that
reported their results on Wednesday were initially unmoved amid
general market preoccupation with the near-term course of
international interest rates. But the results were reflected in
share prices on Thursday.
   Elsewhere, shares in Rowntree PLC fell 19 pence, or 36 cents, to
885 pence, or $16.64, below the effective price of 901.5 pence, or
$16.95, being offered by Nestle S.A. in a hostile takeover bid. It
was the first time the British confectioners' shares have fallen
below Nestle's offer price since the Swiss company launched its bid
last month.
   Dealers said the price decline reflected increased market
speculation that the bid could be investigated by the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission, amid mounting political pressure for such
an inquiry.
