<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Navistar-WisconsinSteel     05-12 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navistar-Wisconsin Steel,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Question of Corporate Responsibility May Be Decided in Wisconsin
Steel Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 11 years after its ill-fated sale of
Wisconsin Steel, Navistar International Corp. is being sued in a
case that could answer the far-reaching question of how much a
company can be obligated to pay retired and laid-off workers.
   Navistar is accused of selling the money-losing steel unit in
1977 to Envirodyne Inc. _ a Los Angeles-based engineering company
with no steel-making experience _ in a bid free itself of
multimillion-dollar pension payouts and other employee-benefit
obligations.
   In a trial scheduled to begin today before U.S. District Judge
James Moran, the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., the federal
insurer of pensions, is seeking $145 million _ $63 million in
unpaid benefits for the laid-off or retired steelworkers, plus
interest.
   In the second lawsuit, Wisconsin Steel creditors _ including an
Envirodyne unit, the EDC Holding Co. _ are seeking $177 million
from Navistar, charging fraud and racketeering in the 1977 sale of
the steel company.
   Navistar, known as International Harvester Co. in 1977, lent
Envirodyne $50 million to finance the $65 million acquisition of
Wisconsin Steel. Harvester's own investment bankers and lawyers had
cautioned against the sale.
   The trial's outcome could well determine whether _ and to what
extent _ the government and others can force corporations to honor
pension-plan obligations to workers.
   Navistar already has reached a $14.8 million out-of-court
settlement with 2,700 former employees of the steel company. The
workers had sought $86 million in claims for benefits lost when the
South Side Chicago steel mill was shuttered.
   The government and the workers filed lawsuits against Navistar
in 1981, little more than a year after Envirodyne, operating as EDC
Holding Co., filed for protection in federal bankruptcy court and
closed the plant.
   The filing came after EDC's key lenders, Navistar and the Chase
Manhattan Bank, called in collateral for past loans.
   EDC sued Navistar in 1982.
   The issue took on added significance last year when Dallas-based
LTV Corp. tried to unload $2.1 billion in pension obligations on
the federal government.
   The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. already is stuck with $2
billion in underfunded pension liabilities from other companies,
and its responsibility could climb to $4 billion if it loses its
court battle with LTV.
   In its annual report, the federal pension insurer said ``a
company cannot escape financial responsibility for its pension
plans by transferring them to a weak third party that cannot
successfully continue the business or fund the pension plans.''
</TEXT>
