<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ResortsInternational Bjt   05-12 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts International, Bjt,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin-Trump Deal For Resorts International Collapses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire investors Merv Griffin and Donald
Trump resumed their battle over Resorts International Inc. after
the collapse of an agreement for Griffin to buy the hotel-casino
company Trump controls.
   The handshake deal, less than a month old, foundered Wednesday
amid a welter of accusations from Griffin and Trump, each blaming
the other.
   In a move recalling the bitter, month-long feud that preceded
the April 14 sale agreement, Griffin vowed to renew a $36-a-share
offer with the outside directors of the Atlantic City, N.J.-based
company.
   Trump responded that the one-time talk show host would never own
Resorts as long as he, Trump, retained control of 88 percent of the
voting shares.
   ``It's like going back to the day before Merv and Don shook
hands,'' Griffin spokesman Mark Gill said of the falling out.
   The failed agreement, which capped months of maneuvering by the
two high-profile businessmen, called for Griffin Co. to pay $207
million, or $36 a share, for publicly held Resorts stock. That
included all 5.7 million Class A shares and the 5.3 percent of
Class B shares that aren't held by Trump.
   It also called for Griffin to acquire Trump's Class B shares,
which give him 88 percent voting control of Resorts, and to sell
the massive, unfinished Taj Mahal casino back to Trump.
   Trump has refused to disclose the price offered for his stake in
Resorts, acquired last year from heirs of company founder James
Crosby for an amount estimated by analysts at $101 million.
   Trump's chief spokesman, Harvey I. Freeman, vice president of
Trump Organization, said Griffin had sought last-minute changes in
the agreement and had failed to prove he could obtain financing.
Freeman predicted failure for Griffin's new overtures to Resorts.
   ``Mr. Griffin can approach anyone that he wants to but it is Mr.
Trump's position that Mr. Griffin will be unable to purchase the
company in that way,'' Freeman said. ``Mr. Trump will resist any
action by Mr. Griffin in this regard.''
   In Los Angeles, Michael Nigris, president of Griffin Co.,
described his boss as ``surprised and disappointed that Donald
Trump was unwilling to proceed with the transaction.''
   ``Financing was never an issue in the negotiations,'' Nigris
said. ``Indeed, the impasse arose from Mr. Trump's refusal to abide
by the original terms of the deal and to accept the fact that the
existing Resorts hotel-casino would remain a viable competitor (to
the Taj Mahal).''
   The battle pits two of the nation's wealthiest entrepreneurs
against each other.
   Trump, who recently turned heads by offering to take over
repairs of a closed New York bridge from the city, is listed by
Forbes Magazine as worth at least $850 million.
   Griffin, 23-year host of the television talk show that bore his
name and creator of the hit game shows ``Jeopardy'' and ``Wheel of
Fortune,'' is listed as being worth $300 million.
</TEXT>
