<HEAD>IBM Introduces New Family of Wheelwriter Typewriters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
introduced a new line of high-performance products that allows
customers to turn their typewriters into modified word processors.
   The Wheelwriter Series II of four typewriters was unveiled
during a news conference Wednesday. IBM also presented an
entry-level Personal Wheelwriter, a new version of the Quietwriter
8 typewriter and two new ``Easystrike'' typewriter ribbons.
   ``It's a triumph of teamwork and technology,'' Charlie Rogers,
IBM's laboratory chief, said of the typewriters.
   The Wheelwriter 10, 30, 50 and 70 all include spelling aids
while the 50 and 70 have 25-line CRT display. They include options
to expand memory to 720,000 bytes with a diskette drive.
   They also allow customers to upgrade from one product in the
series to another by making relatively inexpensive additions as
they need them.
   The typewriters were developed and will be manufactured at IBM's
Lexington facility, said Kailash C. Joshi, site general manager.
   ``They are made in America and made in Kentucky,'' said Joshi,
adding that the products ``demonstrate IBM's commitment to the
typewriter.''
   The suggested retail prices for the typewriters range from $599
for the Personal Wheelwriter to $1,795 for the Wheelwriter 70.
   Wheelwriter 3 and 6 Series II are enhanced versions of earlier
models, with the main difference being the ability to upgrade to
30, 50 and 70 typewriters.
   He said during the past three years more than 1 million
Wheelwriters have been sold, indicating ``a strong customer demand
for office typewriters.''
   The 3, 6, 10 and 30 are on the market now, while the 70 will be
available in late May and the 50 in mid-June, the company said.
