<1ST_LINE>r f BC-LILCO-Shoreham     05-12 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-LILCO-Shoreham,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Agreement To Keep Shoreham Closed Is Near</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HICKSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several ``agreements in principle'' that
would bring about the abandonment of the Shoreham nuclear plant
have been reached by the state and the Long Island Lighting Co., a
published report says.
   Under the agreements, which must be approved by Gov. Mario Cuomo
and LILCO, the state would gain control of Shoreham for $1 and shut
it down, marking the first time a completed nuclear plant would be
shut down before it began operating, the New York Times reported in
Thursday editions.
   LILCO has agreed to pay the estimated $400 million to $500
million costs of the shutdown, the newspaper said, quoting state
officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   The Times said the agreements included guarantees to LILCO of
annual rate increases of 4 percent to 5 percent for the next decade
and the restoration of dividends to the company's shareholders
beginning in 1989.
   Also, LILCO would take a $2.5 billion tax write-off for the
plant, meaning it would pay no federal taxes for at least a decade,
the newspaper said.
   And the state would let the utility float $100 million in
tax-exempt industrial development bonds that could be used to
refinance more expensive debt, the Times reported.
   The $5.3 billion plant has been a rallying cry for opponents of
nuclear energy, politicians campaigning for office and the utility,
which contends the plant's energy was essential if the island was
to have enough energy into the next century.
   Although the plant was supported by state and local officials
when construction first began in the 1970s, opposition grew as
nuclear energy became less popular and more expensive and as the
completion of the plant fell behind 10 years and 10 times over
budget.
   State and local officials argued that Long Island could never be
quickly evacuated in an emergency and they refused to participate
in any emergency plans for the plant, located 55 miles east of New
York City.
   Meanwhile, the Long Island Power Authority, created to consider
a LILCO takeover, is continuing its proxy battle to elect three of
its nominees to LILCO's board of directors.
</TEXT>
