<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MurrayOhio-Electrolux     05-12 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murray Ohio-Electrolux,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electrolux Wants To Work With Murray Ohio Employees; Employees Say
`Nej'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Sweden's AB Electrolux says it
wants good relations with Murray Ohio Manufacturing Corp.
employees, the workers plan to tell the king and queen of Sweden
they want no relations at all with Electrolux.
   Murray Ohio's directors have rejected a $182 million,
$48-a-share offer from Electrolux, a giant appliance manufacturer.
Murray Ohio, which makes lawn mowers and bicycles at Lawrenceburg,
Tenn., and is headquartered in Brentwood, Tenn.
   On Wednesday, Murray Ohio employees said they plan to send a
petition to the king and queen of Sweden opposing the takeover. The
petition will be signed by 5,000 residents of Lawrenceburg and will
accompany a letter to the president of Electrolux, Anders Sharp,
protesting the takeover effort, a spokesman said.
   The employees' news conference came a day after U.S. District
Judge Thomas A. Wiseman of Nashville refused to lift a temporary
restraining order suspending further action by Electrolux
concerning Murray.
   Meanwhile, Scharp issued a statement which said, in part,
``Electrolux has no plans whatever to close the Lawrenceburg
plant.''
   Scharp said Electrolux wants to own and operate the plant.
   ``We need a good relationship at Murray. We regret that the
understandable fears and concerns of Murray employees in this
situation appear to have been exploited,'' he said.
   However, Chuck Brewer, head of the employees' ``Just Say Nej''
committee, said committee members believe the takeover is a threat
to the Murray Ohio's 3,000 employees. ``Nej'' (pronounced ``nay'')
is Swedish for ``no.''
   A copy of the letter to Scharp in Stockholm was released at a
news conference, along with a copy of an advertisement that is to
appear in major U.S. newspapers and a Stockholm newspaper on May 13.
   The letter said, in part, ``We do not dislike you, your company
or the people of Sweden. ... Our relationship with Murray is that
of a family ... They've been exceptional as an employer, and
community leader and friend.''
   Among other things, the ads say, ``We've seen too many workers
lose their jobs, their identity and their self-respect as
independent firms fall prey to hostile outside interests. ... When
pushed, we can be hostile too.''
   Brewer said Wiseman's ruling was viewed as a victory, allowing
Murray more time to fight the takeover. Among other things, Wiseman
ordered the case moved from the state Chancery Court in
Lawrenceburg to his court in Nashville.
   Scharp says Electrolux is committed to purchasing Murray stock
even though it has run against initial roadblocks.
   Brewer released a list showing layoffs by Electrolux after
takeovers of plants in Grand Rapids, Greenville and Belding, Mich.;
Columbus, Ohio; Spain; Italy; Britain; and Ireland.
   As to whether there would be layoffs in Lawrenceburg, Brewer
said, ``It's an unknown. It scares everybody.''
   Bobbie Clark, who helped gather the signatures on the petition,
said, ``We like things like they are.''
   Brewer said the petition will be accompanied by a package
containing ``samples of Tennessee foods. That's the closest we want
them to get here.''
   The petition and package will be delivered today to Sen. James
Sasser, D-Tenn., in Washington, who will accompany employee leaders
to the Swedish embassy. Brewer said they will ask the ambassador to
deliver the petition ``to the king and queen of Sweden.''
   The proposed newspaper ad, signed ``The Working Men and Women of
Murray,'' also says in part, ``We will not stand by and see our
company, our economy and our values compromised. Because money may
buy our company's stock but not our loyalty.
   ``We, the workers of Murray, urge the management of AB
Electrolux to withdraw their bid immediately. Or we will never be
the same company again.''
</TEXT>
