<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CitrusBan     05-12 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Citrus Ban,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Will Appeal Federal Judge's Ruling On Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas Department of Agriculture
will appeal a federal judge's ruling that blocks efforts to keep
fresh Florida citrus out of the Lone Star State, an official said.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela ruled Wednesday that the U.S.
Department of Agriculture did nothing wrong when it lifted a
3{-year ban on shipments of the Florida fruit to other
citrus-producing areas.
   ``We told the attorney general today that we'd like him to start
putting the paperwork together'' for an appeal, said TDA spokesman
Max Woodfin.
   The Florida fruit was quarantined after an outbreak of citrus
canker in parts of Florida in August 1984.
   The USDA on Feb. 11 lifted the ban on shipments of fresh Florida
citrus into Texas and other citrus-producing areas.
   Texas officials had sought to have the quarantine reinstated and
claimed the USDA did not allow adequate time for comment when it
lifted the ban.
   Vela's ruling Wednesday was in response to a suit filed March 9
by the state of Texas, which was trying to stop shipments of the
Florida fruit to the state. The suit contends that the USDA
violated its own rules by failing to allow a comment period before
lifting the ban.
   ``With all the information put before me, I am satisfied that
the USDA followed the law'' in promulgating the rule, Vela said
Wednesday.
   The judge said the new protocol is so similar to one the USDA
proposed last fall but withdrew in January that there had been
plenty of time for comment.
   Canker, which comes in different strains, can damage the plants
and cause lesions on the fruit or make it drop prematurely from
trees.
   Texas citrus producers say an outbreak of canker would devastate
the state's $65 million citrus industry concentrated on 30,000
acres in Hidalgo, Cameron and Willacy counties in the Lower Rio
Grande Valley.
   ``We've maintained all along that the risk of our getting canker
is relatively small, but it's a risk we don't believe we ought to
take,'' said Ray Prewett, director of Texas Citrus Mutual, a
McAllen-based industry group.
   Florida officials have maintained that the canker is under
control.
</TEXT>
