<DOCNO> AP880512-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene 1stLd-Writethru f0023 05-12 0903</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0926</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS date in 4th graf, In a, to Sept. 1, from Aug. 1;
also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drain on U.S. stockpiles and drought
problems in Brazil are raising prospects for American soybean
farmers.
   Soybean futures on the Chicago Board of Trade jumped Wednesday
in response to Agriculture Department figures showing tighter
supplies of soybeans in the year ahead.
   The harvest forecast in Brazil, the main U.S. competitor in the
world soybean market, was reduced by more than 2 percent from
prospects a month ago, according to the latest department figures.
   In a supply-and-demand report issued on Tuesday, the USDA
projected that the nation's stockpile could decline to 145 million
bushels at the close of the next marketing year on Aug. 31, 1989,
from around 275 million bushels on Sept. 1, 1988.
   According to department records, the U.S. soybean inventory
carried over into the new marketing year on Sept. 1, 1989, would be
the smallest in at least five years and possibly longer.
   The Sept. 1 inventory was 436 million bushels in 1987, a record
536 million in 1986, and 316 million in 1985. The carryover had
dropped to 176 million bushels on Sept. 1, 1984, reflecting drought
losses in the 1983 harvest.
   In the 1983-84 marketing year, as a result of the tight supply,
soybean prices at the farm averaged an annual record of $7.83 per
bushel, up from $5.65 the previous year. But the upward spike was
temporary, and prices tumbled sharply as production increased
thereafter.
   The new projections, which USDA officials caution are ``highly
tentative,'' show that farmers can expect soybean prices to average
in the range of $5.75 to $7.75 per bushel in the 1988-89 marketing
year, compared with a reported $5.75 this season and $4.78 in
1986-87.
   According to the projections, this year's soybean harvest _ the
crop is only about 14 percent planted _ could be around 1.88
billion bushels, slightly less than the 1987 harvest.
   Counting a Sept. 1 carryover of 275 million bushels, that would
mean a soybean supply of around 2.155 billion bushels for the
1988-89 marketing year. Of that, some 1.155 billion bushels are
expected to be crushed into high-protein meal and oil. Exports will
take an additional 760 million bushels, and seed, feed and other
uses will account for more.
   In all, 1988-89 soybean use is projected at 2.01 billion
bushels, meaning some of the Sept. 1 carryover will have to be used
to meet next season's demand. Thus, the soybean stockpile could be
a relatively skimpy 145 million bushels by Sept. 1, 1989.
   Historically, the U.S. soybean stockpile a times has been even
smaller _ and prices higher.
   In the early 1970s, for example, the Sept. 1 soybean carryover
dropped below 100 million bushels for three consecutive years from
a Sept. 1, 1970, inventory of 230 million bushels. Prices, which
averaged $2.85 per bushel in 1970, rose to an annual average of
$6.64 per bushel in 1974.
   After that soybean prices averaged in a range of less than $5
per bushel to a peak of $6.81 in 1976. In 1980, however, they
averaged $7.57 per bushel, a record until 1983 when the price went
to $7.83.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China, the world's leading hog producer, has
ended pork rationing, according to an Agriculture Department report.
   ``A Chinese agriculture official privately stated that pork
rationing in Beijing had stopped being enforced,'' the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service said Wednesday. ``Other officials said
that pork rationing had ended throughout the country, though no
official announcement has confirmed this.''
   China began rationing pork in most major cities last fall in
response to shortages. Pork traditionally supplies about 80 percent
of the total animal protein in the Chinese diet.
   ``The pork shortages that led to the rationing did not, however,
affect China's ability to supply hogs to its limited export markets
(primarily Hong Kong),'' the report said. ``In fact, the country
has had a surplus of hogs for export to Hong Kong, but increases in
hog trade between the two countries has been limited by a Chinese
export quota.''
   An end to rationing ``shows that Chinese agricultural officials
believe the tight pork supply situation is now being resolved'' as
producers respond to lower feed prices, higher pork prices and
government incentives to promote larger production, the report said.
   ``It also is an indication that many urban consumers are willing
to pay more for the higher-quality, free market pork instead of
enduring the cheaper, fattier meat that has been sold at lower
prices in state markets,'' the report said.
   A USDA study last year showed that China had a 1983 year-end
inventory of 298.5 million hogs, compared with 55.8 million in the
United States.
   But with more than five times the number of hogs, China's pork
production was less than double the U.S. output _ 13.2 million
metric tons to 7.6 million tons, the USDA study said. A metric ton
is about 2,205 pounds.
   The reason: It took only six months for an American farmer to
raise a 243-pound hog ready for slaughter, while a newborn Chinese
pig can take from eight to 18 months to reach a comparable
slaughter weight.
   Also, the study said, the average U.S. hog will produce a
dressed-out carcass of about 173 pounds, compared with the Chinese
carcass of about 140 pounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
