<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower Thursday
on the Chicago Board of Trade as scattered showers dampened parts
of the Corn Belt and weather forecasters predicted heavier
precipitation this weekend.
   Soybean futures posted the steepest early declines after five
straight days of sharp increases that were based on dry weather
conditions and an Agriculture Department report predicting
dwindling soybean stockpiles.
   ``The market is relatively quiet after all the excitement and
hoopla about Tuesday,'' when the USDA issued the report, said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst with G.H. Miller & Co. in Chicago. ``We're
starting things off on a little more of a so-so situation here.''
   Losses in wheat futures were limited by the USDA's offer late
Tuesday of 1 million metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat to Egypt,
Gidel said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $3.02\ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1 cent lower with May at $1.96} a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 2{ cents lower with May at $1.56 a bushel; soybeans were
1\ cents to 4{ cents lower with May at $7.08 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent lower to .13 cent higher with June at
73.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .45 cent higher
with May at 80.25 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent lower to .25
cent higher with June at 52.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .03 cent to .23 cent higher with May at 53.10 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
advanced sharply.
