<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Panama-Economy     05-12 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama-Economy,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Difficult Recovery Seen for Panamanian Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Panama's political crisis were
resolved tomorrow, it would take at least two years and a vigorous
recovery program for the devastated economy to return to the levels
of early 1987, according to five of the country's top economists.
   In the absence of a prompt solution to the crisis, which stems
from U.S. and local efforts to topple strongman Gen. Manuel
Noriega, Panama could be headed for collapse of its productive
apparatus, hunger and totalitariansim, the five said Wednesday.
   Economist Ruben Carles provided The Associated Press with a copy
of the report, entitled ``A Proposal for Economic Reconstruction.''
Carles is a director of a local bank and adviser to several major
multinational and Panamanian enterprises.
   The other authors _ bankers, consultants and academics _ are
Carlos Valencia, Marco Fernandez, Guillermo Chapman and Jose Galan
Ponce.
   They are all, in varying degrees, opponents of the
military-dominated government.
   But the government also recognizes the dire economic
consequences of the crisis. Treasury Minister Orvin Goodin said
Tuesday the gross national product would decrease by up to 20
percent this year.
   The Reagan administration has for the past 2{ months imposed
increasingly severe economic sanctions on Panama. Washington hoped
the measures would force Noriega to resign and leave the country,
but he has resisted the pressure and appears firmly entrenched.
   The general, who is commander of the Panamanian defense forces,
is the country's de facto ruler.
   In February, he was indicted in federal courts in Florida on
drug smuggling and money laundering charges. He denies the
accusations, contending they are part of an attempt to replace him
with a leader amenable to a strong U.S. presence in Panama into the
next century.
   The 1977 Panama Canal treaties oblige Washington to hand over
complete control of the waterway and U.S. military bases along it
by Dec. 31, 1999.
   The authors of the report say the crisis and resulting sanctions
have produced a more than 50 percent decrease in the amount of
money circulating in Panama.
   ``That allows for maintenance of likewise less than half the
production and transactions normally carried out in the country,''
says the report.
   Banks, which had been closed for nine weeks, reopened Monday,
but with severe restrictions.
   ``Economic activity is principally dedicated to liquidation of
stocks, given that imports are almost nil and it is extremely
difficult, if not impossible, to finance production,'' the report
says.
   The authors say that, in recent months, unemployment has risen
from about 12 percent of the workforce to approximately 20 percent.
They say that, even with a political solution in the coming weeks
or months, more than 40,000 more people stand to lose their jobs
because of the shrinking economy. That would raise unemployment to
26 percent of the workforce.
   Panama uses the U.S. dollar as its currency.
   The report's authors said one option open to the Panamanian
regime would be ``intervention or nationalization of the banking
system and the emission of a local currency with attendant
extremely grave economic consequences that would imply a transition
toward totalitarianism.''
   They propose a series of steps contingent on solution of the
political crisis, which would include abandonment of power by
Noriega.
   The report says extensive international relief will be needed to
alleviate hunger among the poor, who have been battered by the
crisis. It says international financial support totaling hundreds
of millions of dollars will be necessary.
   The U.S. Treasury would have to provide ample credit to
Panamanian banks and the foreign debt of $3.9 billion would have to
be renegotiated, according to the recovery plan.
   ``Our plan ... takes as a starting point the recognition that it
will take a period of no less than 24 months to return to the
levels of production and employment of the first semester of
1987,'' the report says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880512-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv13   05-12 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 13,0696</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday May 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Market Is a Bigger Loser Than Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Day by day it becomes clearer that one of the
big losers in the stock market is the market itself.
   Business is off and layoffs are rising. The public is
disaffected with the way the market operates, especially its
volatility and seemingly senseless changes of direction.
   The publicity is negative. Various study groups complain, in
effect, that the market has become an assembly of institutional
sharpies who skim profits by means of technicalities and
sophisticated computer programs.
   The most devastating criticism comes from within the system
itself.
   Some of the biggest brokers have agreed to shut down their
in-house program trading operations, which seek almost automatic
profits on technicalities, because angry customers feel such
operations work against their interests.
   The head of a prominent small-investor brokerage house, Charles
Schwab, has referred to program traders as manipulators. And
Schwab's own operation has been criticized because investors
couldn't reach brokers on Oct. 19.
   George Ball, chairman of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said
a poll by his company showed individual investors, who generally
invest on the basis of a company's management and earnings, feel
cheated by market manipulators.
   Donald Regan, blunt-speaking former Treasury secretary, told the
Senate Banking Committee this week that the public has a right to
believe the marketplace is rigged. ``It is,'' he snapped.
   Regan's criticism is especially damaging because in his
pre-White House years he was one of the most promiment of all Wall
Streeters, head of Merrill Lynch and a leader in bringing
individual investors into the markeplace.
   Anger is also being directed at the Securities and Exchange
Commission and at the Commodities Futures Trading Commission, whose
jobs are to protect the public from shenanigans that inevitably
arise and must be squashed.
   The worst of these practices appears to be that of capitalizing
on gaps in prices of stock traded on the New York Stock Exchange
and stock index futures traded in Chicago. The players often are
brokerage houses themselves.
   When these gaps appear _ gaps that have nothing at all to do
with basic values _ they can produce wild price swings as money
jumps from one to the other in an attempt to skim off profits.
   Small investors cannot take such advantage. They have too little
capital, they have too little time, they have too little
sophistication. Gaps are discovered by those with immediate access
to data and instant communications.
   These automatic trading practices, mindlessly initiated by
electronic programs that spot opportunities, are believed to have
triggered, accelerated and reinforced the crash of last Oct. 19.
   Oddly, little comment and criticism has been heard from the
companies whose stocks are affected. But that criticism is sure to
come.
   Companies such as General Motors, for example, know that GM
investors are inclined to buy GM products, and they seek to exploit
that relationship with reminders in their quarterly reports to
shareholders.
   If these shareholders aren't protected from marketplace
shenanigans, it is fair to expect that they will lose their
enthusiasm for investing, hurting the value of the corporation's
stock and, quite likely, its sales as well.
   So pervasive are the negative comments about program trading
that it has, for the time being, overwhelmed concern about the
legal problems that had begun to unfold before the Oct. 19 crash
and are about to make headlines again.
   Investigations already have led to jail sentences for several
traders, including Ivan F. Boesky. But those investigations
continue; they are expected to bring in other promiment parties,
perhaps on criminal charges.
   Criminality, according to government investigators, is rampant
rather than existing on the periphery of the marketplace.
   In a pre-sentencing memo in the Boesky case, government
officials said they found ``criminal conduct is at the heart of a
substantial amount of market activity by established securities
industry professionals.''
   In short, the marketplace has an odor that drives away customers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday May 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
