<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Retail     05-12 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Retail,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Reports First-Quarter Earnings About Equal To Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. announced Thursday its first-quarter
earnings fell 3 percent while Gap Inc. reported its earnings
tumbled nearly 73 percent.
   May, the nation's seventh-largest retailer, said that in the
quarter ended April 30, it had earnings of $62 million, down from
$64 million during the first quarter of 1987. The company reported
per-share earnings of 41 cents in both quarters.
   May said its first-quarter sales were $2.28 billion, down from
$2.34 billion for the same period last year.
   The company fell victim _ as did many other major retailers _ to
the sluggish consumer spending climate of the first quarter.
   ``For now, business continues to be slow, with most parts of
sportswear and juniors performing poorly,'' May Chairman David C.
Farrell said.``Expenses and inventories are being watched
carefully.''
   Gap, one of the nation's largest apparel store chains, also was
affected by the spending slump.
   Gap reported its earnings fell to $4.4 million, or 12 cents per
share, from $16.2 million, or 45 cents per share, in the same
period a year ago.
   The company reported it had a $4 million after-tax charge from
the restructuring of its Banana Republic segment.
   Sales for the quarter totaled $241.3 million, up from $211
million.
   Gap operates more than 840 apparel stores across the country.
   May's stores include May and Lord and Taylor department stores
and Venture and Caldor discount stores.
</TEXT>
