<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Lorimar-Davis     05-12 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lorimar-Davis,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Davis Bid for TV Producer That Agreed to Takeover by Warner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis renewed his bid
for ailing television producer Lorimar Telepictures Inc. Thursday,
just two days after Lorimar agreed to become part of Warner
Communications Inc.
   Davis, who previously offered $17 per share for the maker of
such hit TV series as ``Dallas'' and ``Knots Landing,'' notified
the company he would pay $15 cash per share, or $679.5 million.
   Lorimar values the tentative agreement it made with Warner
Tuesday at $1.18 billion. That agreement includes assumption of
$550 million in Lorimar debt and financial penalties if Lorimar
backs out and merges with a third party.
   Pending review of confidential financial information, Davis said
in a letter released by Lorimar, ``we are prepared to consider
increasing our price in a negotiated transaction.''
   A spokesman for Davis, an oil man and investor who formerly
owned Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp., declined to comment.
   Lorimar officials declined immediate comment on the impact
Davis' offer might have on the Warner transaction. That match was
seen as a way to solve Lorimar's cash problems and make Warner a
leader in television production as well as its present strength in
movies and music.
   The deal was conditional, but Lorimar Chairman Merv Adelson made
it clear at the time he saw the tax-free stock-swap deal with
Warner as the ideal marriage.
   Davis' $15-per-share figure for Lorimar matches the minimum
value placed on the stock swap that forms the basis of the Warner
deal.
   That merger, tentatively scheduled to close in September, would
trade .415 shares of Warner stock for each of the 45.3 million
outstanding shares of Lorimar common stock.
   In addition to the stock swap, valued by the companies at $630
million, Warner would assume about $550 million in Lorimar debt.
   Lorimar is allowed to back out if Warner's stock value does not
bring Lorimar shareholders at least $15 per share, a figure Lorimar
calculates would be met if Warner's stock price averages $36 a
share.
   If Lorimar cancels, the agreement commits it to pay Warner $10
million. If Lorimar is acquired by a third party, Warner has the
right to buy 18.5 percent of the outstanding shares at $15 a share.
</TEXT>
