<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WheatTour     05-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat Tour,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Evaluators To Examine Wheat Fields In Seven States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of evaluators will examine wheat
fields in seven states next week to check on the condition of the
crop as it approaches harvest.
   ``The wheat is starting to head out,'' said Jim Quinton, a grain
analyst for the AgriVisor marketing service in Bloomington. ``It is
in a very critical stage _ the reproductive stage.''
   Quinton has organized the wheat evaluation tour, which will
focus on the nation's key soft red winter wheat states of Missouri,
Illinois, Ohio, Indiana, Michigan, Kentucky and Arkansas.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture this week issued its first
estimates of the season for wheat production across the country
based on May 1 conditions. It said the harvest is expected to be up
4 percent for all winter varieties.
   ``We do feel it would be worthwhile to go out and get a
mid-course correction,'' Quinton said Wednesday.
   He said soft red wheat production is projected to be 426 million
bushels from this summer's harvest, up from 348 million bushels in
1987.
   ``This very likely is not so much a yield increase as an acreage
increase,'' said Quinton, noting farmers planted 1.7 million more
acres last fall than the previous year.
   The states in which evaluators will examine fields have nearly 7
million acres of soft red winter wheat out of a total of about 10.5
million in the United States, Quinton said.
   Evaluators will begin the tour Monday, covering several routes
and stopping about every 15 to 20 miles to check fields. The team
will include people from the grain trade, the milling industry, the
government, producer groups and the news media.
   In each field, participants will check the soil moisture
condition, the stage of development of the wheat, the size of the
stand, and the potential number and size of grain heads. They also
will look for any evidence of disease.
   Quinton said most of the soft red winter wheat seems to be in
good condition. Most was planted in a timely fashion last fall, and
cool, dry spring conditions have favored the development of much of
the crop.
   Soft red wheat is milled to make fine flours that are used in
things like cake, cookies and crackers. It is the hard wheat grown
farther west that is used for breads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
