<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid     05-12 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Appoints Independent Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. said Thursday it set up a
committee of three independent directors to hold talks with its two
suitors, Bank of New York Co. and Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA.
   However, Bank of New York maintained it had no intention of
sweetening its hostile $1.08 billion bid, and was not holding any
negotiations with Irving.
   ``We have always said any time Irving will come to the table
with substantive negotiations we would listen. But we're not
prepared to talk to them in an auction environment,'' said Bank of
New York spokesman Owen Brady.
   Irving disclosed the special committee in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission on Thursday. The company said
that while the directors were authorized to meet directly with the
Bank of New York and Banca Commerciale, ``there can be no
assurances that these discussions will result in any improvement in
either.''
   Irving's announcement came nearly a week after its annual
meeting, in which shareholders voted between a slate of 16
incumbent directors that back a restructuring and friendly merger
with Banca Commerciale and nominees from rival Bank of New York.
   The voting results are not expected to be released until a
reconvened meeting May 24, although both sides are claiming victory.
   Banking analysts generally have given Bank of New York an edge
in the proxy battle, mostly because it already has secured the
necessary regulatory approvals. Banca Commerciale, Italy's second
largest bank which is controlled by the government agency Instituto
per la Recostruzione Industriale, has just begun the lengthy
regulatory review process.
   Bank of New York, which owns a nearly 5 percent stake in Irving,
is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's common shares. The offer, which is scheduled to expire May
13, is valued at about $63 a share or $1.08 billion.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $75 a share for 9.5 million Irving
shares, or about 51 percent, valued at $707 million. In addition,
it said it would pay shareholders interest on the purchase price
from May 31 until the deal closes.
</TEXT>
