<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Autos-Canada     05-12 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Autos-Canada,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal Seeks Higher North American Content in U.S-Canada Auto
Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee has tentatively
agreed to authorize the president to negotiate a higher North
American content for automobiles coming under the proposed
U.S.-Canada free-trade agreement, the staff of Sen. Donald Riegle,
D-Mich., said Thursday.
   The proposed treaty requires that U.S. or Canadian parts,
components and labor account for half the content of cars moving
duty-free across the border. Critics of the treaty, Riegle among
them, have said that level is too low.
   Riegle's proposal would authorize the president to negotiate a
higher domestic-content rule with Canada, in the hope of raising it
to 60 percent.
   If negotiations succeed, the president would be able to begin
the higher requirement through a proclamation, rather than
returning to Congress for consent, Riegle's staff said.
   Under the terms of the free-trade negotiations, both houses of
Congress must accept or reject the treaty as is, without amendment.
   However, Congress has the power to tie its acceptance of the
treaty to the fulfillment of certain conditions, or to pass other
legislation authorizing the president to try to renegotiate parts
of the agreement.
   ``My goal has been to improve the implementing language so that
the agreement is better,'' Riegle said. ``We are making some
significant progress.''
   The Finance Committee has not completed its work on the bill.
   The 50 percent North American content requirement has been
criticized by the United Auto Workers and parts suppliers. A level
that low would allow manufacturers to import engines, transmissions
and other major components.
   Another heavily criticized provision would allow Canada to
retain until 1996 agreements giving preferential duty treatment to
manufacturers outside North America who have Canadian production.
   Extending the preferential treatment will allow Canadian
suppliers and Japanese manufacturers to forge agreements that will
shut out U.S. suppliers from part of the market, critics have said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
