<FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Banks     05-12 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banks,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Report Raps Big Banks on Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. banks are undercapitalized and
underregulated and have failed to write down approximately $28
billion in uncollectable foreign loans, the General Accounting
Office said in a report released Thursday.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, found fault with
federal regulators such as the Office of the Comptroller of the
Currency, the Federal Reserve Board and the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. for creating a lenient classification system for
developing country debt.
   Using today's secondary market as a guidepost, the GAO
calculated that the average Third World loan is worth 54 percent of
its stated value. Under this criteria, the report estimated that
American banks have reserved $21.1 billion of foreign loans when a
more realistic figure should be $49 billion.
   In contrast, the criteria regulators developed only required
$2.3 billion in U.S. bank write-downs of uncollectable loans, the
GAO said.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who asked for the report, said, ``In
this `audit of the auditors,' it can be inferred that the record
first-quarter profits recently announced for banks engaged in
overseas lending are a shibboleth and that these institutions
should write off this year loans of a greater magnitude than they
did last year.
   ``Bank earnings are only as sound as their loan portfolios and
those portfolios, the GAO finds, are overvalued,'' Leach said.
   U.S. bank loans to developing countries decreased from $139.7
billion in June 1982 to $107.6 billion in December 1987, while U.S.
bank capital increased from $66.2 billion in June 1982 to $129.2
billion in December 1987.
   As a result, from June 1982 to December 1987 bank loans owed by
developing countries decreased from 211 percent of bank capital to
83 percent. During this time, developing country loans owed to the
nine largest money center banks decreased from 323 percent of these
banks' capital to 139 percent.
   ``While these figures reflect a prudential improvement in
circumstances for American banks, developing country loans are
still large compared with bank capital and are disproportionately
concentrated in a small number of money center institutions,'' said
Leach, a ranking Republican on the House Banking, Finance and Urban
Affairs Committee and its international finance, trade and monetary
policy subcommittee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
