<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower in U.S.; Gold Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished slightly lower against most
other currencies Thursday in the United States after rising
marginally in Europe, and money brokers said there was little news
to influence trading.
   Gold prices rose in New York and London after falling in Hong
Kong. As of 4 p.m. EDT, Republic National Bank of New York quoted
bullion at $450.90 a troy ounce, up from $448.80 late Wednesday.
   ``It was another dull day in the currency market,'' said Graham
Broyd, vice president of foreign exchange at Manufacturers Hanover
Corp. in New York.
   Traders said the boost the dollar got Wednesday from rising
interest rates in the United States was partly eroded by an
assumption that other nations also would raise their rates,
negating the U.S. impact. Higher interest rates make a currency
more attractive to foreign investors.
   Others said remarks by Federal Reserve Board governor Wayne
Angell, who vaguely indicated the central bank may not necessarily
tighten credit further, had little impact on the dollar.
   But some money market economists said they saw long-term
weakness in the dollar because of the continually high trade and
budget deficits and the Fed's apparent reluctance to nudge interest
rates up too much.
   ``From an interest rate point of view, the foreign exchange
market assumes the Fed is constraied on how high interest rates can
go,'' said Michael Broder, an economist at Money Market Services, a
Chicago forecasting firm. ``You have the mere mention of higher
interest rates and the bond and stock markets go into the tank
pretty quick.''
   The dollar rose to 124.39 Japanese yen in Tokyo, vs. 124.24 yen
Wednesday. Later in London the dollar was quoted at 124.47 yen. By
the time trading concluded in New York the dollar was quoted at
124.53 yen, slightly higher than the 124.47 yen quoted late
Wednesday.
   The British pound fell in London to $1.8823 from $1.8870 late
Wednesday. Later in New York the pound fetched $1.8833, higher than
its $1.8815 value late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.6816 West German marks, down from
1.6827; 1.3987 Swiss francs, down from 1.3995; 1.2300 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2314; 5.7005 French francs, down from 5.7037;
and 1,251.00 Italian lire, down from 1,251.50.
   Other late rates for the dollar in London, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.6813 marks, up from 1.6773; 1.3987
Swiss francs, up from 1.3935; 5.7020 French francs, up from 5.6912;
1.8850 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8830; 1,250.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,249.50; and 1.2298 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2315.
   Gold bullion prices rose in London to $451.50 a troy ounce, vs.
$449.30 Wednesday. Zurich markets were closed for the Ascension Day
holiday.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $450.06, down from $451.68.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose $2.20 a troy ounce to $451.90
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.56 bid a troy ounce,
up from $6.55. On the New York Comex, the price was $6.574, up 2.2
cents.
</TEXT>
