<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChryslerContract     05-12 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler Contract,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skilled Trades Workers Reject Chrysler Pact; Leaders to Meet in
Chicago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. skilled trades workers have
rejected a United Auto Workers contract ratified by other union
members, UAW officials said Thursday.
   The rejection does not change the overall ratification, but
could lead to new negotiations solely on skilled trades issues such
as apprenticeships, according to union officials.
   The union scheduled a meeting Friday in Chicago to review the
matter with its Chrysler skilled trades officials, who represent
more than 10,500 of the No. 3 automaker's UAW members.
   The two-year contract, covering 66,000 hourly and salaried
workers in 15 states, was ratified Wednesday by 54 percent of those
voting. Skilled trades _ such as machine tool makers _ and salaried
workers have additional, separate contracts covering issues unique
to them.
   The two groups vote as one on whether to ratify or reject both
contracts, which were approved by the salaried workers. UAW
spokesman Frank Joyce said he had no figures on the skilled trades
rejection or the salaried approval of the contract.
   There is at least one skilled trades delegate for each of
Chrysler's nearly 50 UAW local unions.
   If the skilled trades rejection was based on issues contained in
the main contract, such as economics, neither new negotiations nor
a new skilled trades vote would occur, union sources said.
   Part of the purpose of Friday's meeting is to determine whether
or not the rejection was based on issues unique to the skilled
trades.
   Union officials who asked not to be identified said they
believed the rejection was economic. If so, the meeting will be the
only action on the rejection and skilled trades workers will have
to live with the contract ratified by everybody else.
   The meeting was called by UAW President Owen Bieber and Vice
President Marc Stepp and will include those delegates on the UAW's
140-member national Chrysler council who represent skilled trades
workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
